<HEADLINE>
RUTGERS WOMEN DEFEAT HOLY CROSS, 91-70 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ They were smaller, slower and far less
talented. But for a half of Friday night's first-round NCAA
tournament game at the Louis Brown Athletic Center, the 15th-seeded
Crusaders of Holy Cross were more than enough for second-seeded
Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the 3-point shooting of Anna Kinne, the Crusaders trailed
by just four points at halftime and were all smiles heading into
the locker room. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then the Scarlet Knights wiped the smiles right off their faces
at the start of the second half. Rutgers hit eight of its first
nine shots in a 24-4 blitz and cruised to a 91-70 victory in the
West Regional. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers will meet 10th-seeded St. Joseph's, a 69-48 winner over
seventh-seeded Texas earlier, in a second-round game here Sunday
night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Usha Gilmore led Rutgers (23-7) with 14 points and Kinne had 28
points for Holy Cross (23-7). Rutgers created some breathing room
with a 10-0 run in which the Scarlet Knights made their first five
shots of the second half to take a 51-37 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights began tracking Kinne _ who had scored 19
points in the first half _ more carefully along the perimeter.
Kinne was unable to free herself and the misses began mounting for
the Crusaders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The solution seemed so simple: Krazy Glue a player to Kinne _ in
this case Karlita Washington or Usha Gilmore _ and let Holy Cross
try to score without her. The Knights began talking to Kinne, and
Kinne was talking back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tasha Pointer, who had been nearly a no-show in the first half,
drilled a jumper to increase the lead to 53-39 with under 15
minutes to go. Kinne slid along the baseline for a layup, but
Gilmore answered with a jump shot and then a 3-point play off a
fast break. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights were bigger, faster and better. And in the
second half they were playing like it. When Stewart streaked in for
a layup, it made the lead 61-41 with 12 minutes 20 seconds left and
Rutgers was cruising, much to the relief of a partisan crowd that
included New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross trailed by 41-37 at halftime and was clearly enjoying
itself. Inspired by the shooting of Kinne, the Crusaders made
enough shots to keep Rutgers from picking up the pace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers outrebounded Holy Cross by 21-10, and shot 56 percent to
Holy Cross' 52 percent, in the first half. Holy Cross had seven
turnovers to Rutgers' five, but Kinne's 6-of-7 shooting from
3-point range and an inside push for nine points from Jeanette
Paukert kept the Crusaders in the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross won the Patriot League's regular season and
tournament championships. Of its six losses, three were to Top 20
teams and three were without Kinne, the league's player of the
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Crusaders were shorter, slower and less talented. In an
agonizing first half for the Scarlet Knights, it nearly didn't
matter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph's 69, Texas 48
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph's forward Susan Moran, a member of the Irish national
team, scored a game-high 24 points in her first time playing on St.
Patrick's Day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the luck of the Irish that we're here,'' Moran said.
``And it isn't the luck of the Irish that we won.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tenth-seeded St. Joseph's (25-5), which had allowed an average
of just 53 points a game, limited the seventh-seeded Longhorns
(21-13) and their star, Edwina Brown (14 points), to just one field
goal in nearly 11 minutes while extending its 32-30 halftime lead
to 52-40.
</P>
</TEXT>
