<HEADLINE>
SHIFTING VIEW TOWARD POLICE COMPLICATES DECISION TO TESTIFY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-POLICE-SHOOTING, NY-POLICE-TRAINING) 
(js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The undercover police detective who fired the shot
that killed an unarmed man in Midtown Manhattan on Thursday faces a
pivotal decision: Should he volunteer to testify before the grand
jury investigating the shooting?
</P>
<P>
   The facts are still sketchy and under investigation, and it is
unknown whether the panel of 23 New Yorkers will have grounds to
charge the detective, Anthony Vasquez, with a crime. But after a
spate of high-profile shootings and cases of police misconduct,
defense experts say he should carefully weigh his next move.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, in most police shootings, officers chose to take
the witness stand to explain their use of deadly force, police
union lawyers said. And grand juries _ which decide whether there
is enough evidence for an indictment _ generally gave the officers'
accounts the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   But several legal experts and leading criminal defense lawyers
said Friday that Vasquez should not testify before the grand jury
because the reputation of the New York Police Department has been
damaged so much in recent months that grand jurors may not believe
his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a different era, the police officers carried with them a
strong presumption of integrity,'' said Gerald Shargel, a Manhattan
defense lawyer. ``But unfortunately, because of the conduct of a
few, that has evaporated.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts attribute that change in part to two high-profile
cases with racial overtones: the fatal shooting of Amadou Diallo,
an unarmed black man, by four white police officers, and the
torture of another black man, Abner Louima, in a Brooklyn police
station. In both cases, the accused officers decided not to testify
before grand juries. The Louima case led to convictions in two
trials; the officers in the Diallo case were acquitted last month.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of those cases has spilled into grand jury rooms. The
proceedings are secret, but prosecutors have reported that in
recent months, jurors appear to have become increasingly skeptical
of police testimony, and that they have become increasingly
aggressive in asking all witnesses more questions. For example,
they have asked police officers to explain their conduct in greater
detail, for example, where there were questions about whether
arrests or seizures were proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been more probing,'' said one lawyer who recently
watched police officers testify before grand juries and who spoke
on the condition of anonymity. ``It's question after question after
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Several legal experts said it may be wiser for Vasquez not to
appear before the grand jury, even if he broke no law in shooting
Patrick M. Dorismond, 26, an unarmed black man, after scuffling
with him outside a bar.
</P>
<P>
   If the grand jurors believe civilian witnesses over Vasquez and
indict him, the experts pointed out, then the detective's
statements to the grand jury could be used against him at a trial.
But not testifying carries a risk: if Vasquez does not tell his
side, he may be indicted on manslaughter or criminally negligent
homicide charges for his actions, creating yet another racially
charged police abuse trial in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The officer's lawyer, Philip Karasyk, said Vasquez would not
comment on whether he would testify.
</P>
<P>
   Karasyk said Dorismond was the aggressor in the brief, chaotic
encounter. He attacked one of Vasquez's undercover partners, who
had approached him and asked if he sold drugs, Karasyk said. The
lawyer said that after Vasquez identified himself twice as a police
officer and drew his gun, Dorismond lunged and hit the detective's
gun hand, causing the weapon to fire.
</P>
<P>
   Undercover detectives typically back away from fights, Karasyk
added. ``They are not looking for confrontation. The last thing
they want to have happen is for there to be a fight where their
cover can be blown.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what the evidence will show was unclear Friday.
Prosecutors refused to discuss their investigation or the results
of forensic tests. But potential strategies for both sides emerged
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said relevant forensic evidence might include the
victim's blood alcohol level and the results of tests for gunpowder
traces on Dorismond's sleeve or hand, which would suggest they were
near the gun when it fired.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses have sharply contradicted the version of
events presented by the detective's lawyer. Kevin Kaiser, a friend
and fellow security guard who was drinking with Dorismond before
the shooting, said that after Dorismond angrily answered the
undercover officer's question about drugs, an officer swung first.
Kaiser and other witnesses also said the officers, who were in
plain clothes, never identified themselves as the police.
</P>
<P>
   Based on these statements, said James Cohen, a professor at
Fordham University Law school, prosecutors could argue that the
police were criminally reckless during the encounter for
approaching Dorismond for no apparent reason, being confrontational
and quickly drawing and firing a weapon without justification.
``They stopped these people on the street. The people say, `Get
lost.' The thing escalates, and in an instant, the nondrug dealer
gets killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Hayes, a prominent Manhattan defense lawyer, was the only
expert interviewed Friday who said he thought Vasquez should tell
his story to the grand jury. He said officers need to speak out
more and said the real issues are whether the police have
sufficient training and whether aggressive tactics cause dangerous
confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   He said city officials or the police need to reach out to the
community. ``If the mayor won't do it, the police union should do
it, because otherwise, it's going to be impossible to be a police
officer.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
