<SLUG> BC-NJ-AUTO-TESTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY RELEASES PAYMENTS TO CAR INSPECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey officials said Friday that the company hired to run
the state's new automobile inspection system had significantly
reduced the long waits, and would therefore receive $5.5 million
that had been withheld by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation officials said that waiting times at the 32
inspection stations run by the company had averaged 11 minutes this
month, down from 25 minutes in January. As a result, the state
released the money it had withheld from the company, Parsons
Infrastructure and Technology Group of Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   James Weinstein, the state transportation commissioner, and C.
Richard Kamin, director of the state Division of Motor Vehicles,
said that steps taken by Parsons included increasing its total
number of employees to 825 from 560 and doubling the hours of
training each employee receives, to 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of those areas, we are making significant progress,''
Weinstein said during the first of what is to be a series of
briefings on the inspection system.
</P>
<P>
   The steps were outlined by Parsons in a report ordered by Gov.
Christie Whitman last month, when she withheld nearly $11 million
from Parsons because of the system's problems. The $5.5 million
released Friday was part of that.
</P>
<P>
   But with 15 of the 32 testing stations still using an older,
less stringent emissions test as a temporary means of reducing
waiting times, Assemblyman Neil Cohen, D-Elizabeth, criticized the
release of the money as premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we pay them any more money?'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Sullivan, a spokesman for the Division of Motor Vehicles,
said the partial payment was a response to the progress Parsons had
made.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection system has been a recurring source of
embarrassment to Whitman's administration, which awarded a $463
million contract to Parsons, the lone bidder, in 1998. Three state
investigations related to the contract are pending.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the governor ordered that the 15 busiest stations
revert to the less stringent, faster emissions test. The move was
approved by the federal Environmental Protection Agency, which
enforces the clean-air standards that the new test is intended to
help meet. The newer, more stringent test is to be phased back in
by June 30.
</P>
<P>
   But the move to the faster test infuriated owners of 1,400
private service stations, who do inspections for a fee of up to
$75, and who each invested about $50,000 in new testing equipment.
The owners said that allowing drivers to take the less stringent
test at state inspection stations discouraged use of the private
service stations.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Gasoline Retailers Association, which represents
the service stations, has prepared a lawsuit that it planned to
filed Friday in U.S. District Court in Newark, charging the state
and the EPA with violating the federal Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   But William Dressler, the group's executive director, said he
had agreed to hold off on the lawsuit after Weinstein promised to
negotiate a compromise. Dressler said he was likely to meet with
state officials on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
