<SLUG> BC-BKN-NCAA-EAST-I-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLOWAY'S FULL-COURT ZIP LIFTS SETON HALL OVER OREGON, 72-71 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Give a team the basketball with almost nine
seconds remaining in overtime and there are a lot of offensive
options a coach can order up.
</P>
<P>
   He can direct his players to work it to a big man underneath. Or
a guard can shoot a jump shot from outside. There is time to pass
and screen and post up, too.
</P>
<P>
   Or a team can simply do what coach Tommy Amaker's Seton Hall
Pirates did Friday in their exhilarating victory over Oregon in the
first round of the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by one point, Shaheen Holloway took the inbounds pass
at one end of the court, dribbled through double coverage, shook
another Ducks defender as he raced down the floor and banked a
layup off the glass of the backboard, down through the hoop and out
the net to give the Pirates a 72-71 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way I was going to give the ball up,'' Holloway, a senior
guard finally playing in the NCAA tournament, said. ``Growing up as
a little kid, you watch the NCAA tournament and see people doing
stuff like this. And you say to yourself, `One day, I want to be a
part of that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ducks coach Ernie Kent said: ``He made a great spin dribble at
the top of the key and hit an off-balance runner. Not a lot you can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a memorable moment, ending a game that was occasionally
as ragged as it was exciting, the kind of climactic play in the
clutch that will be replayed on videotape for the rest of this
tournament and probably for years to come. And it elevated 21-9
Seton Hall, the 10th-seeded team in the East, to at least Game 2 of
what it hopes will be an extended adventure. The Pirates will play
Sunday against Temple, which defeated Lafayette by 73-47 Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Amaker and Holloway both said there were other options off Seton
Hall's winning play, but the coach added: ``We want the ball in his
hands. He always has the option to use his instincts to make a
play, to create on the fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes before, Holloway had lost the ball on a
play that gave Oregon the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt devastated,'' Holloway said, quickly adding that he got
over it right away because he knew he was going to get the ball
back and get another chance.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 27 points, the most of anyone in the game, and
was 3 for 3 from 3-point range. Rimas Kaukenas and Darius Lane each
scored 14. Two of Kaukenas' points came with 3.3 seconds remaining
in regulation when he tied the score at 64-64 on a driving layup to
send the game into overtime. Also contributing for Seton Hall was
Samuel Dalembert, the 7-foot-1-inch freshman center who began the
game with two blocked shots and finished the game with six of them
to go with 12 rebounds and six points.
</P>
<P>
   Kaukenas, like Holloway, has played four years at Seton Hall,
gradually helping to build a program that is making its first NCAA
tournament appearance since 1994. Kaukenas knows Holloway as well
as anyone and was asked if he expected the final play to conclude
as it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, probably,'' Kaukenas said, smiling. ``That's how I
expected it to end up. It was real exciting. I knew it would be a
happy ending.''
</P>
<P>
   But not for the Ducks, who finished their season with a 22-8
record after coming into the game seeded No. 7. A.D. Smith scored
17 points for Oregon and Alex Scales added 16. Oregon's players,
having traveled from the West Coast, began the game at what
amounted to 9:30 a.m. for them, although the Ducks had three days
to adjust after arriving. Seton Hall led by as many as 9 points in
the first half, but the margin dwindled to a point at intermission
and the Ducks led by two early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates came back to lead by 10 with less than seven minutes
remaining, but lost the lead when the Ducks went on a 13-2 surge in
a five-minute span to take a 60-59 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably got too excited,'' Kaukenas said. ``That's why we
wasted the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   With 12.7 seconds remaining in regulation, Bryan Bracey sank two
free throws to give Oregon a 64-62 lead before Kaukenas surprised
the Ducks by driving the lane to tie the score. In overtime, there
were seven lead changes. Frederick Jones sank two free throws to
give the Ducks a 71-70 lead _ their final lead _ with 8.7 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Holloway's clincher, leaving Oregon stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your stomach kind of sinks, just like on a roller coaster,''
the Ducks' Darius Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, there are no emotions,'' said Kent, the Ducks' coach.
``There is more of a calm. This was a terrific experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple, seeded No. 2 in the region, improved its record to 27-5
by taking a 38-20 lead at halftime and cruising. Quincy Wadley
scored 17 points, Mark Karcher had 15 and Kevin Lyde 12. Ronald
Rollerson had 10 rebounds in 15 minutes. Tyson Whitfield led
Lafayette (24-7) with 15 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
