<HEADLINE>
THURSDAY'S BIG GAINS MAY _ OR MAY NOT _ BODE WELL FOR INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add graf re bond figures.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If history is any guide, Thursday's powerful
499-point gain in the Dow Jones industrial average augurs good news
for investors for the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, past performance is no guarantee of future success,
as many a mutual fund advertisement has noted. But the statistics
are unambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   Before this week, the Dow, which gained 4.9 percent Thursday,
had rallied 4 percent or more 10 times since the current bull
market began in 1982. On eight of those occasions, stocks extended
their gains for at least three months after the big one-day move,
according to Richard McCabe, chief market strategist at Merrill
Lynch. And the gains were substantial. Even factoring in the two
times the Dow did not continue to rally, the index averaged a 7.5
percent gain over the three months after the end of its big day.
</P>
<P>
   Over a longer period, the positive results are even more
pronounced, according to a study by Birinyi Associates. Including
Thursday, Birinyi looked at the Dow's 25 best days since 1970, a
period that covers both bull and bear markets. The firm found they
presaged a gain of more than 14 percent over the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the last move is showing is that investors have not
abandoned stocks,'' said Robin Griffiths, the chief technical
analyst at HSBC Securities. ``This is greed rather than fear, and
as long as we have greed around, we have a bull market.''
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's big gains, the Dow pulled back slightly Friday,
falling 35.37 points, to 10,595.23, a 0.33 percent drop. The Nasdaq
composite index rose 80.74 points, or 1.71 percent, to 4,798.13,
while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 6 points, or
0.41 percent, to 1,464.47.
</P>
<P>
   Despite history's promise of further gains, Wall Street's
technical analysts said that this week's rally may be an exception
to the rule.
</P>
<P>
   These technicians earn their keep by trying to divine the future
moves of stocks from their price histories. To the large group of
investors and economists who believe that stocks are impossible to
predict that way, technicians are little more than psychics with
computers. But nearly every major Wall Street firm keeps at least a
couple of technical analysts on staff.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to price movements, technicians generally look for a
rally with heavy trading and breadth, meaning several stocks rise
for each stock that falls. Thursday's move seems to fit all three
categories. Almost 1.5 billion shares were traded on the New York
Stock Exchange, an all-time record, and seven stocks rose for every
two that dropped on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   Rallies like Thursday's ``have tended to mean that the market
will go up for a number of weeks and in many cases a number of
months,'' said Ricky Harrington, technical analyst for Wachovia
Securities in North Carolina. But Harrington said he remained
``very cautious about this market,'' in part because the Dow
remains below its average of the last 200 days, a trend technicians
view as bearish.
</P>
<P>
   McCabe is also uncertain that Thursday's gains will hold, though
for a different reason. He is worried that investors are overly
bullish. It may sound counterintuitive, but technical analysts say
that the strongest rallies begin when most investors have turned
very negative and selling pressure has reached a climax. Recent
surveys show that investors are very complacent, as opposed to
negative, about the market, McCabe said. He fears that stocks will
turn down again ``sometime in the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dickey, managing director for technical analysis at Dain
Rauscher, said he expected stocks to remain in a tight range over
the next several months and finish the year not far from their
current levels. Slipping a bit of fundamental analysis into his
explanation, Dickey said, ``We're in a period of rising interest
rates similar to 1994, and so I think this year will be similar to
1994,'' a year most stocks ended slightly down.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Don't fight the Fed'' is one of Wall Street's
hoariest maxims, and Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan has
repeatedly indicated his discomfort with the level of stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   But though the Fed has raised short-term interest rates four
times since June in an effort to slow the U.S. economy, corporate
profits continue to chug along. They are expected to rise 17.7
percent this year, following a rise of 18 percent last year,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial. Long-term interest rates
have also dropped substantially since hitting highs in January.
Lower interest rates are good for stocks, because they lessen the
cost of corporate borrowing while making bonds less attractive as
an investment alternative.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, the price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose
18/32 Friday, to 103 14/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from the price, fell to 6.00 percent from 6.04
percent on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
