<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS MAKE A STATEMENT WITH VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. -- Twenty-four hours after a streak-busting,
milestone-crushing loss, the Lakers' team psyche looked pretty darn
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Laughter on the bench? Check.
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Green playing with his green teddy bear in the fourth
quarter? Check.
</P>
<P>
   John Salley getting the nod to play garbage time in front of his
former home crowd? Check.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the final buzzer sounded Friday night, the only
concerned expression belonged to Shaquille O'Neal, searching for a
missing button on his polo shirt in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   What, they worry?
</P>
<P>
   Not now, after the Lakers crushed the Detroit Pistons 110-82 at
the Palace of Auburn Hills, erasing any sting of the loss at
Washington the night before. The 19-game streak is gone, but the
Lakers made it a point to come back strong, winning for the 20th
time in 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to let too many get away from you like it did
last night,'' said Glen Rice. ``We came out and we tried to make a
statement... `OK, we had a good streak going and in no way are we
going to have too much slippage after our loss.' We wanted to show
that, hey this team is ready. We've got a lot of character, we've
matured a great deal, and we wanted to come in and bounce back. And
we did.''
</P>
<P>
   They did so with ease, after laboring through two wins and a
loss to start the week.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal's 19 second-quarter points staked them to a
double-digit advantage by halftime, and the misfiring Pistons never
made it interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers found their grounding in the usual places -- stubborn
defense that held Detroit to 35.3 percent shooting and big
contributions from O'Neal (35 points, 11 rebounds), Glen Rice (19
points) and Kobe Bryant (25 points, eight rebounds, six assists).
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't entirely surprising -- the Lakers' win gave them an
18-1 record on the second night of back-to-back sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, I thought we carried the type of game that
we wanted, kept the pace of the game the way we wanted it, got the
ball into Shaquille and worked our offense the way we felt it was
necessary to work it,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``Detroit's a team
that plays in fits and spurts and we were able to keep their spurts
down to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were giving up (103.8) points a game for the last four
games, and this game, I told them, I don't expect them perhaps to
keep them under 100 points, but defense has to be our mainstay.
That's what we win on, and that's how we do it. And we got that
idea back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper kept Jerry Stackhouse in check early, and he finished
just 4 for 16 from the field for 18 points. Grant Hill, defended
alternately by Rice, Rick Fox and Kobe Bryant, was a nonfactor,
finishing with 12 points on 5-of-12 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to come in tonight, keep the game at our pace,
and not let their two superstars get off. We did that,'' O'Neal
said. ``(Defense) was a lot better. We had a disappointing loss
last night. We didn't want to make it two in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Bryant, who scored a season-low seven points at
Washington, but came back strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many games in the NBA, you can't just labor on one
game,'' he said. ``You just learn from it. I had a nice little
session with Tex (assistant coach Tex Winter) today. ... He was
just talking about the overall rhythm of the game. Usually when
things like that happen, it's nothing individual, it's the overall
rhythm that you have to kind of adjust to.''
</P>
<P>
   By late in the fourth, the game out of hand, the few thousand
fans left got something to cheer for when Jackson sent John
``Spider'' Salley, a member of two Pistons championships, into the
game. He got a warm reception, and six points on free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was going to play me tonight,'' Salley said. ``I
said I'm not losing in Detroit, that's not going to happen. ... I
did some good things here. I miss this place, but I love L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy-again Lakers? Check.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
