<HEADLINE>
TUREK'S SUCCESS IS NO SURPRISE TO KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Andy Murray is not surprised that St. Louis' Roman
Turek is the hottest goaltender in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Turek defeated the Kings 4-0 Friday night, his Czech
National team defeated Murray's Team Canada for the 1995 World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   But Turek, who set a franchise record with his 37th victory,
took a while to reach this status. Last year, he played for Dallas
but mostly watched as veteran Ed Belfour helped lead the Stars to
the Stanley Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even back then you could see how exceptional he is,'' Murray
said. ``Sometimes it's all about getting an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Turek, 30, is six years older than Kings goaltender Jamie Storr,
but both were rookies last season. Turek entered this season with
just 55 games of NHL experience. Friday night was his 59 games.
</P>
<P>
   Storr said he used to look in awe at opposing goaltenders at the
other end of the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do that anymore,'' Storr said. ``I used to watch
(Buffalo's Dominik) Hasek like that. I have enough to think about.
But you are looking at the Vezina Trophy winner there (as the
league's top goaltender). He is playing so well, but you can't get
caught up in that. You just have to do your job.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Backup goaltender:!off!With Stephane Fiset (right groin)
still at least a week from returning and Marcel Cousineau down
after an appendectomy, the Kings summoned Travis Scott from minor
league Lowell, Mass., to back up Storr.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, signed by the Kings as a free agent Feb. 18, was called
up ahead of Mike O'Neill, who hasn't played much at minor league
Long Beach because of Cousineau and Phoenix holdout Nikolai
Khabibulin.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who has not played in an NHL game, was 13-18-5 with a
3.01 for Lowell with two shutouts. He played last season with
Biloxi, Miss. in the East Coast Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Quick Whistles: Aki Berg, who missed Wednesday's game in Anaheim
with a concussion, skated Friday morning without discomfortand is
expected to play Sunday against Nashville. ... The Kings caught a
break in overtime Wednesday. Defenseman Garry Galley broke his
stick (begin ital)twice(end ital) during the Ducks overtime flurry
with a four-on-three advantage. When a defenseman breaks his stick,
a winger is expected to give up his. Galley, who shoots left, was
given a stick by Bryan Smolinski, who shoots right. The Ducks did
not score. ... Reminder: Sunday's game with the Nashville Predators
starts at 5 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
