<SLUG> BC-Heaster </SLUG>
 col. -KAN  
 A missing link in Greenspan's labor logic  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Alan Greenspan is truly concerned about surging productivity,
he should travel to Main Street USA and talk to large- and
small-business operators alike.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve chairman could start with the Kansas City
area, where executives and managers have been working small
miracles for several years.
</P>
<P>
   When the local labor market began to tighten in the mid-1990s,
the pervasive fear hereabouts was not only finding enough good
employees to keep businesses growing, but in some cases just
maintaining staffing levels adequate to keep the doors open.
</P>
<P>
   The labor situation, if anything, probably is worse now than any
of those worried managers dared imagine when they first felt the
crunch. Despite the apparent dearth of available workers, however,
Kansas City's economy is thriving. There have been no signs of mass
business closings due to inadequate labor supplies. Service at most
enterprises remains at acceptable levels even when the inexperience
of some employees is obvious. And complaints from managers coping
with the problem have been relatively muted.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, life goes on pretty much as usual despite what
is arguably the tightest local labor market since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   If Greenspan were to visit Kansas City, it is here he would see
firsthand the rewards of America's soaring productivity rates. It's
not just a high-tech phenomenon. Business operators at the most
basic level are managing smarter because they must be innovative
just to survive, much less prosper.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of the business-cycle wars recently wrote to take
issue with what he sees as the flaw in Greenspan's contention that
tight labor markets risk wage inflation that will metastasize
throughout the economy. In his view, a labor squeeze produces
``exactly the opposite effect,'' because as volume surges in the
absence of more hires, there's more output from the existing work
force. Meantime, a staff working harder doesn't necessarily
translate into a need to grant inordinate pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who has never met a payroll, except perhaps on Wall
Street, can't truly appreciate this aspect of Main Street
economics.
</P>
<P>
   As the valued contributor noted, smart business managers always
wait to see whether increased business activity is ``for real,''
and not transitory, before hiring more workers.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, he concluded, as business revenues increase, ``the
impact on productivity is very favorable. Even if (wage) rates
accelerate, unit labor costs remain under control because of
productivity gains.''
</P>
<P>
   If Greenspan thinks he can solve the inflation problem with a
soft-landing recession, he is making a big mistake. When a weaker
economy transforms business volume increases into decreases, the
manager is stuck with the additional employees. Layoffs eventually
will correct the problem, but productivity still falls.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation may or may not occur during this reversal of fortunes,
but it's more of a risk than when productivity is rising because
managers will be trying to raise prices to offset their work
force's decline in productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, if Greenspan's reasoning is sincere, his logic
is missing something, because a weak economy would pose as much
inflation risk as a healthy economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 0042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
