<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FINCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTI FINCH, 54, WHO SOLD LUXURY TAKEOUT FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)  (lb) 
 By MIMI SHERATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christi Finch, whose catering shop, Word of Mouth,
was among the first to produce luxury takeout food on the Upper
East Side of Manhattan, died on Tuesday. She was 54.
</P>
<P>
   Her death, at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center in Manhattan,
came after a prolonged gastrointestinal illness, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   Finch's down-home charm made even the newest customers feel
welcome when they shopped for delicacies like brandied pate and
spiced pumpkin mousse or homespun offerings like meatloaf and giant
chocolate chip cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Finch and her partner, Eileen Weinberg, opened the first Word of
Mouth in 1976, at a time when most takeout food was mundane. The
partners had met at Flower and Fifth Avenue Hospital, where they
both worked in administration. Discovering a shared love of food,
the two self-taught cooks baked cakes for doctors, some of whom
became their backers.
</P>
<P>
   Together Finch and Weinberg turned out their interpretations of
ethnic foods, with a strong emphasis on Mediterranean cuisines,
including Moroccan specialties, then rare in New York City. They
offered copious portions of dishes that were lusty, yet subtly
stylish, and their high prices rarely deterred the affluent
customers in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the shop moved to its present quarters in 1979,
Weinberg left to open a restaurant and her own takeout food shop,
Good and Plenty to Go, in the Theater District.
</P>
<P>
   Finch also opened Cafe Word of Mouth and began to work on a
cookbook. The restaurant and cafe are still open.
</P>
<P>
   Christi Kangas grew up in a food-oriented family in Cutler City,
Ore. Her father, George Kangas, was in the grocery business, and
her mother, Janice, tested recipes at home for a local flour mill.
Finch's lifelong appreciation of the freshest seasonal produce
began in the vegetable garden of her grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   As a young woman, Finch settled in New York, where she married
Thomas Finch in 1967; they were divorced a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her daughter, Pilar; her parents, of Lincoln
City, Ore.; and her sisters, Kathryn Amrani, Sheila Coventry and
Sharon Borgford, who all live in the Portland, Ore., area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
