<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BROOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKS TO STICK TO MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ When Garth Brooks was introduced as a
member of the Mets, he made it clear he would never trade his
career as a country singer for one in baseball. In the month since,
Brooks has managed to fit into his temporary surroundings while
never forgetting where he came from.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is a ballplayer until Sunday, when he leaves to begin
preparations for the Academy Awards on March 26. He has not acted
like a celebrity, and he could not have afforded to. ``If he had
come in, didn't do anything and expected to get respect, it
probably wouldn't have worked,'' Mets third baseman Robin Ventura
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the workday, Ventura can sign a few autographs on
his way to his car and disappear into anonymity. Brooks is always a
star. Ventura does not envy that, and said he thought Brooks had
``the worst end of the celebrity business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brooks believes the players have the greater burden. ``As
far as their talent, I've always understood that,'' Brooks said.
``As far as their kind of celebrity, would I want that? No, thank
you.''
</P>
<P>
   No player spent as much time with fans or accommodated reporters
more readily than Brooks did. But the seasonlong, day-to-day life
of a ballplayer is something he said he could not handle. There are
no reporters in Brooks' dressing room when he goes from town to
town on a concert tour. Fans do not know where he stays on the
road. He gives interviews when he has a specific reason to do so.
He performs for fans, and nobody boos. It is an insulated,
protected environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't want to be got to, no one can touch me,'' Brooks
said. ``If I want to blow up and I want to throw a chair through a
Coke machine, I can do it and nobody would ever know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one aspect of a ballplayer's life that Brooks does
envy. ``You look in the stands and all it is are kids, and if it
ain't kids, it's a 6-foot kid that wants to be a kid,'' Brooks
said. ``That's my favorite thing about this game. Anything else
they can have _ those darn buses, those darn planes and staying in
a hotel where everyone knows where you're at, I don't see how they
do it. And 160 games a year _ are you kidding me?''
</P>
<P>
   The main purpose of Brooks' venture has been to advance his
Touch 'Em All Foundation, a charity that benefits children's
causes. He has been successful in doing that: 68 players helped to
raise $2.1 million last year, but more than 100 players, including
13 Mets, participate now. The players pledge money for each hit,
home run or any other statistical measure, and their contributions
are matched by both a corporate and a celebrity sponsor. The goal
for this year, he said, is $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The other reason is that Brooks loves baseball. That is
reflected in his effort. ``He works harder than some guys on this
team do, and that's great,'' the reliever Turk Wendell said.
</P>
<P>
   But the baseball has not gone as well as the charity. Brooks,
who was 1 for 22 last spring for the San Diego Padres, is still
seeking his first hit this spring. He popped out twice against
Detroit Friday and now is 0 for 15 with four strikeouts. His best
chance for a hit came this week on an infield chopper he could not
beat out. Afterward, Wendell asked Brooks if he played the piano,
because it looked as if he was carrying one on his way down the
line. Brooks has earned the right to get such good-natured
clubhouse ribbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of guys have said, `You're here now, you're one
of us,''' Wendell said. By the end of the weekend, though, Brooks
will resume his life in the world he knows best. As much fun as
baseball is for him, that is the world he prefers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 0055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
