<SLUG> BC-LA-PRICES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL COSTS DRIVE UP PRICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ High fuel costs continue to impact the local
economy, helping to drive up the Los Angeles region's consumer
price index by 0.8 percent during February, the biggest monthly
gain since January 1992, the Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices soared 4.5 percent during the month and are 18.8
percent ahead of a year ago. The overall market basket of goods in
the index has increased nearly 3 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   Housing costs increased a robust 0.7 percent last month.
Household furnishings and operations costs increased 0.3 percent
for the month and are 1.7 percent above last year's level.
</P>
<P>
   Total housing costs are up 3.6 percent since February 1999, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation costs increased 1.5 percent in February. ``The
leading factor for the rise in transportation costs is gasoline,''
said Nancy A. Treadwell, a regional economist with the Department
of Labor Bureau of Labor Statistics in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Food and beverage prices last month moved up 0.2 percent and are
0.6 percent higher for the last 12 months. In February, the cost of
dining out rose 0.6 percent while prices paid for alcoholic
beverages fell 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a very tight and stimulated economy,'' said Michael
Darby, consultant economist with City National Bank and a professor
at the Anderson School at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   The only major expenditure category to show a decrease was the
education and communication index, which declined 0.3 percent last
month, but is up 1 percent since last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite no apparent inflation outside of energy, the Federal
Reserve Board is expected to raise short-term lending rates by a
quarter-point when it meets Tuesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``An interest rate increase next week won't help with the
housing shortage and with our gas supply situation,'' said Jack
Kyser, chief economist with the Los Angeles Economic Development
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Darby said Tuesday's expected increase by the Fed is ``only one
more in a series of increases.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest rates should continue to rise for the next three to
six months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the middle of last year, the federal funds rate, which is
the rate the Fed charges banks for loans, has been raised 1
percentage point to 5.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Consumer Price Index for Southern California,
which includes Los Angeles, Orange, Riverside, San Bernardino and
Ventura counties, now stands at 169.2 on the 1982-84 100 reference
base.
</P>
<P>
   Treadwell said the figure means a market basket of goods and
services costing $100 in 1982-84 would have cost $169.20 last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CPI is not a cost-of-living index,'' she said. ``If the
price of beef increases, we don't switch to chicken. We stay with
the same basket of goods and services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 0056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
