<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0775 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-INDIA-CLINTON-2NDLD-W     03-18 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CLINTON-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TRIP TO INDIA IS SEEN AS MAINLY SYMBOLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS 3rd graf with background)  
(See also INDIA-U.S.) 
(lb) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Like a family preparing for a sumptuous
wedding that will unite two great ancestral lines, India has been
dressing itself up for its first visit from a U.S. president in
over two decades _ a visit in which the world's largest democracy
and its most powerful one will again try to build an alliance that
has eluded them for a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   With President Clinton touching down here on Sunday evening,
workmen were out in force on Saturday. There were battalions of
malis _ or gardeners _ planting frowsy-headed yellow dahlias along
the route he will drive. Sweepers with spiky brooms were ridding
lawns of leaves and teams of men were pushing wheelbarrows of
steaming tar to spread in potholes.
</P>
<P>
   Indians believe that it is auspi- cious to paint their homes and
repair what is broken before the occasion of a marriage. And if the
relationship between India and the United States is to progress, a
great deal of good fortune will be required.
</P>
<P>
   But if the relationship between India and the United States is
to progress, it will require more of the genuine love that builds a
good marriage than the decoration and repair undertaken before a
wedding party.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton _ cast as an Indian bridegroom on the cover of a news
magazine here in a full-length golden jacket and curly-toed
slippers _ recently decided to make the trip despite the failure of
intensive U.S. efforts to persuade India to sign the nuclear test
ban treaty or to cap their nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   But with his tenure as president running out, Clinton's timing,
again, has not proved lucky, as relations between India and its
longtime rival and neighbor, Pakistan, have continued to
deteriorate sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to pay the briefest of visits to the United
States' old ally, Pakistan _ despite the explicit opposition of the
Indian prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, and his request that
the Americans instead put Pakistan on a list of terrorist states _
has tempered any euphoria here about the president's far longer,
five-day visit to India.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats, businessmen and policy analysts have been trying
to convince India, the subcontinent's economic power, that the
president's visit is fundamentally about building a broader, deeper
relationship _ one that will encompass cooperative efforts in
trade, science and technology, the environment and health, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   And the Indians, who do not like being treated as though their
country is no more important than far smaller Pakistan, seem
encouraged by a speech that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
gave last week, and its not-so-veiled criticisms of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   While declaring India's decision to conduct nuclear tests ``a
historic mistake,'' she also said that Pakistan should take steps
to ``address the effects of terror on Pakistan's neighbors, notably
India.'' The United States has asked Pakistan to ban a
Pakistan-based Islamic fundamentalist group that the Americans have
categorized as terrorist _ and whose members are waging a holy war
against India in the disputed territory of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians in India applauded the remarks meant for Pakistan in
which Albright also said the so-called Line of Control that divides
Kashmir into Indian- and Pakistani-held portions must be respected.
India holds Pakistan responsible for organizing an incursion into
Indian territory last summer that led to a vicious confrontation
between these two nuclear-armed nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian foreign minister, Jaswant Singh, referred with
satisfaction on Thursday to Albright's ``reaffirmation of the
validity of the Line of Control.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Wisner, who was the U.S. ambassador to India from 1994 to
1997, said Albright's speech was an indication of the United
States' willingness to talk turkey to the Pakistanis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having watched us be careful and nuanced over the years, that
was not careful and nuanced; that was blunt,'' he said. ``If this
speech does not make clear the explicit difference in the American
view of India and Pakistan, I don't know what else you need. A
four-and-a-half day visit to India and a four-and-a-half hour visit
to Pakistan?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The estrangement between India and the United States _ two
great, multicultural democracies that would seem to have so much in
common _ stretches back to the 1950s and the height of the Cold
War. India, the proud new nation finally freed of colonial
domination, chose the path of nonalignment, while Pakistan, its
smaller, insecure neighbor, sought to ally with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the Americans grew cozy with Pakistan's
military dictators, funneling billions of dollars in military aid
that sometimes wound up turned against India. By the early 1970s,
India had drawn closer to the Soviet Union. When the Soviets
invaded Afghanistan in 1979, India refused to condemn the
aggression, while Pakistan was a key player in U.S. support for the
Islamic mujahedeen battling the Soviet army.
</P>
<P>
   With the crumbling of the Soviet Union and India's decision in
1991 to begin loosening barriers to trade and investment, the
conditions that had kept socialist India and capitalist America
apart were profoundly changed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, old habits of mistrust die hard. India, craving
recognition as a global power, often finds what it sees as U.S.
arrogance hard to take. In the eyes of many Indians, the U.S.
opposition to the nuclear tests seemed the height of hypocrisy,
coming from a nation that still has thousands of nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The former Indian foreign secretary, J.N. Dixit, has described
the Indo-American relationship with the Hindi word ``panga,'' which
roughly translates as prickly, petulant, confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   K. Subrahmanyam, who recently headed a committee that looked
into army intelligence failures for the Indian government, offered
a perfect illustration of panga in his contentious reaction to
Clinton's tour of India.
</P>
<P>
   ``This visit is purely symbolic of the fact that two years after
the nuclear tests, India has done nothing to comply with the
stentorian demands of the nuclear hegemonists and still the U.S.
president is coming to visit,'' Subrahmanyam declared in his own
stentorian tones. ``In spite of all the rhetoric, the United States
accepts reality.''
</P>
<P>
   A stream of Americans from Washington institutions have come
through Delhi in recent weeks and many of them have been advising
the president to brave the thorny task of talking with the Indians
for the sake of the rose _ better relations with a country that is
the second-most populous in the world, with an economy growing at a
rate that has averaged over 6 percent since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Few expect any developments of earth-shaking importance from the
visit. India has already declared that the test ban treaty and its
relations with Pakistan are not open for negotiation. Still, given
the history, the symbolism of the visit itself may have content.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rituals of a wedding, the ceremonies of a state visit
could lay the foundations for a new understanding _ at least that
is what diplomats on both sides hope.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd I. Rudolph, an old India hand and a political scientist at
the University of Chicago, said that after over 20 years of neglect
_ the last visit of a U.S. president was that of Jimmy Carter in
1978 _ the Americans need to finally go and pay their respects.
``You sometimes have to have a cup of tea before people will trust
you,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
