<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SHUT OUT BY BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ziggy Palffy watched on TV from a table in the
Kings' trainers room and said that was real pain.
</P>
<P>
   So is the thought that without Palffy, who could be sidelined up
to a month with a sprained right shoulder, the final three weeks of
the regular season could have moments like Friday's 4-0 loss to the
St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was tough; you want to help,'' said Palffy, who raised
his arm to shoulder level after the game, but not without a great
deal of difficulty. ``I'm not sure how long I'll be out, but when
you are playing a team as tough the Blues you want to have everyone
helping out.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Kings were helpless against Blues' goaltender Roman
Turek, who handed them their first shutout since Feb. 28, 1999
against eventual Stanley Cup champion Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   This time it came against the Blues (45-17-9), who have the best
record in the NHL. Turek, who came in with a 1.98 goals against
average and came away with a franchise record 37th victory, turned
away 31 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Handzus had two goals and Pavel Demitra scored an empty
netter with two minutes left after Jamie Storr was pulled.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings (34-28-9) already were struggling on the power
play and without Palffy, who was injured Wednesday on a hit by
Anaheim's Vitaly Vishnevski, things only got worse. The Kings were
0 for 7 with the man advantage and now are 1 for 32 in their last
six games.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have a favorable schedule down the stretch and came in
leading the ninth-place Ducks by 10 points. But losses could impact
playoff seedings and the eighth spot is only four points away.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kings finish there, they would face St. Louis in the
first round. The Blues are 10-1-3 in their last 14 games against
the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now all we're thinking about is getting in, not who we
are going to play,'' Luc Robitaille said. ``Tonight, we missed a
lot of opportunities. You have to score on the power play to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the power play, the Kings looked shaky on the Blues'
first two goals, both in the second period. Storr let Handzus poke
the first one through his legs after a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jamie would tell you that was a bad goal,'' Kings
coach Andy Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Blues second goal, defenseman Jere Karalahti turned the
puck over in his own end. Jochen Hecht took a pass from Marty
Reasoner and beat Storr at the 7:39 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Handzus, who took over as the Blues first-line center in January
when Pierre Turgeon went down with an injury, made it 3-0 when he
parked in front and whacked in his own rebound.
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, newest King Nelson Emerson had a chance
toend the shutout, but Turek was on his game.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, who had an assist in Wednesday tie with the Ducks, had
four shots Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had toyed with the idea of moving him onto the first
line after Palffy went down, but the second unit has shown good
chemistry since Emerson was acquired with Kelly Buchberger last
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Blake replaced Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got hit I wasn't sure how bad it was,'' Palffy
said. ``I woke up today and I could move it better, but it was
still pretty sore.''
</P>
<P>
   So are the Kings, who face lowly Nashville on Sunday at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't available so I tried not to think about him,''
Murray said of Palffy. ``You have to got with what you have. We
will move on without him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
