<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SF-EXAMINER-SOLD-2NDL     03-18 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-EXAMINER-SOLD-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAN FRANCISCO EXAMINER IS SOLD BY HEARST TO A LOCAL NEWSPAPER
OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS circulation figure in 7th graf) 
 (js) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER and EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hearst Corp. sold the San Francisco Examiner Friday, the
newspaper that set William Randolph Hearst on his swashbuckling
publishing career, to the owner of a local newspaper. The new
owner, Ted Fang, vowed that the Examiner would be reincarnated as a
morning paper and would continue its two-fisted competition with
the San Francisco Chronicle, which Hearst bought in August.
</P>
<P>
   Against the odds, the deal keeps San Francisco in the thin ranks
of cities with two competing dailies.
</P>
<P>
   In a single, unexpected stroke, the deal also achieves the
disparate objectives of the haphazard group of politicians,
regulators and businessmen who were tossed into a debate by the
mixmaster of San Francisco politics.
</P>
<P>
   It catapults Fang, who is 37 and a member of a well-connected
family with a strong political base in San Francisco's Chinatown,
into prominence as one of a tiny group of Asian-Americans in top
daily newspaper jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It also represents a success for the city's mayor, Willie Brown,
who had made it his business to make it difficult for Hearst _
whose reporters had long dogged the city's contract dealings _ to
quietly close the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   And Hearst can now focus its money and energies on expanding the
reach and breadth of the San Francisco Chronicle, the city's
dominant daily. The deal also ensures that Hearst can make plans
without worrying about the existing joint operating agreement
between the Examiner and the Chronicle, which expires when the deal
is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle, the largest newspaper in Northern California,
faces tough competition to the south and east from The San Jose
Mercury-News and The Contra Costa County Times, both owned by
Knight Ridder. More than half the 457,000 copies of the Chronicle
circulated every day go to suburban areas peppered with the newly
minted millionaires of Silicon Valley's new economy.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Friday Fang said, ``San Francisco has
once again proved itself as the city that knows how _ the first
city in recent history that has saved a second newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I would say this is a unique ending for the most
unique city in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial terms of the deal were not immediately disclosed.
According to one Hearst executive, Fang's new company, ExIn LLC, is
buying the Examiner's name and circulation list, some delivery
trucks and news racks. It is also assuming some current Examiner
liabilities, according to a release issued by the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies, which committed to a four-month transition period
during which Hearst will continue to handle basic management
functions and advertising sales at the Examiner, also noted that
Hearst would make ``a significant financial commitment to the
continued publication of the Examiner.'' There was no further
elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   That subsidy, whose amount and duration was not disclosed,
appears to be the price that Hearst, the privately held New
York-based media company, was willing to pay to achieve its
objective _ publishing the dominant local newspaper in one of the
nation's wealthiest and best-educated markets _ without running
afoul of federal antitrust regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The sale was handled by the New York investment firm, Veronis &AMP;
Suhler.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One individual with knowledge of the deal said that no
traditional newspaper companies had been among the final three
bidders for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Fang _ whose current newspaper is the thrice-weekly, free San
Francisco Independent _ said that the deal did not include any
presses or real estate, which Hearst had recently offered along
with the Examiner's name and circulation list. The sweetened offer
to prospective buyers of the afternoon newspaper, whose circulation
of 107,129 is mostly based in the city, came as Hearst came under
close scrutiny by the Justice Department's antitrust lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   It also faced a private civil lawsuit, on similar antitrust
grounds, by Clinton Reilly, a former mayoral candidate who had his
ankle broken several years ago in a tussle with the Examiner's
executive editor, Phil Bronstein.
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein is one of a group of Chronicle and Examiner editors
from which Hearst executives will select the leadership of the
joined newsrooms. They include the Chronicle's executive editor,
Matt Wilson, a longtime editor with a scholarly mien; Jerry
Roberts, the Chronicle's managing editor, credited with increasing
the newspaper's aggressiveness and thoughtfulness in recent years;
and Sharon Rosenhause, a managing editor of the Examiner, who has
been a brusque champion of covering the city's mosaic of minorities
and its gay community.
</P>
<P>
   The newsrooms of the Chronicle and the Examiner, which share the
third floor of their building, are physically divided as if by a
gulf by a large composing room used by both newspapers and
psychically divided by their longstanding, fierce competition. They
came together for the first time in memory Friday as a prospective
team: Hearst had guaranteed jobs to all Examiner employees who
didn't want to work for Fang, and apparently, none did.
</P>
<P>
   Both staffs _ the Chronicle's newsroom numbers about 315, the
Examiner's about 200 _ gathered by the Examiner's city desk to hear
the terms of the sale. Reporters and editors at both papers then
spent the afternoon expressing relief that jobs were guaranteed but
were wistful at the impending death of the Examiner they knew.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists with the Examiner, which has a messier newsroom and
the reputation for quirkier, more enterprising stories, said they
were saddened that the newspaper's name and its logo _ an eagle _
would adorn an unknown, unproven new entity.
</P>
<P>
   Keay Davidson, a science writer at the Examiner for 14 years,
said: ``It was always a feisty, eccentric, off-beat newspaper. I
think that it's one of the few last outposts of idiosyncrasy in
American journalism and I doubt it will be that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   No staff members at the Examiner said they would be willing to
work for the new Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Bronstein, the executive editor of the Examiner dismissed rumors
that, as the ranking editor of the Hearst newspaper, he had the
inside track. ``I don't know what I'll be doing yet,'' he said.
``I'm glad that there's finally some resolution. People seem
pleased that they have the opportunity to work for the morning
newspaper. I think everyone is enthused about working for a great
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Chronicle, Ken Connor, an assistant city editor, said
that his staff hoped the Chronicle's management remained in place.
``We have people who we trust and respect,'' he said. ``I think the
feeling now is that people don't know what's going to happen.
There's going to be some overlap. We only need one television
writer, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty was intensified in recent months when a
collection of political odd bedfellows _ including the mayor and
Reilly _ the conservative, non-union newspaper of Fang and the
loudly radical alternative newsweekly, The Bay Guardian, all made
it clear that San Francisco wouldn't become a one-newspaper town
without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   That the fight should end with Fang's ownership of the Examiner
represented an exquisite, if belated, justice for the Chinese
populations reviled in the pages of the newspaper a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas C. Leonard, the associate dean of the Graduate School of
Journalism at the University of California at Berkeley, said
Friday: ``The exquisite piece of irony here is that both the
Chronicle and the Examiner got their start playing into the strong
anti-Asian period in California in the 1880s. I think that to find
more than a century later that the key to their business plans is
an enterprising Chinese family _ that's a real story about
America.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Chronicle and the Examiner had been business partners since
1965, when the joint operating agreement was established, combining
the advertising and circulation departments of the newspapers. At
the time, the Examiner, then a morning newspaper, agreed to publish
in the afternoon. On Sunday, the newspapers publish a joint edition
which sells 578,541 copies, according to the Sept. 30, 1999,
figures of the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   Fang, the son of a Chinese journalist who left the country after
the communist takeover, said Friday that he would not shut down The
Independent to publish the Examiner, and he would not pull punches
in either publication. ``My family and my newspapers have never
been one to shy away from taking positions on issues we feel are
important to San Francisco,'' he said. ``That policy will
continue,'' though the news operation would remain independent of
the paper's editorial pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Examiner will not be the Independent,'' he added.
``Rather, the Examiner will offer a new voice alongside that of the
Chronicle and the Independent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 0126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
