r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN     03-18 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE ROUTS INDIANA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. - Buffalo might be the last place you'd chose to
prove a national point. The only thing this city has in common with
a media mecca like New York City is the N.Y. that follows it's
name.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the precise location for Pepperdine's plea for
nation-wide respect was out of its control. The Waves were just
happy for a platform, no matter how remote an area it was situated.
</P>
<P>
   And so Pepperdine came here this week hoping to state its case.
Not just that it beloned in the NCAA Tournament, but that it could
compete with the nation's elite.
</P>
<P>
   And win.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves, in a shocking, emphatic way, did just that Friday
night, beating up on Indiana 77-57 in a first-round East Regional
victory at HSBC Arena. It is Pepperdine's first Tournament victory
since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (25-8), the 11th seed, moves into the second round
Sunday against third-seeded Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves are the lowest seed to advance in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't just a win, it was a statement. For Pepperdine,
which came here craving a spolight, and the West Coast Conference,
which is now 2-0 in the tournament after wins by the Waves and
Gonzaga, which beat Louisville Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great team effort offensively and defensively, an
exciting win'' Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolf said. ``But I've
been excited all year. Our goal was to get to Syracuse (the Sweet
16) and we have onemore game to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Tezale Archie agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gonzaga put (the WCC) on the map last year, (by
getting to the Elite Eight). They won (Thursday) and we wanted to
keep it up,'' Archie said. ``But we're just halfway to our goal. We
wanted to win two and get to Syracuse. We're half way there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves said all along they wouldn't be intimidated by
Indiana's history and higher seeding, and they weren't. From the
outset Pepperdine went right at the Hoosiers (20-9), opening an
18-8 lead on Tommie Prince's 3-pointer, then extending it to 28-11
on Nick Sheppard's short jumper with 8:43 left in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard, whose had an up and down year, got off to a fast
start, picking up nine points and a blocked shot in the first 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With Sheppard providing a presence inside, things opened up for
the Waves perimeter players.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Armstrong was especially effective, hitting four
3-pointers over the first 14 minutes. With the outside game
rolling, he went to work off the dribble, breaking down Indiana's
Michael Lewis on three drives to the basket, finishing with 18
points in the half, and 22 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively Pepperdine did exactly what it's done all year:
Create havoc with its fullcort pressure, force turnovers (eight in
the half, 21 forthe game) and take its opponent's top scorer out of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Guyton, Indiana's first-team All-American, didn't attempt a
field goal in the first 18 minutes and rarely touched the ball in
that time. Guyton, who came in averaging 20.3 points, was never a
factor, finishing with three points on three free throws. He
attempted just two shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves threw a varity of different looks and players at him,
but mostly just kept the ball out of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I went they had two guys waiting for me,'' Guyton
said. ``They just did a great job defending me.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead grew to 39-19 on a pair of free throws by Prince with
3:35 left.
</P>
<P>
   By then a tone had been established. Pepperdine was more
athletic, quicker to loose balls and rebounds (24-16 in the half,
40-34 in the game) and had more options offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got pounded,'' Indiana coach Bob Knight said. ``They
played really well. I was impressed when I (scouted them). I
thought they were very athletic and aggressive, and tonight they
came to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong led the way offensively, but Sheppard had 17 points,
Craig Lewis had nine and Prince and Kel vin Gibbs each had eight.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Hornsby had 15 for Inidiana and Jeffery Newton had 13, but
no other player had more then six. Kirk Haston, the Hoosier
second-leading scorer, left the game after two minutes with a leg
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The key all year for the Waves has been its defense, the
catalyst to big runs and an actidote for cold spells. Pepperdine
went scoreless over the first six minutes of the second half, but
during that same stetch Indiana managed just five points. The
result: Pepperdine's lead shrunk a bit, but with 14:14 left the
Waves were still out in front by 15 points, and after Sheppard's
jumper it was back up to 17, 49-32.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept the pressure up,'' Prince said. ``Even though we
weren't getting points we kept pressuring them, hounding them on
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The cushion allowed Pepperdine to absorb another run by Indiana,
this one bringing the Hoosiers to within 49-38 on Hornsby's
3-pointer with 11:15 left.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine quickly took back control, getting a driving layup
from Armstrong, 3-pointers from Kelvin Gibbs and Craig Lewis and a
hook shot from Sheppard. All of a sudden the lead was 59-38.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got back to 11 and we needed to keep it going right there,
but they took it right back away from us,'' Knight said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
