u i BC-LEBANON-TERRORISTS-1S     03-18 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-TERRORISTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANON GIVES ASYLUM TO JAPANESE RED ARMY MEMBER, SENDS 4 OTHERS TO
JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS 3rd graf with report that deportees were being taken to
Japan.) 
(bl)  
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Lebanon granted political asylum Friday to
Kozo Okamoto, a 52-year-old Japanese who carried out a massacre of
26 people at an airport in Israel in 1972. Simultaneously, the
Beirut government ordered the deportation to Jordan of four other
members of the Japanese Red Army, an organization that was among
the world's most feared terrorist groups from the early 1970s to
the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The four deportees were immediately placed on an aircraft to
Amman, the Jordanian capital, where the government said without
further explanation that it had agreed to accept a Lebanese request
for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, Agence France- Presse reported that Jordan had
de- nied the four entry, and they were instead being taken to
Tokyo, where they were expected to arrive Satur- day afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate confirmation of the whereabouts of
Okamoto, who like the other Japanese had been held in Lebanese
prisons since being arrested in 1997 on charges of being in Lebanon
illegally, forging documents and using false passports.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings on the five Japanese were handed down immediately
after a meeting of an official asylum committee headed by Lebanon's
interior minister, Michel Murr, and followed months of pressure on
Lebanon from Japan. Led by its prime minister, Keizo Obuchi, who
sent a personal emissary to Beirut late last year, Japan had sought
Lebanon's agreement to extradite the five Red Army members to Japan
for trial on charges of terrorism and offenses against the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese committee said it had decided to grant Okamoto's
request for political asylum ``because of the suffering he endured
in Israeli prisons,'' where he served 13 years of a life term for
the attack at the airport near Lod, outside Tel Aviv, on May 30,
1972. This appeared to be a reference to Okamoto's claims that he
was tortured during his time in Israeli prisons, which ended in
1985 when Israel released him as part of a prisoner exchange with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The airport attack was considered one of the most brutal
terrorist attacks of its time. Okamoto and two other Red Army
members used machine-guns and grenades to attack passengers who had
arrived on an Air France flight from Rome. The dead included 16
Puerto Rican Roman Catholic pilgrims on a visit to the Holy Land as
well as eight Israelis. Another 74 people were injured. Israeli
police shot dead Okamoto's two Japanese accomplices.
</P>
<P>
   The four Japanese who were flown to Amman on Friday were Kazuo
Tohira, 47; Haruo Wako, 51; Masao Adachi, 59; and the only woman in
the group, Mariko Yamamoto, 59. Of the four, the one most wanted by
Japan was Wako, who was identified in the past by Japanese
anti-terrorist officials as the director of military operations for
the Red Army. All four were wanted by Japan for their links to a
series of aircraft hijackings, bombings and embassy takeovers that
occurred across Asia, the Middle East and Western Europe, mostly
during the group's heyday in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   While Lebanon presented its rulings on the five as a
humanitarian issue, domestic politics appeared to have been the
overriding concern. Okamoto, in particular, had been hailed as a
hero in Lebanon for the airport attack, which was viewed by leftist
and anti-Israeli groups not as an attack on innocent passengers but
as a strike for Arab rights. This was also the view pressed by
Okamoto, who wrote letters from prison in which said he had earned
the right, with the airport killings, to be considered ``a citizen
of all Arab countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats in Beirut said Lebanon's decision not to extradite the
five to Japan also appeared to have been influenced by increased
tensions in recent weeks between Lebanon and Israel. Prime Minister
Ehud Barak's announcement that Israel will withdraw by early July
from an occupation zone it has held in southern Lebanon since 1978
has led to an intensification of the warfare between Israeli forces
and Hezbollah, the Party of God, which has presented the Israeli
withdrawal as a triumph for its Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With Hezbollah riding high in public opinion in Lebanon, the
Lebanese government, diplomats said, appeared not to have wanted to
incur popular displeasure by turning the five Japanese over to
Japan. Okamoto is particularly revered by Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Official Lebanese sensitivities may also have been heightened by
the decisions two weeks ago of Okamoto, Tohira and Yamamoto to
become Muslims and take Muslim first names. Adachi converted to
Christianity at the same time and married a Lebanese Christian
woman.
</P>
<P>
   The religious conversions all occurred days before the end of
the three-year prison terms imposed on the five Japanese for living
illegally in Lebanon expired on March 7, and were viewed in Lebanon
as a tactic to enhance the group's prospects of obtaining political
asylum in Lebanon, where the Arab population is divided roughly
equally between Muslims and Christians. The court that imposed the
prison terms after the five were discovered living in Lebanon's
Bekaa Valley in 1997 recommended that they all be deported after
serving the sentences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
