<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0800 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     03-18 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS TODAY, POINT GUARDS WILL BE FRIENDS TOMORROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Ask Matt Santangelo about the games he and Erick
Barkley played to kill time during the World University Games last
summer and he gives you the real lowdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a lot of blackjack,'' said Santangelo, the point
guard for Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``And dice. The whole nine yards. We were in Spain and we didn't
speak the language, so there was time for a lot of guys to lose
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Santangelo and Barkley hooked up again, embracing in
between practice sessions for Saturday's game between second-seeded
St. John's and No. 10 Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, the St. John's point guard, said he and Santangelo
became close during their USA Basketball romp to the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt's a good guy. He's quiet and honest with you, and that's
how you can come to trust someone,'' Barkley said. ``You don't talk
basketball but just talk about stuff going on in my neighborhood,
what's going on in his neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   As for how wild the card games were, Barkley said the favorites
were Pitty Pat and Spades. But when someone mentioned to Barkley
that Santangelo had squealed about the blackjack and dice, Barkley
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his story. But, yeah, anything goes,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of fun. We didn't get a lot of sleep. We'd break
daylight and still go out and win by 50 points the next night. It
was like we'd step out on the court and our friendships helped kick
it to another level.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown between the Bulldogs and Red Storm promises to be
wild. And at the center of it will be Barkley and Santangelo, two
of the best in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got sent to the West and I saw St. John's was in the
bracket and we could be playing him in the second round, I got
really excited,'' Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not just because I know him but because he's one of the best
in America. There's no question about that. I'm excited as a point
guard and as a competitor to play against him.''
</P>
<P>
   The good game Santangelo and Barkley promise to deliver comes in
part from the respect they have for one another.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, take away the allegations and the accusations and the
uneasy underside of big-time college basketball, and here is what
you find:
</P>
<P>
   One player from a small school in Eastern Washington vigorously
defending a fellow point guard from New York whose life under the
NCAA microscope has grown uncomfortably hot.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo has empathy for Barkley and what he has been going
through this season.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo, who said his own recruitment by several big-time
basketball schools was all ``on the straight and narrow,'' knows
that Barkley has been the focus of ongoing NCAA investigations into
his cars, high school tuition money and, finally, the credibility
of his SAT scores.
</P>
<P>
   As Barkley served suspensions and continued to be investigated,
right up until the day St. John's left for the tournament,
Santangelo followed his plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about him because I knew him, but because I
understand what it's like to be a student athlete under the
regulations of the NCAA. So definitely, I was sympathetic with the
situation,'' Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   And what situation is Santangelo referring to? His
characterization of what scholarship athletes face gives pretty
good insight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live by different rules. We live by different rules and
laws than other people live by, for whatever reasons. I don't want
to badmouth the NCAA, but we are under a bit of spotlight and we do
have to be careful about what we do and who we associate with.''
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing about the NCAA tournament is that it is the
showcase forum for basketball _ nirvana for the game's legion of
fans.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, there is growing agitation from all
corners that something should be done to fix the loopholes and make
the system better for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo and Barkley have things to say about how it should be
better for the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an intelligent, educated person, I can look at my checkbook
and see zero, zero, zero and know there's a lot of money being made
and paid somewhere, so how come some of it can't come my way?''
Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financially, it's tough. Someone's making a lot of money but
we're eating Top Ramen.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, meanwhile, is not bitter, nor is he cynical about his
ordeal, although he said he would not mind an apology from the
NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had the opportunity to talk to younger guys (about how to
avoid NCAA investigations), I would tell them don't trust anybody
you're not familiar with. People will come up to you and then later
you'll get blamed for nothing. I wish (someone had told me that). I
probably wouldn't be in this situation,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Barkley is exactly the sort of good-ratings-producing
competitor to whom the NCAA, CBS and the entire college basketball
machine should pay homage _ or maybe just pay.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after listening to his mother, who told him he would
be disappointing her, himself, his team and ``all the people who
bought tickets to watch me play,'' Barkley decided against leaving
St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is concerned about one thing _ winning _ and how much
``I just want to give the viewers a good game to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Barkley is not alone. Everybody wants he and
Santangelo and the Zags and Red Storm to burn the barn Saturday in
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   That is why college basketball can be so compelling. It is why
it is so lucrative, such good TV programming, why it showers
millions of dollars on the key operatives _ except the ones on the
court, playing the game.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
