<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST REGIONAL BOASTS COLORFUL PERSONALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ When CBS shows the West Regional games in
Huntsman Center Saturday afternoon, this is what you'll see: A
tight battle between Texas and LSU, and Wisconsin shocking Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, with its formidable threesome of Chris Mihm, Gabe Muoneke
and Chris Owens, will have a frontcourt standoff with LSU's Jabari
Smith and Stromile Swift. The guards will decide this one.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin, with its precise methodical style and depth, will
outlast the more talented but youthful Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   The announcers can be more specific with their analysis of the
matchups and tendencies. But as much as the NCAA tournament is
about players and teams, it is also about the stories behind the
dribblers and the shooters and the men who direct them. People such
as:
</P>
<P>
   -- Rick Barnes, the Texas coach who as a youngster once rode his
bike naked through his hometown of Hickory, N.C., on a dare to earn
$20 from his brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has graduated to being a prankster whose practical jokes
include stealing his buddy's '59 Corvette and squirting toothpaste
on the earpiece of an assistant coach's phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to have fun,'' Barnes said. ``Sometimes my wife asks
me: `Aren't you ever going to grow up?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes had a lot to deal with as a teenager. After his
18-year-old sister died in an auto accident, Barnes admitted that
he ``went off the deep end. I rebelled. I wouldn't go to school.''
</P>
<P>
   That led to one report card featuring straight F's. Coaches and
teachers helped the 14-year-old get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   -- Torris Bright, the LSU freshman guard who carries a Wilson
basketball everywhere he goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women feel uncomfortable without their purse, I feel
uncomfortable without my ball,'' said Bright, who takes it to class
and even sleeps with it.
</P>
<P>
   Most kids his age name Michael Jordan, Vince Carter or Allen
Iverson as their favorite players. Bright, whose nickname is Chaos,
prefers Utah's Jeff Hornacek.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mihm and Muoneke, the Texas stars whose statistics are
impressive enough. But how about these: Mihm wears size 18 Nike
Composites and Muoneke's hands measure 14{ inches when spread out,
from the tip of his little finger to the tip of his thumb.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gilbert Arenas, Arizona's freshman guard who just turned 18
in January and was wonderfully clueless Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Mike Kelley, the Wisconsin defender who stifled
Fresno State's Courtney Alexander on Thursday night, Arenas said:
``I don't know who he is. I'm not really worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Kelley: ``I certainly know who he is. He's gifted.
He's a player I don't expect to shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Lute Olson. OK, you're familiar with him. But did you hear
what the Arizona coach said about his fellow Pac-10 coaches the
other day?
</P>
<P>
   He was miffed that his point guard, Jason Gardner, did not win
or share the Pac-10 freshman of the year award that went to
Stanford's Casey Jacobsen and UCLA's Jason Kapono. Coaches vote on
the awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my coaching fraternity is extremely intelligent,''
Olson said. ``But for awhile, I wondered about their intelligence.
I will never figure that one out, frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   -- John Brady, the LSU coach who should give hope to Washington
State fans. Working under NCAA restrictions that have reduced
scholarships he can offer, Brady has nonetheless taken the Tigers
from worst to first in the SEC in one season.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's best player, Swift, was wrestled away from Arizona,
Georgetown, Michigan and UCLA. Brady used a little coercive
creativity, telling Swift's mother that if her son came to LSU, the
coach would move a home game from Baton Rouge to Shreveport,
Swift's hometown. That was the clincher.
</P>
<P>
   A recruiting tip for Cougars coach Paul Graham, and Washington's
Bob Bender for that matter: The next time a Luke Ridnour is
waffling, tell him you'll play a home game in Blaine, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jabari Smith, LSU's starting center who, at 6-foot-11 and 250
pounds, is the biggest Jabari this side of the Huskies' Issa.
</P>
<P>
   More accustomed to performing at swamp level, the Tigers
complained about the altitude here affecting them in their
first-round escape from Southeast Missouri State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Brady busted us for making it an excuse,'' Smith said.
``They breathe the same air we breathe. We've just got to suck it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to fortitude, not oxygen, we presume.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 0153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
