<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0809 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HAWKS-CELTICS-BOS     03-18 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWKS-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS BEAT HAWKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ These are tough times for Ted Turner. How else to
characterize a guy who left Jane Fonda but kept John Rocker? Friday
night, his disappointing Atlanta Hawks finally lanced a season-long
boil named Isaiah Rider _ better late than never _ and then were
summarily trounced, 114-90, by a spirited Celtics team on a mission
to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics easily turned in their best road performance since
their season-opening win at Toronto, especially given the
circumstances. They shot the ball well (50 percent) and moved it
beautifully (28 assists). They rebounded (beating the Hawks, 45-35)
and defended, producing 21 turnovers leading to 25 points. It
resulted in a wire-to-wire beauty against the joyless,
passion-less, playing-out-the-string Hawks, who waived a tardy
(again) and unrepentant Rider after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was intensity at its best,'' Rick Pitino said of the
Celtics' solid effort. ``We realize what's at stake. We got on the
floor and fought for every loose basketball. We were very hungry
for a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Walker led the way with 30 points, torching Atlanta from
near and far in another in a string of strong perfomances. He
knocked down four treys, shot 12 of 18 from the field, added 6
rebounds, 6 assists ,and 2 steals in a 31-minute virtuoso. Five
others, led by Paul Pierce with 16, were in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, coupled with Orlando's loss to Toronto, moved the
Celtics to within 1 1/2 games of the ninth-place Magic and two
games of the eighth-place Milwaukee Bucks. The Celtics have won six
of their last seven games, but Friday night represented a season
rarity: a road kill. It was only Boston's seventh road win in 32
road games and its first since Feb. 24 in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics were dominant in a dormant Philips Arena, a typical,
Turner-esque monument to excess. (Read: lots of luxury boxes.) The
announced crowd of 11,621 represented the smallest to see the
Celtics this season. It was understandably quiet most of the night,
with the one exception being when Jim Jackson missed an uncontested
dunk, then was blocked by Tony Battie on the putback.
</P>
<P>
   That came in the third quarter. By then, the Celtics were in
total control and the Hawks were in full retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys were ready to lie down after the half and we
smelled blood,'' said Danny Fortson, who was his usual, active self
(11 points, 9 rebounds, and 4 fouls in 24 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Boston led by 8 after one, 11 at the half, and 16 after three.
The Hawks, who now have gone two straight games against the Celtics
without seeing so much as a single lead, got no closer than 14 the
rest of the way. They made a little run in the second quarter,
twice pulling to within 3. But the Celtics recovered and Atlanta,
with no real scoring threat other than Jackson (26 points),
collapsed. No wonder Turner consigliore Stan Kasten opted for a
trip to Venezuela with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said the team came out pressing to create an up-tempo
pace, which was how the game was played. He didn't want to see a
slowdown game with Atlanta's defenders and shot-blockers
dominating. Instead, the Celtics made the Hawks run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tempo was the theme of the night,'' the coach said. ``We
wanted to play at a high tempo, because they're going to play at a
low tempo. And with their defense, size, and shot-blocking, if you
play at a low tempo, they have a good chance of beating you at
home. If you play at a high tempo, you have a good chance of
beating them.''
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't hurt to play the way the Celtics played Friday
night. The big question, of course, is whether they can carry it
over Saturday night in Dallas against a Mavericks team playing
excellent basketball. That has been their season-long story _ one
step forward, two steps back _ but Pitino thinks they might be
ready to start moving forward, permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good basketball,'' he said. ``We're getting
better. I think the guys are improving their man-to-man defense.
They pressed very intelligently. They're playing very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
