   CIA-PROPAGANDA (Undated) _ _ Watch the 1955 animated version of
``Animal Farm,'' and you'll notice the ending is different than in
the book. Another example of Hollywood butchering great literature?
Yes, but in this case the film's secret producer was the Central
Intelligence Agency. The CIA, it seems, was worried that the public
might be too influenced by Orwell's pox-on-both-their-houses
critique of Capitalism and Communism. So after George Orwell's
death in 1950, agents were dispatched to buy the film rights to
``Animal Farm'' from his widow in order to make its message more
overtly anti-Communist. Rewriting the end of Animal Farm is just
one example of the often absurd lengths to which the CIA went
between 1947 and 1967 that are recounted in a new book. By Laurence
