<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0814 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a BC-FLAG-FLAP-2Takes-LADN     03-18 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-FLAP-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERANS GROUPS AGAINST FLAG SWAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Veterans groups said they oppose a Los Angeles
County veterans commission's request to replace the POW/MIA flag at
the Civic Center Mall with a version of the Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, supervisors voted to remove the Confederate Stars
and Bars flag, but the commission now wants it returned, which
would require the removal of the POW/MIA flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would consider it totally out of synch with the current
mentality of most veterans to put up the Confederate flag and take
down the POW/MIA flag,'' said Ann Mills Griffith, executive
director of National League of POW/MIA Families, which designed the
POW/MIA flag in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason for our POW/MIA flag to come in conflict
with any historic American flag,'' she said Friday. ``The last
thing we would want is for it to be divisive in any way. The
Confederate flag has little to do with the POW/MIA flag, while
recognizing that any flag representing the Confederacy can be
offensive to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission members said the Stars and Bars flag which is
different than the more commonly known Confederate flag
</P>
<P>
   should be hung in chronological order with 18 other historical
flags. They range from the 1774 Taunton flag to the 1960 Official
Flag of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   They contend the Prisoner of War/Missing in Action flag is out
of place in the display at the Court of Historic American Flags
downtown. And another one already flies across the street in front
of the county's Kenneth Hahn Hall of Administration, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The POW/MIA flag flies in its own special place of honor,''
said Sonny Sardo, a Shadow Hills resident and chairman of the
10-member veterans commission.
</P>
<P>
   The POW/MIA flag now in front of the county hall was put there
first in 1987 during a special ceremony, said Sardo, a Vietnam War
veteran who lost his leg to a land mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly it's a very sacred flag, and I respect it
10,000percent. But having the second POW/MIA flag across the way is
just doubling our efforts,'' Sardo said.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans groups disagree.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Carl Jensen, state council president of Vietnam Veterans of
America, said he could not imagine ``with all the pain and
suffering some of the Vietnam War generation has gone through''
that veterans would touch the POW/MIA flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have positive karma associated with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Al Biernesser, the Southern California legislative coordinator
for Vietnam Veterans of America, said some ``people feel a need to
be historically correct on a lot of things,'' but the Confederate
flag has generated divisive controversy in South Carolina where it
flies over the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we want to encourage some kind of wrath here?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Strifler, a 69-year-old Valencia resident and retired Marine
sergeant, said he couldn't believe the veterans commission wanted
to replace the POW/MIA flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be kidding me,'' said Strifler, a member of the
CHOSIN FEW, an organization of Marines who fought in the epic
Korean War battle at Chosin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the flag deserves to be shown, but whether to replace
it with a POW/MIA flag? I'm big on POWs.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, none of the supervisors has agreed to put the veterans
commission's request to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors Zev Yaroslavsky, Michael D. Antonovich and Don Knabe
have declined to comment. Supervisor Gloria Molina said she is
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite Burke, the board's only
African-American, compared the Stars and Bars flag to the Nazi
flag.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Towery, a Canyon Country resident and state division
commander of the Sons of Confederate Veterans, said the
10,000-member international organization and the Sons of the
Revolution want the flag returned because thousands of Americans
see it as a part of their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its sole purpose is to identify troops in the field. If we get
rid of this flag, what's next?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The POW/MIA flag was designed in 1971 by the wife of a Vietnam
War solder missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   On National POW/MIA Recognition Day in 1988, the flag was raised
over the White House. In 1990, Congress passed a law recognizing
the POW/MIA flag as a symbol of the nation's concern to resolve the
fates of Americans still prisoners, missing and unaccounted for in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flown for two reasons,'' Griffith said. ``One is to
remember those who have served our country, both those who returned
and sacrificed their lives. And most importantly, as a unifying
symbol of the American people to get the fullest accounting for
those who have not returned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
