<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0839 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     03-18 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS STAY IN THE HUNT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Mighty Ducks' playoff pulse had been getting
fainter and fainter in recent weeks, but Anaheim's postseason hopes
got a much needed shot of adrenaline Friday night with 4-2 a
victory over San Jose before 16,573 at The Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Technically it might not have been a must-win, but realistically
the Ducks' season was on the line against the Sharks and they
responded to pull within four points of San Jose with 10 games left
to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have been getting plenty of effort, but not nearly
enough points, especially during the four-game winless streak they
snapped on Friday. Outshooting and outchancing opponents was little
consolation.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Sharks the Ducks played role reversal, especially
early in the game when San Jose dictated the pace of play and had
outshot them 10-3 in the first 9 1/2 minutes of play. On Anaheim's
fourth shot of the game Teemu Selanne gave the Ducks a lead they
would never give up.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose continued to build its shot advantage early in the
second period (20-12), but it was Anaheim that built on its lead
with a goal by Fredrik Olausson at 4:29.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defenseman Vitaly Vishnevski got the play started when he
outfought Todd Harvey behind the Ducks net. Kip Miller got the puck
to Ladislav Kohn, who eventually fed Olausson a perfect centering
pass that the defenseman chipped past Steve Shields for his 12th
goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That play seemed to get the Ducks' motor running and they pretty
much dominated the rest of the period. Good pressure by the No. 1
line drew a penalty and then Anaheim's second power play unit
converted it just 12 seconds later 13:32.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's cross-ice pass found Oleg Tverdovsky and the slick
defenseman did the rest. His fake shot sent one San Jose defenseman
sprawling to the ice and pulled Shields out of position. He then
took his time and slipped a shot from the left circle past
defenseman Mike Rathje's vain attempt to play goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky's 14th goal extended his goal-scoring streak to three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Of course any recent Ducks game wouldn't be complete without its
nail-biting moments, and Friday night its was the first five
minutes of the third period and final five minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Shields had made great saves on Kariya and Kohn to keep the
Sharks within shouting distance of the Ducks before giving way to
Evgeni Nabokov to start the third.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey scored at 1:10 as San Jose peppered Guy Hebert with 12
shots in the opening five minutes of play. The Ducks needed nearly
five minutes just to get one shot on net.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim appeared to have gotten things under control, especially
when Bryan Marchment was assessed a five-minute major for spearing
Kariya. But Anaheim was unable to generate any pressure and they
gave up shorthanded goal to Jeff Friesen at 14:45 while Owen Nolan
was in the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   After a long stretch of San Jose domination in the first period
Selanne raced down the left wing and tried to center the puck, but
fortunately for him and the Ducks it bounced off a San Jose
defenseman back to the Anaheim winger. Selanne then skated around
the net and lifted a backhander over Shields' shoulder at 9:46.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's 27th goal of the season was just his second in 10
games, but the Sharks were in town so it was hardly surprising. In
38 games against the Sharks, Selanne has 34 goals and 68 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 0222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
