<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0842 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-L     03-18 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS STAY IN THE HUNT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Mighty Ducks' playoff pulse had been getting
fainter and fainter in recent weeks, but Anaheim's postseason hopes
got a much needed shot of adrenaline Friday night with 4-2 a
victory over San Jose before 16,573 at The Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Then after the game Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg's blood boiled
over after watching replays with general manager Pierre Gauthier of
Bryan Marchment's third-period spear on Paul Kariya and Owen Nolan
pulling the feet out from under Pavel Trnka in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understand why the league sent only one offical (Don
Van Massenhoven) to this game, it's terrible,'' he said. ``Nolan
slew foots Trnka and he is out (with a sprained ankle) -- we had a
guy (Ruslan Salei) suspended five games for that last year. And the
spear on Kariya is a dirty vicious play. You can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks normally don't send tapes to the league office, but
Hartsburg said that is about to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept our mouth shut, we've paid the price,'' he said. ``We
will send the tapes in and let the league decide.''
</P>
<P>
   The anger over the two questionable hits, almost overshadowed a
game that Teemu Selanne described as a ``Hitchcock thriller.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically it might not have been a must-win, but realistically
the Ducks' season was on the line against the Sharks and thanks to
some brilliant play by Guy Hebert pulled within four points of
eighth-place San Jose with 10 games left to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the biggest reason we won,'' said Hartsburg of his
goalie, who stopped 37 of 38 shots. ``I thought we played well in
the second period, but in the first and third he was just
outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of goals by Selanne, Fredrik Olausson and Oleg
Tverdovsky the Ducks took a 3-0 lead into the third period. But
Todd Harvey pulled the Sharks within 3-1 at 1:10 as San Jose
peppered Hebert with 12 shots in the first five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking after the second to just keep doing what we
were doing,'' said Selanne, who also added a empty-net goal with
one second remaining. ``It was great talk ... blah, blah, blah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know when we are going to learn ... but whatever it
takes. It's two points and that is all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have been getting plenty of effort, but not nearly
enough points, especially during the four-game winless streak they
snapped on Friday. Outshooting and outchancing opponents was little
consolation.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Sharks the Ducks reversed roles. They were outshot
38-27, but managed to win thanks to Hebert and some surprisingly
effective penalty killing by the league's worst penalty killing
unit. San Jose was 0-for-4 on the power play and generated little
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' power play wasn't much better (1-for-6), but they did
get a power play goal from Tverdovsky to offset the shorthanded
goal that Jeff Friesen scored at 14:45 to pull the Sharks within
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose dictated the pace of play and had outshot them 10-3 in
the first 9 1/2 minutes of play, but on Anaheim's fourth shot of
the game Selanne gave the Ducks a lead they would never give up.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose continued to build its shot advantage early in the
second period (20-12), but it was Anaheim that built on its lead
when Olausson converted a two-on-one pass from Ladislav Kohn at
4:29.
</P>
<P>
   Good pressure by the No. 1 line drew a penalty and then
Anaheim's second power play unit converted it just 12 seconds later
at 13:32.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's cross-ice pass found Tverdosvky and the slick
defenseman did the rest. His fake shot sent one San Jose defenseman
sprawling to the ice and pulled goalie Steve Shields out of
position. He then took his time and slipped a shot from the left
circle past defenseman Mike Rathje's vain attempt to protect the
Sharks' net.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's two goals were his second and third in 10 games, but
the Sharks were in town so it was hardly surprising. In 38 games
against the Sharks, Selanne has 35 goals and 69 points. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
