<HEADER>
A0860 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKE     03-18 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let the Mud Wrestling Begin
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for your e-mail,'' Gov. George W. Bush wrote to Vice
President Al Gore. ``This Internet of yours is a wonderful
invention.''
</P>
<P>
   When the governor and the vice president exchanged sarcastic
electronic messages last week, it was as if the formalities of the
forthcoming nominating conventions had been written out of the
campaign script, and both Bush and Gore had flipped immediately to
the chapter marked ``General Election: Fall.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates each collected enough delegates Tuesday _ when
voters in several Southern states cast ballots in contests rendered
all but perfunctory _ to secure their parties' nods.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, they were elbowing each other in the news media
for position on some of the issues that are likely to dominate the
race. Gore, trying to brush aside questions about his money-raising
practices four years ago, proclaimed himself a convert to campaign
finance reform; this month, a fund-raiser long associated with him
was convicted in connection with a fund-raising event at a Buddhist
temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake going to that Buddhist temple,'' Gore said.
``I made a mistake in making telephone calls from my office. And I
have learned from those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush sought to paint himself as the nation's No.
1. school booster. In what his staff touted as the first television
commercial of the general election, he began running an attack ad
masquerading as an issue spot. ``Under Al Gore and Bill Clinton,
national reading scores stagnated,'' said the 60-second commercial
on the air in southern Illinois. ``America's high school students
place almost dead last in international math tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, in Bora-Bora recuperating from his defeat,
continued to withhold support for Bush; the prospect of an
endorsement grew more remote after Bush told The New York Times
that McCain had done almost nothing to influence his views (though
Bush said the next day, ``I'm confident we can work together.'')
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Patrick J. Buchanan, in the race for the Reform Party
nomination, spoke at Harvard last week and had equally unkind words
for both Gore and Bush. No word on whether they sent him a testy
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   Cabbies' Curious Cognition
</P>
<P>
   London cabbies are remarkable for getting you where you want to
go, fast. This is commonly ascribed to ``the Knowledge,'' the
grueling licensing exam they must take, which requires that they
virtually memorize the center city street grid.
</P>
<P>
   It's either that, or the fact that their brains have been
altered.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published last week in the journal Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences, researchers at London University's
University College report that the brains of 16 male taxi drivers,
compared with 50 other men of roughly the same age, showed enlarged
rear portions of the hippocampus, which controls our ability to
navigate. The scientists also found the area continued to grow with
years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hippocampus has changed its structure to accommodate their
huge amount of navigating experience,'' Dr. Eleanor Maguire, the
research team leader, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first evidence that healthy adult brains can alter
depending on how they are used, which could lead to new treatment
for injured or diseased brains.
</P>
<P>
   It was all somewhat bemusing to David Cohen from the London Cab
Drivers' Club. ``I never noticed part of my brain growing,'' he
told the BBC. ``It makes you wonder what happened to the rest of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER EDIDIN
</P>
<P>
   Almost Airborne Again At Boeing
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Co. said it needed to hold the line on costs, while its
engineers union said the giant manufacturer was like a bully going
after ``the little kid in the corner with the glasses.'' But the
kid had been ``taking kung-fu,'' said the union's director, and the
result was one of the largest strikes ever by white-collar workers
against a private company.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, after five and a half weeks of picketing had
contributed to serious delays in jet deliveries, Boeing and the
union reached a tentative pact calling for average 8 percent
raises, cash bonuses and the company's withdrawal of a demand for
new health-insurance payments.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers declared victory and national labor leaders said
the accord showed the muscle professional workers could bring to
the table if they unionized.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK
</P>
<P>
   Close to Gay Marriage
</P>
<P>
   It may not be marriage, but it sure is close. A bill creating
civil unions for gay couples passed the Vermont House of
Representatives and is expected to gain approval from the Senate
and Gov. Howard Dean in April.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would create civil union certificates for same-sex
couples, who would be treated virtually as if they were married in
areas ranging from probate law to medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents complained this effectively amounted to marriage;
backers proclaimed it a significant step toward equal rights for
all committed couples.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   The Unacknowledged Legislators of Mankind
</P>
<P>
   Israel's education minister created a political storm,
culminating in a no-confidence vote in the government, when he
decided to include a nationalist Palestinian poet's work in the
high school literature curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   A fierce debate in parliament ensued over whether the poems of
Mahmoud Darwish were too anti-Israel or whether Israeli students
should broaden their horizons by experiencing ``the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The government survived. Darwish's verse got quite an airing.
And the Palestinian culture minister decided to introduce Israeli
poets to Palestinian students. So there.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DEBORAH SONTAG
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
