<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0862 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-POPE-MUSLIMS-REVIEW-N     03-18 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-MUSLIMS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASY RELATIONS: THE CROSS AND THE CRESCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ With the words, ``God wills it,'' Pope Urban II launched
the First Crusade in 1095, a bloody effort to wrest Jerusalem from
Muslim control that lasted more than 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   When John Paul II flies to Jordan this week to begin a Holy Year
pilgrimage to retrace the steps of Jesus Christ in Jordan, Israel
and the Palestinian territories, he will also be leading a crusade,
of an entirely different kind. Though the pilgrimage is mostly
private, the pope will also pursue his longtime dream of
reconciling Christians and Muslims after centuries of hostility and
mistrust. His rationale is much the same as Pope Urban II's _ God
wills it.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the the Second Vatican Council in 1965, the Roman
Catholic Church has made interfaith rapprochement part of church
teaching. This pope, whose 22-year tenure is the longest in the
20th century, has done more than any other to advance dialogue with
other churches. Reuniting Rome and the Eastern Orthodox churches
has been a major, as yet unfulfilled, goal, and he will meet with
the Greek Orthodox patriarch of Jerusalem to try to mend a schism
that dates back more than 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to Israel will provide the papacy's most dramatic
opportunity yet to try and heal wounds that remain deep 50 years
after the Holocaust. But the pope also wants to reach out to Islam,
hoping to give new life to a halting dialogue between the Vatican
and Muslim leaders that began in earnest 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who will meet with the grand mufti of Jerusalem,
rarely forgoes a chance to meet Muslim leaders on his travels. But
formal institutional efforts to overcome deeply rooted enmities
have met with resistance among some Muslim leaders and also within
the Vatican. At the most recent synod of European Bishops, held in
Rome last October, Giuseppe Bernardini, archbishop of Izmir,
Turkey, disrupted the genteel torpor of the speeches by warning his
colleagues about the perils of Islam. He cited an interfaith
meeting he attended where, he said, a Muslim warned his Christian
counterparts, ``Thanks to your democratic laws, we will invade you;
thanks to our religious laws, we will dominate you.'' He also cited
instances of Muslim death threats against nuns and criticized
interfaith meetings as a ``dialogue of the deaf.''
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop's comments, reprinted in the Italian bishops'
newspaper, Avvenire, were denounced by Muslim leaders, and by a few
bishops. ``I fear Christians who don't live in a Christian way in
Muslim countries more than I fear Muslims,'' retorted Giovanni
Martinelli, the bishop of Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
   But some of Bernardini's less alarmist sentiments are echoed by
Catholic leaders involved in dialogue with Muslims. ``Irenicism,''
a term for seeking harmony over contention, pops up often in
Catholic texts about Christian-Islamic dialogue, to describe the
way interfaith discussion tends to stick stubbornly to platitudes.
``The problem is they talk, and we listen, we talk and they listen,
but the most pressing issues are not raised,'' said Father Maurice
Borrmans, dean of The Pontifical Institute of Arab and Islamic
studies in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The pope directly addressed one of those delicate subjects in
1995, when a mosque was erected in Rome. He said the Holy See
encouraged such signs of religious pluralism, then added, ``It is
unfortunately necessary to point out that in some Islamic
countries, similar signs of religious freedom are lacking.''
Christians, who are increasingly a tiny and shrinking minority in
the Middle East, complain of state-enforced Islamic laws and
cultural attitudes that inhibit their ability to worship freely.
</P>
<P>
   Christian leaders who try to discuss such problems complain that
their overtures are not met with reciprocal efforts _ or even
interest. In an essay reviewing the last 30 years of dialogue,
Borrmans noted ``a certain fundamental disinterest vis-a-vis
everything that is not Muslim, and the certainty of having
everything in the Koran (including a clear vision of real
Christianity!).''
</P>
<P>
   Some Muslim scholars involved in interfaith dialogue concede
that their side is not always equally forthcoming. ``Religion in
the Muslim world is often a source of political power, and no
Islamic leader is ready yet to examine what we do to the others,''
said Nazir U. Khaja, president of the Islamic Information Service
in Los Angeles. ``There is still too much of an us-against-them
mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   On social issues like the family, homosexuality and abortion,
however, the Vatican and Islamic institutions have found common
ground, most notably at the U.N. Conference on Population and
Development in Cairo in 1994, and the 1995 Beijing Conference on
Women.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also limits to Catholic acceptance. In 1986, the
pope sponsored a broad gathering of leaders of all the major
religions at Assisi. It was a groundbreaking assembly, and many
Catholic traditionalists complained at the time that it seemed to
suggest that all religions are equal.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cardinal Josef Ratzinger, head of the Vatican's
Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, seemed to disapprove,
saying, ``This cannot be the model.''
</P>
<P>
   Theologians who go too far in affirming that other religions can
also lead to salvation may fall afoul of the Vatican. After a
French Jesuit, the Rev. Jacques Dupuis, published a book on the
subject, ``Toward a Christian Theology of Religious Pluralism,''
his writings were investigated by Cardinal Ratzinger's office for
signs of heresy.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the pope delivered the most sweeping papal apology
ever, asking forgiveness for errors of the Roman Catholic Church
committed over the last 2,000 years. The pope referred only
obliquely to the Crusades, asking that Catholics acknowledge past
injustices committed ``in the service of truth, '' but many within
the Vatican worried about how this would be interpreted in the
Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Mufti of Jerusalem responded by saying that he wanted
to hear a more explicit apology for the Crusades when he meets with
the pope in Jerusalem. This caused eyes to roll in Rome, where many
Catholic leaders point out that their Muslim counterparts have
never expressed regret for the way Islamic armies sought to conquer
Europe from the eighth century on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Muslims already thought we were wrong, so now, we say,
yes, in some cases we were wrong,'' Father Borrmans said. ``Of
course it's difficult, but the pope has decided that we must have
the courage to say it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
