<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, March 19:
</P>
<P>
   THE TAIWAN ELECTION:
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ELECTION (Taipei) _ Chen Shui-bian, an opposition
politician who has long advocated Taiwan's independence, was
elected its new president Saturday, ending more than half a century
of Nationalist rule and risking dangerous new tensions with
mainland China. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHEN (Taipei, Taiwan) _ For many Taiwanese, not least
those who swept him to victory Saturday and ended over 50 years of
rule by the Nationalist party, President-elect Chen Shui-bian's
public image was fixed by a supremely personal tragedy. At a rally
in 1985, his wife, Wu Shu-jen, was hit by a truck; the accident
left her paralyzed from the chest down. Ever since, Chen has
carried the reputation as a man who paid a high price, and
shoulders a heavy burden, for his beliefs. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-VOTERS (Taipei) _ The mood in the current president's
hometown. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Beijing) _ Why the Chinese feel so strongly about
Taiwan. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERNATIONAL STORIES:
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-GEPHARDT (Washington) _ Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri,
the House Democratic leader and a hard-liner on foreign trade, is
an unlikely kingmaker for a decisive China trade deal that he fears
could jeopardize his greater goal of reclaiming the House this
fall. He is walking a political tightrope as Congress debates
whether to grant China permanent normal trading privileges. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RED-ARMY (Tokyo) _ Four Japanese Red Army members
suspected of hijackings, embassy seizures and other crimes were
taken into custody upon entering Japan on Saturday after being
deported from Lebanon. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ President Thabo
Mbeki's decision to seek advice from two Americans who argue that
HIV does not cause AIDS has touched off an outcry at home and
abroad and raised fears that South Africa's already soaring
infection rate will climb still further. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-JERUSALEM (Jerusalem) _ Pope John Paul II's pilgrimage to
the holy land is a deeply spiritual climax of a 22-year papacy and
the first official visit of a pope to Israel. But it is also the
culmination of John Paul's long effort to redefine the way the
church sees Jews _ as ``elder brothers'' rather than traitors _ and
to reconcile Jews and Catholics. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   PUTIN-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ With Russia's presidential elections
just a week away, Acting President Vladimir Putin sought to
reassure voters Saturday that the war in Chechnya was drawing to a
close and that some Russian troops would soon be on their way home.
By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ECON-GAP (Hyderabad, India) _ President Clinton will see
the new modern cyber-India, but the chasm between India's educated
elite and its impoverished multitudes increasingly worries
economists, politicians and some leading software entrepreneurs. By
Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and map.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-LABOR (Otay Mesa, Calif.) _ With unemployment low and a
record number of Americans behind bars, prison labor is coming to
mean much more than painting license plates. As inmates undertake
everything from telemarketing to the manufacturing of computer
circuit boards and furniture, the change has caused a growing
debate over the role the nation's 2 million prisoners should play
in its economy. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   RECRUITING-WORKERS (Kansas City) _ Unable to find enough workers
in the booming economy, corporate America is seeking to expand the
labor pool, trying to attract people not previously recruited so
intensively. To get these new workers, companies are offering all
sorts of lures _ except significantly higher pay. By Louis
Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-AUDIENCES (Hollywood) _ As Hollywood prepares for the 72nd
annual Academy Awards next Sunday, there is a growing sense among
many filmmakers and movie professionals that something exciting and
unexpected has happened to American moviemaking over the last
half-decade and with increasing force in the last year: a
fundamental shift in the taste of the mainstream movie audience. By
Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   NUNS-SAINT (Bensalem, Pa.) _ For the Sisters of the Blessed
Sacrament this is a time for rejoicing, as their founder, Mother
Katharine Drexel, is chosen by the pope to be a saint. By Francis
X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   REPORTERS-PROTEST (San Luis Obispo, Calif.) _ A group of
newspaper reporters in San Luis Obispo County have quit because the
publisher of the papers insists that they only write about gays and
abortion in a negative light. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE-SCANDAL (Providence, R.I.) _ It's a tale out of ``The
Sopranos,'' a saga of official and unofficial corruption at all
levels that culminated on Friday in a guilty verdict against city
tax officials, a sting the feds called ``Operation Plunder Dome.''
But even the verdict doesn't end the city's suspense. The real talk
in Providence, many people say, is whether federal investigators
will bring down the mayor, a convicted felon who is the driving
force behind the city's much-trumpeted renaissance. By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   SUBPRIME-LENDERS (Undated) _ Chicago and other cities are taking
action to thwart predatory lending corporations on the heels of the
Times/ABC report on deceptive practices by large home-equity
lenders like First Alliance. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-VOUCHERS-ASSESS (Undated) _ When a Florida judge declared
last week that giving students taxpayer-financed vouchers for
private-school tuition violated that state's Constitution, he
bulldozed an important national testing ground for school choice
and posted a reminder that the legal landscape for vouchers
included several potential pitfalls. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-BABY-BOOM (New York) _ Millennium, schmillennium. It's the
Year of the Dragon, baby. And among Asian-Americans who abide by
the lunar calendar, this auspicious season of the mythical beast is
also turning out to be the year of the baby boom. By Somini
Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-AIRLINES (Seattle) _ After 64 mechanics at Alaska
Airlines signed a letter saying they had been ``pressured,
threatened and intimidated'' to cut corners on repairs and
maintenance, the airline put one of its managers on administrative
leave and said Saturday that it was conducting detailed interviews
with all of the mechanics. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   HMO-MEDICARE (Washington) _ Exclusive: Medicare officials say
HMOs have disseminated false information in an effort to mobilize
their members to lobby Congress, and federal investigators say they
have found evidence that HMOs bill Medicare for some of their
lobbying expenses. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   LONGHORNED-BEETLE (Washington) _ Federal, state and local
officials will soon renew their campaign to stamp out the Asian
long-horned beetle, which has caused the destruction of thousands
of trees in the New York City and Chicago areas since arriving in
the United States just a few years ago. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-HAMMER (Carthage, Tenn.) _ On the third page of Vice
President Al Gore's most recent financial disclosure report,
following routine listings for his salary and the value of his
house in Washington and his small farm here, is a provocative
entry: $20,000 for leasing land for zinc mining. Behind the yearly
lease payment, which has earned Gore about $450,000 since 1974, is
the story of a sweetheart land deal from long ago, and the unusual
ties between the vice president and his family and the late
millionaire Armand Hammer and his oil company, Occidental
Petroleum. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SYMBOLISM (Austin, Texas) _ At the celebration here after
Gov. George W. Bush all but clinched the Republican presidential
nomination, the person chosen to introduce Bush was not some
longtime Republican bigwig or starry political celebrity. It was
Mayor Carlos Ramirez of El Paso, a Hispanic Democrat. The move was
clearly part of the Bush campaign's attempt to portray the governor
as eager to embrace diversity and intent on broadening the
Republican party's appeal. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-ELECTION (Washington) _ This year's Senate elections seem
likely to produce modest Democratic gains, but too small to take
control from the Republicans, leaders of both parties agree. Both
sides will be watching the outcome closely, because it probably
will set the stage for an even more intense fight for control in
2002. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   With a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   Commentary by Maureen Dowd and Paul Krugman.
</P>
