u i BC-IRAN-TENSIONS-REVIEW-     03-18 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-TENSIONS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITS VOTERS HAVE SPOKEN. NOW MEET IRAN'S GUNMEN. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 21 stressful years of living under clerical dictatorship,
most Iranians would happily settle for a more normal life. But last
week, just as they were celebrating the reformist landslide in
February's parliamentary elections and the hope of a peaceful
progression toward a more democratic society, an assassin's bullet
provided a shocking reminder of how grim and uncertain a struggle
may yet lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The hammer blow came when a man dismounted a powerful
motorcycle, walked down a Tehran sidewalk and fired at the head of
Saeed Hajjarian, a 47-year-old newspaper publisher who has been one
of the reform movement's most valued leaders. By the week's end,
Hajjarian was experiencing brief bouts of consciousness in a
hospital, but doctors remained wary of his ever making a full
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   In the search for suspects, many signs pointed toward a core of
ruthless, corrupt, clandestine men in the state security agencies
who work hand-in-glove with the conservative Muslim clerics at the
pinnacle of power. The motorcycle itself was of a kind that only
Iran's security agencies are allowed to use. Then there was the
provocation Hajjarian had offered in his crusading newspaper,
Sobh-e Emrooz, which has done more than any other Iranian
publication to expose the darkness at the heart of Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
   These exposures have centered on evidence that officially
sanctioned death squads have been at work for years, and
implications that powerful figures in the clerical hierarchy may
have known _ or even approved the killings _ in advance. In the
last few weeks, the revelations, presented in a guarded fashion
that reflected the risks involved, had begun to work closer to the
center of power, hastening, as it now seems, the moment when the
bitter clash between reformers and conservatives could no longer be
finessed.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of things, Iran in recent years has achieved
something remarkable, the gradual advance of democracy within an
Islamic system that, as defended by the conservatives, is inimical
to the very idea of popular sovereignty. A succession of landslide
victories in elections, beginning with the 1997 triumph of the
reformers' main standard-bearer, President Mohammad Khatami and
culminating with the reformist sweep of three-quarters of the seats
in parliamentary elections four weeks ago, had co-existed, however
uneasily, with a system in which clerical hard-liners continued to
hold all critical levers of power.
</P>
<P>
   The principal figures on both sides _ Khatami for the reformers
and Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, the country's ``supreme leader,'' for
the conservatives _ seemed determined not to allow the
contradiction to be pushed too far, and certainly not to the point
of a struggle in the streets. But others, like Hajjarian, were
exploiting fissures in the system _ above all, the emergence of an
independent press _ to drive what amounted to a stake into the
system's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Many reformers, Hajjarian among them, came well-equipped to the
task. Khatami was a trusted loyalist of Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, who led the revolution in 1979. Others, including
Hajjarian, participated in the student takeover of the U.S. embassy
in Tehran, and in the indignities imposed on the U.S. diplomats
held hostage for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Hajjarian and others also worked in the Islamic system's
agencies of enforcement _ in his case as a deputy intelligence
minister from 1984 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   If this has lent credence to the reformers' challenge, it has
added, too, to the bitterness with which their efforts have been
met. Out in the open, major reform figures like Abdullah Nouri were
brought to trial and sentenced to lengthy jail terms, only for
others to carry the baton forward. And more sinister forces have
been at work as well.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 15 months, Hajjarian's paper published exposes of
the intelligence ministry that focused on the murders in late 1998
of five prominent opposition figures. Under pressure from Khatami,
the ministry admitted early last year that ``rogue elements'' in
its own ranks _ a death squad _ had carried out the murders.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the ministry proclaimed the arrest of one of its
deputy ministers as the ``ringleader'' of the death squad, it
reverted to form by announcing that the man, Saeed Emami, had
committed suicide in prison. While rumors circulated of Emami
having died from an injection of potassium cyanide, the ministry
announced the arrest of 26 more people, most from its own ranks.
But none of the others has yet been brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hajjarian's paper did not rest there. In new articles and a
book, the paper's leading investigative reporter, Akbar Gangi, has
suggested that the 1998 murders were a sequel to a long-established
practice of secret killing, authorized, it has been hinted, by a
commission of high-ranking intelligence officials. The murders _ by
potassium cyanide, by knifings, by strangling and by shooting _ are
said to have involved as many as 80 people.
</P>
<P>
   Since the recent elections, Khatami's brother, Mohammed-Reza
Khatami, who led the triumphant reformists, has said they intend to
empanel a parliamentary commission of inquiry into the allegations
and to establish what role, if any, was played in the killings by
the highest-ranking officials of the state. Other reform leaders
have suggested that one of those to be investigated is Khatami's
predecessor as president, Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
   Rafsanjani, a senior cleric himself, has long been an elusive
figure, shifting back and forth between reform and hard-line
policies, and getting rich as he has done so. Significantly, in
light of the new questions about his past, he barely won his own
seat in the elections.
</P>
<P>
   But after the attack on Hajjarian, Iranians are asking
themselves more than ever whether their future will be settled at
the ballot box, or by the darker forces at play. Between reformers
who carry their fight with the searchlight of reason and
disclosure, and hardliners who seem prepared to battle it out with
daggers, the issue seems far from settled. Iranians may have months
or years yet of confrontation before they see their yearning for
broader rights fulfilled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
