<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0872 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CENSUS-RACE-REVIEW-NY     03-18 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-RACE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POLITICS OF RACE AND THE CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The four words on the census form, ``check all that
apply,'' sound more bureaucratic than revolutionary. Yet when used
in a question asking people to describe their race, those words
represent the latest shake-up in the way the country views itself
racially.
</P>
<P>
   With high levels of immigration, rising rates of intermarriage
and groups clamoring for recognition, America's racial and ethnic
stew is undergoing radical change. Some people say this change
portends the end of whites as the majority race by the middle of
the next century _ a dubious theory at best.
</P>
<P>
   Even if whites retain their numerical dominance, the subtly
changing flavor of the country's racial and ethnic bouillabaisse is
already reflected in the forms the Census Bureau is mailing to more
than 120 million households this month. For the first time, people
can describe themselves as members of one or more of six racial
categories. They can check all that apply. Thus individuals could
list themselves as white or black or white and Asian or black and
white and American Indian and ``other.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting 63 potential variations have caused confusion
among sociologists and statisticians, provoked consternation among
some civil rights advocates and become the butt of jokes among
late-night comedians. The new categories also raise questions about
how the government will keep track of this new racial and ethnic
mix (and whether it should be classifying people by race at all).
The changes point out an abiding feature of this country's racial
history: when it comes to determining what exactly is a racial
category, politics _ not biology _ is the deciding factor.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Patterson, a sociologist at Harvard University, said
that Jews, Italians and Irish were once considered separate races.
But as they gained more economic and political power, the larger
society accepted them as white and ethnic. At one point, the census
categorized some blacks according to how many white ancestors they
had. But as state-sanctioned segregation arose, all people of
African descent were classified into one race _ black. ``These are
all basically political decisions,'' Patterson said. ``The census
always just reflects changing attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   The odyssey of the mixed race category on the census form is
further testament to political forces. The grouping was first
promoted by officials in the Office of Management and Budget, which
sets policy on racial classifications. They were moved by the
heartfelt stories of parents whose children were forced to select
either the race of the father or of the mother. In response, the
officials initially proposed a new category, ``multiracial.'' Civil
rights organizations were aghast, fearing that the grouping would
dilute the numbers of blacks, Asians-Americans or American Indians.
They worried that smaller figures would make it harder to show
discrimination patterns and to draw legislative districts where
minorities constitute the majority of voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, said Karen Narasaki, executive director of the
National Asian Pacific American Legal Consortium, the civil rights
groups ``won less on the strength of our intellectual arguments,
and more on our political strength. OMB backed down.''
</P>
<P>
   When the budget office said that instead of a multiracial
category, people could check more than one racial category, civil
rights groups put enough pressure on the Clinton administration
that the OMB announced last week that people who list themselves as
part white and part minority will be counted as a member of that
minority group.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights groups did not relish this battle. Many readily
admit that the issue pulls them between two contending beliefs:
self-determination and their view of a way to fight discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discrimination is not about who you think you are,'' Narasaki
said. ``I could run around thinking I'm white. Many Asians do. Does
that help them in the end? Not always because other people say,
`No, you're not.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still the swirl of categories and politics has prompted calls
for the federal government to stop grouping people by race and
ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back to the `one drop' rule,'' said Michael Lind, a
senior fellow with the New America Foundation, referring to the old
segregationist rule of thumb that designated people with scant
black blood as black. ``I'm disgusted with the whole thing. This
census should have been the first one not to identify people by
race. Mexico got rid of its racial classifications in the 1820s. We
keep ours basically because of the black civil rights lobby, which
has lobbied in favor of the `one drop' rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, whether people like it or not, America's racial mix is
shifting, primarily because of rising rates of intermarriage.
</P>
<P>
   Census figures in 1960 show that there were about 149,000
interracial marriages, generally between whites and blacks, whites
and Asians, and whites and Indians. In 1990 there were more than
1.46 million. Experts say the numbers have risen even faster during
the last decade. The figures do not include marriages between
non-Hispanic whites and Hispanics, which have grown rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The experts have estimated that in 1990 among young native-born
Hispanic women, 31.4 percent have non-Hispanic white husbands and
that among young Hispanic men, 31.6 have non-Hispanic white wives.
The figures are even higher for Asians where 45.2 percent of
native-born women and 36 percent of native-born men have white
spouses.
</P>
<P>
   But intermarriage is far less common for blacks. In contrast
only about 8 percent of black men and 4 percent of black women
marry outside their race.
</P>
<P>
   Lind sees a new racial divide appearing: on one side, blacks; on
the other non-blacks, which would include whites and the offspring
of whites and other racial and ethnic minorities. What that will
mean in terms of solidarity among people of color and for the
aspirations of African-Americans is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Still others like Patterson see an even more nuanced trend
emerging: the Census Bureau's dress rehearsal for the 2000 Census
held last year in Sacramento, Calif., and rural counties in South
Carolina found that intermarriage rates among blacks and whites
were far lower in South Carolina than in California where Hispanics
and Asians are much more prevalent and marrying whites in large
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said that in areas like the Northeast, the Southwest
and West Coast where there has been more immigration tests show
that a new racial amalgam that includes blacks will emerge, while
other sections like the South and the Midwest will be left behind.
``Certain parts of the country are going to become bastions of the
`one drop' rule,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1151EST &QL; 
