<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GASOLINE-MOTORISTS-RE     03-18 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-MOTORISTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAS GUZZLERS: LOOKING FOR THE SUV VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Car drivers probably feel avenged these days when they
see a hulking sport utility vehicle lumber up to a gas station.
Every bing and clank from the pump is another reminder of the
higher cost of filling a gas guzzler: up to $70 for the biggest
models.
</P>
<P>
   But any feelings of revenge, or sympathy, may be misplaced.
Higher gas prices actually hurt car owners as much _ or more _ than
sport utility owners, at least when measured as a percentage of
their incomes. Even as gas prices have cleared $1.50 across much of
the country this winter and are approaching $2 a gallon in some
cities, sales of these light trucks continue to grow slightly
faster than car sales.
</P>
<P>
   Just as soccer moms developed into a political constituency,
truckers and motorists hurt by high fuel costs might emerge as
voters candidates have to woo. But motorists' enthusiasm for lower
gas prices may have more to do with the percentage of their incomes
spent on gas than with their vehicles' fuel efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase loosely Ernest Hemingway's riposte to F. Scott
Fitzgerald's famous comment about rich people, sport utility
vehicle owners are not like everybody else: they have more money.
The income gap between buyers of sport utilities and buyers of cars
is greater than the gap in the fuel economy of their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for example, a Chevrolet Suburban and a Ford Taurus
mid-size sedan. The Suburban burns 53 percent more gas a year than
the Taurus when driven the same number of miles _ 15 miles a gallon
compared with 23 miles a gallon for the Taurus for a combination of
city and highway driving. But the typical household buying a
Suburban can afford the extra gas because it earns 75 percent more
than a typical household buying a Taurus ($94,700 for the Suburban
to $54,100 for the Taurus, according to the auto makers' survey).
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, even with gas prices up by 60 cents a gallon
over the last year, a family that drives a late-model Suburban for
12,000 miles a year can probably afford the $480 increase in its
gas bill. The family that drives a Taurus the same distance may
wince at the $313 increase. And the difference between $313 and
$480 is not likely to change many people's minds about what models
they buy.
</P>
<P>
   There is little sign so far that buying habits have changed,
perhaps because gas prices are still not that high. Adjusted for
inflation, the price of gas is still below the peak in 1981, when
it reached the equivalent of $2.46 today.
</P>
<P>
   Small cars have better mileage but even less-affluent owners. A
Ford Expedition sport utility vehicle burns 93 percent more gas
than a Dodge Neon driven the same number of miles. Yet a median
household buying a new Expedition also earns 118 percent more than
a Neon-buying household. The income gap is even more extreme for
luxury sport utilities like the Lexus LX470, for which the median
household income is $264,600.
</P>
<P>
   So grousing by sport utility owners about gas prices is mostly
just talk, auto analysts say. ``They may complain about it to their
friends because it's the thing to do,'' said Chris Cedergren, an
auto consultant at Nextrend Inc. in Thousand Oaks, Calif. ``But do
they do anything about it? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Affluent families historically have switched to more
fuel-efficient cars only when gas is in short supply and there are
long lines at service stations. Higher prices, by themselves, have
had little effect. Cadillac sales briefly stumbled when there were
gas lines in early 1974, but completely recovered once the lines
disappeared _ even though gasoline cost four times as much as
before. What hurt Detroit was that sales of non-luxury large cars
did not recover, as middle-class families switched to smaller, more
fuel-efficient Japanese cars.
</P>
<P>
   If today's higher oil prices lead to a recession, a stock market
crash or much higher interest rates, as has sometimes happened in
the past, then the auto industry and sales of SUVs will be
devastated. Even without such a calamity, higher gas prices might
prompt a few of the less prosperous families who buy sport
utilities to switch to more fuel-efficient alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, including Gov. George W. Bush of Texas this
year and former Sen. Bob Dole during the 1996 presidential
campaign, have sought the repeal of the 4.3-cent federal gas tax
increase enacted in 1993. But Robert Teeter, a Republican pollster,
said Republicans should criticize President Clinton for not
pursuing energy independence instead of worrying about small gas
taxes. Affluent families who might consider voting Republican are
not going to be swayed by a few pennies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``SUV drivers are not so sensitive to a 20- or 30-percent change
in gas prices as someone on a limited income,'' Teeter said. ``The
guy who is really hurt is the one driving the 15- or 18-year-old
car.''
</P>
<P>
   And the driver of such a clunker, he added, is probably going to
vote Democratic, if at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
