<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0874 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-ECON-STOCKS-REVIEW-NY     03-18 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-STOCKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK ANSWERS: WHOSE ECONOMY IS IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also filed in ``f'' category) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old economy lives.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the dull old stocks that used to dominate the economy
appeared to be dead in the water, they took off with a vengeance
last week. The Dow Jones industrial average was up 666 points, or
6.7 percent, for the week.
</P>
<P>
   That's the largest weekly percentage gain for the Dow since the
summer of 1984, when the average began the big week at 1,114, or
only a little more than a tenth of the current level. In points, it
is by far the largest weekly leap ever.
</P>
<P>
   That move was welcome for investors who had avoided the
technology stocks that have dominated the stock market,
particularly during the last six months. Stocks in such industries
as banking, insurance, retail and electric utilities were trading
at their lowest level in a couple of years, even as the tech stocks
zoomed to ever higher levels.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, stocks that are traditionally sensitive to the
economy, like Caterpillar and Goodyear, were trading as if a
recession were imminent, even though virtually all the economic
numbers show that the boom continues unabated despite four rounds
of interest-rate hikes by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth such move is virtually certain to arrive on Tuesday,
but fear of the Fed seems to have faded.
</P>
<P>
   One reason it faded is that the latest inflation numbers took on
a rosy glow after Wall Street was through interpreting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of oil prices, there is nothing going on on the
inflation front,'' said Bruce Steinberg, the chief economist of
Merrill Lynch, who figures that oil prices will start coming down
this spring as oil producers step up output.
</P>
<P>
   ``Market participants are wagering that Alan Greenspan, faced
with continued good news on the inflation front, will recant,''
said Robert Barbera, the chief economist of Hoenig &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbera thinks that is wrong. He thinks that Greenspan, who
has repeatedly said that Americans are spending too much, in part
because rising stock prices have made them feel wealthier, is
worried about the ways in which the stock market has changed over
the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates caused investors in the old economy to worry, but
technology stocks have roared back after every plunge. That
happened again last week, as the tech-heavy Nasdaq composite fell
more than 11 percent in the first three and a half days of trading,
then made up most of the losses in the final day and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, consumer spending is running higher than most
economists expected and stock market investors are borrowing money
at a record rate to finance their investments.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that mutual fund buyers have continued to pour money
into the narrow group of funds that buy fast-growing technology
companies.
</P>
<P>
   If Barbera is right, then the Fed is likely to keep raising
rates until the new-economy stocks finally go down and stay down.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it remains to be seen whether the old-economy stocks _
not to mention the old economy itself _ can withstand the
onslaught.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0965 &Cx1f; var-z
