<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
March 19 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact
Dennis Liff at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   PEST-INVASION (Los Angeles) _ Southern California's pleasing
climate is attracting such varied pests as fire ants and killer
bees.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Coit. (Will move in the ``a'' national news file and
in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0878 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PEST-INVASION-2Takes-     03-18 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEST-INVASION-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PESTS ATTACKING L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL COIT  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First came the redgum lerp psyllids, tiny
aphid-like pests sucking life from stands of eucalyptus trees
across the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Africanized honeybees ``killer bees''
</P>
<P>
   invaded the Valley, their swarms posing serious health risks.
</P>
<P>
   Now come the red imported fire ants, turning up in Van Nuys last
week to mark the crop-eating, flesh-stinging pest's continued march
north.
</P>
<P>
   Plagues of the Valley, the troublesome threesome are thriving to
varying degrees thanks to the region's warm climate, irrigated
landscaping and mild winters. The killer bees and potentially the
red fire ants are particularly bothersome and could forever alter
the lifestyles of Valley residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is paradise for these pests,'' said Larry Cooper,
spokesman for the California Department of Food and Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen or so new pests are identified in California each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Valley residents have weathered periodic quarantines and
sprayings for the Mediterranean fruit fly and other fruit flies.
Still, backyard fruit remains bountiful.
</P>
<P>
   State and county agricultural officials are trying to combat or
at least control the psyllids, killer bees and red fire ants. But
they concede that the killer bees are here to stay and the red fire
ants will be tough to root out with pesticides developed in
Southern states with different climates.
</P>
<P>
   So residents need to be wary to keep the pests from swarming and
stinging.
</P>
<P>
   The psyllids might be controlled by tiny wasps to be released
this spring. But they won't be eradicated and will remain a
nuisance, spreading a sticky honeydew excretion on leaves that
damages cars and sticks to just about everything, including pet
paws and human hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem like we're being picked on,'' said Cato Fiksdal,
Los Angeles County's agricultural commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pests that are really going to affect people in an
urban environment. It's different from fighting a Medfly. There's
certainly a much stronger direct connection to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents on Cantaloupe Avenue, where the red fire ant find was
reported, already are preparing for life with the pest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm originally from Florida. They've got red fire ants
everywhere,'' said Carolyn Lombardo, who lives on Cantaloupe.
``It's like the smog here, you just live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Campbell appreciated the presence of county agriculture
inspectors on the street last week, passing out pamphlets and
answering questions on how to deal with red fire ants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to know that we should be on the lookout,'' Campbell
said. ``They think it's a hitchhiker, so I'm not worried about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like fruit flies, the psyllids and red fire ants likely arrived
on some plant or cargo material transported illegally around
federal and state inspection efforts, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The killer bees were expected to colonize Los Angeles County
sooner, having moved into the state after getting established in
areas of Texas, New Mexico and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of these pests does not signal some change in the
Valley ecosystem. They're just finding the same pleasing climate
that draws people from across the nation and world.
</P>
<P>
   Psyllids are native to Australia, where the semiarid
Mediterranean climate is comparable to California.
</P>
<P>
   Killer bees have been colonizing and pollinating the southern
reaches of the Western Hemisphere since they were first introduced
into Brazil in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Red fire ants like warm and wet conditions. While Southern
California is considerably drier than the Southeastern states where
the red fire ant is entrenched, vast expanses of irrigated
landscaping provide ample water sources.
</P>
<P>
   Once detected, the pests could be here in numbers too great to
eradicate, said Aurelio Posadas, the state agriculture department's
red fire ant program supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have detection traps. We don't have any lures to set
up a trapping system to allow you to find it in a size small enough
so you can jump in and eradicate rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how widespread the infestation is, ``You have to
decide whether it's going to eradication, management or biological
controls.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The psyllid infestation has been the worst on street trees since
a whitefly descended on ash trees across Los Angeles in 1989. The
psyllid showed up in Los Angeles County and in the Bay Area about
the same time in 1998, spreading to the San Gabriel Valley and
Orange County and from Sacramento to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Although widespread, the psyllid might be controlled by a tiny
wasp found to prey on the psyllid in Australia. A University of
California at Berkeley entomologist has led an effort to breed the
wasp that county officials said should be released this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the verge of knocking them back. We think it will put
them into a control situation,'' said Fiksdal, the county
agricultural commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The same cannot be said for killer bees. No state or country has
been able to keep down the pest since it was first introduced into
Brazil in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   The killer bees began colonizing in the United States in 1990
and have been entrenched in Los Angeles County since last April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning to live with it,'' said Cooper, the state
agriculture spokesman. ``We can eradicate populations quickly, but
that's not going to eradicate infestation.''
</P>
<P>
   State and county officials are more optimistic about eradicating
red fire ants.
</P>
<P>
   The pest entered the Southern United States in the 1920s and has
spread to 11 states. It appeared in California in San Joaquin
Valley orchards in 1997 and made its way to Orange County in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire ants' biggest moves have been through the helpful
human. We still consider it an exotic pest that we have an
eradication program for,'' said Posadas, the state's red fire ant
chief.
</P>
<P>
   County agricultural inspectors are on the front line of the
battle, spraying pesticides that sterilize queens and kill red fire
ants foraging for food. Los Angeles County recently added six
inspectors to the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Quarantines also prohibit the movement of soil and nursery stock
out of Orange County and south Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more than a nuisance,'' said Les Greenberg, a
University of California, Riverside, entomologist leading a new
research project on the pest. ``The fire ant is a broad-based pest,
a pest to people, animals, agriculture, the nursery industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0882 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MOST-WANTED-REVIEW-NY     03-18 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOST-WANTED-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTER BOYS OF CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI marked the golden anniversary of its 10
Most Wanted list last week with a sense of pride, and just a touch
of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   The pride is easy to understand: of 458 men and women who have
made the list in the last half-century, 429 have been caught, with
several choosing to go down shooting it out with their would-be
captors. Cases against 15 individuals who were never caught were
eventually dropped, and four more fugitives were removed from the
list because others were deemed more deserving.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI noted that 134 of the 429 who have been tracked down
were captured as a direct result of cooperation by alert citizens.
Small wonder that FBI Director Louis J. Freeh extolled the ``10
Most Wanted Fugitives'' list, to use its formal name, not just as a
continuing demonstration of his agents' skill and dedication but as
a fruitful partnership of law enforcement people, the public and
the news media.
</P>
<P>
   But why the nostalgia? ``It's part of Americana,'' said Rex
Tomb, chief of the FBI's fugitive-publicity unit. In the good old
days, he said, there were bank robbers, burglars and car thieves,
along with run-of-the-mill killers. ``Now, some of that stuff looks
almost quaint,'' Tomb said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest 10 include Osama bin Laden, the wealthy Saudi Arabian
suspected of masterminding the deadly 1998 bombings of two U.S.
embassies in Africa; Eric Rudolph, who is suspected of six
bombings, including fatal ones at the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta and
at an abortion clinic in Birmingham, Ala.; and Agustin
Vasquez-Mendoza, charged in the 1994 murder of an undercover
anti-drug agent.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the senior member of the list, Donald Eugene Webb,
whose speciality was jewelry-store burglaries. He is 68, if he is
still alive. His face, luckily for him a forgettable one, has been
adorning post office walls since he made the most-wanted list on
May 4, 1981, several months after he capped his career by killing a
police chief in a small Pennsylvania town.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Eugene Webb (also known as A.D. Baker, John S. Portas and
various other aliases) is a good starting point for any discussion
about criminals on the run. But first, some history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, a wire-service reporter asked the FBI for a list of the
``toughest guys'' it wanted to capture. The agency happily
complied, supplying a list of the 10 fugitives it considered the
most dangerous. Director J. Edgar Hoover was so delighted with the
interest stirred by the list that he made it permanent.
</P>
<P>
   On March 14, 1950, the 10 Most Wanted Fugitives program was
born. The first name put on the list was one Thomas Holden, a
Depression-era train robber who had already served 15 years in
prison and tried the straight life.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't like it. In 1949, he shot his wife and her two
brothers to death in Chicago after a drinking party and vanished.
On June 23, 1951, he was captured in Oregon after a newspaper
reader recognized him from a picture accompanying an article about
the most-wanted fugitives. The criminal lived out his days behind
bars.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI chooses candidates for the list based on their criminal
records and whether bureau officials think publicity might help in
catching them. Information leading directly to an arrest carries a
$50,000 reward.
</P>
<P>
   Fugitives have been caught in every state except Alaska, Maine
and Delaware, at an average of 1,000 miles from the crime scene.
Twenty-six have been caught in other countries. Seven women have
made the list. Several criminals have made the list twice, most
notoriously James Earl Ray, who made the list as the suspected
assassin of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and again after he
escaped from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Austin Bryant of Washington had the shortest stay on the
list. He was put on immediately after killing two FBI agents on
Jan. 8, 1969. He was taken off when he was found in an attic _ two
hours later.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, radio and newspapers were the big publicity
engines. Then came television. On May 19, 1996, an American
teen-ager living in Guatemala and surfing on his father's computer
visited the FBI site on that newfangled communications tool called
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager called up the most-wanted list and was amazed to
see the face of a local handyman who called himself Bill Young.
Could Bill Young really be Leslie Isben Rogge, a bank robber who
had escaped from an Iowa prison? He was, and very soon he was back
behind bars, the first most-wanted fugitive captured because of the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures and capsule biographies of the most-wanted are posted
at www.fbi.gov/mostwanted.htm. The site even includes some home
movies, preserving the subjects' strides and accents and tugs at
the ears and other mannerisms that can never be disguised entirely.
</P>
<P>
   There are no home movies of Donald Eugene Webb, who has toiled
as a butcher, managed a restaurant, repaired vending machines and
sold cars and real estate. He leaves big tips and he loves dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Enough about his good points, Tomb said. Webb killed a police
chief, shot him point-blank after beating him. The heartbreak of
the victim's survivors must never be forgotten, Tomb said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the FBI still displays the forgettable face of Donald
Eugene Webb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
