<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0975 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-L.A.-TRANSFORM-REVIEW     03-18 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-TRANSFORM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INSECURE CITY LOSES, OR REDISCOVERS, ITS IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ People here recoiled at the news last week that
The Los Angeles Times had been sold to an out-of-town company, with
many moaning that this insecure city _ frequently described by its
residents as a shapeless megalopolis that doesn't even have, or
deserve, a professional football team _ had been robbed of an
essential piece of its identity.
</P>
<P>
   But the real symbolic weight of the event may not have been that
the Tribune Co., a media giant from Chicago, bought Los Angeles'
most influential newspaper, but that it was up for sale in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   The institutional voice of this multi-throated city, controlled
for more than a century by a wealthy family that defined the
establishment, had been sold off to the highest bidder. The deal
drove home the reality that Los Angeles' once solid civic
architecture has been largely dismantled in recent years, under
pressure from dramatic economic and demographic changes. And no one
is quite sure what will replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what was disconcerting for many is that it is not at all
clear what kind of power structure will replace the one that
appeared to be waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the sale of The Los Angeles Times there's a loss of the
last remnants of our old governing structure,'' said Antonio
Villaraigosa, the speaker of the California state Assembly and a
declared candidate for next year's mayoral race. ``Something will
take the place of the old structure, but it's hard to say what it
will look like.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Legaspi, a real estate developer and a member of the board
of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, said he believed that
the talk here all week of a loss of identity with the sale of The
Los Angeles Times was really code for the resistance of many people
to the strong tide of ethnic change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss of identity was not because companies were sold but
because of the demographic changes here,'' Legaspi said. ``People
tended to react against it. The business and political leaders, the
old stakeholders, they didn't know how to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Eli Broad, the chairman of Sun America and a longstanding civic
booster who has helped create two major museums and is a leader of
the committee planning this summer's Democratic presidential
convention, said he agreed that some people were overreacting
simply out of fear of the new. The city still has powerful
basketball (the Lakers) and baseball (the Dodgers) franchises, he
noted, and the economy, now driven by small, entrepreneurial
companies, is thriving. He said, though, that the changes were
deep, their ultimate impact uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it hadn't happened,'' Broad said of the sale of the
newspaper. ``I wish it had stayed with local ownership, but I'm not
sure it matters. The old power structure is changing and we're
headed toward something new.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs of civic change have been conspicuous. Forty years
ago, when the city's elite decided that they needed a major new
performing arts center, Buffy Chandler, the wife of The Los Angeles
Times' publisher, Norman Chandler, organized her friends and built
a world-class complex. Just a few years ago, efforts to construct a
new cultural complex downtown, Disney Hall, foundered
embarrassingly for lack of money until a last ditch private
fund-raising effort got construction moving.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles lost out to Houston last year in a bid to get a new
professional football franchise, in large measure because city
leaders would not offer as generous a financial package. The San
Fernando Valley, a generally affluent, mostly white swath of the
city, has been trying to secede.
</P>
<P>
   Giant corporate citizens like Lockheed, Rockwell International,
Unocal and First Interstate Bank have either moved, been sold or
broken up, and now Arco, a staunch city booster for years, is set
to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   But even while there are signs that the cohesiveness of the old
elite has frayed, there are also signs that a new civic order is
taking shape and that it is responding to the realities of a city
which is roughly 60 percent Hispanic and Asian American and less
than 28 percent non-Hispanic white .
</P>
<P>
   For instance, this past week the Autry Museum of Western
Heritage said it would open a major exhibit this summer documenting
the role of Chinese Americans in the west, the largest such show of
its kind.
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from its traditional focus on middle-class car
culture, the Petersen Auto Museum has a first-of-its-kind exhibit
on lowriders, the flamboyant street cruisers favored by Chicanos
here. When the Getty Museum was initially flooded with visitors, it
eliminated all radio advertising, except on Spanish-language
stations.
</P>
<P>
   The United Way of Los Angeles, an organization whose board was
often seen as a badge of prestige for the city's elite, announced
earlier this year that it was adopting a new philosophy under which
it would cut contributions to many of the organizations it had
traditionally supported, like the American Heart Association and
the American Lung Association.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it will start contributing a portion of the $62 million
it raises each year to programs that focus on poor people in the
inner city _ meaning largely new immigrants. And the group says it
will be offering not hand-outs but programs to help the recipients
get better jobs, buy their own homes and prepare their children for
English-language schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very much colorblind in making this new policy,'' said
Dominic Ng, the chairman of EastWest Bank and head of the United
Way committee that formulated the policy. ``But what we did will
move us away from what you might call mainstream white America. Los
Angeles is changing, so we had to change. You can't look back and
be sentimental. You move forward and respond to the realities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
