<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; var-z
u s BC-COACHES-MIKES-REVIEW-     03-18 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACHES-MIKES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA'S INDECENT EXPOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(Duplication notice: Also sent with `a' code) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By ALAN SCHWARZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vince Lombardi kept saying no. For three years, Ed Sabol, the
president of NFL Films, had tried every argument to entice the
Green Bay Packers' coach to wear a microphone on the sidelines.
Still no. So with the clock running out, Sabol went deep:
``Vince,'' he said, ``let us put a mike on you, and we'll make you
the John Wayne of pro football.''
</P>
<P>
   That did it. And a few years later, Sabol's 1967 prime-time
special, ``Lombardi,'' captured the autocrat with a new dimension
of authenticity. Showing him rail at referees and bark at his
players _ ``Everybody grabbin' out there! Nobody tacklin'! Grab!
Grab! Grab! Grab! Grab!'' _ the film cast his legend forever.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three years later, the never-ending rush for ``inside
access'' to sports personalities hit a speed bump last week:
Several National Basketball Association coaches risked $100,000
fines by refusing a league edict to wear microphones during games.
Their reasoning was simple _ that as much as fans would love to
hear snippets of how they sketched out that last pick-and-roll or
lit a fire under a sullen superstar, some parts of their jobs can't
be done properly with the specter of millions of eavesdroppers.
</P>
<P>
   What they were saying, in effect, was that this is not the
Lombardi era any more; rather than embrace what the media can do
for them, they fear what it can do  &UR; to &LR;  them. It's the difference
between John Wayne and John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA wanted to wire coaches to make their product more
appealing to the interactive generation, which craves more intimate
glimpses behind what were once closed doors. (Cameras inside locker
rooms have also been proposed.) Network television ratings are down
14 percent this season, and the league is scrambling to deliver
something more delectable.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what the coaches fear they will provide. Giving
away strategy is one thing, but ``No more laziness, Alonzo!''
morphs from an exhortation into a public flogging. Although remarks
are not heard live but are spliced together by a production crew
for use minutes later, what the networks and coaches consider
worthwhile will surely lie on opposite ends of the salacious scale.
</P>
<P>
   A feeling of helplessness before the increasingly invasive news
media has already pushed sports figures further and further into
the bunker of cliche-speak, robbing the public of the authenticity
it craves. (Interviews with the Los Angeles Lakers' Shaquille
O'Neal, for example, have the effervescence of oatmeal.) With any
untoward utterance instantly picked apart throughout an impregnable
web of talk shows, newspaper polls and Internet sites, judgment
travels as fast and undaunted as electricity itself.
</P>
<P>
   As athletes retreat, technology moves in. Microphones have
sprouted all over the baseball diamond. They are mounted in the
foul poles, along the fences, in the bullpens and in the bases.
Catchers now wear Catcher-Cam, a gizmo that delivers video from the
top of their heads. ``For the casual fan, I think you have to bring
more of the game to them,'' said Steve Lyons, a Fox baseball
announcer and a former major leaguer known most for dropping his
pants on live TV after diving into a base. ``It's not just about
the game anymore. It's about the entertainment value.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees manager Joe Torre was less than entertained
when his curse word eluded the editors during a Fox broadcast three
years ago. During the 1998 playoffs, Mark Wiley, the Cleveland
Indians pitching coach, didn't realize his NBC microphone was on as
he went through the signs with his catcher. ``I called my wife
after the game,'' Wiley recalled afterward, ``and the first thing
she said was, ``Did you mean to say all the things you said?'''
</P>
<P>
   Football pioneered the use of in-game wireless microphones with
NFL Films in the 1960s. Its first attempt, during a 1965 game
between the Philadelphia Eagles and Baltimore Colts in Miami,
evidenced a few bugs _ the weak transmission from Eagles coach Joe
Kuharich often intermingled with dispatches from the Biscayne
Maritime Commission relaying mackerel locations to nearby
fishermen. The current president of NFL Films, Steve Sabol (Ed's
son), remembers how Chicago Bears coach George Halas was so
profane, ``There wasn't one sentence we could use.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL Films protected its coaches at every turn, editing out, for
example, Houston Oilers coach Bill Peterson's goofy mixed metaphors
(``Let's run that play up a pole and see if it floats''). Tommy
Protho had so little faith in his dreadful 1975 San Diego Chargers
that his locker-room pep talk consisted of, ``If each of you guys
play the game of your lives, and they play the worst game of their
lives, we still don't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabol didn't broadcast that speech because, he said, ``We're
part of the family.'' Speaking of the current NBA situation, he
added: ``I'm not sure some kid in a truck who's going to be working
for another network in two years will do the same thing. I can see
why the coaches are concerned about it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the NBA mollified its coaches somewhat. The league
allowed them to trade their clip-on microphones for one mounted
near the bench _ right on the edge of the bunker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
