<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0901 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-OIL-POLITICS-REVIEW-2     03-18 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-POLITICS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXING OIL AND POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(Also see GASOLINE-MOTORISTS-REVIEW) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Super Tuesday has come and gone, but stand by for
another defining event. Call it OPEC Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the stage. The oil cartel, once dismissed as a
has-been, has displayed startling muscle in the past year, sending
oil prices tripling to more than $30 a barrel. That has sent
gasoline prices soaring, and suddenly the American economy no
longer seems quite so invincible.
</P>
<P>
   At the next meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, on March 27 in Vienna, the question on the table will be
whether it is time to reverse the price tide. The answer matters a
lot, and not just to experts worried about the pace of
international economic growth. In this election year, what happens
March 27 will touch directly on American wallets, by determining
just what kinds of prices American voters confront every time they
pull up to the pump all spring and summer _ and right up to
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, then, that oil is quickly becoming an issue
between George W. Bush and Al Gore, who effectively clinched their
party's nominations in the Super Tuesday primaries of March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of issue voters take home with them,'' said
Andrew Kohut, a public opinion expert and director of the Pew
Research Center in Washington. ``On some issues, like campaign
finance, that don't really affect voters directly, the voters will
often say that neither candidate is any better than the other. But
on issues that affect the old pocketbook, there is a greater
propensity for voters to choose sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, a bedrock assumption about the political campaign has
been that anyone trying to unseat the Democrats from the White
House would have a tough job persuading Americans to be
dissatisfied. Even as Wall Street rockets along, the economy has
managed to keep inflation down and unemployment almost nonexistent
at the same time _ for most of a decade. That is not the kind of
situation to make a voter uneasy about his or her wallet, or
resentful of a member of the White House team. Or so Al Gore's
managers have assumed.
</P>
<P>
   Enter uncertainty. A first blast of ire over soaring fuel prices
is already being registered by American truckers, who have
demonstrated twice in Washington in the past month. And government
statistics released last week showed that producer prices increased
by 1 percent in February, their largest such gain in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of that surge was due to higher energy costs. Even
though Wall Street seemed to shrug off the bad news, the
inescapable nature of gasoline prices will make them all but
impossible for ordinary Americans to ignore, experts say. Bad news
at the pump is bound to compound any gnawing sense of uneasiness,
particularly if the Federal Reserve Board continues to weigh in
against inflation with incremental increases in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gasoline prices are the most visible prices in the United
States,'' said Donald Ratajczak, director of economic forecasting
at the University of South Georgia. ``Every time you drive to and
from work, they're staring you in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Translate that into political terms, and it is easy to
understand how high the stakes are for the Clinton administration,
and Gore in particular, at that meeting in Vienna. Even if a
decision is made then to boost oil production, prices will remain
high over the summer. But if they are receding by, say, October,
voters could approach Election Day reassured about the future. And
that is what Democrats are hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps explain the sense of alarm with which the
administration sent Energy Secretary Bill Richardson off to the
Middle East to push for a decision to produce more. For now, at
least, all signs do point to such a move, , easing the yearlong
shortage if not eliminating it. In the last week, prices have
fallen back from their $34 peak, thanks to a Saudi-Iranian
agreement to seek a production hike.
</P>
<P>
   One thing going for the Americans as they seek a price rollback
is the knowledge that the oil producers' unity last year was
exceptional _ a product of cooperation not just among OPEC members
but by non-OPEC members like Mexico and Norway, whose economies
also suffered when prices fell too low. Now the situation is
reversed, and Americans can argue that if oil prices choke the U.S.
economy, the producers will be damaging their most important
customer, on which the entire global economy and their hopes for
economic partnership rely.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson made that case on a two-week trip last month in which
he met with top Saudi and Kuwaiti officials. He has also made it in
meetings with other oil producers, including Venezuela, a member of
the cartel, as well as Mexico and Norway. Those last two have
already signaled a receptiveness to the U.S. argument, and neither
is expected to sign on to renewed OPEC production limits, making
them much harder to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite Richardson's entreaties, at least some OPEC
countries _ particularly price hawks like Iraq, Libya and Algeria _
have so far remained reluctant to tamper much with a strategy that
restored their upper hand after years of budget shortfalls that
they traced to low oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   What many remember with trepidation is what happened after a
meeting in Jakarta in 1997, the last time the cartel agreed to a
big production increase. The price of oil plunged, ultimately to
well below $10 a barrel. That is what set the stage for last year's
production cutback.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0986 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-OIL-POLITICS-REVIEW-2     03-18 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-POLITICS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXING OIL AND POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(Also see GASOLINE-MOTORISTS-REVIEW) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
