</P>
<P>
   Richardson made that case on a two-week trip last month in which
he met with top Saudi and Kuwaiti officials. He has also made it in
meetings with other oil producers, including Venezuela, a member of
the cartel, as well as Mexico and Norway. Those last two have
already signaled a receptiveness to the U.S. argument, and neither
is expected to sign on to renewed OPEC production limits, making
them much harder to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite Richardson's entreaties, at least some OPEC
countries _ particularly price hawks like Iraq, Libya and Algeria _
have so far remained reluctant to tamper much with a strategy that
restored their upper hand after years of budget shortfalls that
they traced to low oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   What many remember with trepidation is what happened after a
meeting in Jakarta in 1997, the last time the cartel agreed to a
big production increase. The price of oil plunged, ultimately to
well below $10 a barrel. That is what set the stage for last year's
production cutback.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This time, no one is sure how far the countries will be prepared
to go. The experts' best guess so far is a quota hike of about 1
million barrels a day _ less than half of the 2 million to 2.5
million barrels a day that Energy Department statisticians say will
be needed to meet world demand.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that scenario, the department's Energy Information
Agency still predicts that U.S. gasoline prices will turn higher
before there is any sign of relief. The national average, now at
$1.53 a gallon, is now projected to peak at between $1.56 and $1.80
a gallon sometime in May. And though prices would then begin to
turn down, it is highly unlikely that the average price would drop
below $1.30 a gallon by Election Day, said Jay Hakes, the agency's
director
</P>
<P>
   That sets the scenes for a long summer and autumn in which high
gas prices could become an even bigger part of American life and
the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Republicans have rushed to exploit what they see as a
chink in Gore's economic armor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he would have pressed harder to persuade OPEC
countries to ``turn on the spigots,'' and said he is considering a
call to repeal a 4.3 cent federal gasoline tax approved in 1993 as
part of President Clinton's economic plan, for which Gore cast the
tie-breaking vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore spokesman, Douglas Hattaway, said: ``The administration
is in tough negotiations with the OPEC countries, and that is where
the solution lies.'' One Republican, Sen. Charles Grassley of Iowa,
is calling for cuts in aid and arms sales to OPEC members, on
grounds that the organization is seeking a stranglehold on the
world economy. So far, though, the two presidential candidates have
steered clear of such table-thumping.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps tellingly, the Clinton administration chose last week to
extend a new olive branch to Iran, a major adversary for 21 years
but also a pivotal member of OPEC. Last year, its cooperation with
Saudi Arabia in clamping down on production was crucial in the
decision to squeeze oil supplies. This year, it and Saudi Arabia
seem likely to play precisely the opposite role.
</P>
<P>
   News of the gesture to Iran immediately provoked criticism from
some Republicans on grounds that Iran remains on America's list of
terrorist nations. But, then, it was also a week when the
television news was showing some gas prices hitting $2 a gallon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
