<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0903 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-POPE-JERUSALEM-ART-97     03-18 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-JERUSALEM-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE'S PILGRIMAGE TO ISRAEL FRAUGHT WITH TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator
map is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ What best represents the tensions that await Pope
John Paul II when he arrives on Tuesday for a momentous six-day
pilgrimage to ``the lion's den,'' as an Israeli magazine cover
labeled the Holy Land?
</P>
<P>
   Is it the Islamic mufti's refusal to attend an interfaith
gathering convened by the pope because the Israeli chief rabbi will
be there? (A last-minute substitute sheik was found.)
</P>
<P>
   Is it the brouhaha in Israel after the Star of David was erased
from the ambulance that will travel in the pope's entourage, though
it is customary to remove insignia wherever he travels?
</P>
<P>
   Is it the Palestinian assertion that the pope's visit to a
refugee camp will signal Vatican support for the right of
Palestinian refugees to return to their former homes in Israel?
</P>
<P>
   Or is it perhaps the heaping garbage that surrounded the
Basilica of the Annunciation in Nazareth until late last week?
Fearing a fetid embarrassment, the Israeli government reluctantly
paid the indebted city to settle a strike so that the trash mounds
could be removed from the site where tradition says the archangel
Gabriel told Mary she was pregnant with Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   For John Paul, 79, this pilgrimage is a deeply spiritual climax
of a 22-year papacy during which he never visited Jesus'
birthplace, walked in his footsteps or prayed at the site believed
to hold his tomb.
</P>
<P>
   (He did make a previous pilgrimage, however, in 1963, and Pope
Paul VI, never uttering the word Israel, made a 12-hour stop in the
Jewish state in 1964.)
</P>
<P>
   As the first official visit of a pope to Israel, it is also the
culmination of John Paul's long effort to redefine the way the
church sees Jews _ as ``elder brothers'' rather than traitors _ and
to reconcile Jews and Catholics. For many Israelis who stopped to
gape on President Street last week, the sight of the Vatican's
yellow and white flags being hoisted to flutter beside the Israeli
Stars of David was a breathtaking, history-making image.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is purely spiritual or brotherly in a land where
religion and politics are permanently entwined, almost embedded in
the sandstone that has borne witness to millenniums of turbulent
history. And so the pope's visit is freighted with multiple layers
of sensitivities, and each stop on his carefully negotiated
itinerary means different things to different people with different
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   So many of the steps he makes will be on diplomatic eggshells,
tuning out the claims and counterclaims of sovereignty, religious
rights and nationalism. There is the recent claim by Yasser Arafat,
the Palestinian leader, that the apostle Peter should be considered
a Palestinian, for instance. And then there is the rabbis' demand _
unmet _ that the Vatican cancel a Mass in Nazareth on the Feast of
the Annunciation because it falls on the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's schedule was carefully balanced: a visit to Yad
Vashem, the Holocaust memorial site, in Jerusalem, and a visit to
the Dehaisheh refugee camp in Bethlehem; a meeting with the chief
rabbis, a meeting with the mufti (who agreed to see the pope
without the rabbis.)
</P>
<P>
   But demands are being made for even more symmetry. Since the
pope has recognized the enormity of the Holocaust, Islamic
religious leaders say he should acknowledge the atrocities
committed during the Crusades, too. ``He has asked forgiveness from
the Jews, so he should ask forgiveness from the Muslims,'' said
Sheik Ikrima Sabri, the mufti, who heads the Higher Islamic
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul will arrive in Tel Aviv on Tuesday evening as
Israelis, dressed in costumes, will be celebrating the festive
holiday of Purim. A parade to mark this proud, raucous holiday of
Jewish survival will be led by a float featuring a 12-foot-high
figure of John Paul. That is, unless the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party
succeeds in having it banned as what one Shas member called a way
of ``debasing ourselves before the goyim,'' or non-Jews.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60,000 pilgrims _ 45,000 on special charters _ will
fly in from around the world to accompany the pope. They will join
a very small group of Roman Catholic faithful in Israel and the
Palestinian territories. Counts vary, but combined Palestinian and
Israeli statistics suggest that 180,000 Christians are in the Holy
Land, and many of them are Eastern Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the numbers, the Christian population of the Holy Land
has dwindled because of emigration and accounts for about 2 percent
of the overall population, down from 13 percent in 1900. This
raises another agenda for the pope, one that is more germane to his
trip. Many Palestinian Catholics want a heightened incentive _ like
a papal appeal _ to soldier on as the guardians of the faith in the
Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Christians in general, while they welcome the
spotlight on their existence, do not want to be mistaken for the
pope's faithful or those who must make amends for anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not representing the local Christian community but the
Western church,'' said Michael Karayanni, a Greek Orthodox,
Palestinian law professor who lives in Jerusalem. ``Religious
tensions between Christians and Jews are not felt here. Political
tensions, yes. But there isn't much anti-Semitism in our
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope will devote a full day to the Palestinian-governed
Bethlehem area.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, a Muslim, has assiduously courted the pope and
aggressively moved to propose the Palestinians as less ambivalent
caretakers than the Israelis for Christian holy places in the Holy
Land.
</P>
<P>
   For Arafat, the pope's visit is a tremendous coup, an on-site
and almost unrivaled affirmation of Palestinian sovereignty. To
have the pope make simultaneous first visits to Israel and the
Palestinians suggests a kind of equivalency of recognition that the
Palestinians have long sought from the world.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians are, comparatively speaking, ahead of the game.
The Vatican established diplomatic ties with Israel in 1993, 45
years after the country was founded. Before a Palestinian state has
even been established, the Vatican has recognized Palestinian
aspirations and did so more strongly than ever in a new agreement
last month, irking Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This visit reaffirms the Vatican's longtime support for the
legitimate rights of the Palestinian people,'' said Emile Jarjoui,
a senior official of the Palestine Liberation Organization. ``His
visit to the Dehaisheh refugee camp is a clear message that the
suffering of refugees should end and their cause needs a just
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis have grown up suspicious of Christians and many
are ignorant about Christianity. The Israeli textbooks'
presentation of Catholicism leaves off more than 35 years ago,
before Vatican II discarded dogma that blamed Jews for the death of
Christ. It ends with Pope Pius XII's failure to speak out publicly
against the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The textbooks ignore decades of profound transformation in the
church's attitude toward Jews,'' said Rabbi Ron Kronish, director
of the Inter-Religious Coordinating Council in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   At a forum last week in Jerusalem, Rabbi David Rosen, local
director of the Anti-Defamation League, was asked skeptically how
deep the transformation really went. ``Well, as the pope said to
me, in my eleventh visit to the Vatican, as we were being served a
glatt kosher meal,'' the rabbi said, pausing for emphasis because
he felt part of his point was already made.
</P>
<P>
   The ultra-Orthodox are largely indifferent to the pope's visit
while a small number of religious extremists are openly
antagonistic. A scrawl on the rabbinate building last week
screamed, ``Don't meet with the pope!'' But polls show that most
Israelis view the pope's visit favorably, even if they question the
potential for profound reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Most are far more interested in the political than the religious
significance of the trip, especially the pope's handling of
Jerusalem's status. But they perceive the pope to be a positive
force, and he is widely portrayed here as having done more than any
other Christian leader ``in 2,000 years'' to reach out to the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his visit can change some attitudes in Jewish
communities toward Christians,'' said Moshe Hellinger, a modern
Orthodox Jew and political scientist at Bar Ilan University. ``But
it depends how firmly he says things. Remember, Jews are afraid
that Christians feel compelled to convert us. As long as the church
doesn't say firmly that we don't want to convert Jews, no serious
dialogue will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's visit to Yad Vashem will be watched closely by many
Israelis who want to hear the pope apologize more concretely than
previously for the church's wartime silence and for its role in
fostering the anti-Semitism that fed the Nazi demonization of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli political leaders have commented little about the visit,
which represents an overwhelming logistical and security
undertaking for the state. Some, like Shlomo Ben Ami, the internal
security minister, see it as an opportunity to demonstrate to the
world that Israel is a tolerant, open society. Most, however, give
the impression that their aspiration, as one senior security
official said, ``is to get through it without a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope hoped keenly to bring together the three Abrahamic
faiths during his trip. But even this well-intentioned goal bumped
up against the tensions of the place.
</P>
<P>
   First the chief rabbi objected, because he did not want to enter
a church complex for the interfaith meeting. Later, he was
persuaded after learning that the gathering would not be held in
the church itself.
</P>
<P>
   The mufti, on the other hand, started with a positive attitude
and then apparently underwent a change of heart, said Monsignor
Eugene Nugent of the apostolic delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not see a need to meet with Jewish religious leaders,''
Sheik Sabri said in an interview. ``Meeting with them at this time
will make it appear as if everything is normal in Jerusalem, when
in reality it is not. There is an occupation and it should be clear
that there is no peace in the city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
