<HEADER>
A0917 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-CHEN-NYT &LR;      03-18 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN IN THE NEWS: CHEN SHUI-BIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TAIWAN-ELECTION, TAIWAN-VOTERS and CHINA-TAIWAN) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ People here who know Taiwan's president-elect,
Chen Shui-bian, often describe him as remote and impersonal. In
interviews, the 49-year-old politician comes across as almost
robotic, reciting policy positions with a blank gaze and a frozen
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for many Taiwanese, not least those who swept him to victory
Saturday and ended more than 50 years of rule by the Nationalist
Party, Chen's public image was fixed by a supremely personal
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   When Chen was greeting supporters at a rally in 1985 after
losing a county election, his wife, Wu Shu-jen, was hit by a truck.
Chen's supporters say the accident, which left Wu paralyzed from
the chest down, was politically motivated. Evidence to prove that
is sketchy, but it cemented Chen's reputation as a man who paid a
high price, and shoulders a heavy burden, for his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two sides to the Taiwanese spirit: the fighter, and
those who want to maintain the good life,'' said Paul S.P. Hsu, a
lawyer here. ``Chen Shui-bian is a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen's grim determination has fueled a political career of
vertiginous highs and pitiful lows. And it has now made him
Taiwan's first leader from outside the long-ruling Nationalist
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's Democratic Progressive Party formally favors an
independent Taiwan _ a position dangerously at odds with that of
China. Chen has said he will not declare independence, though it is
far from certain that this will mollify the leaders in Beijing, who
view Taiwan as a renegade province.
</P>
<P>
   Born on Feb. 18, 1951, in a farming village in southwestern
Taiwan, Chen is the son of illiterate parents who worked as day
laborers. Life for the Chen family was bleak. They lived in a mud
house with little furniture and the constant fear of destitution.
At school, the young Chen often went without lunch.
</P>
<P>
   But he was an extraordinarily diligent student, and education
became his ticket out of deprivation. He graduated from primary
school first in the country. In 1969, he enrolled in National
Taiwan University, where he studied law and graduated with yet more
accolades in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Taiwan was still firmly under the grip of the
Nationalists _ followers of Chiang Kai-shek who fled China after
the Communist takeover in 1949 and established a government in
exile on the island. Chiang dreamed that Taiwan would reunify with
the mainland, and he brooked no dissent. Yet there were already
stirrings of an opposition movement, which advocated independence
for Taiwan. That movement would later became the Democratic
Progressive Party.
</P>
<P>
   As an ambitious young lawyer in the 1970s, Chen initially had
scant interest in politics. He joined a prestigious maritime law
firm and married Wu, the daughter of a wealthy doctor, in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Chen entered politics by accident in 1980. He was asked to
defend two pro-independence leaders who had been charged with
sedition, after a protest in the port city of Kaohsiung. To
nobody's surprise, in an island firmly controlled by the ruling
Nationalists, Chen lost the case. But his political senses were
piqued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized this experience was not just a legal issue,'' he
said in an official biography published in 1998. ``I came to accept
the defendants' political arguments and ideals. I became a
believer. We should have two separate countries across the Taiwan _
one country on each side of the straits.''
</P>
<P>
   That belief was to become both the root of Chen's appeal and a
cudgel in the hands of his political enemies. Supporters,
particularly native Taiwanese, flocked to Chen. But the
Nationalists, and more recently the Chinese government, portrayed
the studious lawyer as a wild-eyed zealot who was intent on
dragging Taiwan into a dangerous and futile split from its Chinese
motherland.
</P>
<P>
   Chen began his political career with a successful bid for the
Taipei City Council, where he acquired a reputation as a crusader.
But his fortunes soon reversed. He lost a county-wide race in his
native Tainan County, and his wife was injured. Worse, in 1986, he
was jailed for eight months after losing a libel case filed by a
Nationalist official, whom he had accused of plagiarizing a
doctoral thesis.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's release from prison in 1987 coincided with the
Nationalist government's decision to suspend martial law and
legalize political parties. Chen joined the Democratic Progressive
Party, where his keen intellect and indefatigable work habits made
him a star.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Chen was elected mayor of Taipei, and swept into the
city like an avenging angel, shutting down its sex trade and
evicting apartment dwellers to build public parks. After a stormy
term, during which he managed to make enemies and alienate friends,
he was turned out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said the defeat matured Chen. Never the
zealot that his opponents claimed, Chen has now become a master of
political nuance. He recognizes that very few Taiwanese are willing
to risk their material well-being on a lunge for independence.
``You can see that he has basically abandoned the idea of a
Republic of Taiwan,'' Hsu said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the verbal traps that Chen must avoid in discussing
Taiwan and China may be one reason he is so programmed. In a recent
interview, Chen noted that he was the only candidate with a son who
would be drafted if Taiwan were invaded by China. ``As a father, I
understand the fear of parents who don't want to put their children
into danger,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0923 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-2TAKES-N     03-18 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN NATIONALISTS LOSE PRESIDENCY AFTER HALF-CENTURY REIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Chen Shui-bian, an opposition politician who
long advocated Taiwan's independence, was elected its new president
Saturday, ending half a century of Nationalist rule and risking
dangerous new tensions with mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, a 49-year-old lawyer who served as mayor of Taipei and
struggled and against martial law in the 1980s, won with 39 percent
of the vote in a bitter three-way race. The Nationalist candidate
slumped to third place.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's victory, the first transition of power in Taiwan's young
democracy, was made possible by a schism in the Nationalist Party
that led one of its leaders, James Soong, to mount an independent
candidacy. Soong, a populist former governor of Taipei province,
came in second with a strong 37 percent showing; Vice President
Lien Chan, the Nationalist candidate, got just 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Chen and his Democratic Progressive Party called for
independence from the mainland, which considers Taiwan a wayward
region that must return to the motherland. The president-elect, who
will take office May 20, succeeding Taiwan's first elected
president, Lee Heng-tui, has recently moderated that position,
saying no declaration of independence is needed because Taiwan is
already sovereign.
</P>
<P>
   But Beijing has called Chen deceitful and issued dire warnings
against his election, with Prime Minister Zhu Rongji all but saying
last week that it could provoke a war.
</P>
<P>
   To reassure nervous citizens and governments abroad _ including
Washington, which has pledged to help Taiwan defend itself if
attacked _ Chen tried to reach out to the Chinese in his victory
speech Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   He avoided inflammatory references to Taiwanese ``statehood,''
and said he would seek deeper economic ties and ``a permanent
peace.'' He has promised he will not declare independence or hold a
referendum on the issue unless Taiwan comes under attack.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a statement certain to anger Beijing, he also
pledged, ``We won't let Taiwan become another Hong Kong or Macau.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement read on Chinese television, Beijing said it
would adopt a wait-and-see attitude toward Taiwan's new leader, and
reiterated its view that Taiwan is part of Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton said the election ``clearly
demonstrates the strength and vitality of Taiwan's democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the election provides a fresh opportunity for both
sides to reach out and resolve their differences peacefully through
dialogue,'' he said. ``The United States strongly supports such
dialogue and is committed to promoting peace, stability and
prosperity in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some 82 percent of Taiwan's voters turned out after a campaign
dominated by worries over relations with China and public
impatience with the corrupt political practices of the
Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Chen faces a legislature still dominated by the Nationalists,
who have ruled firmly since Chiang Kai-shek retreated here from the
Communist-dominated mainland in 1949. Taiwan is in for a period of
unprecedented political reshuffling and uncertainty, even as it
faces a possible confrontation with China.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Speaking to thousands of cheering supporters, Chen declared
Saturday night that his success ``is not a victory for the
Democratic Progressive Party _ it is a victory for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a subtle friendly gesture to China and to some of his
fiercest enemies at home _ those who fled the mainland after the
Communist victory in 1949 _ Chen gave his acceptance speech in
Mandarin Chinese rather than in the Taiwanese dialect he often used
in campaign rallies.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen refuses to accept China's hallowed notion of ``One
China,'' and in answer to a question Saturday night he said China's
``one country, two systems'' formula for enlisting Taiwan as an
autonomous region ``would never be accepted by the Taiwanese
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to defend this island but we are also
determined to seek peace and stability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reassure foreign governments that he will not
take reckless actions, Chen has promised to retain the current
defense minister, top national security officials and the military
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, like 85 percent of the island's population and many
supporters of his political party, is considered an ethnic
Taiwanese, descended from people who immigrated from the mainland
centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Taiwanese resentment of the brutal takeover of their island
by Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists in the late 1940s eventually
spawned a dissident movement for democracy and independence. In the
1970s and '80s, early leaders of what would later become the
Democratic Progressive Party were imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Chen became involved as a defense lawyer for the dissidents and
then entered politics after martial law was lifted in 1987 and the
Democratic Progressives became the main opposition party. For many
of the party's supporters, Saturday night's victory is an emotional
culmination of decades of struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists, for their part, have been thrown into turmoil
and their powerful chairman, President Lee Teng-hui, is now on the
spot. Lee's feud with Soong helped cause the devastating defeat and
the party could suffer a permanent split if the popular Soong tries
to form his own party now.
</P>
<P>
   Soong apologized to his supporters for losing, but did not say
whether he would seek to form a new party or try to take over the
Nationalist Party.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Already Saturday night, Huang Quen-huei, the secretary general
of the Nationalists, offered his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, a large crowd of Soong's supporters, most
of then longtime Nationalists who felt Lee had betrayed the party
by snubbing Soong, marched to Lee's official residence and his
party's headquarters in central Taipei to shout for Lee to step
down as party boss. Both buildings were surrounded by riot police
and there were some scuffles.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has called for public disclosure of the Nationalists'
multibillion-dollar investments and confiscation of any properties
that should belong to the state rather than the party.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen also said Saturday night that he bore no animosity
toward his campaign opponents and that he hoped to work with the
Nationalists to build a ``cross-party alliance,'' though he did not
offer specifics.
</P>
<P>
   His ability to forge a coalition will be crucial to his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chen Shui-bian's immediate challenge is that he has to act as
a president, not just a leader of an opposition movement,'' said
Chu Yun-han, a political scientist at National Taiwan University.
``Nearly two-thirds of the electorate didn't vote for him, and many
are deeply suspicious of his approach to the mainland.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeated Nationalist candidate, Lien, had used scare tactics
in the final weeks of the campaign, suggesting that Chen could
bring disaster to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night he was more gracious in conceding, calling the
transition a milestone for Taiwan's democracy. ``I hope the new
president will handle state matters properly, leading our country
into a new era,'' he said before a crestfallen line of party
leaders. ``We can still regroup. From today we need to engage in
self-examination and reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee remained silent and secluded in his residence, where he
summoned the military chief of staff and the defense minister.
There have been reports here of Chinese troop movements on the
mainland, although no one expects imminent military action.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's victory reflected, in part, a demographic trend that
bodes ill for the Nationalists and also for China's hope of
peaceful reunification: many younger people have no allegiance to
the Nationalist Party their parents long served, and think of China
as a distant concept.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first presidential election in 1996, more than 1
million young people became eligible to vote, Chu noted. And fully
half of them said in recent surveys that they were voting for Chen,
who is seen as representing youthful energy and cleaned-up
politics.
</P>
<P>
   China's military threats do not intimidate such people. A
typical example is Yang Jie-lung, a 27-year-old graphic designer.
Approached Saturday morning as he left the polling booth, he would
not discuss his preferences until his mother, a lifelong
Nationalist, was out of earshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Chen Shui-bian can win,'' he said. ``He's the best one
to clean up the problems left by the Nationalists, and as mayor he
did a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the mainland's dark warnings, he said: ``We are not
obliged to take any advice from China. We are electing our own
president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
