<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING SAYS IT WILL WAIT TO SEE HOW TAIWAN VICTOR ACTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see CHINA-TAIWAN-ARMS-REVIEW) 
 (bl)  
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The surprisingly strong victory of Chen Shui-bian in
Taiwan's presidential election generated plenty of buzz in Beijing
on Saturday, but was greeted with an official cold shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Through much of the last month, China's top leaders have been
threatening trouble if Chen won the election (although they
carefully never referred to him by name), suggesting that if
Taiwan's voters chose pro-independence forces they might not get
the chance to choose again.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night those remarks clearly needed some clarification.
And in its few terse words the government seemed initially at least
to be setting off on a moderate course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election of the leader of Taiwan and its outcome cannot
alter the fact that Taiwan is part of Chinese territory,'' said a
government statement that was read at the tail end of the 10 p.m.
news in a brief first report about Chen's victory. ``We will listen
to the words and observe the actions of Taiwan's new leader and
wait and see in which direction he takes cross-straits relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Some midlevel officials and researchers said that the government
was almost certainly at work revising its failed Taiwan policy and
would probably come out with a more explicit statement soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result was really unexpected, and also the margin of
victory,'' said a researcher at a Communist Party research agency.
``But it puts them in a really tight spot because they worked so
hard to avoid this outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The news took a while to sink in with the official news media.
Long after Chen had delivered his acceptance speech, the only
mention of the election was a brief sentence from the government
news agency, Xinhua, noting that Chen was ahead in the Taiwanese
provincial elections. China still considers Taiwan a renegade
province that will someday reunite with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   But it was hard to keep a lid on since many urban Chinese
quickly learned of Saturday's stunning victory on the Internet and
watched Hong Kong television stations, which are now widely
available in up-market housing complexes.
</P>
<P>
   And in this group the news met with general nervousness but also
mixed reactions, with some expressing anger at the party as well as
anti-American sentiment, but most predicting that China should and
would take a wait and see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the future very much depends on Chen's policies after
he is elected,'' said Zhang Yunling, director of Asia Pacific
Studies at the Chinese Academy of Social Science. ``The only thing
the Chinese government can do now is wait and see what he will
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Chen's party is theoretically in favor of independence
for Taiwan, Chen himself has backed away from this position, saying
that he would declare independence only if invaded.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang said that if Chen ``made some compromises,'' the currently
tense situation could be improved. But he added: ``I think the
danger was never more than it is now. If his policies lead to a
more pro-independent stance, then the leaders are pushed into a
corner and will have to react.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people still doubt that there will be war, but some said
Chen's win would certainly strengthen the hard-liners who have
advocated stronger measures against Taiwan. Just before the last
Taiwanese elections, in 1996, the Chinese lobbed missiles toward
Taiwan as a warning.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The leadership will be under pressure,'' said a propaganda
official. ``This time they held off from military exercises and
used words and threats. And now look what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   On Chinese Internet chat rooms throughout the day, students
suggested demonstrating at the U.S. Embassy if Chen won.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, in the hours after Chen declared victory, the
streets in the embassy district were quiet, but both the U.S.
Embassy office building and the ambassador's residence had more
than the normal guard force from the People's Armed Police, at the
request of the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday there were practical as well as ideological
considerations that sway party decisions _ like China's drive to
enter the World Trade Organization _ and many suggested they would
put a damper on any reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the leadership would have intellectually prepared for
this result, the reality will take time to swallow and it will make
for many complications,'' the researcher at a government research
agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
