<HEADER>
A0928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1055(     03-18 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1055(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLE OF RUSSIAN OLIGARCHS UNDER PUTIN IS UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ When Boris Yeltsin was re-elected Russia's president in
1996, he owed his victory in large part to the so-called oligarchs,
a group of Russian multimillionaires _ bankers, oilmen and media
moguls _ who in turn owed their wealth and influence to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   This closed and cozy circle worked very well for a few in Russia
until Dec. 31, when Yeltsin suddenly resigned, putting the Kremlin
in the hands of Vladimir Putin, the man poised to win Russia's
presidential election on March 26.
</P>
<P>
   Now observers are asking whether a Putin victory will be bogged
down by the same kind of debts to the same, or a similar, group of
oligarchs that compromised Yeltsin's final scandal-ridden years in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Having obtained their wealth by buying state assets on the
cheap, trading heavily on their Kremlin connections, most of
Russia's oligarchs survived the devastating financial crash of
August 1998 by a cynical manipulation of their remaining
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Some have since moved to legitimize their holdings, while others
have rushed to acquire new ones _ the recent dash to divvy up
Russia's aluminum industry is a case in point. But now, with a new
era beginning in the Kremlin, virtually all are looking over their
shoulders at Putin, an ex-KGB agent who is promising to put
Russia's affairs in order, and its criminals in jail.
</P>
<P>
   For Russian businessmen and foreign investors, Putin's treatment
of the oligarchs will be a litmus test of his promises to put the
Russian economy, and its vast natural wealth, under the rule of
law, with equal opportunities and conditions for all.
</P>
<P>
   For Russian voters, many of them poor and bitter, how Putin
handles such figures as Boris Berezovsky _ the most notorious of
oligarchs _ will be a sign of the new leader's relationship to the
Family, an almost mythical clique made up of rich businessmen,
Yeltsin relatives and Kremlin aides that has become the watchword
for Russia's crippling crony capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   On this issue, as on others, Putin has made reassuring
statements. ``It is necessary to prevent anyone from latching onto
power and being able to use it for their own purposes,'' he told
supporters late last month. He also put forward _ albeit in vague
terms _ an agenda of legislative reform, such as long-awaited
changes to the tax code that are hailed by business leaders as a
step toward more sensible regulation of Russia's unruly economy.
</P>
<P>
   But looking at deeds rather than words, Putin has yet to show
his hand. And that is a disappointment for those who expected him
to start by taking a tough line against the favorites of the
Yeltsin era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, my own hopes that he would distance himself
from them are wrong,'' said Evgenia Albats, a well-known Russian
investigative reporter.
</P>
<P>
   According to Albats and others, the signs of Putin's continued
engagement with Yeltsin's inner circle are small, but telling.
Mostly they revolve around individuals _ such as Alexander
Voloshin, the Kremlin's chief of staff, or Valentin Yumashev, one
of his predecessors, both bona fide members of the Family and both
widely reported to have kept a hand in the Putin campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left the same gatekeepers in place, Yumashev and Voloshin,
and we know that they are closely connected to Berezovsky,'' Albats
said. There are also reports that Yeltsin's daughter, Tatyana
Dyachenko, who emerged publicly in 1996 as her father's campaign
adviser, has also been involved in the Putin campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When Putin took office on New Year's Eve, his first decree
granted immunity to Yeltsin, and provided material support _
housing, cars, medical benefits _ to members of the Yeltsin family.
Soon afterward, he dismissed Dyachenko from her official Kremlin
job, but reappointed Voloshin. He demoted the first deputy prime
minister, Nikolai Y. Aksyonenko, reputedly a Family favorite, but
kept him in government in his old job as railway minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear rumors that he promised to keep Voloshin for a year,
and if he does, it means that the Family is still in full
control,'' said Igor Malashenko, president of NTV-Holding, part of
the media group controlled by Vladimir V. Gusinsky, another
oligarch who has been at war with the Kremlin _ and Berezovsky _
for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Malashenko and others say the appointment of Mikhail Kasyanov,
who as first deputy prime minister now heads Putin's government and
has been linked in the Russian press to members of Berezovsky's
clan, could also be a sign of Putin's dependence on that clique.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Putin appoints Kasyanov as the next prime minister,'' Lilia
Shevtsova, a senior analyst at the Carnegie Endowment for Peace,
said at a recent conference, ``it would be a very nasty, a very bad
sign. It would be a sign that Putin cannot be independent, that he
cannot brush aside the influence of several important and very
powerful groups that still continue to rule Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The doings of Russia's oligarchs have long been a running soap
opera in the Russian press, where feuds and alliances are reported
on regularly, usually with scant detail and heavy interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   The recent fight over the aluminum industry has been widely
depicted as a clash between two clans _ one including Berezovsky
and his ally Roman Abramovich, and the other including Oleg
Deripaska, an aluminum magnate and ally of Anatoly Chubais, the
former Kremlin aide, head of Russia's electrical utility monopoly,
and an honorary oligarch.
</P>
<P>
   According to investment analysts, Berezovsky and Abramovich,
operating through 24 separate offshore companies, are believed to
have acquired 60 percent to 70 percent of the Russian aluminum
industry by buying up stakes in two major plants, Krasnoyark and
Bratsk.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has done nothing to stop the property deals, nor has he
shown favorites. Although both he and Chubais have connections that
date from their days together in St. Petersburg, Putin has been
distinctly cool to his old colleague, particularly in a recent
book-length interview released last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he tries to distance himself, he tries to find some point
above the oligarchic fray,'' Shevtsova said of Putin's silence.
``He cannot control, he probably knows this, and he takes it rather
calmly because he doesn't have enough power to stop it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, the battles portrayed in the media are a
reflection of battles over the media, which some analysts see as
the area of Russian life in which the oligarchs wield the most
political influence.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his control over ORT, Russia's largest and most
watched television station, Berezovsky has often proved to be a
useful, even essential, ally for the Kremlin. That was most
apparent in last fall's parliamentary election campaign, when
several prime-time programs on ORT mercilessly, and successfully,
slashed the main opposition party headed by former Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov and the mayor of Moscow, Yuri Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential campaign has been spared such vicious attacks,
although NTV, the flagship station of Gusinsky's empire, has
maintained a critical view of Putin and, in particular, the war in
Chechnya. Putin, in return, has refused all interviews on NTV, and
with any other media in the Gusinsky empire.
</P>
<P>
   A recent announcement that ORT's broadcasting license will go on
the auction block in May, when it expires, has been seen as an
attempt to show Berezovsky his place. ``Berezovsky is a loose
cannon and ORT is a huge propaganda machine,'' Malashenko said. ``I
doubt very much he will accept being pushed out, but they are
keeping him hanging, which means until the end of May he should
behave loyally.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Shevtsova, feel the real test for Putin will be
whether he chooses to pursue investigations against Berezovsky and
others that were dropped a year ago when the Kremlin forced out
Russia's chief prosecutor, Yuri I. Skuratov, with a sex-and-video
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Others doubt that Putin would be ready, during his first months
in office, to take on such a powerful opponent, and the team that
engineered his meteoric rise. Both Berezovsky and Voloshin are
widely credited with the strategy that propelled Unity, a pro-Putin
party, to victory in the December parliamentary elections. It was
that result, many analysts believe, that convinced Yeltsin to
relinquish his office six months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Pyotr Aven, a former finance minister and president of Alfa-Bank
who supports Putin, argues that relations between the oligarchs and
Kremlin officials have been inflated in the public mind, and that _
despite the habit of some Kremlin insiders of vacationing in Europe
with favored businessmen _ it is those in government ministries who
really bend to oligarchs' pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Aven feels that Putin himself is independent and will remain so.
For one thing, the Putin campaign is not as dependent on private
money as Yeltsin's was in 1996, when the president had to stage an
extravagant, come-from-behind victory over Gennady Zyuganov, the
Communist Party leader. This time there are no Putin advertisements
on TV, no T-shirts, no rock concerts.
</P>
<P>
   And Aven, for one, has not been asked to donate money this time,
as he was then. ``They don't need it,'' he noted wryly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
