<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-RED-ARMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN ARRESTS 4 TERRORISTS AFTER LEBANON EXPELS THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a swift denouement after years in flight, four
members of the Japanese terrorist group known as the Red Army were
arrested here Saturday after they were expelled from Lebanon and
denied entry into Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of the four, who have been pursued by Tokyo for two
decades, came after an intricate legal and diplomatic minuet by
Lebanon that seemed filled with subtle betrayals. Lebanon was eager
to relieve itself of an embarrassing burden, but wary of strong
Arab public opinion in support of the suspected terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Having served their time in Lebanese prisons for entering the
country illegally, the four were put on a Middle East Airline
flight Saturday to Jordan, which had reportedly granted them entry
visas. Upon their arrival in Amman, however, the four were
immediately handed over to Japanese diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised by their arrival and they left to an unknown
destination after we refused to allow them to enter Jordan,'' said
the Jordanian minister of information, Saleh Qalab. ``We considered
them transit passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the unknown destination was a heavily guarded
tarmac at Narita airport outside Tokyo, where the four arrived
aboard an Aeroflot flight at 5:19 p.m. They were arrested aboard
the airplane and then driven under heavy police escort to two
detention centers in Tokyo for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth Red Army member, Kozo Okimoto, 52, was granted asylum in
Lebanon but remains at Roumyieh prison outside Beirut, where he
reportedly awaits a suitable place to resume private life.
Okimoto's asylum was officially granted for health reasons, related
to the torture he says he suffered in Israel during his 13-year
imprisonment there.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese authorities said Saturday night that they were
``disappointed'' about Okimoto's asylum in Lebanon, where he is
something of a popular hero for his role in the May 1972 grenade
and machine-gun attack on Lod Airport at Tel Aviv. The three-man
attack killed 26 people, including 16 Puerto Rican Roman Catholic
pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   Okimoto, who converted to Islam last week, adopting the first
name Ahmed, had been serving a life sentence in Israel for the Lod
attack but was released in 1985 in a prisoner exchange with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of the four other fugitives, who are wanted in
connection with aircraft hijackings, bombings, embassy takeovers
and other terrorist attacks that made the Red Army one of the most
feared subversive groups of the 1970s and '80s, was nonetheless a
major victory for Japan's patient, persistent diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Successive Japanese governments have quietly but relentlessly
maintained the pressure on Lebanon and other Middle Eastern
countries to cooperate in their efforts to apprehend the suspects,
whose photos are still posted at every Japanese immigration point.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Saturday's arrest, only a handful of the 40 or so
active members of the Red Army were in Japanese custody. Indeed,
the woman who founded the group in 1971, Fusako Shigenobu, remains
a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   According to a State Department report on the group, Shigenobu,
who is 54, established the Red Army after breaking away from
another radical leftist group, the Japanese Communist League-Red
Army Faction. The group is believed to have trained its members in
the Syrian-controlled Bekaa region of Lebanon with support from a
radical Palestinian group, the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Army's stated goals were to overthrow the Japanese
government, eliminate the monarchy and foment world revolution. For
two decades, until it began to fade into obscurity, the Red Army is
believed to have worked in a loose network with other international
revolutionary groups, including the Baader-Meinhof Gang in Germany
and the Red Brigades in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four members returned to Japan Saturday is Haruwo
Wako, 50, who was in charge of the group's military operations and
reportedly planned the occupation of the American and Swedish
Embassies in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Masao Adachi, 59, a former film director who joined
the group in 1974 and was its spokesman. Adachi married a Lebanese
woman in a highly publicized ceremony in Lebanon and converted to
the Greek Orthodox faith last month.
</P>
<P>
   The only woman in the group returned Saturday is Mariko
Yamamoto, 58, who was a publishing house employee before leaving
Japan in 1972. She reportedly joined the Red Army in Paris, where
she worked at a department store.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth returnee is Kazuo Tohira, 46, who had also served
prison time in Sweden in connection with his activities for the
group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
