<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HMO-MEDICARE-740(2TAK     03-18 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-MEDICARE-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DEMANDS TO REVIEW MEDICARE MAILINGS BY HMOS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Calif.)   (jw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Medicare officials have accused health maintenance
organizations of sending false information to their elderly
subscribers in an effort to mobilize them to pressure Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In response, federal officials have begun demanding that HMOs
submit newsletters and other documents to the government for review
before sending them to Medicare beneficiaries. In this way, the
government says, it will be able to ``correct any misstatements or
misleading information.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said they could also impose civil fines and
other penalties on HMOs that send misinformation to beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The health plans insist that they are only exercising their
right to communicate with their members on important public issues,
including recent cuts in Medicare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But federal investigators say they have found evidence that HMOs
billed Medicare for some of their lobbying expenses. Federal
regulations generally prohibit government contractors from using
federal money for lobbying intended to influence Congress.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs say that some lobbying expenses may indeed have been
included with other administrative costs in the past. And they
insist that the practice was not forbidden by the Medicare law.
</P>
<P>
   A new study by the Health Care Financing Administration, which
runs Medicare, says HMOs have disseminated ``false and/or
misleading information'' that blames the agency for rising health
care costs, increased premiums and reductions in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   One HMO, run by Highmark Inc., a Blue Cross and Blue Shield plan
in Pennsylvania, told members that the Clinton administration was
cutting $11 billion from Medicare ``without approval from
Congress.'' It urged Medicare beneficiaries to send letters of
protest to Congress and the administration.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Dr. Robert A. Berenson, a senior Medicare
official in charge of the managed care program, said, ``We are very
concerned about health plans that have been misleading
beneficiaries and misrepresenting facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Berenson acknowledged that any restrictions on the free-speech
rights of HMOs could run afoul of the First Amendment. But in a
recent memorandum to the head of the Medicare agency, Berenson said
some restrictions were necessary because otherwise patients would
receive inaccurate information, and the agency would be ``unfairly
blamed for benefit cuts or premium increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials considered issuing a regulation that would
flatly prohibit HMOs from using their members' names and addresses
for lobbying or political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   But, Berenson said, lawyers at the Department of Health and
Human Services have ``serious concerns about the statutory basis
for such a regulation,'' fearing that it could be challenged as
``an unconstitutional restriction on speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than ban such communications, federal officials said,
they will review them in advance to correct any inaccuracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat of public criticism'' by the government will
probably be effective in getting HMOs to revise their
communications with beneficiaries, Berenson said in his memo. ``In
extreme situations,'' he said, the government can correct the
misinformation by writing directly to patients.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Berenson said that ``we would not engage in
prior restraint,'' but that HMOs would find it advisable to
cooperate with the government. ``You shouldn't hear a political
message in the midst of promotional material for the medical care
at a particular organization,'' Berenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare provides health care to 39 million people who are
elderly or disabled. More than 6 million of them, about 16 percent
of all beneficiaries, are in HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Karen M. Ignagni, president of the American Association of
Health Plans, the main lobby for the managed care industry, said,
``The Clinton administration is limiting our ability to communicate
with our members because it disagrees with our message.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, she said, federal officials have told some HMOs
that they cannot use their newsletters to inform Medicare
beneficiaries of a grass-roots coalition lobbying Congress for more
generous HMO payments and benefits. More than 80,000 elderly people
have joined the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're merely imparting information to beneficiaries,'' Ignagni
said. ``They have a great deal at stake. They depend on us for
coverage of prescription drugs and other benefits not available in
the traditional Medicare program.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and HMOs are theoretically partners
in the Medicare program, but their relations have deteriorated in
the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton contends that HMOs are overpaid by Medicare,
while the health plans contend they are paid too little to cover
the benefits they provide.
</P>
<P>
   Health plans have also clashed with Clinton over legislation
that would grant patients a wide range of new rights, including the
right to sue HMOs for injuries caused by negligent treatment or the
denial of care.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare payments to HMOs vary from county to county, and many
HMOs have pulled out of the Medicare program in counties where they
consider the payments inadequate. Many health plans that remain in
the program have cut benefits, including coverage of prescription
drugs, or increased the premiums and co-payments charged to
beneficiaries this year.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Weinstein, a spokesman for Highmark Inc., which operates
Keystone Health Plan West in Pennsylvania, said the company lost
$18 million on its Medicare HMO business in 1998 and lost $5
million to $10 million on the program in 1999. But, he said, the
company continues to operate the health plan for 145,000 Medicare
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein defended the letters to beneficiaries in which
Highmark accused the Clinton administration of making ``arbitrary
cuts'' in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a grass-roots communication with our members,''
Weinstein said. ``We felt it was important to do what we could to
preserve managed care as an option for the tens of thousands of
Medicare beneficiaries who want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elderly people often join HMOs to obtain low-cost drug benefits,
and they lose such benefits if they return to the traditional
fee-for-service Medicare program. Insurance companies offer
supplemental insurance with drug benefits, but those Medigap
policies can be expensive, often costing more than $2,200 a year.
</P>
<P>
   June Gibbs Brown, inspector general of the Department of Health
and Human Services, said HMOs had billed Medicare for tens of
thousands of dollars in lobbying and political activities. Such
items were lumped together with other ``administrative costs''
reimbursed by Medicare, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., the ranking member of his party on
the Ways and Means Health Subcommittee, said: ``HMOs have been
lobbying Congress, spending millions of dollars against the
patients' bill of rights and seeking more money from Medicare. That
is their right.''
</P>
<P>
   But to pay for such activities, Stark said, ``HMOs should use
their profits, not the money that is supposed to go to
beneficiaries in medical care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
