<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-VOTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN'S VOTERS YEARN FOR FRESH STYLES AND IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANCHI, Taiwan _ Lee Teng-hui has loomed large over Taiwan, and
nowhere more than in this hilly seaside village northwest of
Taipei: Lee, the island's first democratically elected president,
was born here in a sturdy red brick farmhouse that still draws
visitors every day.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, as Taiwan's voters went to the polls to elect a
successor to Lee, the president's birthplace was deserted. And in
town, where people lined up to cast their ballots, Lee's legendary
influence over Taiwanese politics was disappearing at the voting
booth as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I admire Lee, it's important for me to vote for
someone who will change Taiwan's society,'' said Chiang Wen-ding,
53, a retired factory worker who voted for Chen Shui-bian, the
Democratic Progressive candidate, over the president's anointed
successor, Vice President Lien Chan.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Jian-long, a 22-year-old business management student who
voted for James Soong, the independent candidate, said: ``As a
young person, I'm not influenced at all by whom Lee Teng-hui says
to vote for. I voted for James Soong because he would be a new kind
of leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang Ai-huei, 31, an office worker, said she too voted for
Soong, because she yearns for fresh leadership after five decades
of rule by the Nationalist Party. ``Voting for Lien Chan is like
voting for Lee Teng-hui, and I think it is time for a change,''
said Chang, as she gestured impatiently toward the Nationalist
Party's campaign headquarters across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with more than a dozen voters in Sanchi on Saturday
indicated strong support for both the eventual winner, Chen, and
the runner-up, Soong, who is a bitter rival of Lee. Remarkably,
even in the president's hometown, voters _ young and old, male and
female _ rebuffed Lee's repeated pleas to elect Lien and extend the
Nationalist Party's half-century reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I listen to Lee Teng-hui?'' asked Pan Yue-ching, a
38-year-old housewife. ``I have my own opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime loyalists consoled themselves that although they
were rejecting Lee's party, they were not necessarily flouting his
deeper wishes. They seized on widespread rumors that Lee has frosty
relations with Lien and prefers Chen on a personal level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee is secretly supporting Chen, but as KMT chairman, he must
support Lien,'' said Chiang, the factory worker, using the initials
for Kuomintang, the Nationalist Party's Chinese name. Another Chen
supporter interjected, ``President Lee keeps shouting Lien Chan,
but when he holds up his hand, it says 5,'' a reference to Chen's
number on the presidential ballot.
</P>
<P>
   People who voted for Chen said they believed that he would shake
up Taiwan's political culture, which has been ossified by more than
50 years of single-party rule. They accused the Nationalist Party
of corrupting the electoral process by buying votes and through
other forms of bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Although some voters said that electing Chen could increase
tension between Taiwan and mainland China, they said it was not
enough to disqualify him. ``It's always the same between these two
countries,'' said Lee Fung-lin, 38, an unemployed restaurant
worker. ``They just shout at each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiang said he was not about to let Beijing dictate his choice.
``I've been living with the threat of mainland China for 50 years,
so I'm used to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on this day of defeat for Lee Teng-hui and his party, a
cousin, Lee Teng-wong, stopped on a bucolic road near the family
home to chat about the legacy of his famous relative. ``The
Taiwanese people will remember him for bringing them democracy,''
the cousin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
