u i BC-PUTIN-CHECHNYA-545&AMP;AD     03-18 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-CHECHNYA-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN CHIEF SEES AN END TO RESISTANCE BY CHECHENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With Russia's presidential elections just a week away,
Acting President Vladimir Putin sought to reassure voters Saturday
that the war in Chechnya was drawing to a close and that some
Russian troops would soon be on their way home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no more organized resistance,'' Putin said.
``Large-scale military operations are coming to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's assurances were intended to pre-empt an emerging debate
about Russia's military campaign. And they have coincided with a
demand by Russia's Press Ministry that rebel leaders in the
separatist southern region of Chechnya be denied air time on
Russian television and radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   The Press Ministry insists that its ban is needed to fight
terrorism. But the political aim appears to be to minimize news
media coverage of rebel commanders, whose defiant comments are an
unpleasant reminder that a Russian victory is not yet at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly most Russians still consider the military operation a
long-overdue effort to bring order to the breakaway republic.
Opinion polls also indicate that a majority of Russians still
consider the military campaign a success.
</P>
<P>
   As the March 26 election draws closer, however, Russians have
been jolted by some disturbing scenes, including the solemn funeral
in the western Russian town of Pskov for 84 paratroopers killed in
a single battle, and bitter fighting over the Chechen town of
Komsomolskoye, which passed from Russian to Chechen control and
then back again.
</P>
<P>
   It is also apparent that the Russian military has not met its
self-declared deadline to wrap up the fighting well before the
March elections. Even so, the official Russian casualty toll now
stands at 1,628 killed and 4,308 wounded since the start of the
military operation on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   So Putin sought to paint a brighter picture Saturday, reassuring
voters on a state-owned radio station that Russia had broken the
back of the rebel resistance. Putin also said that surplus troops
would soon be brought home, although he was careful not to provide
any specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's generals, for their part, did their best to buttress
Putin's confident message. Russian soldiers in Chechnya and other
remote regions began casting their presidential ballots on Friday.
Gen. Gennady N. Troshev, the deputy commander of Russian forces in
the North Caucasus, left no doubt whom he expected his troops to
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the right to vote for whomever they want,'' Troshev
said. ``But I think the military has made its choice. We know who
the man is who today stands by and supports the military as we
complete our task.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, however, neither the task in Chechnya nor the debate
about it is over. Russian commanders have said that about 25,000
troops will be stationed indefinitely in Chechnya after the main
fighting is over to counter guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
   They include the Russian military's 42nd motorized division, a
brigade of Interior Ministry troops and a unit of border guards.
And even Russia's allies in Chechnya have cautioned that much
fighting lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illusions that spring will arrive today or tomorrow should not
be nourished,'' said Akhmad-Khadzhi Abdul Kadyrov, the Chechen
mufti, who has supported Russia's military intervention.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Confronted with the prospect of a prolonged fight, Russian
authorities have pressed the news media to tone down the already
careful coverage of the war. The Press Ministry warned last week
that news organizations that broadcast interviews with rebel
leaders or quote them directly would violate Russian laws on
fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The main targets of the ban include Shamil Basayev, the Chechen
warlord; Aslan Maskhadov, the leader of the Chechen republic; and
Movladi Udugov, a spokesman for the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mass media have no right to give terrorists and people
suspected of terrorism an opportunity to advertise themselves,''
said Mikhail Lesin, the press minister.
</P>
<P>
   The warning was, in effect, a shot across the bow of news
organizations, and it is not yet clear how vigorously the Russian
government will enforce the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Ekho Moskvy, a Moscow radio station with a heavy news format,
managed to finesse the ban earlier this month by interviewing
Maskhadov but then having one of its broadcasters read the quotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ministry's initial request was not to interview the
leaders of the Chechen military bands at all, but we refused,''
said Aleksei A. Venediktov, the editor in chief of Ekho Moskvy.
``We narrate their words, we just don't broadcast their voices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
