u i BC-TRADE-GEPHARDT-875&AMP;AD     03-18 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-GEPHARDT-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CHINA TRADE, GEPHARDT'S ON A TIGHTROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mich., Calif., Ore., Va.)  (mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House
Democratic leader and a hard-liner on foreign trade, is an unlikely
kingmaker for a decisive China trade deal that he fears could
jeopardize his greater goal of reclaiming the House this fall.
</P>
<P>
   He is walking a political tightrope as Congress debates whether
to grant China permanent normal trading privileges, a vital step
for its entry into the World Trade Organization. Congress now
conducts an annual review of China's trading status.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Gephardt's party is in the minority, House
Republican leaders say they need 80 to 100 Democratic votes to
ensure victory. Senate approval is considered likely. That is why
Gephardt, of all people, is trying to make the best of a trade pact
that, on his past record, he should be fighting.
</P>
<P>
   On virtually every contentious trade issue during the Clinton
administration, from the 1993 North American Free Trade Agreement
to fast-track consideration of other trade pacts, Gephardt has led
the opposing charge, calling for tougher labor, environmental and
human rights standards.
</P>
<P>
   But in the bruising battle over China trade, Gephardt has been
conspicuously, and deliberately, noncommittal, urging his
colleagues to vote their consciences. He has told business leaders
he will not rally Democrats against the pact.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's allies say he is worried that his open opposition
could inflame an already divisive issue among House Democrats and
imperil the prize he covets so dearly: regaining control of the
House and becoming its speaker instead of minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick has his eye on November, as he should,'' said Rep.
Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., who opposes permanent trade relations.
``He's got to make sure whatever he does he doesn't exacerbate the
split in the caucus over this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt is also responding to changing dynamics within his
caucus and with the politics of money on Capitol Hill. Pushed by an
increasingly influential bloc of so-called New Democrats in the
House who are pro-trade and fiscally conservative, Gephardt is
courting American companies, especially high-tech concerns, with
the promise of a more business-friendly Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is working. Soft-money contributions doubled in a
year, to $12 million last year, from corporate donors who
traditionally have funneled their campaign money to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Openly opposing a China deal that corporate America warmly
embraces would undercut Gephardt's new fund-raising tack.
</P>
<P>
   So for now, at least, Rep. David E. Bonior of Michigan, the
Democratic whip, is leading the political fight against the accord,
while Gephardt assumes a behind-the-scenes role to keep his rank
and file united and to explore prospects for a party-healing deal.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Thursday, Gephardt again sidestepped the
question of how he would vote, and said he was trying to broker a
compromise with the administration, labor unions, business groups
and House Democrats who support the accord and those who oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a way to have an alternative to simply taking
away the process of looking at China's performance on human rights
in the Congress and leaving nothing in its place,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Such an alternative would include a ``methodical way'' to ensure
that China abides by its trade treaties, a mechanism to evaluate
its human rights record, and a code of conduct for American
companies doing business in China, he said. Under any compromise
legislation, Gephardt said, the United States should have the
option of imposing trade sanctions against China if it violated the
agreement, as long as the penalties were consistent with World
Trade Organization rules.
</P>
<P>
   But Gephardt conceded that hammering out conditions ``with
teeth'' at this stage might be unrealistic. ``I don't know if it
can be done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic aides said another possibility was legislation that
could halt lending from the World Bank, the International Monetary
Fund and the U.S. Export-Import Bank should China flout
international norms.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of suggestions are being floated, none of which have
come to point of resolution,'' Commerce Secretary William Daley
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Foes of permanent trade status for China say that Gephardt's
strategic silence does not mean he is any less committed to their
cause, and they insist that his coyness has not hurt their
campaign. ``It's going great for us, and our numbers are growing,''
said Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Bonior, working closely with labor unions, environmental groups
and human rights organizations, asserts that two-thirds of the 211
House Democrats will vote against giving up Congress' annual review
of China's trading status. ``The leader shares my views,'' Bonior
said of Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   But other foes of permanent trade relations, while voicing
sympathy with Gephardt's political plight, say they will need his
influence come crunch time in late May or so when the
administration wants Congress to vote on the accord. ``I expect
that when the chips are down, Dick Gephardt will be with us because
that's what's in his heart,'' said George Becker, president of the
United Steel Workers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Peter A. DeFazio, D-Ore., said: ``He's been given a nearly
impossible problem by a president who doesn't care. When we get
down to the last few critical votes, and the White House is
offering bridges and defense contracts, that's when we're going to
need Dick to weigh in.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of permanent trading status applaud Gephardt's
statesmanship, and they say that by playing peacemaker rather than
spear-carrier, Gephardt has buoyed their chances of winning. ``He
has been very balanced in his presentation,'' said Mickey Kantor,
Clinton's former chief trade official and commerce secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James P. Moran, D-Va., who favors permanent trade status
for China, predicted that Gephardt's bridge-building with the White
House would succeed, and ``it'll bring another 20 to 30 Democratic
votes on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican supporters of permanent trading status are more
suspicions about Gephardt's motives. When the administration
earlier last week released the previously classified details of the
agreement the United States negotiated with China last fall, House
Speaker Dennis Hastert chided Gephardt and Vice President Al Gore
for their relative silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the release of the text of this agreement will
prompt the vice president and minority leader to finally let the
American people know where they stand on this issue,'' Hastert
said.
</P>
<P>
   That may not happen until the final floor vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't twist arms on most bills, and certainly on trade
bills,'' Gephardt said. ``Every member has their own set of views,
their own situation with their own district, and they're going to
make up their mind on what they think is the right thing to do, and
that's the way it ought to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
