<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-SYMBOLISM-NYT &LR;      03-18 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SYMBOLISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING SIGNALS AND CUES TO PROJECT BUSH'S IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At the celebration here after Gov. George W.
Bush all but clinched the Republican presidential nomination
Tuesday night, the person chosen to introduce him was not some
longtime Republican bigwig or starry political celebrity. It was
Mayor Carlos Ramirez of El Paso, a man outside the traditional
party mold.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Ramirez is Latino. For another, he is a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   He took the stage after a reel of video highlights from Bush's
campaign that included a close-up of a cleric, presumably Roman
Catholic, who was smiling and laughing, presumably in adoration of
Bush. And Ramirez praised the Texas governor in a mixture of
English and Spanish, saying that Bush was a politician for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gracias a mi amigo,'' Bush told hundreds of supporters, who
happened to be gathered in a Jewish community center.
</P>
<P>
   It was a confluence of details and circumstances clearly meant
to portray Bush as a candidate eager to embrace diversity and
intent on broadening the Republican Party's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the definitive illustration of the extent to which
the Bush campaign stakes its ground, sculpts its appeal and manages
its image in the realm of verbal gestures and visual cues, subtle
signals and obvious signs.
</P>
<P>
   All last summer and fall, when Bush was cultivating a reputation
as a new-style Republican with a greater sensitivity and broader
reach than his political peers, the effort was largely grounded in
the places he went and the tableaus he assembled.
</P>
<P>
   He made more campaign stops in neighborhoods inhabited by
Latinos, blacks and Asians than perhaps any leading Republican
presidential candidate before him, and his campaign staff
demonstrated a knack for making sure the television footage and
magazine and newspaper photographs from these events showed Bush's
visage flanked by faces of different colors.
</P>
<P>
   It was a motif so prevalent that Vice President Al Gore's
advisers and allies fumed about it privately.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush sought to secure a victory in the South Carolina
primary by reaching out to religious conservatives there, he did
not suddenly take new positions, as news accounts of a rightward
tilt to his candidacy suggested.
</P>
<P>
   But he did speak in a different language and drape himself in
different surroundings, like Bob Jones University, a bastion of
Christian conservatism with a history of racial discrimination and
anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   And when Bush subsequently labored to ditch that political
baggage, Catholic priests began popping up near him in various
places: at an airport rally in Kansas City; on the dais with him at
a luncheon in Springfield, Ill.; in the footage shown at his
victory party here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading to the primary in New York, the Bush
campaign managed to find an upstate city _ Binghamton _ that staged
a St. Patrick's Day parade two weeks before the holiday. Bush
participated in it.
</P>
<P>
   Early this week, when he visited a strawberry festival in Plant
City, Fla., Bush stopped for a snack at a booth that happened to be
set up by St. Clement Catholic Church, and the word Catholic was
prominent on a banner in the backdrop of news photographs capturing
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've taken the Reagan model of symbolism to the 21st
century, down to every detail on every day at every event,'' said
Scott Reed, who ran Bob Dole's 1996 presidential campaign,
referring to Bush and his aides. ``They've taken it to the next
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said that such symbolism simply complements
substantive proposals that the governor has made to reach out to
many people whom the Republican party has sometimes overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's boldest education ideas, for example, aims to
improve the kinds of troubled urban schools in which minority
students are disproportionately represented.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's mission to encourage religious organizations to
do more social work counts on the participation of Catholic and
Jewish leaders and African-American churches, and many of his
visits to the inner city are to promote and explain this plan.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several political analysts said that Bush can surround
himself with so many visual reminders of racial and religious
diversity and not seem overly manipulative because these scenes
underscore actual alliances he has made.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's able to do it because he was forced, through two terms in
Texas, to forge relationships with Latinos and African-Americans,''
said David Doak, a Democratic strategist.
</P>
<P>
   But the company that Bush has kept and the language that he has
used on the campaign trail have not always been consistent,
suggesting that there are also strategic considerations at play.
</P>
<P>
   Before his battle with Sen. John McCain in South Carolina, his
answers to repeated questions about issues concerning gays were
worded in a relatively soft, conciliatory vein.
</P>
<P>
   But in South Carolina, Bush's diction was occasionally
different, as in his response when an interviewer for a Christian
radio station asked him how he felt about the possibility of
appointing someone who was forthcoming about his or her
homosexuality to a job in a presidential administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``An openly known homosexual,'' he said, ``is somebody who
probably wouldn't share my philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there was his appearance at Bob Jones
University, the public memory of which he sought to banish when the
Republican contest moved to states like New York and California,
where he needed to appeal to moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, who had not stumped with Bush in about a month,
suddenly reappeared on the campaign trail to attend that event, to
introduce the governor at several subsequent campaign stops in New
York and to extol his appeal to women.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Bush delivered a speech about the need for
acceptance and open-mindedness at the Simon Wiesenthal Center and
Museum of Tolerance in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
