<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0951 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-VOUCHER-ASSESS-63     03-18 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-VOUCHER-ASSESS-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: FLORIDA CASE CASTS DOUBT ON FUTURE OF SCHOOL
VOUCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Wis., Ohio, N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a Florida judge declared last week that giving students
taxpayer-financed vouchers for private-school tuition violated that
state's constitution, he bulldozed an important national testing
ground for school choice and posted a reminder that the legal
landscape for vouchers included several potential pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   For years, advocates of vouchers have watched enthusiastically
as the U.S. Supreme Court chipped away at the wall separating
church and state. The Florida ruling suggests, however, that even
if the Supreme Court upholds vouchers under the First Amendment _
as is expected _ vouchers could still be blocked by state
constitutional promises of a free public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strongest policy objection to vouchers is that it would
undermine the system of public education,'' said Laurence H. Tribe,
a constitutional scholar at Harvard University. ``What's
interesting about the Florida decision is it identifies a state
constitutional problem in that policy objection.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida ruling, which is being appealed, sets no precedent
for judges elsewhere but it might dim enthusiasm for voucher bills
pending in more than 20 state legislatures, as politicians already
wary of the heat surrounding the issue worry about passing programs
only to have them killed by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the political fallout on either side of this issue,''
said Eric Hirsch, an education analyst at the National Conference
of State Legislatures, ``to go through this and not be sure it can
be implemented is going to be a difficult decision for
legislators.''
</P>
<P>
   As vouchers gain in popularity, backed by a growing coalition of
poor inner-city parents and conservative philanthropists who share
a concern about failing public schools, their legal prospects are
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's ruling by Judge L. Ralph Smith of the Circuit Court
in Tallahassee, was the seventh in a string of victories for
opponents of vouchers in court cases around the country. ``We're on
a roll,'' exulted Robert Chanin, a lawyer who has led the legal
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of vouchers have kept a different tally, pointing
to five Supreme Court cases over the past two decades that
suggested a 5-4 majority supporting some use of public money in
parochial schools. They also noted that a Wisconsin ruling similar
to Smith's was overturned by that state's Supreme Court, leaving a
mixed record on even the narrow state issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way on earth that I would trade places with the
other side as far as jurisprudence is concerned,'' said Clint
Bolick, litigation director of the Institute for Justice in
Washington, which has helped defend most of the court cases.
``Everybody understands that the court that matters most is the
United States Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's ruling turned on a provision of the Florida Constitution
guaranteeing a ``uniform, efficient, safe, secure and high-quality
system of free public schools.'' Virtually every state added a
similar promise of public education to its constitution during the
Progressive Era early in the 20th century, but the language varied
widely, as has the litigation history in each state.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the fate of vouchers is more likely to be decided by
federal church-state questions, largely the interpretation of the
First Amendment's assertion that ``Congress shall make no law
respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free
exercise thereof.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has declined three times to review voucher
cases in recent years, but is widely expected to accept either the
Florida case _ should Smith be overruled by the state Supreme Court
_ or an Ohio case in which a federal judge declared in December
that Cleveland's voucher program illegally mixed government and
religion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of vouchers are relying on a 1973 case in which the
Supreme Court rejected a voucher program in New York State. But
advocates of vouchers contend that attitudes have shifted, pointing
to decisions that have allowed tax deductions for parochial school
tuition; public payment for an interpreter for a deaf student
attending a Roman Catholic school; and the use of state-paid
remedial tutors in religious school classrooms. A crucial test is a
New Orleans case pending this term on whether the government can
pay for computers and Internet connections at private as well as
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are basically two images that are vying for control: one
is the image of strict separation, the wall, the other is the idea
of equality,'' said Akhil Amar, a professor at Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ``The separation idea says no government money can ever go to
religion in any way. The equality idea says government shouldn't be
giving money to religion as such, but if government is giving money
to everyone, the religions should get money on equal terms.''
</P>
<P>
   It may come down to determining the difference between a fire
extinguisher and a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Few would argue that churches and synagogues are not as entitled
to fire and police protection as their secular neighbors. If the
government decided to distribute free fire extinguishers, surely it
should not skip over mosques and monasteries.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the state handed every child a computer to be used
at school? Could parochial-school students use their laptops for
religious instruction, or even prayer? If so, why not make the
whole cost of education transportable, from public school to
private, perhaps even to individual homes where parents handle
schooling themselves?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving toward the equality model,'' said Amar, one of
several liberal scholars who said they were skeptical of the
effectiveness of vouchers, but believed they passed constitutional
muster. ``Taken to its extreme, separation requires the
discrimination against religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolick and other supporters of vouchers see their programs as
comparable to the G.I. Bill, giving each family a check that can be
cashed at an array of schools _ public, private and parochial. But
there are two major differences: the vast majority of schools that
accept vouchers so far are religious, and the program is much
larger in scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it is true that the court in recent years has been
prepared to uphold some programs that channel some government money
into parochial schools, none of those programs have involved the
transfer of this massive amount of money,'' said Steven R. Shapiro,
national litigation director for the American Civil Liberties
Union, which has fought vouchers in court. ``There's a point at
which a difference in quantity becomes a difference in kind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
