<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PROVIDENCE-SCANDAL-2T     03-18 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDENCE-SCANDAL-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LATEST PROVIDENCE JOLT, EX-TAX OFFICIAL CONVICTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Renaissance, shmenaissance, some things in
Providence remain very much the same, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   In this reviving old city _ the real one, not the NBC prime-time
television version _ the central public drama playing lately
centers on a nest of graft-grabbing functionaries.
</P>
<P>
   It began more than two years ago when a world-class
whistle-blower agreed to secretly record his dealings with corrupt
tax officials, a sting federal authorities called ``Operation
Plunder Dome.''
</P>
<P>
   And it reached a denouement of sorts on Friday: A jury found the
city's former deputy tax assessor, Rosemary Glancy, guilty of
conspiracy, attempted extortion and mail fraud. Glancy, a city
employee for 26 of her 47 years, maintained her innocence and wept
in court.
</P>
<P>
   But that verdict does not end the drama's suspense. The real
talk of Providence, many people say, is whether federal
investigators will ultimately bring down Vincent A. Cianci Jr., the
city's beloved, marinara-sauce-making, convicted felon of a mayor,
who is a driving force behind its current much-trumpeted
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Cianci denies all wrongdoing, saying he accepts responsibility
for the City Hall corruption, but only because ``the buck stops at
my desk,'' not because of any criminal liability. In a telephone
interview, he also denied that the Plunder Dome affair reflected
much about Providence. ``There are many cities in America that have
the same thing going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But few cities have quite so extensive a rap sheet of
corruption, with scandals or actual convictions reaching from the
bottom to the very top echelons of city and state power _ from the
16 city workers and contractors jailed on charges including
conspiracy and fraud in a previous Cianci administration to the
conviction of former Gov. Edward D. DiPrete in late 1998 on 18
charges of corruption to resignations under the threat of
impeachment by supreme court justices.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island has put into effect some significant
anti-corruption provisions in recent years, but culture changes
slowly. So few in Providence have been surprised at the Plunder
Dome revelations, including one defendant's bald assertion,
captured on tape, that ``To do business in the city of Providence,
one must pay money to the appropriate official or authority.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rather, many sound like Steve Gordon, a 58-year-old teacher, who
said that as an honest taxpayer, he found it annoying that some
people paid bribes instead of taxes, but that it was nothing new in
Providence: ``As Yogi Berra said, it's deja vu all over again,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some specifics in the Plunder Dome case are certainly new, from
one defendant's instructions to refer to bribe money as ``pizza''
or ``things,'' to the Broadway-style closing argument in Glancy's
trial by Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Rose, in which he went
from roars to whispers and repeated, again and again, ``Innocent
dupe? Or corrupt public official?''
</P>
<P>
   The tapes have also offered some classic lines, like a
defendant's statement that he passed on bribes to other officials:
``I throw them money,'' he said. ``Then they cut the bull. I throw
them money, and they're happy. He's happy. Everybody's happy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Operation Plunder Dome'' came to light last spring, when FBI
agents descended upon City Hall to seize documents and arrested two
members of the Board of Tax Assessment Review.
</P>
<P>
   But the inquiry began more than a year earlier, when Antonio R.
Freitas, a businessman, began secretly video- and audio-taping his
bribery of city officials in exchange for favors like lowering his
property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   From April 1998 to April 1999, he recorded more than 100
conversations, federal authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes implicated Joseph Pannone, the 77-year-old former
chairman of the tax board, and David Ead, the vice chairman, in
deals in which they secured tax abatements worth many thousands of
dollars in exchange for bribes of much less. One bribe was $2,400,
for example; others reportedly ranged from $10,000 to $200.
</P>
<P>
   Four other people have also been charged, but all except Glancy
pleaded guilty. Glancy was only a minor target of the FBI inquiry,
but her trial turned into a forum at which the public could get a
peek at the Plunder Dome doings. They could hear snippets of tape
like the one in which Pannone said of Glancy, ``She bends, you know
what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I show some green, and she's all right, she's happy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pannone also claimed on tape that he had received tutelage on
bribery from Cianci, whose nickname is Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy told me to never talk on the phone, never get a check,
take cash one on one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cianci has told reporters that he had no involvement with
Pannone.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict on Friday, Margaret Curran, the local
U.S.attorney, told The Providence Journal that federal authorities
would push on with their inquiry into City Hall corruption, adding,
``This is one small part of a larger investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The question remains of how far, or rather, how high, the
investigation will reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems with this kind of corruption is that it's
sometimes hard to tell how far it leads,'' said H. Philip West Jr.,
executive director of Common Cause in Rhode Island. ``Is it only an
isolated pocket in an office where people keep the secret among
themselves, or does it extend upward in the administration? This is
a real tough one to analyze, but it increasingly appears that this
will reach upward.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In general, West said, Rhode Island has cleaned up its act
somewhat since the 1980s, overhauling its campaign finance laws,
its ethics rules and its judicial procedures, as well as
introducing term limits for statewide officials.
</P>
<P>
   But West is concerned, he said, by the ``enormous war chest'' of
campaign money Cianci has built up, and he is disturbed, he said,
that Cianci's approval ratings remain very high in polls: ``It's as
if we don't care what he does as long as we keep getting this
national shining city reputation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in some ways, Providence voters have already shown
exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Cianci was forced to leave office after he was
convicted on felony charges stemming from his assault using a lit
cigarette, ashtray and fireplace log on a contractor he accused of
having an affair with his estranged wife. But in 1990, he was
elected again, and he is now, with a total of more than 18 years in
office, the city's longest-serving mayor ever. He remains extremely
popular.
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, the city has moved rivers to create lovely
canals and lagoons, built a gigantic shopping mall and a new
convention center, and generally become a national model for how to
make a run-down old city hot again. It now boasts gondolas and a
new skating rink, among much more, and is increasingly attracting
high-tech companies that flee the steep prices of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview about the Plunder Dome investigation,
Cianci said, ``I'm sure that's a lot of drama, and it's the saga of
the city, ``but I can assure you _ I'm sure that my name has been
used, but I can assure you I had no involvement in any of that
stuff. And we continue on, we're just moving along, we're building
four brand new schools in the city and we'll be building new
hotels.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The city is also moving along somewhat in trying more
energetically to prevent such corruption. Cianci has been pushing
for a city ethics watchdog, and John J. Lombardi, the president of
the city's council, is calling for an ``ethics and integrity''
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The team should not only investigate but work to educate people,
Lombardi said. ``So, for example, person X walks into a department
and says, `May I have a copy of this? Oh, thank you, here's a
dollar bill, go buy coffee.' How do you handle something like that?
A lot of people don't know. They may not think it's anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-NYT &LR;      03-18 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AIRLINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA AIRLINE REPAIR CENTER IS IN TURMOIL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash., Alaska, Calif.)   (jw) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After 64 mechanics at Alaska Airlines signed a letter
saying they had been ``pressured, threatened and intimidated'' to
cut corners on repairs and maintenance, the airline put one of its
managers on administrative leave and said Saturday that it was
conducting detailed interviews with all of the mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil at the maintenance center here comes amid a
continuing federal investigation into the Jan. 31 crash of one of
the airline's MD-83 jetliners in the Pacific Ocean off the
California coast. All 88 people aboard were killed. The airline
also faces a separate federal grand jury investigation into charges
that supervisors at a separate Alaska maintenance center in
Oakland, Calif., had signed papers for repairs that either were not
done or that they were not authorized to approve.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Friday, Alaska said that it was
cooperating fully with all federal inquiries into its practices and
that it would talk extensively with its mechanics to study charges
of improprieties in the maintenance hangar here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alaska will take whatever steps are dictated by these
interviews, including immediately grounding any aircraft involved,
in order that we may all have assurances of safety,'' said John
Fowler, the air carrier's executive vice president of technical
operations and system control.
</P>
<P>
   But, the statement said, in its interviews of the mechanics so
far, ``while all acknowledged signing the letter, none were able to
cite specific incidents in which they were aware of an aircraft
being returned to service in an unairworthy or unsafe condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics' letter to airline executives, delivered earlier
this week and described by The Seattle Times on Saturday, did not
cite any specific instances of inadequate repairs.
</P>
<P>
   But, the mechanics wrote, ``Our consciences constrain us to make
you both aware of an ongoing situation on the heavy check which we
have heretofore brought before management in the hangar, but our
pleadings have gone unheeded.'' A heavy check involves repairs to a
major flight-control part.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics' complaints centered on Robert Falla, manager of
the Seattle maintenance base, the official now placed on temporary
leave. ``Amazingly,'' the letter said, ``in the midst of our grief
and shock subsequent to the crash of Flight 261, many amongst us
have been pressured, threatened and intimidated by Mr. Falla in the
daily performance of our work.''
</P>
<P>
   When Falla drove into his home on Friday morning and was asked
by The Seattle Times about the letter, he said, ``No aircraft under
my authority has ever gone out unairworthy or unsafe.'' And, he
added, ``There is nothing I have to hide, and there is nothing
Alaska Airlines has to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline said it had delivered a copy of the letter to
federal investigators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
