<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TERROR-DEATH-PENALTY-     03-18 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-DEATH-PENALTY-1,180(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE IN BOMBING CASE WARNS AGAINST EXECUTIONS ON WIDE POLITICAL
GROUNDS
</HEADLINE>
   (Exclusive) 
(rk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyers for three men charged in the 1998 African
embassy bombings are arguing for their clients' lives on political
grounds, contending that executing them would be a foreign-policy
disaster for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorandum that is being sent to Attorney General Janet
Reno, the defense lawyers contend that executions of their clients,
whom they describe as mere ``foot soldiers'' in a terrorist
conspiracy, would only turn them into Islamic martyrs while
creating a blood feud between the United States and the Muslim
world.
</P>
<P>
   The effect, the lawyers say, would be to seriously damage the
government's chances of prosecuting Osama bin Laden, the wealthy
Saudi exile who has been accused of leading a global terrorist
conspiracy that included the embassy attacks and other acts of
violence against Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently worried that the issue may be viewed too narrowly,
the lawyers have also taken the unusual step of circulating their
30-page document to top officials in the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it plain,'' the Feb. 7 memo declares, ``that the
State Department ought to be fully consulted, and its views
considered, on all of the grave foreign policy, national security
and human rights implications of a U.S. government request for the
death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   All three men have pleaded not guilty and plan to fight the
charges in court later this year. But the memorandum assumes for
the sake of argument that they have been convicted and that the
death penalty would be inappropriate. Such pleas are routine in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers in the case, U.S. vs. bin Laden, are seeking a much
broader audience in the government for their fears for their
clients' fates.
</P>
<P>
   The case is the first in which federal prosecutors have sought
to impose the death penalty against a defendant accused of
terrorism in a foreign country. It is also the first time the
government has begun to pursue the death penalty in the series of
major terrorism prosecutions of about two dozen Islamic militants
in New York that began with the 1993 World Trade Center bombing.
Among those cases is another plot to blow up major landmarks in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   One defense lawyer who has read the memo said: ``This case lies
at the intersection of the criminal justice system and foreign
policy. The whole point of the memo is that it is folly to simply
treat this as a mere criminal case, much as we might wish things
were so simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense decided last week to send the memo after the U.S.
attorney, Mary Jo White, indicated that she would seek the death
penalty for at least one of the defendants, Mohamed Rashed Daoud
al-'Owhali, for his role in the attacks on embassies in Nairobi,
Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, which killed more than 200
people and wounded thousands. The decision must be approved by
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the memo, which was written in the names of the nine
lawyers who are representing the three defendants who could face
capital punishment, was provided to The New York Times by a person
who has read it and believes that the death penalty issue should be
debated in a broader forum.
</P>
<P>
   The memo makes the defense strategy clear: to catch the
attention of top national security advisers to President Clinton
and to cast the death penalty issue not in legal terms but in a
larger context of the government's stand against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The memo notes, for example, that if prosecutors seek to execute
al-'Owhali and his two co-defendants, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh and
Khalfan Khamis Mohamed, it would be the clearest signal that bin
Laden would also face execution were he ever brought to New York,
tried, and convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The government could hardly spare the leader of the conspiracy
if it planned to execute his lower level ``foot soldiers,'' the
memo asserts.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden remains at large, living in Afghanistan under the
protection of the fundamentalist Taliban, and the United States has
conducted sensitive negotiations with other Muslim countries in
hopes of having him arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if the world knew bin Laden could receive a ``lethal
injection'' in a federal prison if he were turned over to the
United States, that would certainly chill any chance of cooperation
from Muslim countries, ``who must respond to domestic public
sentiment against handing over a Muslim leader to a Western
power,'' the memo says. But if bin Laden is not captured or is
spared execution as part of a deal for his extradition, it would be
all the more unfair to execute his lower-level operatives, the memo
says.
</P>
<P>
   Already, three other defendants in the case face charges that do
not carry the death penalty, even though they are charged with
playing more important roles in the organization that conspired to
carry out the bombings. The U.S. government said it would not seek
the death penalty against one of them to win his extradition from
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   If higher-ups are convicted, the memo says, they will be immune
from capital punishment. Likewise, it says, if al-'Owhali and his
two co-defendants are sent to prison for life, they too ``will
vanish from view and soon be forgotten. But a sentence of death
will rescue them from oblivion,'' the memo says, ``and transform
them into celebrated martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very fact that the United States will have designated
these defendants for execution,'' it goes on, ``will guarantee that
their pictures will be held aloft over crowds of protesters. Babies
will be named for them, and young men from Morocco to Pakistan will
make plans to emulate them. Their actual executions will ignite
outrage and protest in many Muslim countries, and will leave a
legacy of further violence and revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Placing bin Laden on death row would have enormous ramifications
for the United States, the memo says. In the World Trade Center
case, it notes, the defendants did not face capital charges because
their crime occurred before the 1994 death penalty law was passed.
An attempt to arrest bin Laden and imprison him for life, the memo
contends, will be seen as a credible punishment, ``because it
displays the self-restraint and moderation of a great nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the United States declares that its success in this
effort will be measured by its ability to kill bin Laden once he
has been taken prisoner and rendered harmless,'' the memo says,
``the story line will quickly shift in a direction that could do
considerable harm to long-term American interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers have made separate submissions tailored to
each man's personal circumstances, offering arguments of why the
death penalty is not appropriate. Those documents are not being
circulated outside the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyers argue in their policy memo that the death
penalty decision is too big to be left solely to Reno. The memo
asks her, in making the ``momentous decision,'' to involve ``those
agencies which do possess genuine expertise and experience in how
the actions of U.S. courts may affect American policy interests
around the world.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In their memo, the lawyers argue that retribution would not
justify the death penalty. They say they went to Kenya and
interviewed the blast's survivors, ``but we met no one who wanted
to see them executed,'' the lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   They also argue that deterrence is also not a valid
consideration for these defendants. They note that the government
has accused al-'Owhali, for example, with being a would-be suicide
bomber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, given the centrality of the concept of martyrdom in
extremist Islamic political movements,'' the memo says, ``a
stronger case could be made for the counterdeterrent effect of the
death penalty _ that is, that the death penalty would actually
stimulate rather than deter similar crimes in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death penalty is simply not what they fear,'' the memo
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Because court-ordered executions can take years to carry out,
the memo likens Reno's decision to ``a cruise missile with a six-,
eight- or ten-year trajectory.'' By that time, the political
terrain may be totally different, the memo says, and ``it may be
self-evident that executing three Islamist prisoners under the
glare of world attention is exactly the wrong thing for the United
States to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps its most chilling section, the memo describes bin
Laden's being convicted in the United States and sentenced to die.
The memo says he would likely present a ``dignified and charismatic
figure'' in the courtroom, and ``his denials of legal
responsibility for the Africa bombings will be credited by millions
throughout the world, to whom he will appear as a martyr for
Islam.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
