<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LONGHORNED-BEETLE-ART     03-18 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGHORNED-BEETLE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BATTLE OVER TREE-KILLING BEETLES TAKE ON NEW URGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Vt., Ill., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tree experts around New York City and Chicago are
girding for a warm-weather offensive against a creature, little
more than an inch long, that could destroy as much woodland as some
of the worst forest fires in history.
</P>
<P>
   The creature is the Asian long-horned beetle, which kills trees
by eating them from the inside and which has no natural enemies in
the United States. Once a tree is infected, it is doomed. Thousands
of trees have been felled and ground into bits to try to check the
beetles' advance.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state agriculture officials have spent several
million dollars and expect to spend millions more in fighting the
beetle, which was first spotted in the United States four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture has assigned some of its top
experts to the campaign. Now, the department and the Environmental
Protection Agency are weighing whether to use a nicotine-based
pesticide, one they think would carry minimal risks to people and
other trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is potentially a very, very serious problem,''
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said in a recent interview. ``If
established, this beetle could have a severe impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials who have followed the problem say huge tracts of
forest could be ruined, changing landscapes for generations.
Vermont, which relies on maple trees for its syrup business and its
famed autumn foliage, has particular reason to worry. Maples are
among the many trees the beetle loves to dine on, although none of
the creatures have been spotted in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Female beetles bore deep into trees to lay their eggs. When the
eggs become larvae, they eat their way back out, flying away as
adults and leaving their doomed hosts pocked with perfectly round
holes. Because adult beetles are active only in the summer and
fall, their pursuers are mapping their plans now.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman and several others involved in the fight said that they
were optimistic and that this year would be the turning point. They
think the nicotine-based pesticide will work even though others
have not. But they conceded that there was a long battle ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to eradicate it,'' said Vic Mastro, an
entomologist with the Department of Agriculture. ``It's not going
to be an easy or short process. But we said that at the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, there was Greenpoint, Brooklyn. The beetle's
first known outpost in this country was discovered there in 1996,
after the beetle-colonists traveled from China in a shipping
container.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the beetles were found in other sections of
Brooklyn, then in parts of Queens and Manhattan. Soon, they were in
Amityville, and soon after that elsewhere on Long Island. More than
4,000 trees were cut down in the New York region, some of them
magnificent giants that were saplings when Lincoln was president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had it off the mainland,'' said Joe Gittleman,
the federal Agriculture Department's leading beetle fighter in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   So there was a sense of dread in 1998 when long-horned beetles
were found in the Chicago area, perhaps because young beetles
hitched a ride on a truck fender, or in logs from infected trees.
More than 1,000 infected trees have been cut down around Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service and local agencies have been planting new
trees, of species less susceptible to the beetles, but it will be
years before they are as tall as the ones that were lost.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the Chinese have agreed to treat wooden shipping
pallets, in an effort to stop more beetles from coming to the
United States. Quarantines have been imposed on firewood from areas
where infected trees have been found. Scores of warehouses have
been inspected.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Kruse, the Agriculture Department's beetle-campaign leader
in Chicago, said tree trimmers and landscapers had been very
cooperative in identifying and destroying infected trees. ``But how
do you get the last one?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Still, although the battle is long and hard, it is also
interesting for scientists who were not previously familiar with
the Asian long-horned beetle. ``It's something you could spend a
career on,'' Mastro said. Not that he wants to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0972 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-18 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE HEART WANTS ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore was supposed to be the SNAG in this race, the Sensitive
New Age Guy sharing his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, after all, was the one who believed in using
principles of therapy to run his White House office, who brought a
facilitator to Camp David so the cabinet could bond over childhood
insecurities, who gave weepy prime-time convention speeches about
his son's accident and his sister's cancer.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, oddly enough, it is W., the alleged SWAG (Swaggering
Carnivorous Texan), who is forcing us to focus on his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's emotions are so close to the surface that we always know
if he's testy or tired or aggrieved or homesick or defensive or
cocky.
</P>
<P>
   He can be sketchy on issues and foreign leaders, but he
constantly fires off bulletins about his state of mind: ``I am
tough enough. I know how to lead. I am ready. I am steeled. I can
handle adversity. I am real comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   These assertions are intended to counter fears that he lacks the
fiber to run the big show. It's the same sort of shorthand his
father used with ``Message: I care.'' W., too, is always reading
his stage directions aloud, protesting that he  &UR; will not be
defined &LR; . Clearly, he hasn't pondered the implications of being a
person without definition.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than proving he has the qualities of mind to be
president, he yammers about his heart: ``I'll tell you what's on my
heart,'' he says, or ``Don't you judge my heart.'' Billy Graham
``planted a seed in my heart,'' he said, and Christ ``changed my
heart.'' He'll give the party ``a compassionate heart.''
</P>
<P>
   He made another cardiological revelation last week in a
startling interview with The New York Times' Richard Berke and
Frank Bruni. It would have been so easy, and savvy, for W. to waft
an olive branch John McCain's way. But he preferred to vouchsafe
the American public another glimpse of his innermost self.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the bruising, bitter and sometimes humbling nature of
his primary campaign against McCain,'' the reporters wrote, ``the
governor emerged without any regrets about his campaign's conduct,
any second thoughts about his strategy or any new resolves for the
way he positions himself for the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   The wild McCain ride is a phenomenon of profound interest,
especially to a pol. But W. once more displayed an unnerving lack
of curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   He was clearly irritated that his great victory was being
sullied by pesky questions about the guy he squashed. He regards
John McCain as a nuisance and a party pooper, an impertinent
interference in the adulation that W. believes is his due. He
thinks McCain was a hypocrite on campaign finance reform who got
more admiration than he deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Some old Bush hands had predicted that W. was too tetchy, too
much like his mother, to handle a national campaign. And that
prickly, sarcastic, grudge-collecting side blazed in the interview.
(Afterward, W. lamely tried to say he was taken out of context, but
the text belied it.)
</P>
<P>
   He was not the uniter he had promised to be. He was the Loyalty
Enforcer he used to be for his dad. McCain had had the temerity to
challenge W.'s coronation and throw a spotlight on his weaknesses.
The gracious Bushes have a strangely Nixonian quality: You're
either with them or against them.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in an equally disturbing Times interview last week,
Al Gore revealed that he has no feelings. He tried to wrap himself
not only in the aura of John McCain, but also Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's emotional efficiency is a little terrifying: Like many
politicians, he will do what has to be done, except that in his
case, there is no evidence of anguish. He will shapeshift brazenly,
going from campaign finance abuser to campaign finance reformer,
with no trace of shame. He is chillingly consistent in his
indifference to his inconsistencies.
</P>
<P>
   He has the temperament of the class snitch. Whenever W. acts the
chucklehead, Al raises his hand to make sure it has escaped
nobody's attention. After Bush's Times interview, Gore tut-tutted:
``I think he should have been taking notes from John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   So this is our choice? President Rattle or President Tattle?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
