<SLUG> BC-SUBPRIME-LENDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS OF `PREDATORY LENDING' TAKE AIM AT WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mayor Richard M. Daley of Chicago announced last Wednesday
that he was backing a broad city campaign against ``predatory
lending,'' he helped spotlight what consumer advocates say is a
small but growing challenge to the banks and big Wall Street
institutions that help finance high-cost home equity loans.
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts include plans for picket lines in Washington by
neighborhood groups and increased shareholder activism by major
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with sharply escalating foreclosure rates in some
working-class neighborhoods of Chicago, Daley has proposed an
ordinance that would require every financial institution seeking to
do business with the city to attest that it has not engaged in
predatory lending, either directly or through an affiliated
company.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance, which will face a vote by the City Council next
month, is a direct challenge to the big banks and other
institutions that have expanded into the growing business known as
subprime home equity lending, so called because it caters to
homeowners with less than top-quality credit.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred at first by financial deregulation in the early 1980s
and more recently by access to Wall Street's secondary mortgage
market, subprime home equity lending has become an increasingly
important feature in the consumer finance landscape. But the
industry's growth has been accompanied by complaints from consumer
advocates and state regulators about deceptive sales practices and
home equity loans structured in ways that, they say, increase the
likelihood of default and foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's proposal has strong support on the City Council, said
Alderman Theodore Thomas, who has his own anti-predatory-lending
plan pending before the council but said he would support the
mayor's plan.
</P>
<P>
   As the Chicago initiative indicates, some organizations
concerned about predatory lending are beginning to look beyond the
lenders themselves to focus on the banks or Wall Street
institutions that are increasingly important players in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   One concerned organization is the Social Investment Forum, a
nonprofit association for investment professionals and institutions
in the $2.16 trillion industry of ``socially responsible''
investing, which includes mutual funds, pension funds and
endowments that screen their portfolios to avoid products or
services they consider harmful to society.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, many socially responsible investors have shunned
tobacco company stocks, casino gambling companies and clothing
manufacturers accused of using sweatshop labor. Others have used
their muscle as large institutional shareholders to pressure
companies involved in these products or activities.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, the group's board of directors endorsed a national
campaign against predatory lending. The campaign includes a call
for shareholder activism and support for screening portfolios to
exclude securities that help support those involved in making such
loans, said David J. Berge, the group's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be looking at who the worst offenders in this area
are, and at what large-block shareholders can do to address that
behavior,'' Berge said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, the group intends to develop a practical
way to identify investments that those concerned about predatory
lending should avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all would like to believe that a lot of the money that's
been put out there to support predatory lending is just a result of
a lack of education,'' Berge said. ``Once people are aware of the
kind of behavior they're supporting, we believe they will be
willing and anxious to make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Berge said, the group will help support those who are
resisting predatory lending at the grass-roots level by encouraging
investors to steer at least 1 percent of their portfolios into
neighborhood organizations working to support affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the organization's campaign will be worked out at
meetings next month and posted on the Web site
www.socialinvest.org, Berge said.
</P>
<P>
   In another form of activism, a coalition of community
organizations is planning demonstrations on Monday at the
Washington offices of Salomon Smith Barney, the giant brokerage
company that has helped finance several large subprime lenders.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration is planned by the Association of Community
Organizations for Reform Now, known as ACORN, as part of a
conference focusing on predatory lending.
</P>
<P>
   ACORN's executive director, Steve Kest, said Salomon Smith
Barney was singled out because it is one of the largest purchasers
of loans from Ameriquest Mortgage Co., which ``we believe is one of
the most egregious of the subprime lenders we have studied.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, for example, Salomon raised nearly $800 million to
buy more than 6,200 mortgages from Ameriquest with an average
interest rate of 9.56 percent, roughly 2 points higher than
conventional mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   ACORN has staged demonstrations at various offices of
Ameriquest, which is based in Orange, Calif. Asked about the
group's accusations Friday, an Ameriquest spokesman denied that the
company had engaged in predatory lending and cited its support for
consumer education programs aimed at low-income and minority
homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said that ACORN's accusations were disputed by
another grass-roots organization, the National Association of
Neighborhoods in Washington, which has conducted consumer education
programs that have been financially supported by the mortgage
company.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Byrd, the association's executive director, confirmed
that his group ``considers Ameriquest to be one of the enlightened
lenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd added: ``We support ACORN shedding light in this area. But
we think they have unfairly targeted Ameriquest.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Salomon Smith Barney, Duncan King, said the
company declined to comment on the demonstration or its
relationship with Ameriquest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
