<HEADLINE>
LOCAL NEWSPAPERS BECOME THE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. _ The Gazettes still arrive every
Thursday in every home, post office box and business in San Luis
Obispo County, fat with high school basketball scores and the
latest City Council arguments. The front page still carries the
slogan ``Hometown journalism at its best.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite making more news in the last few weeks than their
owner would ever see fit to print, The San Luis Obispo and
Atascadero Gazettes are doing better than ever, says Todd Hansen,
the weeklies' chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Hansen said, since the papers' policy of not ``promoting
the gay lifestyle or abortion'' _ not writing any articles on the
subjects that may be construed as supportive _ was made explicit a
month ago, there has been some fallout. Reporters and editors have
quit en masse. Advertisers have pulled out. Readers have asked that
their names be removed from the mailing list.
</P>
<P>
   But he said: ``We've actually had our best week in advertising
revenue last week. We've had advertisers step up and say, `I got to
be in San Luis now.' We have a better staff, everybody is aware of
us now, everybody who works for us has a clear understanding of our
beliefs and we feel we are by far a better paper.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is one other thing: ``We've got all this free media,''
Hansen said with a laugh. ``If you didn't know about the Gazettes,
you sure as heck know about them now.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. Over a few weeks, several small newspapers in this
part of the central California coast, with its easy-on-the-eyes
landscape of old missions and working farms, have stirred an
earthquake's worth of ruckus. And it is not over.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps partly because the controversy centers on freedom of the
press, one of journalists' favorite topics, and perhaps partly
because it concerns two of the most important issues of the day for
the religious right, homosexuality and abortion, this story has
legs. The dozen or so reporters and editors who have quit the two
weeklies spend a great deal of time talking to talk-show hosts or
to other reporters from all over.
</P>
<P>
   The Gazettes, Hansen said, are inundated with calls and letters
_ ``80 percent of them supportive'' _ and the city of San Luis
Obispo, a trendy, liberal bastion surrounded by conservative
Republicans in the countryside, is more fired up than anyone here
can remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a story that I think is important because it goes beyond
the hot-button issues,'' said Ron Bast, a longtime local writer who
quit his job as editor of The Atascadero Gazette over the policy.
``Everybody has a take on gays and abortion. But I think we all
have a sense of what's fair. It's just patently obvious that in
this case what the owner is doing is not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   When a local multimillionaire, David Weyrich, holder of a vast
development empire, began the first of his weekly papers, The Paso
Robles Gazette, in July, readers and journalists were excited.
</P>
<P>
   By October, when the next two newspapers, the San Luis Obispo
and Atascadero Gazettes, began publishing, San Luis Obispo County
was abuzz with the possibilities of community journalism. All three
weeklies are free, and are distributed to 120,000 households and
businesses in the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember having a conversation with Ron Bast, the editor, in
February about how much fun it was to be doing The Atascadero
Gazette,'' said Kathy Johnston, a feature writer for San Luis
Obispo magazine (which was bought by the Gazette Newspaper Group)
before she began covering the City Council for the Atascadero
weekly in October. ``We thought it was great fun because Atascadero
is not a town that has had any media scrutiny, and these reporters
came along and reported what was out there and put it in everyone's
mailbox.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was in that conversation with Bast, she said, that the
editor told her the fun might be ending.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen had warned the publisher of The Atascadero Gazette, Steve
Martin, to stop running an item announcing the monthly meeting of
the Parents and Friends of Gays and Lesbians, known locally as P
Flag. Later, he made it clear that not only was P Flag banned from
the paper, but also any letters protesting the ban and any
editorials or articles that showed support for gay rights or
pro-choice views on abortion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bast, referring to Hansen, said: ``I asked him how we would
cover the annual AIDS bike-a-thon from San Francisco to Los
Angeles, which brings 10,000 people through town, presumably most
of them in support of gays. He said we won't cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   To explain the newspaper group's position, Weyrich and his wife,
Mary, the parents of eight children, wrote a front page editorial _
their first and last word on the subject _ in the Gazettes on Feb.
24. ``We strongly believe in the family, as God defines it, and we
are strong supporters of the sanctity of life,'' it read in part.
``These are not always popular beliefs in our society today.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Luis Obispo, which has a sizable gay and lesbian
population, the news of the ban was met with sadness and
disappointment. Charles Myers, who owns the Big Sky Cafe and is
gay, printed cards for the staff members who quit the papers,
offering them free meals. The Chamber of Commerce and Downtown
Association voted to remove their advertisements from the Gazettes,
and the performing arts center pulled its items from the papers'
calendars.
</P>
<P>
   But Hansen said that while San Luis Obispo was roiled ``because
it tends to be more liberal,'' towns like Atascadero and Paso
Robles were buoyed by the policy. ``We just started two more papers
on March 9,'' Hansen said, ``and counting the countywide revenues,
we just expect to be doing better and better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
