<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-INTELLIGENCE19-C     03-18 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-INTELLIGENCE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush passes smarts test given by voters
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Final report cards won't be issued until
November, but, so far, voters around the country have given Texas
Gov. George W. Bush passing grades on a question he didn't
anticipate facing on his road to the White House: Is this guy smart
enough to be president?
</P>
<P>
   A year into the presidential campaign, Bush's brainpower remains
the target of self-appointed smart guys and late-night comedians
who wonder aloud whether Texans have twice made a dumb guy their
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek recently ruminated about it in its ``The Buzz'' column,
noting Bush might need a ``wonk'' as a running mate but pointing
out, ``This strategy could backfire, though: too big a brain might
highlight Dubya's deficit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a former C student at Yale, insists the is-he-smart-enough
question doesn't faze him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me because I know it's wrong. It's just part
of the game. It's part of the media elite game,'' he said of the
persistent inquiries about his IQ. ``I think anybody who doesn't
think I'm smart enough to handle the job is underestimating. I hope
Al Gore feels that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the barbs continue, exit polls from the primaries
indicate voters are not overly concerned about Bush's intelligence.
In several states, voters were asked if Bush ``knows enough'' to be
president. It's not exactly the same as: Is he smart enough, but it
comes close.
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas GOP primary, 90 percent of those questioned said he
knows enough to handle the job. In New York, 68 percent of the GOP
respondents agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan's GOP primary, won by Arizona Sen. John McCain, 66
percent of the respondents said Bush knows enough. But in what
could be a troubling statistic for Bush in a key state in November,
91 percent of the Republicans who said Bush does not know enough
voted for McCain, a number indicating those Republicans may be
hard-pressed to back Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will face a tougher set of graders, of course, when
Democrats are added to the mix in November. For example, in
California's recent open primary, opinion was split on whether Bush
knows enough to be president. Forty-eight percent said Bush knows
enough. Forty-three said he does not.
</P>
<P>
   And in perhaps the most telling statistic of all as Bush heads
toward November, the exit pollsters didn't feel compelled to ask
anyone whether they thought Vice President Al Gore, who clinched
the Democratic nomination last week, knows enough to be president.
</P>
<P>
   The smarts question began when Bush fouled up a television
reporter's pop quiz on world leaders and has been furthered by his
penchant for misspeak. A Canadian comedian recently got Bush to
express his appreciation for an endorsement from Canadian Prime
Minister Jean Poutine.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Bush, Jean Poutine is a type of Canadian fast
food. Jean Chretien is the Canadian prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in discussing possible upcoming trips, Bush moved
Mexico to another continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go down to South America. There is a complicating
factor there. The Mexican presidential election is taking place and
I certainly don't want to get involved in that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texans who have worked with and against Bush say they never
questioned his intelligence. Former Land Commissioner Garry Mauro,
Bush's 1998 for for governor, said he believes Bush lacks passion
for issues. But Mauro raises no concerns about the governor's
smarts.
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell, a San Angelo Democrat
who has endorsed Bush for president, said the governor is a quick
learner who understands both the details and the big-picture
implications of complex issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised by anything that goes on in these
campaigns,'' Junell said of the questions about Bush's
intelligence. ``They are going to make not only the governor, but
everybody from Texas look like a bunch of goobers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president is from one of those intellectual Ivy
League states, Tennessee,'' said Junell.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
