<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-MAYHEM19-COX     03-18 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MAYHEM19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The madness of renaming NCAA series `Mayhem'
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ To most hoop fans, the annual NCAA men's
basketball tournament is best known as March Madness. But that name
seems passe at CBS, the broadcast company that pounded the phrase
into the national consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   After years of hyping the competition as March Madness, the
network this year is pushing a different name: March Mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the switch lies in a thicket of corporate
connections and trademark disputes. The Illinois High School
Association claimed it coined March Madness in the 1940s to
describe its own basketball tournament. That was long before CBS
began using the phrase during broadcasts of the NCAA Tournament in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, the association sued a video game maker that
licensed the name from the NCAA. The association said it was
entitled to royalties but three courts disagreed, saying March
Madness had come to signify the NCAA Tournament in the public mind.
</P>
<P>
   CBS continued to use the name, but the same wasn't true for its
Internet arm.
</P>
<P>
   Sportsline.com never had permission from the NCAA to use March
Madness, according to spokesman Larry Wahl. So in 1997,
Sportsline.com came up with the phrase March Mayhem, which has been
used in its Web coverage of the tournament ever since.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS spokeswoman says the network is entitled to use March
Madness on the air, but has been stressing March Mayhem to promote
its Internet offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the NCAA and the Illinois High School Association
agreed to share the term March Madness, forming a corporation to
control use of the trademark. Does that mean CBS _ will forget the
Mayhem and reclaim the Madness?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Wahl says it's hard to tell whether anyone really cares
about the name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think on the (Web) site that it matters that much,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1406EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WEATHER-MARCH19-COX     03-18 0264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MARCH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winter gets its marching orders
 &HT;    By GRETEL DAUGHERTY
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Ah, March.
</P>
<P>
   Named after Mars, the Roman god of war, this is the month when
winter and spring battle for possession of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   The two seasons prance around each other like fighters in a
ring, locked in a subtle dance across the sky and the valley.
</P>
<P>
   A patchwork of soft green spreads through the crisp, golden dead
grass of winter in yards and pastures.
</P>
<P>
   As early-morning fog blankets the valley, wisps of steam rise
from the fields and roads warmed by the sun the day before _ then
freeze into the delicate lacy glaze of hoarfrost on all they touch,
transforming the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   As black storm clouds roil over the Monument and cast shadowy
outlines of the cliffs behind gray curtains of rain, puffy white
clouds hide the rim of Grand Mesa with veils of falling snow.
</P>
<P>
   And so the two seasons struggle. Yet even as winter dusts the
valley with snow and sleet, crocuses and daffodils bravely blossom.
As a chilly March wind races through the bare bones of trees,
willow branches with budding leaves of kelly green and gold sway
with the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   As the weakening winter fades, spring grows stronger. The sun
shines more warmly, and the scent in the air changes from woodsmoke
and snow to a moist, earthy green aroma. The lilting songs of birds
fill the morning air. And, once again, spring reigns victorious.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, March.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
