<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-ANNIVERSARY _ TICK BITE, N.C. _ Six months after Hurricane
Floyd's devastation in North Carolina unleashed hundreds of
millions of dollars in government relief aid and brought out
volunteers by the thousands, flood-stricken residents such as
Herman Edwards are still reeling. The 76-year-old retired iron
worker doubts he'll ever return to his home, classified as
unihabitable because it is in a flood zone, or that he'll ever
again collect the $1,200 a month in rent from the five mobile homes
he rented. Four were ruined; he now lives in the fifth. ``It's been
traumatizing,'' he said. ``You walk out every morning, and you see
that everything you worked for all your life is gone.'' An
asessment of North Carolina's recovery from its worst natural
disaster. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-BOX _ Six months after Hurricane Floyd, state and federal
agencies have earmarked more than $3 billion for eastern North
Carolina's recovery. Of that, $305 million awaits congressional
approval. Chart of expenditures. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-HELP _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The Salvation Army is still
giving out furniture. Greenville has an interfaith task force
(GIFT) to help with rebuilding/recovery issues. N.C. Baptist and
Methodist men are regulars in Grifton, federal money available for
mental counseling etc. Reader service info on who and where flood
aid is still available --phone numbers and resource info. (Hunt,
Greenville Daily Reflector). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Fifth of six installments looking at Eastern North
Carolina's recovery from Hurricane Floyd on the six-month
anniversary of the storm.
</P>
