<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TEEN-CARS19-COX     03-18 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-CARS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Today's teens scaling down on auto horsepower, gearing up
accessories
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KETTERING, Ohio _ A year ago, Fairmont High School senior Doug
Collins acquired a clean, hand-me-down '96 Sunfire from his mom,
but his automotive work in progress had just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Collins added ground effects, a ``slammed'' Euro-style
suspension, neon underlights, interior painting, 18-inch custom
wheels, an ear-pounding stereo system with Rockford amplifiers and
a cold-air intake to pump an extra 10-horsepower into his meager
2.2-liter engine.
</P>
<P>
   Total price tag for improvements? Around $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   And all that for a car hard-pressed to break a highway speed
limit until it hits fourth gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't go for the speed aspect, I go for the looks,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers who remember the days when hot teen-age cars packed
350-plus horsepower and macho nameplates such as Mustang, Barracuda
and GTO will be surprised at what passes for ``hot'' among today's
teens.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with exorbitant sticker prices and environmentally correct
engines, young car enthusiasts are buying econo-boxes such as
Neons, Escorts, Cavaliers and Civics, then jazzing up the
peripherals to turn them into lean, mean street machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look really cool, and they sound fast, but in a modern
car there's not a lot you can do'' to increase the horsepower, said
Larry Webster, technology editor of Car and Driver magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance rates have become a bummer, too. ``A lot of young
people like the Camaros, especially the Z-28,'' said David Martin,
a new-car salesman at Frank Z Chevrolet in Dayton. ``But they're a
higher-dollar car and the insurance is out of sight for somebody
under 25 if you have any kind of driving record at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bowling, a senior at Fairmont High School, agreed. ``Big
engines are out. You get into trouble for them, man.'' Bowling
drives a '93 Beretta GT with a modest 3.1-liter engine.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Garblik, professor of automotive technology at
Sinclair Community College, sees no reason to disregard the
performance of today's four-cylinder sport coupes. ``Sure, they
probably max out at 200 horsepower, but the cars are much lighter,
maybe 30 percent lighter (than the old muscle cars), so that a lot
of that disadvantage goes away. A highly tuned Honda would probably
run with some of those bigger engines.''
</P>
<P>
   On the East and West coasts, Webster said, Honda Civics have
become the car of choice for teens who want to supe up a smaller,
less expensive car.
</P>
<P>
   But in Dayton, with its strong GM influence and tradition, teens
are more likely to turn to Sunfires or Cavaliers for their basic
raw material. ``A lot of them have relatives who work at GM who can
help them out'' financially, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodge Neon ES, with power windows and locks, is big among
young buyers, said Albert Murell of Dave Dennis Dodge in Fairborn.
``It's definitely about pricing. It's hard to get a new car under
$14,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the loose rumbling V-8s of old, today's higher-revving
four-cylinder engines are so efficient there's little that
teen-agers can do to squeeze out additional horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're already running around 80 horsepower per liter (of
engine displacement) from the factory, which is awesome,'' Webster
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many teens, including Collins, replace the air box with a
cold-air intake in the hope of adding power, ``but it's a tossup
whether it works or not,'' Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   Nitrous oxide systems can add as much as 100 horsepower to a
highly tuned, four-cylinder engine, but they can only be used for
short bursts of speed or they can damage the engine. And, by the
way, most of them are legal.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, so are most of the parts sold for modifying engines
these days, assuming teens can get them to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a whole new level of expertise'' to work on today's
computer-assisted engines, Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   With traditional hot cars such as Camaros, Firebirds and
Mustangs starting at $30,000 and up, up, up, male teens have had to
turn to other automotive outlets for their excess of testosterone,
and a big one has been trucks, Garblik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves trucks,'' he said. ``They make up 50 percent
of the market nowadays, along with SUVs.''
</P>
<P>
   They can also attract attention from the opposite teen sex, says
Larry Baker, a 19-year-old Sinclair automotive student who plans to
drop a 351-cubic-inch V-8 into his 1985 Ford F250 pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I get more dates, because I've been with the
same girl for three years now,'' he said. ``But it definitely turns
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially since Baker jacked up the suspension and installed
40-inch Stahl tires for that fetching off-road racer look. And if
that doesn't get their attention, the headers and Corvette
sidepipes he added are loud enough to drown out even his Pioneer
sound system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty cool, if you like that type of thing,''
said Baker's girlfriend, 19-year-old Jamie Honious of Miamisburg.
``Sometimes when he goes very fast, though, you can't hear yourself
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all teens are out to promenade their vehicles, but they are
looking for something peppy and affordable, says Sam Garten, a
salesman for Bob Tatone in Fairborn.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Ams and Escorts are hot sellers among the youth market, he
said. ``It's the lower-price two-doors they think are really cool _
something with slightly more horsepower than the usual
four-cylinder,'' he said. And selling for less than $14,000, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for teens who aren't automotive prodigies is that
automakers are again aiming a line of products at young buyers,
with new fuel-efficient but more stylish models that they can buy
without borrowing big bucks from Daddy, Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota introduced the Echo this year and Ford has its new Focus
_ both with advertising campaigns and sticker prices targeted at
the youth market.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to create brand loyalty from a teen's very first
car, Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids of the baby boomers _ the `echo boomers' _ are an
even bigger population slice than the boomers were,'' he said. The
automakers ``are trying to get them in on the ground floor and keep
them in the fold.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if they can't lay a long patch of rubber down a back
country road, today's youth-oriented cars are safer and better
engineered than ever, Garblik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have great acceleration and handling and braking in
one car now,'' he said. ``It's a good time to be young and to like
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
