<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ASIAN-BABY-BOOM-ART-N     03-18 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-BABY-BOOM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR OF THE DRAGON AND THE DIAPER PAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT9, NYT10 are being sent to NYT photo clients. A
graphic of the Chinese zodiac symbols is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Millennium, schmillennium. It's the Year of the
Dragon, baby. And among Asian-Americans who abide by the Chinese
lunar calendar, this auspicious season of the mythical beast is
also turning out to be the year of the baby boom.
</P>
<P>
   Word to the nonlunar: the Year of the Golden Dragon, which began
Feb. 5 and ends next January, is regarded as an especially
propitious year to make business deals, buy property and have a
baby. It is believed that a child born under the sign of the
ferocious, fire-breathing creature _ as opposed to less
dignified-sounding signs, like, say, that of the rat (1996 being
its latest incarnation) _ will grow up to be a brave, powerful
leader. In Chinese tradition, the dragon is the symbol of royalty.
</P>
<P>
   So it is easy to understand why it already appears to be, well,
a rather productive year for baby-making among Asians who abide by
the lunar calendar _ in New York, they are mainly Chinese and
Koreans, but also smaller numbers of ethnic Chinese from places
like Vietnam and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   In Chinatown and other heavily Asian neighborhoods like
Flushing, in Queens, health workers say they are already seeing
more and more broad-grinned, big-bellied mothers-to-be ambling into
clinics and hospitals for checkups and prenatal classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dragon's a lucky sign,'' said Judy Chen, a Flushing
resident who is expecting a baby this year. ``If you have a dragon
in your house, everything will go up. Maybe you'll have lots of
kids. Your family will get rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is impossible to tell just how many new births
have been planned because of the dragon designation; the year 2000
has no doubt roused the reproductive proclivities of those who also
observe the lunar calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the anecdotal evidence is hard to ignore. At the
Chinatown Health Clinic in Lower Manhattan, enrollment in prenatal
classes has gone up from an average of about 50 women a month to
about 80 since January. At the Chinatown clinic of St. Vincent's
Hospital and Medical Center, a social worker has seen her caseload
of pregnant women go up to about 50, from an average of 40 a month,
since January.
</P>
<P>
   At New York Hospital Medical Center in Flushing, an attending
physician in the department of obstetrics and gynecology said he
would not be surprised to see a 50 percent increase in births this
year. At Elmhurst Hospital Center, where more than a tenth of the
patients are Chinese or Korean, births in February alone _ babies
born at the head of the dragon, if you will _ have jumped by nearly
20 percent since February last year.
</P>
<P>
   An attending obstetrician at the hospital, Dr. Ing-Yann Jeng,
said he and other Queens doctors with a large number of Chinese
patients had anticipated the trend. ``We were joking last year _
after this year, we can all retire!'' Jeng said. ``The reason: this
is the year 2000 and also a dragon year.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the mothers-to-be, many of them have already started to
reap the benefits of an especially auspicious pregnancy. Li Fang
Huang, 33, said her husband, a restaurant worker who was more
enthusiastic than she was to have a baby this year (little wonder,
since she delivered a baby girl just last year) made this promise:
``He said he is going to work harder than before,'' she said,
grinning, as Brenda Wan, a health educator at the Chinatown Health
Clinic, translated from Cantonese.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, did Sherry Hu's husband. In the past, he spent a few
nights a week staying with his co-workers in New Jersey, where he
is a restaurant worker, instead of coming home to Bensonhurst,
Brooklyn. But ever since Hu, an immigrant from Fujian province in
China, got pregnant, her husband has been coming home every night,
she said. He even drove her to work every morning, until she gave
up her job at an insurance agency a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Wan explained this behavior: ``There is a Chinese saying _ I
don't know how to translate it exactly. Because of the baby, the
mother becomes very precious.''
</P>
<P>
   Hu, 31, the mother of an 8-year-old girl, waited until the
dragon came around to plan for her second child. ``Since last year,
I'm planning,'' she said. ``I have a lot of friends who have been
trying. It's very tough this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Year of the Dragon, one of 12 zodiac signs in the Chinese
lunar calendar, comes once every 12 years. A baby born this year
``is endowed with this aura,'' explained Ho Yong, director of
curriculum at the China Institute, in Manhattan. While some people
believe that it is better to have a dragon boy, Yong said, a girl
is considered just as likely to inherit the dragon's sterling
attributes. ``A dragon daughter,'' he said, ``is a female child who
is powerful, who is outgoing.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if you're just getting hip to the lunar timetable,
time is running out. If you're not well on your way, there are
precious few weeks left to conceive a dragon baby.
</P>
<P>
   After several months of effort, Chen, 35, got news of her
pregnancy just last month. Her first child was born a year and a
half ago, in the Year of the Tiger, and she knows that when her
second comes along, she will have her hands full. ``If you have a
dragon and a tiger at home, they fight a lot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. A child born under a lucky sign is believed to bring
good fortune to the entire household. And she should know. Chen, an
immigrant from Taiwan, was born in the Year of the Snake,
affectionately known as the little dragon. ``If you have a little
dragon in the house, it's better than nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the dragon baby that Nicole Tran is expecting in
August wasn't exactly planned. Nor is Tran, a Vietnamese immigrant
of Chinese heritage, a big believer of the zodiac. Sure, she feels
lucky. But the birth of her baby under such a rare and auspicious
sign is important for a very different reason. The baby's father,
to whom Tran is engaged, is not Chinese, and so for her, it is
particularly gratifying to be able to pass along such an important
Chinese symbol to their child.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me,'' she said, ``the dragon signifies being Chinese.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
