<HEADER>
A1015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-2TAK     03-18 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOSSUP STATES; RECYCLED CAMPAIGN FOOTAGE; BUSH COATTAILS;
MCCAIN'S FUTURE; MAJORITY GAY COUNCIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Del., Pa., Miss., Mich., Ohio, Ky., Tenn., Iowa, Wash., La.,
Ark., Maine, N.M., Fla., Ga., Nev., N.C., Minn., Okla.)  (jw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAND OF TOSSUP STATES MAY PICK THE WINNER
</P>
<P>
   Now that it is all but certain who the presidential nominees
will be this fall, the buzz is beginning about which states will
hold the key to victory.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows the answer, of course, not this soon in the
game. But there is a rough early consensus among the pundits and
pros and it goes something like this:
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast and the West Coast are leaning Democratic and
likely will mostly end up in Vice President Al Gore's column.
</P>
<P>
   But the South, the High Plains and the Rockies are leaning
Republican and probably will end up mostly in Gov. George W. Bush's
column.
</P>
<P>
   That works out to an electoral vote wash _ thus far.
</P>
<P>
   So who gets to decide?
</P>
<P>
   If the talk means anything, keep an eye on an irregular band of
states, heavily industrialized, that stretches west from New Jersey
and Delaware into Pennsylvania and then on to Ohio, Michigan and
Missouri. Most of those states look like tossups.
</P>
<P>
   Then throw in a scattering of other states that also have a
tossup look, subject to plenty of argument and qualification.
</P>
<P>
   Among those states are Arkansas, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maine and
New Mexico, and possibly Georgia and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   And do not forget Florida, Iowa, Tennessee and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Washington state and Iowa, and most especially Tennessee, should
be Gore country.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush pulled a big vote in the Iowa caucuses and the
Washington state and Tennessee primaries and there is some
speculation that he might be inclined to commit the resources to
try again in the general.
</P>
<P>
   As for Florida, with its big cache of electoral votes, it is
Bush country _ the governor is Jeb Bush _ but Gore has considerable
strength there and he might have even more should he pick the
state's popular senior senator, Bob Graham, as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, speaking of vice presidential choices, should
Bush pick Pennsylvania's well-regarded governor, Tom Ridge, as his
running mate, he might be able to tip that state into his column.
</P>
<P>
   Or should Bush try to grab New York by choosing Gov. George E.
Pataki?
</P>
<P>
   Or New Jersey by choosing Gov. Christie Whitman?
</P>
<P>
   This is a tricky game. Especially in the early innings.
</P>
<P>
   Place no bets.
</P>
<P>
   AD FOOTAGE RECYCLED: ONLY NAMES CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   Election 1998. Lewis Massey, Georgia's secretary of state, is a
candidate for governor, running an advertisement that shows a
teacher sitting at her desk as a long line of pupils rushes past,
faster and faster, each putting an apple on the desk until the pile
almost reaches the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Massey, a Democrat, appears on screen, calling for more money
for education and lamenting:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Georgia classrooms have more kids and more kids and
more kids. As class sizes grow, it's hard for teachers to keep
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Cut to Election 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Easley, North Carolina's attorney general, is a candidate
for governor, running an advertisement in which a teacher is
sitting at her desk as a great long line of pupils rushes past,
faster and faster, each putting an apple on the desk ...
</P>
<P>
   Same teacher. Same children. Same apples.
</P>
<P>
   Now Easley, a Democrat, appears on-screen, calling for more
money for education and lamenting:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, North Carolina classrooms have more kids and more kids
and more kids. As class sizes grow ...''
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   Same consultant for both campaigns _ Saul Shorr of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had access to footage that is effective,'' Amanda Crumley,
Easley's press secretary, explained the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Massey lost.
</P>
<P>
   A CAUTIONARY WORD ON BUSH'S COATTAILS
</P>
<P>
   Back in the days when George W. Bush had $70 million in campaign
funds in the bank and a double-digit lead over Al Gore in the
polls, many congressional Republicans, especially House members,
were gleeful about the prospect of riding the governor's coattails
to victory in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But now Bush has spent most of that $70 million and, after a
bruising battle with Sen. John McCain of Arizona, the polls have
him running no better than even with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Worried Republican leaders have begun warning candidates not to
depend too heavily on the governor's coattails in November,
especially candidates locked in tight races that could determine
whether the Republican Party keeps control of the House. In fact,
says Rep. J.C. Watts Jr. of Oklahoma, the chairman of the House
Republican Conference, a new party poll indicates that the governor
may no longer have any coattails at all.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, a solid Bush supporter, is keeping the exact poll numbers
to himself. But in an interview last week with Roll Call, a paper
that covers Capitol Hill, he was blunt about their portent. ``We
can't rely on the presidential nominee,'' he said. ``There's no
coattails at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   MAPPING A NEW ROUTE FOR A MCCAIN RUN
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, the nation's most successful
third-party candidate, says that Sen. John McCain could win the
presidency if he would only take that route now. But Ventura
insists he is not pressuring McCain to bolt his party and go for it
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Doug Friedline and Dean Barkley, the political
masterminds of Ventura's surprising 1998 victory. Recently, they
have been on the phone numerous times to McCain's campaign manager,
Rick Davis, pushing him to push the senator toward a third-party
bid, but not under the banner of the Reform Party, which Ventura
has since bolted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could win,'' Friedline said. ``But I'd steer him away from
the Reform Party, that mess.''
</P>
<P>
   The word coming back from McCain: He was, is and will remain a
faithful Republican.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA CITY COUNCIL HAS A GAY MAJORITY
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Wilton Manors, Fla., made political history last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They installed a mayor who is gay, as well as two council
members, meaning that the city's five-member ruling body now has a
gay majority.
</P>
<P>
   The only other city in the nation where elected gays also are
running things is West Hollywood, Calif., said the Gay and Lesbian
Victory Fund, a political action committee based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Wilton Manors, a community of about 12,000 just north of Fort
Lauderdale, has one of Florida's fastest-growing gay populations.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1450EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
