<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     03-18 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE WORLD'S CHUDNEY GRAYS, ANOTHER STOP ON LIFE'S JOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ There is a section in the St. John's men's
basketball media guide where each player discloses personal
information: hobbies, favorite movies, favorite foods.
</P>
<P>
   The entries are often funny _ Jack Wolfinger says one of his
superstitions is ``to listen to at least one Wu-Tang song before I
start my day'' _ though most of them seem as if they were hastily
put together. One more chore a student athlete has to perform.
</P>
<P>
   When you get to Chudney Gray's page, you get the sense of a
person who took the time to consider the content.
</P>
<P>
   Under the category: ``If you had three wishes'' Gray writes:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I wish my mother was alive to see me graduate this year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I wish I could understand the things I don't already know.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I wish I could help end poverty and homelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his biography in the guide Gray did something none
of his teammates did: he inserted an addendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also would like to thank everyone that stood by me
throughout my four years, especially my father and grandparents.
It's been a great journey and, yes, I have many roads to travel. I
just hope to be successful and strong enough to face the different
obstacles of life. I love you `ma' and also the one that smiles in
her sleep. TR-1 Forever!! And just live life to its fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray is a 6-foot-3 senior guard who has become a crucial member
of the St. John's team that plays with a seven-player rotation,
limited size and a lot of desire. Gray's role is to keep the desire
going.
</P>
<P>
   Last season St. John's reached the final eight with a team
anchored by Ron Artest, a multitalented forward who is starting for
the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   This year's team lacks the extraordinary player and lacks depth
and size, but in some ways is more cohesive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're very good this year,'' Gray said. ``I even think
that we're even a little bit better because we know that we need
each other even more. When you have so many players that can do so
many things, they tend to take it upon themselves to try to win
games when you need everybody. That's one thing that we learned: We
need each other. No one single player on this team can actually
take over a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray's college basketball odyssey began in 1996 when he was
recruited to play for Manhattan College out of Rice High School by
Fran Fraschilla. When Fraschilla took the St. John's job before the
next season began, Gray, feeling that he could play at a top
Division I program, followed.
</P>
<P>
   Gray didn't enroll for the fall because he failed to get the
required SAT score. He didn't receive a qualifying test score until
October and was eligible in December. For two seasons Gray sat on
the bench. When Fraschilla was dismissed and replaced by Jarvis
last season, Gray began to prove himself.
</P>
<P>
   In midseason last year, he became the first substitute off the
bench. He responded with a career-high 15 points against
Pittsburgh. A game later he had nine points, two rebounds, two
assists and a steal in 20 minutes in a victory over West Virginia.
This season Gray has become a critical part of the St. John's team.
</P>
<P>
   Gray's crucial contribution this season began in December when
his friend and teammate Erick Barkley underwent knee surgery. Gray
made the first start of his career against Niagara and led St.
John's to an 81-66 victory. He contributed 14 points, seven assists
and a dynamic tomahawk dunk. After the game, Niagara coach Joe
Mihalich said: ``Gray was terrific. He kept the team together''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said, ``My role is to come in and give the guys energy and
just keep everybody together and just try to change the pace of the
game, or keep it on that high note.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Big East tournament Gray, had a big game in St. John's
75-70 quarterfinal victory over Villanova, and he scored 14 points
as St. John's defeated Miami in the semifinal game.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago this month Gray's mother died of leukemia. He and
his sister Tiffany were raised by his grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said that through all the sorrow and sadness he felt, his
mother's death helped sharpen his goals and establish priorities.
He wants to play some level of professional basketball without
forcing a career, without chasing one. Playing the role of the
point guard. Taking what's there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to waste four or five years,'' he said. ``I'm not
going to sit around and hope and pray and be sad and sulk and lie
to myself saying: `I'm going to go here. I'm going to do this,' and
having everybody pushing me when that's not really the reality of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The great thing about the national college tournament is that
there are so many different dimensions in the diverse tapestry.
Large programs with multimillion dollar budgets; small programs
that run on a shoestring. The highly recruited can't-miss prospect.
The player who rarely gets off then bench.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Chudney Grays of the world. The salt of the
earth type player who form the core of the student-athlete motif:
good, not great, a piece of the puzzle, not the puzzle itself. More
important, they have used sports to discover education and prepare
for success in a larger journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten realistic,'' Gray said. ``I know that there's
something out there for me to do, either going back to school and
getting my master's degree or playing somewhere. I want to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   This tournament is hot and exciting. For players who have put
their eggs in one basket this is the defining moment of their
lives. For players like Chudney Gray, this is only a stop along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1458EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     03-18 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LEARNING AT TEMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BUFFALO, N.Y. _ When John Chaney says he will do anything to
motivate a player, take him at his word.
</P>
<P>
   He has done a number of gross things as the basketball coach at
Temple, including trying to duke it out with John Calipari, then
coach of the University of Massachusetts, and calling players names
like ``Mr. Diaper'' _ and that's just what he does in public.
</P>
<P>
   This is how low Chaney sank in goading Juan ``Pepe'' Sanchez,
his current point guard who was recently selected as a third-team
all-American: Chaney learned to curse in Spanish. Or, rather,
Chaney thought he learned to curse in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   This excursion into linguistics took place during the first year
at Temple for Sanchez, who was recruited out of Bahia Blanca,
Argentina, on the basis of a five-minute tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know much English,'' Sanchez said the other day with
hardly a trace of accent. ``I could say `Hi' and `How are you?' and
`My name is,' and that was about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the freshman point guard, Sanchez often ran out of control
and, back in those days, he even entertained the odd predilection
for tossing up a shot once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   To try to cure him of these expansive habits, Chaney would yell
at him in his own particular patois _ an unapologetic stream of
billingsgate far more creative than Marine drill instructors or
master rappers.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney was afraid, however, that he was not getting through to
the young man because of these transcultural misunderstandings. So
Chaney went to a friend and asked for a list of phrases that might
help bridge the gap between a gentle Argentine and a ferocious
down-home bootstrapper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nasty words,'' Chaney rasped, in a voice worn down by a
68-year diatribe against idiocies.
</P>
<P>
   There was one session when Chaney invited Sanchez to depart for
Bahia Blanca on the first plane out, as soon as the airport opened.
(Temple practices are held at 5 a.m., long before flights depart
for South America, or anywhere.)
</P>
<P>
   To cap off the invitation, Chaney added a few of the phrases on
his list. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``His Spanish was terrible,'' Sanchez recalled. ``I didn't
understand a word of it. I had to ask, `What is he saying?'''
</P>
<P>
   So Sanchez stayed around, and produced one of the truly unusual
statistics: Sanchez must be one of the very few college players
whose scoring average dropped three straight times from his
freshman season _ 10.0 in his freshman year, 9.6 as a sophomore,
8.2 as a junior and at the moment 5.8 for this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez has not scored a single point in the last two games, or
a field goal in three, yet he was the best player on the court
Friday night with 15 assists and three steals and only two
turnovers in a clinical 73-47 dismemberment of Lafayette, in the
first round of the national tournament. Sunday he will have more of
a challenge, matched against Seton Hall's point guard, Shaheen
Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   They are polar opposites, with Holloway finding creative ways
for everybody to score, most certainly including himself, and
Sanchez displaying a selfless array of soft passes. Bounce passes.
Tip passes. Blind passes. Laser passes against the zone.
</P>
<P>
   In these Iverson days, there are almost no point guards who pass
almost exclusively. Sanchez is a throwback to point guards of
nearly half a century ago, like Dick McGuire of the New York
Knickerbockers, who needed a full-throated chorus of ``shoot!''
from his teammates before he would attempt such a selfish act.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez says his role models are two former point guards on the
Argentine national team, Alberto Cabrera in the '60s and Miguel
Cortijo in the '80s, both of whom refrained from shooting whenever
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad told me about them,'' Sanchez explained.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez was playing in high school in Bahia Blanca, a city of
250,000 and Argentina's main port, 400 miles south of Buenos Aires.
A neighbor had an uncle visiting from Philadelphia who encouraged
Sanchez to send a short tape of his games. Chaney, according to
legend, gave him a scholarship on the basis of Sanchez not taking a
single shot in five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him run like a rabbit and throw passes off a dribble,
which is a lost art,'' Chaney whispered hoarsely the other night.
``I saw a lot of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez did not arrive as a selfless player. He liked his
points, and he liked to drive aggressively to the basket. The loud
man at Temple ultimately cured him of that, as Chaney has cured
many others of their solipsistic tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   This is all part of the learning process. John Chaney ultimately
picked up a smattering of Spanish, and Pepe Sanchez learned from
the Chaney school of English as a Second Language. The National
Collegiate Athletic Association likes to somberly intone about its
wonderful ``scholar-athletes.'' Here is a case where learning
actually took place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
