u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-BRYANT-780     03-18 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BRYANT-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT TONES DOWN ACT TO WIN BIG
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Fox noticed something peculiar the past two months, the way
a teammate he used to think of as impetuous began to harness his
talent and conserve his flair. After watching for so long while
Kobe Bryant struggled to fold his game into his team's, Fox could
not believe how suddenly Bryant arrived at a crucial understanding:
that the needs of the Los Angeles Lakers outweighed his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to tell him the other day, `I'm proud of you, man,'''
Fox said. ```I'm really proud that you recognized a lot of our
success relies on your ability to remain calm and composed, to step
your game up when we need it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to be a few years away still, but it's
almost been overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parallel. Bryant grows up as a player and the Lakers just
happen to become the very best of the NBA. It is no coincidence how
the evolution of a rising young supernova has mirrored the
incredible success of his and Shaquille O'Neal's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're `the Combo,''' O'Neal said last week, coming up with a
nickname for himself and Bryant. ``One-two punch. If one of us
doesn't get you, the other will.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq's force plus Kobe's flash have always equaled fear among
opponents. But this is different. ``What's happening now is
downright scary,'' said Jerry West, the Lakers' president and the
man responsible for pairing the two.
</P>
<P>
   Before their loss to Washington on Thursday night, the Lakers
had won 19 straight _ the third-best winning streak in league
annals. That followed a 16-game run between Dec. 11 and Jan. 12.
Their run has separated them from Portland and the class of the
Western Conference and made the Lakers the favorites to give Los
Angeles its first post-Magic championship.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year on the job, coach Phil Jackson is folding his
arms in contentment, smiling that
my-guys-get-it-and-your-guys-don't smile that characterized his
six-title run with the Bulls. His new team is 53-12 and running
away with home-court advantage throughout the playoffs. As they
walk into Madison Square Garden Sunday for a high-noon NBC ratings
bonanza against the Knicks, their coach is the first to acknowledge
one of the primary reasons the Lakers are so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Kobe, the process has been: How do you meet your own goals
and desires while also escalating the play of your team and
including yourself in that group?'' Jackson said. ``He has met that
challenge. His development as a playmaker has been crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Before their 19-game streak, Bryant was averaging 22.6 points
and 3.9 assists. During the run, his point production remained
steady while his assists jumped to 5.6. When he is feeling spry and
the Lakers need his offense, he still takes over on occasion _
witness the career-high 40 points he dropped on Sacramento last
Sunday as the Lakers erased a 16-point second-half deficit.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Bryant's quest to sacrifice his athleticism _ to save
his indefensible crossover and his lean-in windmill dunks for the
right moments _ that have impressed his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't take every situation as a personal challenge,''
said Fox, the reserve forward. ``He's so competitive that, when
challenged, he'll find a way to redeem himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer is he taking it to a level that at times became
detrimental to the team. Flat-out, he's picking and choosing his
opportunities a lot better and making us more dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said: ``It has to do with me figuring out what my
teammates want from me and where they were on the floor. I don't
feel like a completely different player, but I will say this: I've
been able to hold back a lot from my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that pains a player with his skill level, Bryant
laughed and said: ``It's tough sometimes, because I know what I can
do. There's certain moments where I can do those things and it
actually benefits the team. Finding those moments now is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been growing pains. During a lackluster victory over
Cleveland on Jan. 19, Jackson chastised Bryant during and after the
game for essentially thinking, ``Kobe first, Lakers second.''
O'Neal even voiced his displeasure in the locker room, saying,
``We've got to act like a team,'' a pointed reference to Bryant's
one-on-one forays.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Jackson held his first and only Lakers meditation
session, turning down the lights as the team searched for a sense
of self amid the occasional selfishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil doesn't mind getting on players, even star players,''
West said. ``I think that's helped. He will sit Kobe down if he
thinks he needs to. In watching Kobe play the last six weeks, he's
been phenomenal. His defensive play, the way he's settled in on
offense. It's just been great.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite his immense popularity outside the locker room, Bryant
is often described as a loner on the Lakers, a bit of an aloof
celebrity who almost levitates above the air his teammates breathe.
But then, he only turned 21 in August. As guard Derek Fisher said
last week, ``Kobe can finally go out with us now.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning has partly healed an old rift between he and O'Neal.
``Kobe understands, like we all do, Shaquille is the man on this
team,'' Fisher added. ``That took awhile. He has definitely
accepted the responsibility to be a better team player, to allow
his ability to fit in with everyone while also having the freedom
to dominate a game by himself sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said, ``People will always throw stuff out there because
of barber-shop talk, but me and Shaq are cool. And me and Phil have
a good relationship, too. He has been great for us. He is a more of
a teacher than I ever imagined. He knows so much about basketball.
Personally, I think it's helped me as an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have more than merely Bryant to thank for their run.
O'Neal has been simply awesome, worthy of every corny nickname he
has ever bestowed on himself. The Diesel was named NBA player of
the week last Monday for the third time this season, averaging 43
points and 18 rebounds a game in three victories. After Vince
Carter dropped 51 points on Phoenix in his national television
debut two weeks ago, Shaq-Daddy had 61 points against the Clippers
on March 6 _ a display of dominance that brought both euphoria and
disbelief to the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   By raising his free-throw percentage nearly 10 percentage points
during the 19-game streak, the Big Luggage has also made the
Hack-a-Shaq defense passe. You cannot simply foul O'Neal anymore
and expect him to miss.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran leadership has been key, too. Glen Rice has sacrificed
his game to accommodate the two young stars. The skills Robert
Horry once brought to the Houston Rockets have re-emerged in L.A.
He did nothing for Jackson to begin the season, but after
recovering from a broken nose has managed to secure the majority of
minutes at power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Shaw, who used to click with O'Neal for alley-oop dunks in
Orlando, has again found his friend hovering above the rim. Like
Ron Harper, Horry and A.C. Green, Shaw still has something left in
his legs and understands the growth process in becoming an elite
team.
</P>
<P>
   These Lakers also stop people. They lead the league in opposing
field-goal percentage. Last season, opponents made 46 percent of
their shots against them. Today, teams barely shoot over 41 percent
against the Lakers. The wingspan on Bryant's 6-foot-8,
sinewy-yet-muscular frame made Allen Iverson an ineffective
perimeter player earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant's ability set up his teammates _ the ability to worry
about others before himself _ has been the genuine key. Whether
lobbing to O'Neal down low or recognizing a cutting teammate as the
double-team swarms him, Bryant is seeing the possibilities unfold
before acting rashly.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson used to rely on Harper, the former Bull, to settle
Bryant down and to organize the offense. Gradually, Bryant is
becoming the Lakers' primary playmaker. At one point during the
streak, he and his teammates were averaging five more assists a
game than their season average, contagiously sharing the basketball
because the player West refers to as ``best two-guard in the game''
has become so unselfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really has gone to a place where I didn't think he would be
for a few years,'' Fox said. ``His game has stepped up to a level
where you want the ball in his hands, running this team. You don't
even question it anymore. You know he's going to make the right
decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
