<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TERROR-DEATH-PENALTY-     03-18 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-DEATH-PENALTY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,180(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE IN BOMBING CASE WARNS AGAINST EXECUTIONS ON WIDE POLITICAL
GROUNDS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs throughout to expand, clarify and add quotes from memo;
Subs 10th graf, The defense ..., and adds 11th graf to update
status of defendants ;  Adds 4 grafs at beginning of 2nd take with
expert opinion.) 
 (Exclusive) 
(rk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyers for three men charged in the 1998 African
embassy bombings are arguing for their clients' lives on political
grounds, contending that executing them would be a foreign-policy
disaster for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorandum that is being sent to Attorney General Janet
Reno, the defense lawyers contend that executions of their clients,
who are accused of being mere ``foot soldiers'' in a terrorist
conspiracy, would only turn them into Islamic martyrs while
creating a blood feud between the United States and the Muslim
world.
</P>
<P>
   The effect, the lawyers say, would be to seriously damage the
government's chances of prosecuting Osama bin Laden, the wealthy
Saudi exile who has been accused of leading a global terrorist
conspiracy that included the embassy attacks and other acts of
violence against Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently worried that the issue may be viewed too narrowly,
the lawyers have also taken the unusual step of circulating their
30-page document to top officials in the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it plain,'' the Feb. 7 memo declares, ``that the
State Department ought to be fully consulted, and its views
considered, on all of the grave foreign policy, national security
and human rights implications of a U.S. government request for the
death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   All three men have pleaded not guilty and plan to fight the
charges in court later this year. But the memorandum assumes for
the sake of argument that they have been convicted and that the
death penalty would be inappropriate. Such arguments to prosecutors
are routine in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers in the case, U.S. vs. bin Laden, are seeking a much
broader audience in the government for their concerns about their
clients' fates.
</P>
<P>
   The case is the first in which federal prosecutors have sought
to impose the death penalty against a defendant accused of
terrorism in a foreign country. It is also the first time the
government has begun to pursue the death penalty in the series of
major terrorism prosecutions of about two dozen Islamic militants
in New York that began with the 1993 World Trade Center bombing.
Among those cases is another plot to blow up major landmarks in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   One defense lawyer who has read the memo said: ``This case lies
at the intersection of the criminal justice system and foreign
policy. The whole point of the memo is that it is folly to simply
treat this as a mere criminal case, much as we might wish things
were so simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense decided last week to send the memo after the U.S.
attorney, Mary Jo White, indicated that she would seek the death
penalty for at least one of the defendants, Mohamed Rashed Daoud
al-'Owhali, and was still considering doing so against two other
defendants. Reno must approve all decisions to seek the death
penalty in federal cases.
</P>
<P>
   The bombings at Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania,
killed more than 200 people and wounded thousands. Mr. al-'Owhali
is one of two men in custody accused of playing a direct role in
the Nairobi bombing.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the memo, which was submitted by nine lawyers
representing the three defendants who could face capital
punishment, was provided to The New York Times by a person who has
read it and believes that the death penalty issue should be debated
in a broader forum.
</P>
<P>
   The memo makes the defense strategy clear: to catch the
attention of top national security advisers to President Clinton
and to cast the death penalty issue not in legal terms but in a
larger context of the government's stand against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The memo notes, for example, that if prosecutors seek to execute
al-'Owhali and his two co-defendants, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh and
Khalfan Khamis Mohamed, it would be the clearest signal that bin
Laden would also face execution were he ever brought to New York,
tried, and convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The government could hardly spare the leader of the conspiracy
if it planned to execute his lower level ``foot soldiers,'' the
memo asserts.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden remains at large, living in Afghanistan under the
protection of the fundamentalist Taliban, and the United States has
conducted sensitive negotiations with other Muslim countries in
hopes of having him arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if the world knew bin Laden could receive a ``lethal
injection at USP Terre Haute'' _ the federal execution facility in
Indiana _ that would certainly chill any chance of cooperation from
Muslim countries, ``who must respond to domestic public sentiment
against handing over a Muslim leader to a Western power,'' the memo
says. But if bin Laden is not captured or is spared execution as
part of a deal with another country for his extradition, it would
be all the more unfair to execute his lower-level operatives, the
memo says.
</P>
<P>
   Already, three other defendants in the case face charges that do
not carry the death penalty, even though they are charged with
playing more important roles in the organization that conspired to
carry out the bombings. The U.S. government said it would not seek
the death penalty against one of them to win his extradition from
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   If higher-ups are convicted, the memo says, they will be immune
from capital punishment. Likewise, it says, if al-'Owhali and his
two co-defendants are sent to prison for life, they too ``will
vanish from view and soon be forgotten. But a sentence of death
will rescue them from oblivion,'' the memo says, ``and transform
them into celebrated martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very fact that the United States will have designated
these defendants for execution,'' it goes on, ``will guarantee that
their pictures will be held aloft over crowds of protesters. Babies
will be named for them, and young men from Morocco to Pakistan will
make plans to emulate them. Their actual executions will ignite
outrage and protest in many Muslim countries, and will leave a
legacy of further violence and revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Placing bin Laden on death row would have enormous ramifications
for the United States, the memo says. In the World Trade Center
case, it notes, the defendants did not face capital charges because
their crime occurred before the 1994 death penalty law was passed.
An attempt to arrest bin Laden and imprison him for life, the memo
contends, will be seen as a credible punishment, ``because it
displays the self-restraint and moderation of a great nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the United States declares that its success in this
effort will be measured by its ability to kill bin Laden once he
has been taken prisoner and rendered harmless,'' the memo says,
``the story line will quickly shift in a direction that could do
considerable harm to long-term American interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers have made separate submissions tailored to
each man's personal circumstances, offering arguments of why the
death penalty is not appropriate. Those documents are not being
circulated outside the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyers argue in their policy memo that the death
penalty decision is too big to be left solely to Reno. The memo
asks her, in making the ``momentous decision,'' to involve ``those
agencies which do possess genuine expertise and experience in how
the actions of U.S. courts may affect American policy interests
around the world.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Experts who were interviewed last week agreed that the case
posed troubling and even unprecedented questions. ``I think
Washington is attempting to treat these cases as criminal, and, in
one sense, the rationale is not bad,'' said Graham E. Fuller, a
former vice chairman of the National Intelligence Council at the
Central Intelligence Agency, who is writing a book on the future of
Islamic movements around the world. ``They are trying to say, look,
we have nothing against Islam. This has only to do with criminal
activity, period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, by treating it purely as a criminal case,''
Fuller said, ``they may be falling into the trap of saying there
are no political ramifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip B. Heymann, a former deputy attorney general under Reno
and author of ``Terrorism and America'' (M.I.T. Press, 1998), said
the death penalty was probably being seen as appropriate for the
case because of the sheer number of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the death penalty is going to be used in any case,''
Heymann said, ``it's hard to fail to use it in a case with 200
deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   In their memo, the lawyers argue that retribution would not
justify the death penalty. They say they went to Kenya and
interviewed the blast's survivors, who said they wanted those
responsible arrested and brought to justice, ``but we met no one
who wanted to see them executed,'' the lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   They also argue that deterrence is also not a valid
consideration for these defendants. They note that the government
has accused al-'Owhali, for example, with being a would-be suicide
bomber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, given the centrality of the concept of martyrdom in
extremist Islamic political movements,'' the memo says, ``a
stronger case could be made for the counterdeterrent effect of the
death penalty _ that is, that the death penalty would actually
stimulate rather than deter similar crimes in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death penalty is simply not what they fear,'' the memo
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Because court-ordered executions can take years to carry out,
the memo likens Reno's decision to ``a cruise missile with a six-,
eight- or ten-year trajectory.'' By that time, the political
terrain may be totally different, the memo says, and ``it may be
self-evident that executing three Islamist prisoners under the
glare of world attention is exactly the wrong thing for the United
States to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The memo cites the Turkish government's struggles over whether
to carry out the death sentence of Abdullah Ocalan, the most
prominent Kurdish rebel. Under pressure from European leaders,
Turkey has delayed his execution.
</P>
<P>
   The case ``ought to stand as a warning about how easily in
political cases a death sentence can entrap the government that
imposes it,'' the memo says.
</P>
<P>
   It also notes that the Allied powers did not execute the ``rank
and file SS officers who ran the German concentration camps, but
reserved the death penalty for the very highest-ranking civilian
and military officials who conceived and directed this vast
criminal undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps its most chilling section, the memo describes bin
Laden's being convicted in the United States and sentenced to die.
The memo says he would likely present a ``dignified and charismatic
figure'' in the courtroom, and ``his denials of legal
responsibility for the Africa bombings will be credited by millions
throughout the world, to whom he will appear as a martyr for Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``His sentencing hearing will provide him with a forum for
denouncing U.S. policies in the Muslim world,'' the memo continues,
``and to identify U.S. military actions which have undeniably
produced unintended collateral harm to civilian populations far
greater than even the Nairobi embassy bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The propaganda value of this opportunity for bin Laden and his
terrorist organization would be immense,'' the memo notes, ``and
the psychological impact of such a dramatic and highly personal
confrontation between the soon-to-be martyred bin Laden and the
United States government might well reverberate throughout the
Muslim world for decades to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1529EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     03-18 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A DISTURBING DOUBLE STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent story that came across the wire began with the news
that although Pedro Astacio still faces a trial on domestic
violence charges, he is scheduled to be on the mound for the
Colorado Rockies when they open the season in Atlanta on April 3.
</P>
<P>
   What a relief for the Rockies and their fans that their 17-game
winner from last season will be available to start the season, and
will be playing at least through July 5, when he faces possible
deportation to the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day Astacio pitches for the Rockies, absent from the
same ballpark will be John Rocker, beginning his 14-day suspension
for his off-season remarks about various ethnic groups and gays.
Astacio, meanwhile, is free to pitch, even though he had once
admitted guilt _ a plea that was withdrawn last week _ to hitting
his estranged and pregnant wife in August.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that for months after Astacio received a two-year
deferred sentence in exchange for a guilty plea on charges of
third-degree assault, Commissioner Bud Selig had nothing to say
about the quick-fisted pitcher. He had no fine to impose, no
discipline to mete out, no standard to uphold and no integrity of
the game to protect.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Selig the righteous has been all over Darryl
Strawberry for abusing himself with drugs, and on top of Rocker for
insulting so many, while injuring nobody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, when a crime is part of it, we let the criminal
procedure take place without interfering,'' said Richard Levin of
the commissioner's office. ``Then we may or may not take action.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds fair and just, except that Astacio had already, in
effect, admitted to hitting Ana Astacio in the right eye in an
argument at the home they had shared until the couple separated in
June. The police report noted that Ana Astacio had swelling and a
red mark on her face.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, immigrants convicted of domestic violence _
felony or misdemeanor _ are subject to deportation. When the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service initiated proceedings,
Astacio sought to withdraw his plea. In Littleton, Colo., last
week, a county judge allowed him to, on the grounds that Astacio's
lawyers did not adequately inform him of the consequences of his
plea.
</P>
<P>
   An INS district director, Joe Greene, said, ``Our efforts to
seek his deportation are suspended until the courts have spoken.''
He explained the attempt by adding that ``the message should be
that no matter what your station in life or public visibility,
you're not above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the Rocker ruckus, this story has not been so much
as a footnote. Should we be surprised? This winter, an athlete who
has been accused of murdering his pregnant girlfriend (Rae Carruth,
formerly of the Carolina Panthers) caused less of a national uproar
than the lunkhead left-hander who sounds like a rebroadcast of
Howard Stern's show every time he opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker got a standing ovation last week when he pitched in his
first spring training game, which only proves that wrestling fans
go to baseball games. In other and more significant news, the
National Football League suspended three players for two games
apiece, the first time it has sidelined a first-time offender for
off-the-field violence under the league's violent-crime policy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the players, Denard Walker of the Tennessee Titans, was
cited after pleading guilty to assault on the mother of his son.
While this is no earth-shattering development against the alarming
trend of athletes who physically abuse women, it is a good start,
and at least the NFL has a policy.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has none, said Levin, though he correctly pointed out
that baseball's off-the-field violence _ at least those cases we
find out about _ has not been close to the plague on football.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Selig's aggressiveness with Rocker and his silence on
Astacio opens a window into baseball's soul. Rocker created a
celebrity scandal, a media event, the South's most disparaging
mouth vs. the country's most diverse market. Something had to be
done. The image of the game had to be saved. The notion of
ballplayers as role models for children had to be preserved. But
when Astacio beats on a pregnant woman, baseball is happy to let
the courts handle it, in the hope that some judge or jury will
finesse the case and the only remaining blemish will be the one on
Ana Astacio's face.
</P>
<P>
   The double standards are as depressing as the way we react to
them, and report them. While we were consumed with Rocker,
analyzing his words as if they were preceded by thought, an Arizona
relief pitcher named Bobby Chouinard is being accused of choking
and slapping his wife on Christmas for refusing to buy him more
beer. When that did not persuade her, his wife told the police that
he held a loaded pistol to her head and made her beg for her life.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard, facing five to 15 years if convicted, asked to be put
on waivers by the Diamondbacks so he could work on ``difficult and
regrettable problems.'' This relieved baseball, for the time being,
of any obligation to suspend him. Selig's inaction on the Astacio
case suggests that Chouinard may have, no pun intended, jumped the
gun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1532EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
