<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-GIULIAN     03-18 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI AND CLINTON PURSUE DIFFERENT ROADS TO SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story is running on Page One in city editions.) 
(mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the six weeks since Hillary Rodham Clinton
announced her candidacy for the U.S. Senate, she has delivered a
stream of policy addresses that have begun to sketch out the
ideological foundation for her campaign. She has given a score of
newspaper and television interviews and traveled across New York
state, staging campaign events day after day.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's style could hardly be more different from that of her
opponent, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. The mayor, a Republican, has yet
to deliver a full speech discussing what he might do in the Senate.
While he holds regular freewheeling news conferences on the daily
happenings in his city, he has thus far declined most in-depth
interviews on the subject of his Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign trips have been irregular, as his aides
acknowledged on Friday in announcing that he would travel upstate
this weekend for a day and a half, his longest venture so far on
the campaign trail. Giuliani has not even staged the formal
announcement that most candidates welcome as a high-profile
opportunity to make the case for their candidacy. Giuliani's aides
say that he most likely never will.
</P>
<P>
   This is a matter of design, and not happenstance. In the weeks
since Clinton announced her candidacy, leaving almost no doubt
about the makeup of the field, she and Giuliani have chosen starkly
different roads to the Senate. And that has become increasingly
clear through their actions _ or the lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, it is the more traditional campaign of speeches,
events staged to highlight popular issues (education one day,
health care the next), and, of course, parades, like the St.
Patrick's Day parade in Manhattan, in which she marched to a good
bit of booing on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Giuliani's advisers have concluded that the best
way for him to run for senator is to be the mayor. That means, at
least for now, eschewing policy speeches and lengthy interviews
devoted to the subject of his candidacy, and spending far less time
on the campaign trail than his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani attacks Clinton frequently, it is typically over
tangential subjects, like her failure to tip a waitress during an
upstate campaign swing, rather than any policy differences between
them. The attacks are intended to rattle Clinton, one of Giuliani's
advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Giuliani has resisted engaging Clinton on issues she
has raised and has typically declined to respond to her attacks.
When Clinton criticized Giuliani's education record last weekend,
the mayor's campaign responded with an attack on her campaign fund
raising. If there is any recurring theme for Giuliani, it is
reminding voters that Clinton is not from New York.
</P>
<P>
   This pattern could change, advisers to Giuliani and Clinton say,
but probably not any time soon. More important, they don't want it
to.
</P>
<P>
   Given the enormous skepticism about Clinton's character and
experience that exists among many New Yorkers, the methodical style
she embraces is arguably the only one available to her. Clinton's
advisers have concluded that if the campaign becomes a referendum
on the first lady _ about her years in Washington, her relationship
with her husband, her recent move to New York _ she almost surely
will lose. She is on much stronger ground, her advisers believe (as
do Giuliani's aides), if the election revolves around the question
of how the candidates might vote and conduct themselves in the U.S.
Senate, which accounts for how she has spent these last six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's style reflects a whole different set of calculations.
The most obvious one is the advantage he presumably enjoys as a
Republican mayor in a Democratic city. Being seen every day as an
effective mayor helps him not only in New York City, which normally
provides the geographical base for a Democratic candidate for
statewide office, but also in the suburbs, where voters generally
get their news from New York City-based television stations.
</P>
<P>
   There are less obvious reasons as well. Giuliani, as even his
closest supporters acknowledge, has a blunt personality that may
not wear well over time. That is particularly dangerous for him
upstate, where there is already evidence of hesitancy to embrace
this brash symbol of New York City. There is reason for him to keep
something of a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is, of course, prone to the unconsidered campaign
utterance; one prominent Democrat supporting Clinton said that the
best thing Giuliani's advisers could do to ensure his election
would be to wrap a handkerchief around his mouth. And why, as one
of Giuliani's advisers said, should he get out there and run
against Clinton when on so many days she seems to be doing such a
good job running against herself?
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, New York is a Democratic state. It is not in
Giuliani's interest, except in the broadest sense, to get drawn
into a partisan discussion about the Democratic and Republican
views of issues that might arise in the Senate in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   There are some risks to both strategies. Clinton's restrained
speeches can certainly get lost in the glare of Giuliani's
fireworks. Clinton also does not have the obvious advantages on
issues that Sen. Charles Schumer enjoyed in defeating Alfonse
D'Amato in 1998: Both current candidates support abortion rights,
gay rights and gun control, for example.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the stance that Giuliani has adopted so far
allows the perception that he is running either an ideologically
slight or overly negative campaign. The latest New York Times/CBS
News poll found that a majority of voters believed that Giuliani
was spending more time attacking than explaining. An implicit
calculation in Clinton's plodding schedule of daily policy speeches
is that voters will ultimately turn away from a candidate who runs
a race like that.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Giuliani's approach reflects his essential calculation
that voters want the same qualities in a senator that they do in a
mayor. Clinton, as she tries to turn the discussion away from City
Hall and to Washington, is betting that they do not. In the end,
that might prove to be the key question in determining what happens
in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
