<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HRAP-COP-PROFILES0319     03-18 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HRAP-COP-PROFILES0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death is hitting co-workers hard
 &HT;    By Alfred Charles and Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It has been 41 years since a Fulton County sheriff's
deputy was shot and killed in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday the department struggled to cope with the shooting
death of Deputy Ricky Kinchen and the wounding of his partner,
Deputy Aldranon English.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worst fear has come true,'' said Maj. Michael J. Cooke, who
supervised the warrant deputies. ``I have never had to deal with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time a Fulton sheriff's deputy was shot and killed in
the line of duty was 1959. An inmate wrestled a gun away from a
deputy in the county jail.
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers praised the work of both men shot Thursday, described
as hard workers who loved their jobs. Although the men had other
partners while serving warrants, their superiors said they often
rode together during their 4 p.m. to midnight shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say anything about those two other than to say they
were both outstanding,'' said Sgt. Clarence Huber. ``In all the
years I have known them, they have been great.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood was solemn Friday at Grady Memorial Hospital, where
both men were taken for treatment. At least 40 deputies, Sheriff's
Department administrators and Atlanta police officers gathered
outside the seventh-floor rooms where the men were being treated.
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen's wife sat on the steps outside Grady and wept
uncontrollably, consoled by a Fulton marshal. She declined to speak
to a reporter about her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen, 35, suffered gunshot wounds to his abdomen, said Dr.
Jeffrey Salomone, one of the Grady surgeons who treated the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kinchen is a very good officer,'' Cooke said before news of
the deputy's death. ``He has street instincts and is never one to
shy away from anything if necessary. He just did what he was asked
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Kinchen lost an enormous amount of blood and needed a
transfusion of about 50 units. Kinchen was pronounced dead around
3:30 p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen had been a deputy for nine years. He was a Florida
native who had served time in the Army. He was the father of two
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a quiet guy with a dry sense of humor,'' Cooke said.
``He didn't say much in roll call. ''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Marshal Capt. Philip Pickett was stunned when he
heard that Kinchen had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't prepare for something like that,'' Pickett said.
``You never know what is going to happen. There was nothing wrong
with their tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickett said that he trained both Kinchen and English in the
Fulton County Public Safety Training Center and they often assisted
each other on issuing warrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was someone you liked to have around to have your back.
Every time something like this happens, you lose part of your
family,'' Pickett said. ``Officers fight sometimes, but we always
stick together.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Jackie Barrett said English managed to signal for help
with his flashlight after he had been shot and lay on the ground
bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did well in a tough situation,'' Barrett said. ``I'm very
proud he maintained his composure.''
</P>
<P>
   English, 28, has been with the Sheriff's Department for four
years. He joined the warrant division after stints with the
sheriff's juvenile division and executive team.
</P>
<P>
   An Alabama native, he is a former Marine who has a wife and
three children, the Sheriff's Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said English was shot several times in both legs, his
left arm and his right chest wall. He was in serious condition
Friday, but doing well. Those who spoke to English said he was
alert but somber. English's family declined through a hospital
spokeswoman to talk to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   The flag outside the County Government Building has been lowered
to half-staff. Inside the building, 146 pints of blood collected
Friday during a blood drive scheduled weeks ago was donated to
Grady in honor of Kinchen and English.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
