<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TAIWAN-ELECTIONS-0319     03-18 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECTIONS-0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAIWAN ELECTS PRO-INDEPENDENCE PRESIDENT IN FACE OF BEIJING
THREATS
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI _ The people of Taiwan spoke loudly and clearly against
corruption and Chinese intimidation Saturday, kicking out the
ruling party after more than 50 years of political domination and
electing Chen Shui-bian, a former Taipei mayor and lawyer for
political dissidents, as president.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the opposition Democratic Progressive Party
triumph, the margin was larger than what most people expected and
what months of neck-and-neck polling suggested: Chen got 39 percent
of the vote; independent James Soong 37 percent; and Vice President
Lien Chan of the ruling Nationalist Party had just 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Voters were swayed neither by repeated warnings from Lien that a
victory by Chen, whose party calls for formal independence for
Taiwan, could lead to war with China, nor by a recent speech of
Chinese premier Zhu Rongji reiterating Beijing's willingness to use
force to prevent Taiwan independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to thank Zhu Rongji for helping us elect Chen
Shui-bian,'' said a Taipei accountant surnamed He, shouting above
the din of fireworks, air horns and general merriment of tens of
thousands of Taipei residents who turned out at Chen's campaign
headquarters to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was also an unmistakable message to the Nationalist
Party that voters see it as corrupt and tied too closely with mafia
elements. Both Chen and Soong campaigned as clean-government
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``(With a) 39% vote for Chen and 37% vote for independent James
Soong, the 'throw the rascals out' message was the clearest message
from this vote,'' said John Tkacik(CQ), a former U.S. diplomat who
now publishes a weekly business bulletin on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   As for China, he said it may now be forced to re-evaluate its
Taiwan policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Politburo moderates in Beijing are now telling the
hard-liners, 'See! I told you the heavy-handed bullying would only
blow up in our faces. The time has come to completely revise our
approach to Taiwan,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two governments have been estranged since the Nationalists
lost a civil war to Mao Zedong's communist party in 1949 and fled
to Taiwan. Reunifying Taiwan with the mainland is one of Beijing's
top priorities.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign progressed, Chen backed down from his party's
independence platform, sounding more like his opponents in pledging
to negotiate with China and not make any drastic changes in policy.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech Saturday, he said he wanted to make a
``journey of reconciliation'' to China before his inauguration. He
also invited Chinese president Jiang Zemin and Premier Zhu to visit
Taiwan. Yet he added that Taiwan's sovereignty would be eternal and
Taiwan would never become a second Hong Kong, which reverted to
Chinese rule in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Chen also proposed a ``peace agreement'' and ``military
confidence-building'' measures, but did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by state-run news media, the Chinese
government reacted cautiously, saying it would wait and see what
Chen would say and do. The election results ``will not change the
status of Taiwan as a part of China,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Bill Clinton congratulated Chen on his
victory and said the United States ``strongly supports'' dialogue
between China and Taiwan ``and is committed to promoting peace,
stability and prosperity in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the election provides a fresh opportunity for both
sides to reach out and resolve their differences peacefully through
dialogue,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to conduct close unofficial ties with the
people on Taiwan through the American Institute in Taiwan in
accordance with the Taiwan Relations Act and our one-China
policy,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Chen and his party have been criticized for their lack of
experience in the foreign policy arena, having never held
national-level office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not have high-level credibility to conduct his mainland
policy,'' said Szu-yin Ho, professor of political science at
National Chengchi University in Taipei. ``China will probably not
give Chen any benefit of the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   His supporters counter that he is better positioned to negotiate
with China because people in Taiwan will not second-guess his
motives, just as Richard Nixon, a fierce anti-communist, was able
to establish relations with China 28 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Soong supporters are troubled by the thought of a Chen
Shui-bian presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very worried about relations across the Taiwan Straits,''
said Susan Chang, 28. ``We don't want to underestimate the military
power of China.''
</P>
<P>
   She is also pessimistic about the economic effects of Chen's
victory. At her job at a Taipei bank, she saw long lines of people
converting their money to U.S. dollars or transferring it out of
the country this past week. They were motivated first by a 6.6
percent drop in Taiwan's stock market Monday _ its largest
single-day decline ever _ and then by Zhu's fiery speech on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   David Yu, chairman of Summit National Bank in Atlanta, said he
knows of one bank branch in San Francisco that received $20 million
in transfers from Taiwan in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After 51 years in power, the Nationalist Party has accumulated
massive riches and become entrenched not only in Taiwan's political
institutions but its financial ones as well. Political and economic
uncertainty are bound to ensue with Chen's victory, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipate some chaos and confusion in Taiwan,'' Joseph Wu,
deputy director of the Institute of International Relations in
Taipei, said earlier this week. ``It would be the first time we
have a president who doesn't have a majority in the (parliament).''
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists' huge defeat perhaps could have been foreseen
given a clear downward trend in the last 10 years in its share of
parliament and county-level seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, the KMT is bound to be in trouble,'' Wu said.
``In the major urban areas, the KMT is starting to lose its grip.
This is an alarming sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown that the Nationalist Party's strongest base of
support is in rural areas, among less-educated voters and older
voters. The opposition party is most popular among voters under 40
and the highly-educated.
</P>
<P>
   His head down, Lien said quietly in his concession speech that
he would engage in ``self-examination and self-criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're going to see the disintegration of the party,''
said Yawei Liu, a Chinese native and history professor at Georgia
Perimeter College who has been in Taiwan for the past week to
observe the elections unofficially for the Carter Center.
</P>
<P>
   People have already been talking about Soong forming a new
party, which he hinted at in his concession speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of KMT members will quit and join Soong,'' said
Liu.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Chen, the other big winner in this election was
democracy itself, observers said. After Taiwan lifted 38 years of
martial law just 13 years ago, political reforms followed quickly,
with its first full parliamentary elections in 1992, its first
direct presidential election in 1996, and now, the first-ever
peaceful transition of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably unprecedented in the whole of Chinese
civilization _ one power replaced by another without bloodletting,
and all of the people accepting it,'' said Liu.
</P>
<P>
   The Taiwanese people themselves were enthusiastic about the
opportunity they had to influence their destiny. The voter turnout
rate was roughly 83 percent, which surpassed the already-high 74
percent turnout rate of the last presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Shin Chang, a Taiwan native who has lived in the United States
for 35 years, has been working since the 1980s for human rights and
democracy in Taiwan. He, along with more than 2,000 Chen supporters
from the U.S., returned to Taiwan this week to vote for their man.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's victory is ``the biggest fulfillment of my life,'' said
Chang, who retired last week after 25 years working in research and
development for Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co. ``This is what I have
hoped for for a long time . . . the democratization of Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
