<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1069 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     03-18 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS TURN IN BOOK REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal was given a book written by the German
philosopher Friedrich W. Nietzsche. Derek Fisher found the writings
of Chinua Achebe in his locker one day and re-read a book from his
youth called ``Things Fall Apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant's literary gift from Phil Jackson?
</P>
<P>
   ``The White Boy Shuffle'' by Paul Beatty, the story of a black
child who grew up in a white community having to deal with the
cultural dichotomy of going back to his roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little hip-hop and I thought very typical of Kobe's
life,'' Jackson said. ``He grew up in Italy and Europe for part of
his life and came back here. I felt it was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Jerry West has joined Phil's Book Club. Jackson gave the
Lakers' president a copy of ``Confederates in the Attic,'' a
frightening expose on bigoted Southerners who still subscribe to
the beliefs of their Civil War ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being around him, he's one of the real bright guys we
have in the league,'' West said. ``I have a different belief system
than him, but he's been able to incorporate some things that have
really helped us grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made a mark in Chicago by combining standard coaching
philosophy with his beliefs in Zen and other forms of spirituality.
But it was an open question how O'Neal and his teammates would deal
with incense and candles in their lockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're beginning to get the indoctrination, some of the
community things that I've always felt were important for a team to
grow and develop bonds together,'' Jackson said. ``Beyond the
basketball, I've always tried to make the experience worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant enjoyed and appreciated his book. Given the provocative
content, though, he thought Jackson assumed a bit too much about
his upbringing so early in their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said of Nietzsche: ``He was ahead of his time. Everybody
else was analog and Nietzsche was digital. They perceived him to be
crazy. So they put him in an asylum, which is how I'll probably end
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's book, ``Things Fall Apart,'' is about a child growing
up in Africa who encounters major obstacles in his tribal setting.
Convinced he is destined to live a hard life, he stays the course
and things end up working out for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``His message to all of us in different ways has been, `There's
so much more we can accomplish,''' Rick Fox. ``Phil brought that to
Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Jackson's philosophy has achieved the impossible:
mellowing West, whose penchant for taking the game home with him
has often tested him physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say he's not made me as crazy and enabled me to relax a
little more during games I guess is true,'' West said. ``I think
it's because I watch him and he doesn't seem like he feels the
pressure of the game. Phil has such an unusual ability to laugh at
things, whether we're behind or tied. That to me expresses the
confidence he has. I think it does help relax the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Their egos have run up against each other on occasion. Jackson
pushed for the acquisition of Toni Kukoc before the trading
deadline, but West held firm and decided to keep Glen Rice at least
until the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The two men once competed against each other on the floor in the
1970s: Jackson, the mustachioed Knick hippie, and West, the
clean-shaven, homespun Laker, Zeke from Cabin Creek. To this day,
they have few things in common. But one thing they do share is a
fierce desire to win, and that has softened any potential rough
spots in their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear I wanted to have my hand on the throttle when I
first came in, to have a little more control,'' Jackson said. ``And
yet this team has convinced me that I can let go sometimes, the way
they've come back from second-half deficits and found ways to get
back in games and perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Of West he added: ``He's a very personable guy. Working with him
has been fine.''
</P>
<P>
   West said: ``These games torment me because I know there's a
certain way to play the game. It's the ultimate team game when you
do what you're supposed to. So it's a sense of comfort to say that
I don't worry about every game like I once did. I still don't take
anything for granted, but I'm much happier about things now. It all
started when we hired Phil. I can't give him enough credit.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Microphone Issue Lingers
</P>
<P>
   Michael Goldberg, the Manhattan lawyer who serves as the
executive director of the National Basketball Coaches Association,
was instrumental last week in helping the league and its coaches
come to a resolution over the microphone controversy.
</P>
<P>
   After much debate, the league backed off its mandate to put
mikes on unwilling coaches on the sideline during nationally
televised games. The compromise involved the coaches allowing a
boom mike to be used over their huddles during timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue still won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   A union official who declined to speak for attribution, said the
players association was not happy about the most recent
development. The union felt as if the coaches recouped some of
their own privacy at the expense of the players _ who can be more
clearly heard with the boom mike during timeouts. The players feel
as if they have been left out of the negotiations, that the matter
has essentially been put to bed because the coaches have been
satiated.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, Goldberg appears to have a conflict of interest on
his hands. Though he represents the coaches, his company, National
Media Group, also counts on the NBA for part of its livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 Sports Sponsor Factbook, the sports marketing and
consulting firm trumpets the NBA as one of its most significant
clients.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches do not have a union and are regarded as separate
employees of their respective teams. Goldberg said most of his
company's NBA business is related to the marketing and sponsorship
surrounding the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not beholden to the NBA for anything,'' Goldberg said.
``My first loyalty is to the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   But records show that the group is responsible for Schick's and
IBM's sponsorship deals with the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said ``we're not totally on the same page'' with the
players association because of the players' union status. But he
added: ``I've been in contact with the players association on a
number of occasions on this issue. They know: I work for the
coaches. I've been doing it for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   League officials plan to meet with the coaches after the season
to address their marketing needs, Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is by no means dead, but we're working toward a
resolution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Warriors No More
</P>
<P>
   John Starks, a former Golden State Warrior, is sitting at home
in Tulsa, Okla., awaiting the outcome of an arbitration hearing
Tuesday to determine whether he can leave the Bulls permanently and
become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Cummings recently suffered a partly torn rotator cuff in
his right shoulder and is expected to miss the rest of Golden
State's forgettable season.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mills? He will also not play again this year after having
surgery Dec. 29 to remove bone spurs from his right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months after trading away Latrell Sprewell to the
Knicks, the Warriors do not have a single player left on the court
from that deal. Turning down a benevolent offer from Pat Riley of
P.J. Brown and Dan Majerle at one juncture, the Warriors basically
gave up one of the top swingmen in the game for three role players
who have no current role with the team.
</P>
<P>
   No one believed Golden State would get fair market value for
Sprewell, given the choking incident in December 1997. But how the
Warriors ultimately received so little in return is just another
example of why they are having such an awful season.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the three former Knicks either in another uniform or on
the injury list, there was another indirect casualty of the deal.
P.J. Carlesimo is currently serving as a college basketball
analyst.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
