<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1078 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HRAP-NEIGHBORHOOD0319     03-18 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HRAP-NEIGHBORHOOD0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents fear gunning down of two deputies will tarnish the
area's reputation
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider and Mae Gentry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From a rooftop loudspeaker, the Islamic call to prayer
peals out across the park and small homes of the southwest Atlanta
community of West End.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintive song calls worshippers _ some in business suits
and some in religious attire _ to a small green home with white
trim, their mosque on West End Place.
</P>
<P>
   Among them walks Khalid Abdul Muhammad, a former spokesman for
the Nation of Islam, dressed all in black and wearing a Black
Panthers pin. He sweeps by news crews as though they aren't even
there.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was unlike any other day in West End.
</P>
<P>
   People here fear that this tight-knit community of 3,400 people,
with its proud history of self-reliance, will be defined by the
gunning down of two deputies Thursday night. Their concern is
intensified because police are searching for a leader in this
community, Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, known in his days as a Black
Panther as H. Rap Brown.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to the story of West End, people say. It is a place
that is predominantly black but also home to a thriving historic
district, respected cultural centers, an amalgam of religions and
cultures _ Christians, Muslims, African Hebrew Israelites _ who
live in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diversity is great, and that's one of our strengths,''
said Sharon Allen, president of the West End Neighborhood
Development community association.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a mile from the mosque is a vegetarian restaurant run
by the African Hebrew Israelites and the historic West Hunter
Street Baptist Church, once the pulpit for Ralph David Abernathy
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Christian Nation operates the Shrine of the Black
Madonna Bookstore and Cultural Center one of the premier black
bookstores in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Colvin has driven from a neighboring county to the
bookstore on a spiritual journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for truth,'' said the 33-year-old computer
student, who grew up in a traditional Christian household but now
is exploring his African heritage. Paying for a book on African
cultures, he said, ``This bookstore has so much more than Barnes &AMP;
Noble.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking his money was Safiya Angolwisye, a member of the shrine
who lives in the church's apartment building nearby on Peeples
Street. ``I think it's safer than Buckhead,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Peeples Street says a lot about West End. At the end of a block
lined with restored Victorian homes worth several hundred thousand
dollars each is a burned-out hulk of a home left to rot, one of
many in this community. And across the street, on another moribund
building, is graffiti that reads like community activism rhetoric.
In white spray paint on red brick, it reads, ``No More Turning Our
Backs on West End.''
</P>
<P>
   Activism in West End has always been hard-core. Some of the
strongest community leaders were once members of the Black
Panthers. The vibrant political scene is continually recharged by
students from the nearby Atlanta University Center.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, the community, Atlanta's oldest community, has
been uplifted by its own designs and forcefulness. In the 1960s,
West End was devastated when the construction of I-20 displaced
entire blocks. The neighborhood since has rebounded, with new homes
built on land left vacant by the expressway.
</P>
<P>
   ``This community is anchored by homeowners _ African-Americans
who put money into this community to buy houses and apartment
buildings,'' said Janice White Sikes, a former president of the
community association.
</P>
<P>
   When she moved here about 25 years ago, ``It was in really bad
shape, a shell of a community.'' Boardinghouses abounded, and they
brought with them crime and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Muslim community, which began moving into West
End in the 1970s and has grown continuously, have been ``good
neighbors,'' she said. Many residents say the Muslims have helped
rid the neighborhood of drugs and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972 the Mall West End was the first shopping center in
Atlanta to feature a black Santa.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, residents believed banks and insurance companies
were red-lining the neighborhood, keeping loans from blacks.
Neighborhood activists, such as Sikes and her late husband,
complained all the way to Washington and prompted a federal probe.
</P>
<P>
   The 1991 designation of a portion of the neighborhood as a
historic district helped stem the tide of boardinghouses.
</P>
<P>
   When the neighbors were fighting to create a historic district,
developers tried to tear down Brown High School. Sikes and the
community battled back, and the building now stands as the only
technology middle school in the city.
</P>
<P>
   But community leaders acknowledge there are problems. There's
the homeless man known as Arnold who stands at the Lee Street exit
ramp, holding a sign asking for money. The gas station there
requires that you pay before you pump.
</P>
<P>
   Vacuuming his 1982 Buick LaSabre at the station was Ulysses
Cofield, 36. ``I like the West End,'' he said. ``It's a black
neighborhood. Lots of soul food joints. Everything I need is here _
bars, stores. It's self-contained.''
</P>
<P>
   There's crime, but he believes there's crime everywhere. The
homelessness gets him down, though.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Christmas, a 3-year-old boy was kidnapped during
a carjacking at Kroger CitiCenter. Also, a elderly woman recently
was murdered in an apartment complex on the fringe of West End.
</P>
<P>
   But many people say they feel safe on the streets here, and the
streets are always busy with activity.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, 19-year-old Dalir Asad, dressed in a blue
pinstripe suit, was selling bean pies on the street outside Mall
West End. Nearby, a man was preaching to raise money for his
church.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street is a strip of stores including a pawnshop, a
check-cashing service, a wig shop and a music store.
</P>
<P>
   With the coming of spring, plans are under way for the annual
Malcolm X Festival at West End Park. But now that park is filled
with news crews pointing cameras at the Laundromat operated by
Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Walking into the Laundromat, Alvin Munson, 43, brought $15 in an
envelope ``to show my support'' for Al-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   What does the future hold for West End?
</P>
<P>
   Troy Sikes, 22, offered a positive spin during lunch with his
mother, Janice, at Chanterelle's restaurant, where Vice President
Al Gore recently visited.
</P>
<P>
   He sees more young people settling here, ``understanding that
it's a community, not just a neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others worry about recent events.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Edward Spriggs, director of Hammonds House
Galleries, met with officials of the Atlanta Chamber of Commerce.
The meeting went well. They spoke about the West End as an
undiscovered gem.
</P>
<P>
   But before he went to sleep that night, he heard the news of the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that will overshadow their opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
