<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HIALEAH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIALEAH MEET OPENS AT GULFSTREAM WITHOUT THE FLAMINGOES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ The 700 flamingos didn't make the trip, but
everything else did, from horses and trainers to hot-dog vendors
and parking valets. It was a trip that covered only 15 miles on the
ground, but it covered decades of rivalry that took a rare and
perhaps softer turn Friday when Hialeah opened its racing season at
Gulfstream Park.
</P>
<P>
   To most racing fans in South Florida who had become accustomed
to the yearly haggling and legislative battles over racing dates,
it seemed unworkable _ like the Hatfields moving in with the
McCoys. But it came about after a hurried series of negotiations
triggered by Frank Stronach, the Canadian industrialist who bought
Gulfstream Park last year and assumed a growing reputation as the
new strong man of racing.
</P>
<P>
   The switch was agreed upon only two weeks ago, leaving much
confusion about immediate details and much uncertainty about
long-range issues. And the transition led to overnight turmoil.
Gulfstream ended its 63-day season on Thursday; Hialeah began its
58-day season on Friday. Even the public-address voices changed
overnight. But the lush setting stayed, with perhaps the uneasy
feeling that an era was ending, or maybe beginning. Still, only
5,283 persons showed up Friday to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace in Florida racing,'' said John Brunetti, the chairman of
Hialeah. ``This has been a long day coming.''
</P>
<P>
   And David Romanik, who took over on Friday as president of
Gulfstream, said in a greeting printed in the Hialeah program in
green ink for St. Patrick's Day: ``Gulfstream Park is pleased to be
the site of the 2000 Hialeah Park meeting, marking a new era of
cooperation in Florida thoroughbred racing.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. But nobody honestly believed that a few
diplomatic words could ease the pain of three decades of angry
words spoken in legislative sessions where both tracks struggled to
gain the same thing: the lucrative racing dates in the winter
tourist season. Gulfstream won, but deemed the victory insecure;
Hialeah lost, but stayed alive with smaller audiences and with
simulcasting revenue tiding the track over its hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Stronach with his resources and his vision of
racing, and suddenly Hatfield was being invited to visit McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   Historic overtones could be heard. Hialeah was opening its 75th
racing season with memories of the days when it operated the most
beautiful track in America and ran horses on a surface widely
acclaimed as the best in the country. It was where the wealthy
spent their winters: arriving by special train, wintering in Palm
Beach, racing at Hialeah with its royal palms and Mediterranean
buildings. The 700 flamingos who nested on the slopes of the
infield lake were symbolic of a way of life as they flew in mass
formation every afternoon past the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Hialeah was in the center of a largely working-class
community and was being upstaged by Gulfstream, its neighboring
track to the north of Miami. Each track opened for only two months
of the year, which left six months of racing to a third track in
the area, Calder, which was bought last year by Churchill Downs in
a networking spree that rivaled Stronach's.
</P>
<P>
   So, Gulfstream and Hialeah half-buried the hatchet and searched
for answers. But the differences were wide.
</P>
<P>
   In the season it closed Thursday, Gulfstream averaged 10,373
customers a day, a decline of 3.8 percent from the 1999 meeting.
On-track betting totaled $2 million a day, a tiny fraction below
last year's.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues still to be solved: how to run grass races on
Gulfstream's worn-out turf course. For a time, it was suggested
that Gulfstream was negotiating another revolution with Hialeah:
running one day each week, probably Thursday, on the lush turf at
Hialeah and simulcasting the races back to Gulfstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking, but it doesn't look imminent,'' Romanik
said. ``Too many details to be ironed out in too short a time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
