<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SOUR-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: EARLY CAMPAIGN CLASHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, March 19:
</P>
<P>
   Removing any doubts that theirs would be a long, tough campaign
for the White House, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush
attacked each other last week in extremely personal terms. Whether
the public as a whole has an appetite for months of squabbling is
an interesting question. Bush has the additional problem of
demonstrating that he truly is a uniter, not a divider, of his own
party. Based on his resistance to fully embracing the campaign
finance agenda of Sen. John McCain and the confusion over meshing
his policies with those of congressional Republicans, he has some
work to do.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates need to reach beyond their parties as well. The
task may be easier for Gore simply because while Bush was forced to
the right to get the nomination, the vice president stayed in the
center. But Bush is clearly hoping that he can prevent the vice
president from winning independent votes by hammering at the issue
of Gore's trustworthiness. That is part of the reason this campaign
has begun on such a sour note. By asserting that Gore will do
anything to win the election, the governor may have hit on an
effective way of tying together the doubts that many people have
about Gore's tendency to exaggerate and his fund-raising in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem for Bush is that he cannot yet claim to have
calmed down his party. He asserted in an interview with this
newspaper that his views had not been changed by his competition
with McCain, then later took a more conciliatory tone. The Bush and
McCain camps are in a struggle over the makeup of the Michigan
delegation. On Tuesday, in his first speech since suspending his
campaign, McCain may well renew his demands for Bush to become a
full supporter of campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has begun sending signals to Republican congressional
leaders that he would love a compromise with the White House that
might take gun control off the table. But GOP hard-liners, echoing
the National Rifle Association, do not want to give an inch. On
budget issues there is even more discord. Bush's tax-cut scheme is
so extreme that the Republican leadership rejected it, coming up
with a smaller tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Gore faces a test of his own skills as a
uniter on the trade issue. Many Democrats are opposed to granting
favorable trade status to China and approving its entry into the
World Trade Organization. Some cite China's human rights record
while others are simply echoing organized labor. Gore has made
clear his own support of China's membership in the WTO, but he is
not exactly leading the fight on Capitol Hill. He is leaving that
to President Clinton. Bush, by contrast, has been speaking in favor
of Chinese membership, even though some in his party would block
China because of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects either Bush or Gore to be singing from his party
song book all the time. But these early tests of their ability to
work with their own colleagues may give clues as to their ability
to reach out to skeptics in the middle. There was a big turnout of
independent voters this year, in large part because of McCain. On
the Democratic side, for all the fireworks of the contest between
Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, turnout was low. Voters may want
more than eight months of hurling insults. They will be looking for
signs of maturity, leadership and an ability to listen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1604EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
