<HEADER>
A1086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-HISTORY-NYT &LR;      03-18 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN'S NATIONALIST PARTY UNDONE BY FORCES IT ENCOURAGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TAIWAN-ELECT and related stories.) 
(mk) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Taiwanese election marks a huge defeat for the Nationalist
Party, which in the 20th century controlled first China and then
Taiwan, and which presided over the emergence of the very
democratic forces that ultimately upended it.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Yat-sen, the great Chinese nationalist and revolutionary,
formed a predecessor organization of the Nationalist Party in 1894
while he was living in exile in Hawaii. The party's initial aim was
to overthrow the corrupt Qing Dynasty, which was already
disintegrating and finally collapsed in 1911-12.
</P>
<P>
   The party dominated China for the next few tumultuous decades,
although power was also divided among warlords and for a time the
Japanese invaders. Party leaders, such as Generalissimo Chiang
Kai-shek, were initially impressed by the organization of the
Soviet Communist Party and modeled the Nationalist Party along
Leninist principles, even calling each other ``comrade.''
</P>
<P>
   While they had a good deal of support from Americans, the
Nationalists became detested in China because of their corruption,
brutality and failure to fight the Japanese invaders. In 1949, the
Communists under Mao Tse-tung defeated the Nationalists and forced
them to flee and move their seat of government to the offshore
island of Taiwan, which had just been recovered from Japan in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2 million Nationalist soldiers and officials settled on
Taiwan, where they were bitterly resented by many local people. In
particular, the Nationalists were hated for massacring local people
during upheavals that began on Feb. 28, 1947, and ever since then
the phrase ``2-28'' has been a sensitive code word in Taiwan that
conjures those antagonisms between local people and the
mainlanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists might well have seized Taiwan in the early 1950s,
because Chiang's army was in chaos and America was unwilling to
help it. But then fate intervened: In 1950, North Korea invaded
South Korea, and Americans became increasingly fearful of communism
around the world. The upshot was that President Truman sent the
Seventh Fleet to protect Taiwan. Ever since, the United States has
either promised or hinted that it would protect Taiwan from a
mainland Chinese attack.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling Taiwan, the Nationalist Party had little ideology
other than self-aggrandizement and self-enrichment. Particularly in
the 1950s and 1960s, the security forces under Chiang and his son
and successor, Chiang Ching-kuo, often dragged away critics of the
regime. Initially, they were often killed immediately; later they
tended to face torture and sham trials.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists imposed their ideas and language on Taiwan, and
children were forced to speak Mandarin Chinese and punished if they
spoke the Taiwanese or Hakka dialects that they spoke at home.
There was almost no teaching of local history, and instead children
learned about distant mainland Chinese provinces that they could
never visit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Nationalist Party redistributed land, promoted education
and encouraged the Taiwanese people to form businesses and get
rich. The result was an economic and educational revolution in
Taiwan that laid the seeds for a political one as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the Nationalists responded to popular aspirations
and began to permit opposition party activities _ although even
then critics of the Nationalists were tortured and occasionally
killed. The playing field was never level, for the Nationalists
manipulated the news media and owned companies that gave them huge
economic resources, but they gradually allowed opposition figures
to win local elections and form local power bases.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest changes came after the death of Chiang Ching-kuo in
1988. Control of the Nationalist Party passed uneasily to Lee
Teng-hui, a Taiwanese who as vice president was Taiwan's new
president. Lee transformed the Nationalist Party by democratizing
it, distancing it from its mainland Chinese roots, and ultimately
by creating a more pluralistic Taiwan in which an opposition
victory became possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1625EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
