<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CLINTON-SOUTHASI     03-18 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-SOUTHASIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLINTON'S JOURNEY TO SOUTH ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, March 19:
</P>
<P>
   With just 10 months left in office, President Clinton on Sunday
begins one of the most important trips of his presidency. Though
India, Pakistan and Bangladesh make up a sixth of the earth's
population, no American president has visited this turbulent region
since Jimmy Carter in 1978. In part, the long neglect is
attributable to the Cold War, when Pakistan was assigned the role
of front-line ally against the Soviet Union while India got written
off as a friend of the Kremlin. Now, it is the tensions between
these two countries that threaten a nuclear war, and the United
States needs to re-energize its approach to their problems.
</P>
<P>
   India is the first stop and showcase of Clinton's trip, as it
should be. Since the acceleration of economic reforms in 1991,
India has enjoyed impressive economic growth. Most of its
population still lives in hundreds of thousands of small villages,
while other Indians are developing software in high-tech centers
for export to America. Appropriately, Clinton plans to visit both
of these Indias, and to stop at tourist sites like the Taj Mahal.
It has always been odd for the United States not to have a closer
relationship with the world's most populous and diverse democracy,
and the president's visit can move toward that goal. But while
trying to reach agreements on trade, technology transfer and
environmental issues, Clinton must make clear that his greatest
interest is to see India and Pakistan reduce the danger of a
nuclear confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   In Bangladesh, which has also made economic gains in recent
years, Clinton will encounter another reminder of the region's
violent past. Like so many South Asian leaders of recent decades,
the country's prime minister, Sheik Hasina Wazed, is the daughter
of an independence leader. Her father, Sheik Mujibur Rahman, was
assassinated in 1975, a few years after he led Bangladesh to
freedom in the last India-Pakistan war. Clinton's visit can lead to
further assistance to help Bangladesh fight disease, hunger and
overpopulation.
</P>
<P>
   But the trickiest part of Clinton's trip will come at the end,
when he stops briefly in Pakistan. The visit was added in response
to Pakistani warnings that a snub would encourage terrorist and
fundamentalist tendencies. In a speech last week, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said correctly that Clinton's decision
must not be seen as a sign of approval for the military coup in
Islamabad last year. Clinton needs to use his brief visit to press
for a quick return to democracy and for military restraint,
including an end to Pakistan's ties with terrorist and insurgent
groups in Kashmir, India's only Muslim-dominated state.
</P>
<P>
   By devoting four days to India and traveling throughout the
country, Clinton may earn enough good will for some frank talk
about Kashmir with his host, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee.
There can be no military solution to the Kashmir problem. India can
take a step toward eased tensions by reducing its military forces
in Kashmir in return for reciprocal action by Pakistan, including
withdrawal of insurgent groups it may be supporting. In the nuclear
area, both countries need to make progress toward signing a
test-ban treaty and curbing deployment of missiles and production
of fissile materials.
</P>
<P>
   In his waning months in office, Clinton has a chance to nudge
peace efforts ahead in Northern Ireland and the Middle East.
Whether he can do so in South Asia as well will depend in large
part on how effectively he handles this week's visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1628EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
