<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, March 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the chill in the surface air across the Northeast, the
upper levels of the atmosphere will begin a warming trend Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A very large high-pressure system cresting over New Brunswick
Sunday morning will have barometric readings near 30.80 inches of
mercury. It will produce sunny and cool weather from New Jersey to
Quebec. Its broad circulation will draw moisture from the Atlantic
inland over a shallow dome of chilly air in the Southeast. This
combined with an approaching disturbance will cause cloudy skies
and a chill rain in parts of the Carolinas and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Winds from the south extending from the surface to 30,000 feet
will transport milder, moist air into the Ohio and Tennessee
valleys. Thickening clouds and advancing showers will temper the
warming trend. Low pressure in Arkansas will move slowly east. A
corridor of cold rain will soak the region on the northwest flank
of this storm. Strong thunderstorms will drench the central Gulf
coast as a cold front plods eastward.
</P>
<P>
   A dense overcast will cover the central Great Lakes, and patches
of light rain are expected from northeast Iowa to Michigan. Sunny
and pleasant conditions are expected from the Dakotas to the
Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp cold front will swing through the northern Rockies with
heavy snow in the Bitterroots and northern Wasatch along with mixed
showers in the valleys. The snow will arrive across the southern
Wasatch on Sunday night. Colder, damp weather will be the rule west
of the Cascades. California will be bright, windy and not as warm
in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Spring Arrives
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of spring at precisely 2:35 a.m. Eastern Standard
Time on Monday will mean little meteorologically. However, during
the next several weeks as the rays of the sun become more direct,
the weather will surely respond. The sun does not heat the
atmosphere directly, since the envelope of air is mainly
transparent to its high-energy radiation. The earth absorbs much of
the sun's energy. Lower-energy radiation from the ground then heats
the atmosphere from below. For several more weeks, the chill of the
past season will linger aloft, making possible more bouts with
wintry weather.
</P>
</TEXT>
