<HEADLINE>
GOALS OF TOP AWARD WINNERS ARE BOLSTERED BY REALISM AND OPTIMISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One was honored for a memorable season at the helm of
one of yacht racing's toughest, trickiest one-design keel-boat
classes. The other was praised not only for her skills on the race
course, but also for organizational and leadership abilities in the
footlights of sailing's grandest stage.
</P>
<P>
   Though they had crossed tacks on numerous occasions during the
recent America's Cup trials in New Zealand, they were recently
reunited in New York for a ceremony to laud their accomplishments.
Last Wednesday, at the New York Yacht Club headquarters in
Manhattan, the Star sailor Eric Doyle and the America True
syndicate head Dawn Riley were named the 1999 Rolex Yachtsman and
Yachtswoman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, 31, a sailmaker who began his racing career off the Gulf
Coast of Mississippi and who now resides in San Diego, spent a busy
year competing aboard Melges 24s, his Star-class boat, and as the
mainsheet trimmer aboard Dennis Conner's cup challenger Stars and
Stripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going from the Star to Stars and Stripes wasn't that hard,''
Doyle said. ``Like the Star, a cup boat has a great big main, a
small jib and a deep keel with a bulb. The overall concepts are
similar although they're obviously applied quite differently.''
</P>
<P>
   But Doyle's eyes grew wide as he described making the transition
from the 75-foot cup racer, with its 16-man crew, back to his
two-man Star dinghy, which is just short of 23 feet. ``Now that's a
lot harder,'' he said, laughing. ``You think, boy, this thing is
small.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades the Olympic-class Star has attracted some of the
world's best sailors, a fact that's underscored by its roster of
gold medalists and world champions, including Paul Elvstrom, Lowell
North, Dennis Conner, Paul Cayard, and Torben Grael. Conner has
said the planet's toughest regatta to win is the Star worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle added his name to that illustrious list with a one-point
victory in the 1999 Star world championship off Punta Ala, Italy.
``The quality and depth in the fleet was just tremendous,'' he
said. ``To this point it's the pinnacle of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just one step toward a greater goal, however, because
next month Doyle and his crew, Tom Olsen, will compete in trials
off San Francisco for the Star-boat slot on the U.S. Olympic
sailing team. ``We're not through yet,'' he said. ``Not even
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, a 35-year-old native of Detroit, is also looking ahead.
But her sights are once again set on Auckland, where her San
Francisco-based America True coed squad emerged as one of the top
American efforts in the challenger's trials leading up to the
recent cup match, which was won in convincing fashion by Team New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``America True is moving ahead,'' she said. ``Winning this award
is kind of a thank you for everyone who's supported us so far, and
it also gives us a nice platform to jump off for the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   Though America True's budget of $12 million was a fraction of
that spent by many of the challenging syndicates, Riley's squad was
a giant killer in the early round robins before running out of
steam in the semifinals of the series. ``Every single person on our
team was doing what they'd dreamed of, which was doing an America's
Cup campaign,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Having a small budget was actually a strength. It
meant we really had to think through problems and use every dollar
effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the cup, Riley's San Francisco rival, Cayard
of America One, said he believed that the United States needed to
merge forces into a super-syndicate to ensure future success
against the Kiwis.
</P>
<P>
   Riley didn't buy that. ``It was a statement made in defeat,''
she said of Cayard's remarks. ``If they'd limited it to one
American team, we wouldn't have existed. Sure, with one team you'd
have America's best sailors the next time around. But what happens
when they retire? We didn't start out with the big names, but we
brought 23 new cup sailors up to a very good level of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, a realist, said the New Zealanders will be tough to beat.
In fact, in the days before their match versus Italy's Prada
Challenge in the cup finals, she correctly predicted the 5-0 Kiwi
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many little things they were doing that you
could see they'd thought through every eventuality,'' she said.
``And they wouldn't have made all those little changes if they
weren't very happy with their boat speed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Riley, who decided at age 13 that she would compete for the
cup, is also an optimist. ``We have to make ourselves stronger as
challengers, and hope they don't progress as fast,'' she said. ``I
think catching up to them is doable. We're closing the gap.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
