<SLUG> BC-SOC-ALGARVE-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASTAIN'S PENALTY KICK WINS ALGARVE CUP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOULE, Portugal _ This was not the most important soccer match
Brandi Chastain has ever won with a penalty kick, but she
nonetheless provided the American women with another substantial
victory Saturday, even if the stakes were not as high as the sun in
this beautifully whitewashed region at the southern tip of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain provided the only scoring in a 1-0 victory over Norway
in the Algarve Cup, the most significant tournament outside the
World Cup and the Olympics and the only meaningful event the United
States had never won in five previous attempts.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most consequential victory for the American women
since their penalty-kick victory over China in last summer's World
Cup. Nothing had remained the same for the team, not the coach, the
lineup or even the preferred formation of attacking and defending.
However, some of the uncertainty about security under the new
coach, April Heinrichs, seems to have dissolved as she appears to
have decided that the World Cup roster will not significantly
change for the 2000 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's penalty kick did not have the drama or arresting
celebration of Chastain's World Cup moment, but it was equally
decisive. It came early in the run of play, rather than after two
hours of regulation and a pair of overtimes. In the ninth minute,
the Norwegian defender Bente Kvitland headed the ball too softly
toward goalkeeper Bente Nordby and Mia Hamm ran on to the pass in
the penalty area. She was taken down by Nordby and awarded a
penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   Having made the World Cup winner before 90,000 spectators,
Chastain could afford to be relaxed before Saturday's audience of
850, including a couple of hundred fans in their sports bras, which
she more than anyone could appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last year's Algarve final, when she clanged her shot off
the crossbar against China, Chastain calmly placed a right-footed
kick into the upper left corner of the net. She had taken her
decisive World Cup kick left-footed, but switched because the right
foot felt more comfortable during practice. She is one of the few
women in the world who can shoot assuredly with both feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just have a feeling,'' Chastain said of placing
her kick into the upper left corner. She had gone to the other side
during the World Cup, but Saturday noticed that Nordby seemed to be
favoring that direction. ``I saw her lean to her left and I went
the other way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After a month of experimenting with younger players, Heinrichs
went to a lineup of World Cup regulars, missing only Michelle Akers
(nasal surgery) and Briana Scurry (strained quadriceps muscle). The
Olympics are six months away, but it was important for the
Americans to send a message to Norway, the only team to hold a
winning record (13-11-1) against them.
</P>
<P>
   Last month in Florida, Norway twice defeated an American team
that had just resumed training after a contentious contract dispute
and a boycott of a tournament in Australia. Norway remains the most
contentious rival of the Americans after handing them a bitter
defeat in the semifinals of the 1995 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   This American team was fitter and fresh, despite playing its
fourth game in seven days. Siri Mullinix replaced Scurry and
assertively patrolled the penalty area from the American goal in
her fifth international appearance, Lorrie Fair hustled to balls in
the defensive midfield, Hamm played with her usual roaming
intensity and Kate Sobrero displayed smothering muscularity in
central defense.
</P>
<P>
   Norway, which received a hat trick from midfielder Dagny
Mellgren in a surprise 3-0 victory over China in the semifinals,
did not muster a shot for the first 33 minutes Saturday. Mellgren
was muted by Chastain and Kristine Lilly on the wing and by Sobrero
inside, though she did strafe the goal mouth with a slicing shot in
the 47th minute. And in the closing minutes, Mullinix came off her
line several times to dive onto the ball and to thwart Mellgren,
once making a lunging save.
</P>
<P>
   Having used a 4-3-3 formation during the World Cup, the
Americans under Heinrichs have since preferred a 4-4-2, which gives
them one less forward but one more midfielder, allowing Shannon
MacMillan and her energetic skills into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was important psychologically, because it was a
tournament we had never won, and even though we have time until the
Olympics, everyone is jockeying for position, and we want to take
whatever momentum you can get,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
