u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      03-18 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES STILL DEALING WITH SERIES SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBO-NOTEBOOK) 
(rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ It was to be the championship that validated
their label as the team of the '90s. The Atlanta Braves had
previously won seven successive division championships but had
appeared in ``only'' four World Series and, worse, had won only
one. By winning the 1999 World Series, however, the Braves would
provide proof that they deserved to be ranked with the greatest
teams ever.
</P>
<P>
   And then the New York Yankees swept them.
</P>
<P>
   ``To lose the Series is one thing; to be swept, to be honest
with you, is embarrassing,'' Terry Mulholland, one of the Braves'
veteran pitchers, said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine, the longest-running Braves' veteran pitcher, did
not disagree. ``Yeah,'' he said, ``I think it's a little more
embarrassing getting swept than it is to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Glavine added, ``losing is losing. It's not fun. I
don't know that I feel any better about losing in 1991 because it
was a great World Series than I do in 1999 when we got swept. The
bottom line is we lost. It's a bad feeling either way, but
particularly so because it was a matchup we were looking forward
to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, the left-hander said, were playing well going into
the Series. ``We thought the outcome was going to be a whole lot
different than it was,'' he said. ``We didn't execute. We were
ahead in two games and had a chance to win, but we didn't close it
out. That was the big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland recalled his previous World Series experience. ``When
I went through the Series in '93 with Philadelphia,'' he said, ``we
had quite a tough Series with the Blue Jays. It came down to Joe
Carter hitting a home run in the ninth inning to beat us. That
wasn't the case last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, the Braves' manager, disagreed that even losing to
the Yankees was a negative development. He cited his team's 103
regular-season victories, most in the major leagues, as evidence of
the great season the Braves enjoyed. Managers, of course, are
supposed to see the positive side and dismiss any negative aspects.
</P>
<P>
   But Eddie Perez, one of the catchers, offered a similar view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' he said when asked if losing in four games
was embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Mets have a better team than us and we beat them,''
he added, a curious comment considering the Braves finished 6{
games ahead of the Mets. ``Going to the World Series with the
Yankees, a lot of people thought let's do the best. I think we did
the best when we played the Mets because they have a better team
and we beat them. I don't think we did a great job in the World
Series, but I think we did a great job going to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan, the right fielder, said the Braves deserved credit
for overcoming a collection of serious ailments and injuries, but
he acknowledged that being swept ``was difficult; there's no
question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not they thought the sweep was embarrassing, the
Braves did not foresee the possibility that they could suffer any
aftereffects this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened the year before in the playoffs is the furthest
thing from your mind in the regular season,'' Glavine said,
``particularly for us this year.'' He mentioned the return of the
ailing players, Andres Galarraga and Javier Lopez, and how their
healthy presence has the Braves excited about the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean anything,'' the pitcher added, referring to
the awful end to October. ``When we won in '95, it meant nothing in
'96. We had to go out and start all over on April 1 just like
everybody else. You have to put that behind you and be prepared to
do it all over again just like you do when you lose. You have to
put the anger or the soreness of losing behind you and look at what
you need to do in front of you to get back to that spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, however, was candid enough to suggest a different
mind-set could possibly take over if the team returns to the
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe when you get in the playoffs,'' he said, ``you start
thinking about, `OK, we have an opportunity here; let's not lose
this year.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were the second successive team to lose to the
Yankees in four World Series games. The Braves, despite their
crushing disappointment, saluted the Yankees for their remarkable
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impressive,'' Glavine said. ``It's something you would
never in a million years bet on somebody doing. The odds are not
good, particularly in that forum where you have two teams so
closely matched. It's just tough to beat somebody four straight.
For them to do it eight straight over two years is really amazing,
but you've got to give them credit for being as good as they were
and going out there and executing as well as they did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1644EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      03-18 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING ROBBED AT POKER  
 A NEW CHANCE FOR HALTER 
2 LONG-TERM PROSPECTS
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBN-BRAVES) 
(rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The incident last week in which two armed robbers menaced six
minor league players in the Houston Astros' organization reminded
Bobby Cox of a similar experience more than 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cox was managing Syracuse in the New York Yankees' system in the
early 1970s, and the team was in Charleston, W.Va., for the start
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was downstairs sitting in the lobby,'' the Braves manager
said. ``The players had saved up their meal money from being in the
big league camp in spring training, and they were playing cards
upstairs like we all did in the old days. There was a poker game
every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two guys with shotguns came in and tied them up. They took
their money and their clothes and their briefcases. It happened at
10:30 at night. They tied them up with cords from telephones and
lamps. They tied up Jimmy Ray Hart, put him halfway under a bed and
they were stomping on his hands. Jerry Kenney came downstairs and
said, `You gotta come up here, you gotta come up here.' I said
what's going on. He couldn't talk. He said, `These guys stuck
shotguns right in our faces.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said police determined that it was an inside job, that
someone from the hotel was involved. In the Astros' episode, the
robber who was shot and wounded six times and was in the hospital
had a long record of arrests.
</P>
<P>
   A New Chance for Halter  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shane Halter spent six years in the minor leagues before getting
a chance in the majors with the Kansas City Royals in 1997. But the
utility infielder-outfielder appeared in only seven major league
games last season, pinch-running five times for the Mets and
batting not at all. He will not bat for them this year either. The
Mets put him on waivers last week, and Detroit claimed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised at what came about,'' Halter said.
``I didn't want to get released. I didn't want to leave the Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 30-year-old did not help himself in his quest for a job
with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had eight at-bats, went 2 for 8,'' he said. ``It was kind of
rough. I had two ground balls go right between my legs in games.
Spring training just started really so I was shocked to see it
happen as early as it did. But I'm kind of glad they did it because
I got an opportunity to go somewhere. Peoples' rosters weren't
full. I don't think I ever got a shot over there. I believe they
were going to keep Kurt Abbott and Charlie Hayes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Halter's second day in the Tigers' camp, another player at a
nearby locker was curious about the Mets' manager, Bobby Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you think of Valentine?'' the player asked Halter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was all right,'' Halter replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the only person I ever heard say he liked him,'' the
other player said. ``All the guys in Texas hated him.''
</P>
<P>
   2 Long-Term Prospects  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is Johnny Oates just trying to make the best of off-season
developments, or could he turn out to be right? Clip and save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next three years,'' the Texas manager said, ``we will
score more runs with Kapler in right and Mateo in center than we
would have with Goodwin in center and Gonzalez in right.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez (trade) and Tom Goodwin (free agent) are gone. In
their place are a pair of youngsters, Gave Kapler and Ruben Mateo.
Oates' projection is bold. The Rangers' future fortunes rest on how
right he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short term? I'm not sure,'' Oates said. ``Long term there's no
doubt in my mind we're better off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers let Goodwin leave because it was time to find out if
Mateo is what they think he will be. They traded Gonzalez because
they did not want to pay him $17 million or more a year. The one
development they did not expect was the defection of Todd Zeile to
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had Zeile and it just didn't work out,'' Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the manager felt the decision to trade Gonzalez was a sound
one. ``If we don't do something, we'll be in trouble starting next
year,'' he said, meaning the Rangers would have lost Gonzalez as a
free agent and received nothing for him. ``We can be good this year
and very good next year. But if we hadn't have made the trade, we
could have been pretty bad next year. And I don't like the thought
of being bad any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates added: ``I want a chance to win every year. I do not want
to be the Miami team. You win it all one year, but their season is
already over this year and next year and probably the next year and
probably the next five years.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the Rangers to be good, Kapler, who came from Detroit in
the Gonzalez package, and Mateo, a farm-system product, will have
to produce, if not instantly, soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what these guys can do,'' Oates said. ``Together
they could drive in 150 runs. They could drive in 200. They could
drive in 75.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1644EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
