<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-REED-NYT &LR;      03-18 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' REED GOES ALL OUT FOR THE PERFECT PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ When it comes to taking the ball out of
Rick Reed's hand, Al Jackson has succeeded where Reed's mother
never could.
</P>
<P>
   When Reed was growing up, his mother saved the home run balls he
hit in youth games. But Reed was more interested in pitching and
would use the keepsakes to throw against the brick wall he
practiced on.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, Reed would pitch to the wall, tossing curveballs
into the square he had drawn, or aiming for corners. The balls
would scuff and his mother would protest. But Reed pitched anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, the 34-year-old Mets right-hander, is still stubborn. When
he throws between starts, he persists until he finds what he seeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm working on something in the bullpen, I want to be
perfect,'' Reed said. ``I won't quit until it is. I'll stay out
there all day and throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least simulate throwing. Jackson, the Mets' bullpen coach,
tries not to let Reed wear himself out in those sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've just got to take the ball,'' Jackson said. ``But then
he'll stand there and shadow throw.''
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares for his start against the Chicago Cubs in Tokyo
on March 30 in the second game of the Mets' season, Reed is trying
to tire himself in his bullpen sessions so he does not feel too
strong and leave his pitches up too high in the strike zone. His
six-inning, 83-pitch effort against Detroit on Friday was one of
the best starts by a Met this spring, manager Bobby Valentine said,
and Reed succeeded in keeping the ball down.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the things Reed feels he must do to last longer
in games. When his pitches are down, he gets ground balls. When
they are up, those outs become line drives to the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can train myself to keep the ball down, I can pitch more
innings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his three seasons with the Mets, Reed
averaged fewer than six innings a start last year. His improvement
in that area will be important to a team that must preserve its
strong bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   After letting Orel Hershiser and Kenny Rogers leave as free
agents and trading another starter, Masato Yoshii, the Mets have no
proven fallbacks if Reed or another starter falters.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed was at his best when it mattered most last season. He
pitched the game he considers his best ever: a three-hit,
12-strikeout shutout of Pittsburgh that kept the Mets alive in the
final weekend of the regular season. He followed that with two
strong starts in postseason victories.
</P>
<P>
   Reed had been 0-3 with a 5.04 earned run average in September
1998. Two stints on the disabled list in 1999 kept him fresh at the
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 50 innings behind everybody else,'' Reed said. ``I guess
that played a big part in it. But I'm not saying I want that much
time off again.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Reed knows he got a break because of the
injuries, a torn calf muscle and a strained middle finger. Since he
plans on staying healthy, he has to maintain his stamina by
regulating himself in the bullpen. That means going against his
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll throw and throw and throw on his side day until he feels
like he's gotten it right,'' Dave Wallace, the pitching coach,
said. ``Theoretically, that's fine, until August and September.
You've got to save some bullets. He can still throw as often, just
not with the intensity that he likes.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the example of the Atlanta Braves' starters, Reed
likes to throw twice between starts, not once. He cuts back at
times late in the season, but it is his preference to make practice
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been that way,'' Reed said. ``I guess you can't
teach an old dog new tricks. I guess I'm a little too hard on
myself sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed was fortified by his extra rest down the stretch last year,
but another problem almost undid him. The Mets had lost four of his
last five starts before the Pittsburgh game, and he knew something
was wrong. He analyzed videotape, searching for a flaw in his
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson noticed that Reed's fastball was not moving sharply, and
he discovered that Reed was holding the ball too far back in his
palm, choking it. After two or three bullpen pitches, Reed knew he
had solved the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed has learned it is easy to fall into bad habits. In a
side session before Friday's start, coaches noticed the same
problem again, and Reed re-adjusted his grip. Even if he perfects
it, there will always be something to work on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll throw one good, and then want to make it better,'' Reed
said. ``I think that's when I need to back off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1647EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-INDIA-CLINTONSIDE0319     03-18 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CLINTONSIDE0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton visit encourages peace hopes in Kashmir
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India _ At the CNS cybercafe in downtown Srinagar,
owner Omayan Balti and his friends contemplate President Clinton's
visit to India, which starts today.
</P>
<P>
   How will Clinton travel to Bangladesh from New Delhi, one of
Balti's friends wonders. On a chartered flight?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no. He will fly on Air Force One,'' says Balti. ``Or is it
Air Force Two?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has the ability to bring peace to Kashmir,'' Balti
continues, examining Thursday's headlines about Clinton in several
of India's English-language daily newspapers. ``After all, he is
the most powerful man on Earth. We wish Clinton would come to
Kashmir and see what is happening here, but he can't because of
security reasons. So we hope he can talk to Prime Minister (Atal
Bihari) Vajpayee in New Delhi and (Pakistani leader Gen. Pervez)
Musharraf in Islamabad and persuade them to talk; persuade them to
both let go of Kashmir.''
</P>
<P>
   As South Asia gears up for the first presidential visit to the
region in 22 years, Indians are expressing cautious optimism about
Clinton's potential as peacemaker. While most of India waits to see
if the American president can offer an acceptable peace deal, many
Kashmiris are hoping that he will help alleviate their predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Clinton's trip, the Kashmiri problem will get much more
visibility. In that way, it's a very positive development for us,''
said Sheikh Showkat Hussain, a professor of international law and a
member of the Jammu and Kashmir High Court Bar Association.
``Whether it will yield any concrete results, I can't say.''
</P>
<P>
   `TINDERBOX' SITUATION
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have fought three wars over the disputed
territory of Kashmir since they gained independence from Britain in
1947. For the past decade, Indian army and paramilitary forces have
battled an armed insurgency led by Islamic militants who want to
carve out an independent Kashmiri state or merge with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   India accuses Pakistan of arming the insurgency. Pakistan claims
it only provides ideological support.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by both nations' testing of nuclear devices in 1998,
Washington has kept a close watch on the ``tinderbox'' situation in
Kashmir. Now, with Clinton's trip, Kashmiris are hoping Washington
will move one step closer to diplomatic intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Clinton really wants to, he can really solve the problem
here,'' said Abdul Rashid Bhat, a farmer in Tulmulla, a village 15
miles east of the Kashmiri capital of Srinagar. ``If he can
persuade Israel to vacate the Golan Heights, then why can't he find
an answer to this? But the problem is that we don't have oil, and
the Americans, well, they are looking out for their own interests.
It is said that even God will not listen to poor people.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Kashmiris compare the situation here to that of the Middle
East, Northern Ireland or the former Yugoslavia. If the United
States can help resolve ethnic and religious disputes in those
troubled spots, they say, it should be able to do the same in the
subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is a complicated situation,'' said Abdul Qadir, a
Srinagar resident whose only son was killed by Indian security
forces in 1993. ``The solution has to satisfy India, Pakistan and
the Kashmiris. The three parties should be put into a room and told
to hammer out a solution and not be let out until they do so.
Clinton can help with third party mediation.''
</P>
<P>
   The All Parties Hurriet Conference, one of the militant groups
in Kashmir, has requested a meeting with Clinton to ask for the
appointment of an international arbitrator. But the Times of India,
quoting U.S. Embassy officials in New Delhi, said the president
would not agree to such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The APHC and other militant groups have promised large
demonstrations in New Delhi when Clinton addresses Parliament on
March 22. Syed Shabir Shah, the president of the Democratic Freedom
Party, announced that the protests are planned to draw world
attention to the Kashmir problem.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the Kashmiris who are hoping Clinton's visit
will trigger a solution to the conflict in Northern India.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone has to step in and solve the problem. It has been
going on for 50 years, after all,'' said Samir Basu, a former
managing director of Chloride India in Calcutta. ``Our economic
relationship with the United States is developing strongly. Now is
the time for Clinton to step in.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between India and the United States were strained
during Jimmy Carter's visit to New Delhi in 1978, when the Cold War
dominated policies in South Asia. Indians, said Calcutta resident
Ashim Basu, a retired hematologist, are much more eager now to
welcome an American president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much more interest in Clinton's visit than there was
in Carter's _ especially because of the tension with Pakistan,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton can include South Asia in his list of foreign
policy successes remains to be seen, but Indians _ Kashmiris in
particular _ are banking on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is the only one who can solve this problem,'' said
G.N. Najar, a Kashmir villager from Tulmulla. ``For us, he is next
to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1650EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
