<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.J.-COLUMN-JOBS-NYT &LR;      03-18 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.J.-COLUMN-JOBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STEP RIGHT UP, TEST YOUR SKILL AND WIN A NEW JOB
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MATT PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERSET, N.J. _ Joyce Axelrod and her partner, wearing matching
red shirts and white pants, delivered the exact same pitch again
and again to the milling crowd. Axelrod is no day worker hawking
soap samples on the street. She is a business executive, and she
spent Thursday asking anyone who would listen: ``Do you have any
clinical research experience? Do you have any clinical research
experience?''
</P>
<P>
   Only in certain company is that a workable pick-up line. But
Axelrod was in the thick of it, in a hotel ballroom near New
Brunswick amid hundreds of people at a job fair for the
pharmaceutical, biotechnology and health care industries.
</P>
<P>
   When Axelrod snagged a prospect for her company, which places
researchers in jobs, she implored: ``Do you know anyone else you
can recommend? If we place them, you get $500.''
</P>
<P>
   Job fairs, once picked-over salad bars for the downsized, are
now smorgasbords where worker-starved companies comb the thin ranks
of the underemployed, and where the gainfully employed scout better
deals. One day last week, there were two fairs just off I-287, a
corridor of corporate campuses and new housing developments, both
flush with the sense of possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The fairs _ the other was for high-tech jobs _ drew heavily from
the now-fashionable pocket protector crowd, for whom one's
abilities are a ``skill set'' and stock options are not an option,
but a must. You could hear a chemist lamenting, ``I think I'm going
to be stuck in polymers the rest of my life,'' or a swaggering tech
jockey delivering a postmodern come-on: ``I'm a hardware guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy McNish, staffing the popular Aventis Pharmaceuticals booth,
said, ``You would think that with unemployment as low as it is that
this place would be empty, but look at this line.'' Little wonder,
with many drug companies offering on-site fitness clubs,
convenience stores, dry cleaners, day care and prepared dinners _
plus top salaries and flextime. Still, she said, ``we really have a
lot of open positions.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Brad Roman and Tom Molesky, fresh business graduates
of Fairleigh Dickinson, were in the Aventis line envisioning
entry-level sales jobs paying $40,000, plus a car, a laptop, maybe
a 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   More people at the Hirehealth fair were like John DeMarco. ``I'm
a physicist,'' he said, ``and I'm just here to see how much I'm
underpaid.'' Happy with his job, he said he had taken off work to
meet with a roofer about his new house _ which could make anyone
look hard at his paycheck. How far underpaid is he? ``About
$10,000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The glitter of promise can be harsh for those left out. John
Lewinson, a chemist in his ``low 60s,'' has been trying to fit into
the soaring drug industry since his chemical industry job was
eliminated a few years ago. A consultant, he's often told he's
overqualified for permanent jobs, which he takes as a euphemism for
being too old. ``I've kept my spirits up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eroding loyalty on all sides of the work equation feeds the
perpetual job hunt. An information technology specialist waiting in
the Bayer Corp. line said that since immigrating from Russia a
decade ago he had worked for three major corporations ``and a
couple of smaller ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, and 30 miles north, the specialist, 48,
surfaced at the Hi-Tech Career Fair at a Parsippany hotel. ``This
is a country where all your dreams become reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorne A. Epstein, recruiting for Telco Systems, a computer
communications company in Washington and Boston, came to Parsippany
in desperate search of engineers and programmers. Last week he
prospected in Ottawa. The salaries, he said, ``are getting crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Telco's literature promises a ``highly competitive compensation
and benefit package, including 401(k), two weeks' vacation, casual
dress and volleyball and basketball courts for lunchtime games.''
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere of plenty is infectious, even for a high-tech
recruiter, making $40 to $60 an hour. ``I met a woman in Ottawa,''
he said. ``She's a contract recruiter. She said, `Come out to
California. I'll pay you $150 an hour.' That's $350,000 a year.''
</P>
<P>
   So when's he leaving? ``I thought about it,'' he said, then
corrected himself. ``I'm thinking about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
