<SLUG> BC-BKC-IOWAST-TINSLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINSLEY BRINGS A BIT OF BROOKLYN TO IOWA STATE'S OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Iowa)  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Jamaal Tinsley hustled to the court at Public
School 305 in Brooklyn by 10 o'clock each morning and played
basketball until long past dark. Sometimes, it was 9:30 p.m. when
his mother would stop hollering his name, march to the park and
drag him home. Jamaal was 6 years old.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 7, Tinsley caused people to stop and gawk
whenever he touched a basketball. He could dribble the ball between
his legs and around his back, treating it like a yo-yo while most
7-year-olds had trouble even lifting the ball over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could do things,'' Tinsley said, ``that people never saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley was 15 when he played at the famed Rucker Park against
much older players. He slithered inside so easily and scored on
taller players so effortlessly that he was nicknamed the Abuser.
Anyone who tried to throttle Jamaal, you see, was eventually
abused.
</P>
<P>
   So, before Tinsley was even in high school, he was a playground
legend in Bedford Stuyvesant and was expected to be the next great
somebody. Tinsley was another slick point guard out of New York
City, another kid with a great handle, a great game and a great
nickname. How could this special player not make it to the big
time? The Abuser almost did not because he abused himself by not
caring enough about life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some of my friends going to jail,'' Tinsley said. ``I
saw someone get shot and killed right there. I saw it all.
Sometimes it was scary. Sometimes, it was fun. At that time, that's
how I was. Seeing someone get hurt, like one of my friends, was
scary. But seeing someone shoot at us was fun. I escaped it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely. Tinsley was sitting on a red and tan table in Iowa
State's locker room at the Metrodome during the Midwest Regional,
recounting the details and the detours that have seen someone who
never played a high school game miraculously develop into an NBA
prospect this season.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley is a smooth playmaker who can dribble in the paint,
seemingly get lost for a second and then somehow flip the ball
through the basket. He burned Central Connecticut State for 26
points, six assists, six rebounds and four steals and is one player
Auburn must contain when the Tigers oppose Iowa State Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As Tinsley recalled the road he navigated to go from playground
legend to high school dropout to neighborhood nomad to junior
college standout to a player who is one victory away from guiding a
team into the Sweet 16, he told the story with traces of pride and
depression. Tinsley knows how lucky he is. He was asked where he
might be if he had not reversed his routine of loitering on the
streets, and the 6-foot-3-inch junior kicked at his loosened
sneakers and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd probably be in trouble somewhere,'' Tinsley said. ``I'd
probably be on the corner, a nobody, like some guys on the corner
right now who are nobody. It would have been hard for me. My life
would have been hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Leatrice Smith, Tinsley's mother, expects her apartment on
Clifton Place in Bed-Stuy to be filled with Jamaal's seven siblings
and more friends when the Cyclones play. She called her son's
turnaround a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as a dream,'' Smith said. ``He could still be
standing on that corner, doing nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   During the four years Tinsley was supposed to be going to high
school, from Brooklyn to Cleveland, where he lived with relatives,
and back in New York, he estimated that he went to a full day of
classes for a total of 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd yell at him to go,'' Smith said. ``I couldn't get through
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could. Tinsley's father, James Henderson, and his
mother's husband, Mitchell Smith, both died within four months of
each other when Tinsley was 6. With his two most significant male
role models gone, Tinsley said it was easier to disobey his mother.
He would hang with older men who did not care if he lacked
ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't going to school,'' Tinsley said. ``All they did
was hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley even spent one week at Manhattan Tombs Juvenile
Detention Center for his involvement in a robbery when he was 14.
While Tinsley said his friend committed the crime and he was a
bystander, even his mother is skeptical of his story. ``I don't
believe him,'' Smith said flatly.
</P>
<P>
   If Tinsley had not felt jealousy toward his teammates from the
Brooklyn Amateur Athletic Union team, he might still be chilling on
corners. But Tinsley saw that Stephon Marbury, Ed Cota, Jacquay
Walls and Allen Griffin were playing Division I. So, Tinsley earned
a high school equivalency diploma and went to Mt. San Jacinto
Community College, where he resuscitated himself.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley was the California community college tri-player of the
year after averaging 21.6 points, 9.8 assists, 4.5 rebounds and two
steals a game as a sophomore. Then, at Iowa State, he was the Big
12's newcomer of the year, helping the team surge from a 15-15
record to 30-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real happy because I knew I had it in me and I never gave
it a shot,'' he said. ``I have flashbacks. I'll be happy about
this, then I'm not happy. I know my life could have ended. But I
just kept hanging on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
