<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-CONE-NYT &LR;      03-18 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE WANTS IT KNOWN HE IS READY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ He has built a career on obstinacy, playing a
kid's game and competing with the pure willfulness of a child.
There will be runners on base, second and third and nobody out, and
it's as if David Cone folds his arms, locks his jaw and holds his
breath until he gets his way, until he gets out of the inning.
Never give in.
</P>
<P>
   So he has regrets now, at the way he gave in to his emotions at
the end of last season. He was angry with his manager and his
pitching coach, and for the first time he could remember, he gave
in to that fury in one tense meeting in Joe Torre's office. He was
bitter over the way the condition of his arm was being perceived
and portrayed by the Yankees and the news media. He was burned out.
</P>
<P>
   He believed his time with the Yankees was coming to an acrid
end. ``Thanks for saving my regular-season win with the Yankees,''
Cone told Mariano Rivera after beating Tampa Bay on the
next-to-last day of the regular season last fall, his playful tone
masking his disgust.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched once a week in the final five weeks of the season and
wasn't used in the three games of the first playoff series against
Texas. He gave in to ``the human element,'' Cone said last week.
``I didn't handle it very well. I let it get to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of that's ego and part of that is pride. But the last
thing I want to be perceived as is a once-a-week pitcher, or a
five- or six-inning pitcher. I still believe I can handle my
workload and pitch over 200 innings and be reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone went 9-4 with a 2.86 ERA in the first half of the regular
season, and in his first start after the All-Star break he threw a
perfect game against the Montreal Expos, dropping to his knees with
his hands on his head, disbelieving, as Scott Brosius caught the
final out.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone won only one more decision in the next 10 weeks.
Sometimes he pitched well and received scant run support _ the
Yankees scored two runs or fewer in eight of Cone's 11 starts from
July 29 to Sept. 25 _ and occasionally Cone pitched badly. Always
there were questions about the condition of his arm, even as Cone
insisted he felt fine, much stronger than in 1998, when he faded.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Aug. 24, the Texas Rangers pounded Cone for six
runs in 1 2/3 innings, and Cone readily acknowledged to reporters
afterward that he had had a bad game, that his stuff had been
lacking. When the nature of the questions changed to address a
larger issue _ was he falling apart? _ Cone's face reddened, his
anger barely contained, his responses clipped.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Torre and Mel Stottlemyre, who had been Cone's
pitching coach for years with the Mets and Yankees, summoned Cone
and initially informed him that he would be given a week off to
rest his arm. ``We know you are a warrior and you're going to say
you feel fine when you don't,'' Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was furious _ enraged that they would make that decision
without asking for his input, incensed they did not believe him
when he said he felt fine _ and he snapped at Stottlemyre, the
first time he could remember doing so. Cone insisted he was being
honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a growing sense last year that no one would believe
me,'' Cone said last week. ``I was kind of like the boy who cried
wolf. My reputation is that I'll pitch hurt, or I won't be
completely honest if my arm hurts. That can undermine the trust
factor between player and coaching staff. To me, that's important
and it always has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone, Torre and Stottlemyre ultimately agreed to a plan under
which Cone would pitch once a week, to give his arm extra rest for
the postseason, and Cone apologized for his outburst; he and Torre
agreed they could communicate better. Cone understood why they were
resting him: They wanted him as fresh as possible for the
postseason. But he fumed at the implications of the decision,
because it fed directly into the media's conventional wisdom that
he was wearing down, that he couldn't handle a full workload. ``I
can understand where he was coming from,'' Stottlemyre said.
``Maybe we could've been more sensitive to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone commiserated often with Chili Davis, the veteran designated
hitter, who had decided to retire, the two of them sitting in a
back room, Cone sharing his bitterness with Davis. As the playoffs
began and Cone waited for his turn to pitch, Davis suggested he put
his feelings aside and concentrate on enjoying each day.
</P>
<P>
   And this is what Cone did, beating the Red Sox in Game 2 of the
American League Championship Series with nine strikeouts in seven
innings, holding Atlanta to one hit in seven innings, reminding
himself to savor each moment. He and Davis lingered in a remote
corner of the clubhouse after the Yankees swept the World Series;
Cone concluded he probably wouldn't pitch another game in
pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees initially offered a one-year deal for a salary
along the lines of what Cone earned last year, he was unsure
whether their interest was legitimate or whether he was politely
being pushed out. What Cone did not know was that in a staff
meeting in early November, two of the Yankees' most prominent
scouts _ Gene Michael and Lin Garrett _ had argued strongly to keep
Cone. ``He will always give you everything he has,'' Michael said,
according to someone else in the room.
</P>
<P>
   So long as Cone was willing to sign for one year, general
manager Brian Cashman told him, they wanted him back, and once
Cashman began increasing his offers, Cone began to realize the
Yankees' interest was sincere.
</P>
<P>
   The questions about his arm persist, and intellectually, he
understands that they will continue through the end of his career.
Cone allowed three runs in two and two-thirds innings in his first
exhibition game this spring, and he again found himself fending off
questions about his durability, his ability to compete as a
frontline pitcher. He insisted at one point that he expects to
compete for the Cy Young Award this year; it was as if he was
trying to convince everybody he's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it kind of got to me constantly being on the
defensive, having to defend my health,'' Cone said. ``I still feel
like I'm defending the second half of my season last year. I'm
still struggling with it. I should handle it better. I'm still
working on it. I shouldn't let those things affect me as much as it
did, because it's going to happen and there's nothing you can do
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   His fastball was 80-83 mph in his first outing of this spring,
82-85 mph in the second, and he reached 87 mph once. In his most
recent outing, his fastball repeatedly reached 87 mph, as it did
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cone finished second in the league in ERA in 1999 and pitched
exceptionally in the postseason. At 37, he keeps telling everybody
he feels great. He gets the feeling few believe him, and he's
trying not to worry about that anymore, trying not to give in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
