<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-HELP0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Content of story varies from budgeted version - focus here
is on federal agency assistance
 &HT;    Federal agencies help flood victims get back on their feet
 &HT;    By Bobby Burns
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Federal agencies helping area flood victims
have significantly curtailed their presence but still are on the
job six months after Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA and the U.S. Small Business Administration have closed
recovery centers, began wrapping up site inspections and ended a
167-day aid application period after four deadline extensions.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, the agencies responded to more than 87,000
requests for assistance and committed nearly $1 billion to help the
state rebuild from its worst natural disaster, officials said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of federal dollars has been committed. Now
it's up to the citizens to take those resources and utilize them,''
said John Copenhaver, Region VI director for the Federal Emergency
Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies are in the process of distributing more than $434
million in SBA loans, nearly $160 million in grants and more than
$217 million in assistance to local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Together with state and private aid programs, the totals account
for a strong package to help flood victims back to their feet,
Copenhaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Many already have used the funds to relocate or begin repairs.
</P>
<P>
   About 57,000 structures were damaged statewide as a result of
the flooding, according to the latest figures from FEMA and the
state. Of those, 7,000 structures were destroyed and 17,000 were
left uninhabitable.
</P>
<P>
   More structures were damaged in Pitt County than anywhere, the
figures show. Structures flooded by water 5 feet or deeper numbered
781; water 2-5 feet flooded 2,826 structures; and 4,354 sustained
damage from less than 2 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding affected fewer buildings in neighboring Edgecombe
County, but in some cases damage there was more severe. A total of
1,278 structures there were flooded by water greater than 5 feet
deep, for instance. Water 2-5 feet deep damaged 2,028 Edgecombe
structures.
</P>
<P>
   In Pitt County, 10,650 individuals and businesses applied for
aid, again more than in any other county. The federal government
committed $125 million to assist here, second only to Edgecombe's
$159 million.
</P>
<P>
   Such numbers bolster confidence that the agencies provided some
level of assistance to everyone who wanted it, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A minority of flood victims may not have wanted the assistance
that FEMA had to offer, however, including 19,000 people who called
the agency's toll-free registration line but never returned
paperwork to apply for the low-interest SBA loans _ the first step
in obtaining any federal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Those people likely did not want the obligation of repaying a
loan, officials said. A common complaint among flood victims about
the aid was that they needed a grant, not another loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a lame excuse quite frankly,'' said Eric
Tolbert, head of the N.C. Emergency Management Division.
</P>
<P>
   Between the SBA loan package and state supplements most flood
victims could refinance and reorganize debt and
</P>
<P>
   ``come out ahead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials tried throughout the application period to convince
flood victims that with interest rates at 3 percent, SBA loan
packages in many cases were better even than the grants.
</P>
<P>
   Grants by themselves often did not provide enough funds to make
full repairs. Large enough loans could be obtained to pay off
existing debt, make repairs and reduce interest rates by several
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The loans also did not rely on tax funds, and there is some
question how large a burden taxpayers should have to shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   That's already reached $130 per person in North Carolina for
state-level assistance alone, Tolbert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should appreciate that. It's an unparalleled amount,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials now are shifting the bulk of their energies from
recovery to prevention, focusing on the purchase of about 8,000
homes that sit in the 100-year floodplain.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing buyout of flood-damaged property is expected to be
the largest anywhere resulting from a single presidential disaster
declaration, including Midwest flooding of the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are staggering,'' said Copenhaver. ``This is
historic.''
</P>
<P>
   More than $50 million has been set aside to purchase the
property, including close to 1,000 buildings in Pitt County.
</P>
<P>
   By September officials hope 50 to 75 percent of the property
will have been converted to green, open space. And in the long run
that green space will prevent similar damage when the next
Hurricane Floyd comes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It's unwise to believe that last year's storms and flooding
won't repeat themselves anytime soon, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality says it's happening here more than anywhere else''
Copenhaver said. ``And predictions for 2000 are that it will be
another above average year. So the reality is there's more
opportunity (for damage) to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
