<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/NFL
</P>
<P>
   FBN-THEHOOD _ Ray Lewis hangs out with his hometown boys from
Miami; the Bills' Derrick Holmes admits that he sends money to his
LA gang members back home. Tamarick Vanover and Joe Horn are
accused of associating with people running an underground drug
network, and Seahawks receiver Charles Jordan says he's still part
of a Miami gang. The NFL admits it has a problem. More and more of
their athletes -- Ray Lewis included -- can't break ties with the
'hood when they become rich and famous. ``Used to be, we'd
eliminate three or four players a year in the draft because of
character questions,'' a league source said. ``Now, it's 25 to 35.
And it's all because of who they hang out with.'' (Schlabach,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HOODCAP _ Sociologist Harry Edwards says salary cap has led to
NFL problems because teams don't have, and keep, necessary
leadership in clubhouse to steer young millionaire players.
(Schlabach, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   HOODSIDE _ Running backs Jamal Anderson and Terrell Davis
discuss how they school their ``entourages'' to deal with problem
situations before going out on the town. (Schlabach, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-GOODWILL _ The Braves are doing more than just
playing baseball during their visit to Venezuela. It's also a
goodwill mission for the team as players visit areas throughout the
country damaged by recent floods. We will spend the day with
players as they tour Caracas. (CRogers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL/NCAA
</P>
<P>
   FINALFOUR _ It was in 1975 when the phrase ``Final Four'' was
coined. What is now called March Madness came from humble
beginnings. The first tournament drew 5,500 fans and was composed
of a mere eight teams. It was played at Northwestern and Oregon
beat Ohio State 42-33 in the championship game. Oregon beat Texas
in the regional semifinals. The tournament wasn't televised until
the 1950s and only on a regional basis. Today, the tournament is 64
teams, spurned office pools across America, and is so popular that
employees take off from work. (Maher, Austin American-Statesman).
25.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-MAYHEM _ DAYTON, Ohio _ To most hoop fans, the annual NCAA
men's basketball tournament is best known as March Madness. But
that name seems passe at CBS, the broadcast company that pounded
the phrase into the national consciousness. After years of hyping
the competition as March Madness, the network this year is pushing
a different name: March Mayhem. (Keilman, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
