<SLUG> BC-AUTO-GORDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON OF ADJUSTMENTS FOR GORDON AND CREW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's still early in the NASCAR Winston Cup Series season, but
one of the sport's marquee drivers, Jeff Gordon, has been a
conspicuous also-ran thus far. Fact is, it has been nine races
since the three-time champion has had a top-five finish.
</P>
<P>
   The scary part for Gordon is that he is getting trounced at some
of the places where he normally has dominated. He went into the
season's initial race having won two of the last three Daytona
500s. He finished 34th, after developing an oil leak early. And at
Hampton, Ga., last week at the Cracker Barrel 500, where he had two
firsts and a third in the last five years, he came in ninth.
</P>
<P>
   As un-Gordon-like as it seems, that ninth place is his best
finish in four races. He is 17th in the point standings heading
into Sunday's race at Darlington, S.C. Bobby Labonte leads with
Mark Martin next and legendary Dale Earnhardt Sr. third. The
defending champion Dale Jarrett is sixth.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Gordon, 28, is still adjusting not only to a
new crew chief in Robbie Loomis _ hired in December _ but also to
driving a redesigned Chevrolet Monte Carlo. NASCAR veterans say
that it normally takes at least half a season for driver and crew
chief to get on the same wave length.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'm not sure if I should step in where I used to
before,'' said Gordon, whose cohesion with his previous crew chief,
Ray Evernham, was exemplary _ producing 47 victories in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt I had higher hopes than this. But you can't panic. We
want to run better, but we realize it's not going to happen
overnight. As competitive as it is in NASCAR, you can't afford to
have any little glitch, any little change in your program, and
expect to go out there and just win races.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet came out with a redesigned Monte Carlo this year and
Gordon believes that is part of his slow start. He thinks the car's
``rear downforce problem'' makes it more difficult to keep the car
balanced through turns.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials last week offered an olive branch to all the
Chevy owners whom had been complaining about rules they felt
favored the Fords and Pontiacs. They allowed the Chevys to lower
their front air dam by 2 inches, making them more aerodynamically
balanced.
</P>
<P>
   A Chevy _ driven by Earnhardt _ proceeded to win the Cracker
Barrel 500, even if it was by less than 2 feet. So Gordon is
optimistic that better days are ahead for car No. 24.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to NASCAR said that Hendrick Motorsports, whom
Gordon drives for, has been experimenting thus far with new chassis
components ``to try and get an edge.'' Obviously they are still
experimenting, with Gordon off to the worst start of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Trickle Up for Foyt
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Foyt is in his first year of owning a Winston Cup series
team, but the legendary driver still cannot stand failure. After
not qualifying for three straight races with the rookie Mike Bliss,
Foyt has ordered a driver switch for this week's Darlington
qualifying. Dick Trickle, a 58-year-old known for his ability to
decipher engine problems, will drive the next two weeks for Foyt,
as he seeks to find out what is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The move will be announced Friday. Bliss' return after that is
likely but uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Remains of the Day
</P>
<P>
   Eight days after nearly dying in the inaugural Craftsman Truck
Series race at Daytona on Feb. 18, Geoffrey Bodine gazed upon the
mangled remains of his truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when it sunk in how close I was to being killed,'' said
Bodine, who sustained back and wrist injuries and numerous burns
and abrasions. ``If it hadn't been me in there and I just came in
and saw the remains of that wreck, I'd say that whoever was in
there got killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Lap
</P>
<P>
   The last word comes from Mike Skinner, without a victory in 114
Winston Cup series races: ``I'd crash my mom to win that first
race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
