<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: PREPARING IN CASE OF A STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the next few weeks, the owners, managers and
residents of about 2,900 New York City buildings will begin
preparing for the possibility that the porters, superintendents,
elevator operators and other staff members who work in the lobbies,
basements, elevators and hallways of their buildings might soon be
walking and carrying signs on the sidewalks outside.
</P>
<P>
   On April 20, the three-year contract between owners of
residential buildings in Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens and Staten
Island and Local 32B-32J of the Service Employees International
Union expires. (The Bronx is covered by Local 32E.)
</P>
<P>
   And while strikes have often been averted _ only three of the
last eight contract renegotiations resulted in employees taking to
the picket lines _ representatives of the owners say that the only
way to approach the situation is to be adequately prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most significant issue facing most buildings is keeping
the building habitable during a strike,'' said James F. Berg,
president of the Realty Advisory Board, the property owners'
bargaining organization. ``And the only way to keep the building
habitable is to maintain vital services.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg said that while his organization has no reason to believe
that a strike is more or less likely than in previous contract
years, the fact that the safety and security of hundreds of
thousands of residents could be put at risk if a strike occurs
makes it imperative for building owners and managers to prepare for
the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiations pretty much always go down to the wire,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Berg said that while most of the 26,000 residential building
workers in Local 32B-32J could walk out if a contract agreement is
not reached, some workers will likely stay on the job even if there
is a strike.
</P>
<P>
   In many larger buildings, Berg said, the superintendent is not
covered by the same contract. In buildings with more than five
employees, the superintendent is considered a resident manager and
is usually bound by a separate contract that expires in June.
</P>
<P>
   However, Berg said, even though a superintendent may remain at
work in some buildings, the super should not be expected to take
over the striking employees' jobs. He said that superintendents who
continue working should be able to maintain the heating plant and
make emergency repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Most buildings, however, will have to do without even those
services if an agreement is not reached by the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main issue most buildings will be dealing with during a
strike is the sense among residents that there's nobody downstairs
minding the store,'' said Arthur Davis, a Manhattan property
management consultant. ``Whether your building has one employee or
30, management has to have contingency plans in place to provide
residents with some peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that the managing agent should ensure that the
building's mechanical systems _ including elevators, water heaters,
trash compactors and heating, ventilation and air conditioning _
are inspected in the next couple of weeks and repaired immediately
if defects are found.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something goes wrong during a strike, you might have a hard
time finding contractors who will cross the picket lines,'' he
said, adding that most union workers, including plumbers,
electricians and deliverers, are likely to refuse to enter the
building while a strike is in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Two other major issues are building security and garbage
disposal. ``Management has to decide, on a building-by-building
basis, whether there is a need for front-door security,'' said
Jeffrey Heidings, president of Siren Management, a Manhattan
property-management company. ``And if the decision is made to hire
a security guard, you have to do so well in advance of April 20 to
avoid the last-minute rush.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Heidings said that the last time building employees went on
strike _ in 1991 _ it was difficult to hire guards on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manpower was very tight,'' he said, adding that it is
generally worthwhile to arrange with security firms to guarantee a
guard, even though one might not be necessary if a strike is
averted. ``Most companies will allow you to reserve guards in
advance. And if there's a cancellation, they'll only charge you for
one shift. That's a small amount to pay to ensure that someone will
be watching over the lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is trash disposal. ``We plan to give out
extra plastic bags to tenants and urge them to make sure all trash
is securely bagged,'' he said. ``Even if you're lucky enough to
have a superintendent remain on staff, he's going to be a one-man
show and he's going to need help from residents.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Rothman, the executive director of the Council of New
York Cooperatives and Condominiums, said buildings should top off
heating-oil tanks before April 20 to avoid problems if fuel
deliveries are stopped by a picket line.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, management should compile a list of every
person authorized to enter the building. ``This will be invaluable
to the security guard or the resident volunteers who will monitor
the front door during a strike,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably a good idea to sort the names of authorized
individuals into two lists, she said. The first should have the
names in alphabetical order, accompanied by apartment numbers. The
second should be compiled according to apartment number, with the
names of residents as well as sitters, housekeepers and others
authorized to enter when the residents are not home.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman said that residents should be notified when the
entrances will be locked or monitored by a guard and should be
provided with a key or building identification card.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she said, building management should try to identify
elderly or disabled residents so that arrangements can be made for
other residents to provide needed assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Tips for residents and managers are in a booklet distributed by
the council to its members. Rothman said that building managers not
part of the council may buy the booklet for $5 by calling (212)
496-7400.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
