<SLUG> BC-BKO-DEHERE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEHERE, IN BERLIN, AWAITING THE CALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALAN MAIMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Released by the Indiana Pacers in November 1999, Terry
Dehere packed his bags for the Continental Basketball Association.
Two days after signing with the Idaho Stampede however, Dehere
called it quits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like the atmosphere there,'' Dehere said. ``If I had
stayed, I would have gotten depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dehere returned to his Los Angeles home and spent his days bike
riding, working out and hoping a better offer would come along. In
December, Dehere's agent called to tell him that Alba Berlin, the
top team in the German Basketball League and one of the best in all
Europe, was interested in him.
</P>
<P>
   The six-year NBA journeyman with career averages of eight points
and three assists a game sat down to think. The European basketball
leagues, historically a refuge for exiled NBA players or for young
players who recognize that they will never make it in the NBA, was
not necessarily the logical choice for the 28-year-old Dehere.
</P>
<P>
   As a 6-foot-4-inch shooting guard, he had led Seton Hall to
three straight appearances in the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament from 1991 to '93. In his senior year, he
parlayed a consensus all-America season into a first-round
selection (13th overall) in the draft by the Los Angeles Clippers.
But that was 1993. This was late 1999, and Dehere was trying to
jump-start a stalled NBA career.
</P>
<P>
   Dehere was eager to get back on court. He put faith in the fact
that Berlin would better suit him than Boise ever could and decided
to give the German league a try.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financially, it was a no-brainer,'' Dehere said last week from
his Berlin apartment. ``A guy like me can make just as much money
over here as in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``And more importantly, I knew I would get the minutes and the
shots that I wouldn't get even if I caught on with a team in the
NBA right now.''
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve 1999, Dehere signed a one-year contract with
Alba Berlin. He woke up in Berlin the next morning with bronchitis.
While Dehere convalesced, his new coach, Svetislav Pesic, publicly
questioned whether Dehere, who had not played in two months, was in
game shape. Once Dehere was healthy, he was faced with a new team
and a new system, and he had to learn fast. All in a foreign
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult, not speaking any German,'' Dehere said. ``I
try to judge what coach is saying by his facial expressions and
tone. But sometimes I can't tell if he is angry or just excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on Dehere's performance during his first month in Berlin,
Pesic was probably a little of both. In his role as sixth man,
Dehere occasionally dazzled but also showed a tendency to force
shots. On off days, Dehere found himself doing a lot of running in
the woods, a staple of Pesic's grueling training regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of workouts that go on in the NBA during training
camp last the whole season here,'' Dehere said. ``It got me back in
shape fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, starting in his second game of the season in place
of the injured former North Carolina Tar Heel Henrik Roedl, Dehere
exploded for 35 points in a German league game against Weissenfels.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his increasing point totals, Dehere's nonstop
verbal assaults on opposing players indicate that he is beginning
to feel at home in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't stopped trash talking just because I'm in Berlin,''
Dehere said, grinning. ``And the more shots you get, the more trash
you can talk. But I have to say, it is usually the other bench that
starts with me. They definitely see it as a challenge to play
against a guy with NBA experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Weissenfels game, Dehere began covering the wrong man, a
result of an hourlong Pesic tirade about the importance of defense
that deprived the team of seeing film to prepare for the game.
Dehere thought he had his man identified. Meanwhile, his true
responsibility was left open to sink a 3-pointer. An embarrassed
Dehere heard the taunts from the opposing bench. Then he dropped 35
points on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one gets angry about it, because it's all in fun,'' Dehere
said of the linguistic exchange. ``It gets me more into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from the court Dehere has had a chance to recover from
culture shock. He often tunes in to taped-delay NBA games on German
television, and he keeps in touch by phone with friends like Malik
Sealy of the Minnesota Timberwolves out of St. John's and Seton
Hall Coach Tommy Amaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be the icing on the cake,'' he said, ``if I could
finish up my career with the New Jersey Nets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
