<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRZYZEWSKI TRIES TO INSPIRE THE BLUE DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BARRY JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _ Just under two minutes remained in
top-seeded Duke's 82-55 defeat of Lamar in opening-round action in
the East Regional. Duke's starters, resting on the bench and done
for the night, sat together and watched the reserves go through
their paces at Joel Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Mike Krzyzewski, the Blue Devils' head coach, strode
down the sideline and crouched in front of Shane Battier, Carlos
Boozer, Chris Carrawell, Nate James and Jason Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski then proceeded to tell them in firm tones that he was
disappointed in their uninspired effort on a night he had intended
for them to send the rest of the field a message about purpose,
passion and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If tonight didn't shock your system and get you ready to play,
nothing will,'' Battier, a junior forward, said.
</P>
<P>
   The first test of whether their resolve has been quickened comes
Sunday afternoon when Duke (28-4) faces eighth-seeded Kansas
(24-9), an 81-77 overtime winner over No. 9 DePaul. That follows a
game between fourth-seeded Illinois (22-9) and No. 5 Florida
(25-7).
</P>
<P>
   The Illini, an at-large entrant from the Big Ten, dispatched No.
13 Pennsylvania, 68-58. Florida, an at-large team from the
Southeastern Conference, eliminated 12-seeded Butler, 69-68, in
overtime on a last-second lay-in by forward Mike Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, is deep, talented and young, with eight underclassmen
among its top 10 players. The Gators rank among national leaders in
scoring (84.3 points a game) and field-goal accuracy (48.4
percent), their uptempo style fueled by full-court pressure that
forces 20 turnovers a game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet against a disciplined Butler team, Coach Billy Donovan's
squad showed unaccustomed maturity by playing solid half-court
defense and patient offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won a game that was really our style of game, our score
of the game,'' Barry Collier, the Butler coach, said.
</P>
<P>
   That experience should come in handy against a physical Illinois
team, which is coached by Lon Kruger, Donovan's predecessor at
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois, which led the Big Ten in steals, turnover margin and
3-pointers made, is led by the guards Frank Williams and Cory
Bradford. Williams, a freshman, had a personal-best 21 points
against Penn.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, making its 11 straight tournament appearance, was
likewise led in scoring by a perimeter player, Kenny Gregory, who
had 22 points against DePaul.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks, an at-large pick from the Big 12, missed 11-of-21
free throws; often took ill-conceived shots and committed 19
turnovers, many unforced. Yet they rallied to force overtime, then
won after trailing by 6 points in the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, it's like a lot of these Duke teams in recent years;
they're just shooting the ball so extremely well from the
perimeter,'' DePaul Coach Pat Kennedy said. ``I think for Kansas to
have an effectiveness, they've got to get the ball down low, and
their post guys have got to answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
