<SLUG> BC-JFK-AIRPORT-REAL-1070(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: JFK ENTERS THE ERA OF THE MEGATERMINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After years of failed promises and false starts, it
seems that there is a tunnel at the end of the tunnel at Kennedy
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The tunnel in question will run out to a new kind of building at
Kennedy: a midfield concourse that will substantially add to the
capacity of Terminal 8, a 57-gate giant for American Airlines that
will dwarf its predecessors. In January, workers began
disentangling utility lines around the 107-acre site, setting the
stage for a seven-year, $1.3 billion construction project.
</P>
<P>
   Across the field, in mid-February, the first passengers arrived
at the west concourse of the new International Air Terminal. The
structural framework of its vast departures and retail hall was
topped off three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   And all around these construction sites, looking (and sprouting)
like mushrooms, are 326 columns for the AirTrain light-rail system
that will link the terminals to one another and to mass transit
stations in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kennedy is still saddled with a well-earned reputation as
one of the least hospitable of the world's transportation hubs, the
early results of its $9 billion makeover have become remarkably
visible.
</P>
<P>
   None of this will untangle the politics. The Giuliani
administration wants to wrest control of Kennedy from the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey, which runs the airport on a
lease from the city, as it has since opening day in 1948. The
authority says it has no intention of giving up control.
</P>
<P>
   But the squabbling has not visibly impeded the first significant
transformation of the airport since the Eisenhower era, when
Terminal City took form, giving each airline its own distinctive
architectural presence, rather like a collection of World's Fair
pavilions. ``They had their logic, and they had their time,'' said
Barry Abramowitz, the assistant director of the aviation capital
program at the Port Authority. ``We're now past that.''
</P>
<P>
   In their place will rise a ring of megaterminals, diaphanous
arenas with airfoil roof lines, connected to parking garages and
the elevated AirTrain stations.
</P>
<P>
   Terminal 1 opened in 1998 and now serves 11 airlines. It will be
eclipsed next year by the International Air Terminal, Terminal 4,
which will dominate the field until 2006, when American finishes
Terminal 8. That may be rivaled by a Delta Air Lines terminal next
to and perhaps linked with Terminal 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta wants to make New York City one of its major terminals
and destinations in the eastern United States and is committed to
developing a very substantial project,'' said D. Kent Turner, a
senior principal in Hellmuth, Obata &AMP; Kassabaum, the architectural
firm that is working on plans for the area around Terminals 2 and
3.
</P>
<P>
   William Nicholas Bodouva &AMP; Associates, the architects for
Terminal 1, are working with United Airlines and the new airline
JetBlue on the area around Terminal 5 and Terminal 6, which they
share.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, British Airways is expanding and renovating
Terminal 7. The $220 million project, designed by Corgan
Associates, will add 83,000 square feet of space to the 30-year-old
structure, in part by extending the building forward and connecting
it to a new parking deck.
</P>
<P>
   In front of Terminal 7, construction crews are erecting one of
the elevated sections of guideway for the AirTrain system.
</P>
<P>
   The first 5.3-mile leg of AirTrain is to open in 2002 with
service from eight stations around Kennedy to and from the A train
stop at Howard Beach, Queens. By 2003, AirTrain is expected to
reach Jamaica, Queens, on an elevated guideway along the median of
the Van Wyck Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   AirTrain is being designed, built, operated and maintained for
the Port Authority by the AirRail Transit Consortium, led by
Bombardier Transportation of Canada and Skanska (U.S.A.), a unit of
the Swedish construction and development company. The architects
and engineers are STV Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Three years from now, travelers departing from Manhattan will be
able to reach Kennedy on the Long Island Rail Road or the subway,
transferring to AirTrain for a trip around the terminals.
Passengers bound for Terminal 4 will get off AirTrain in the
building itself, since it incorporates a station on the mezzanine.
</P>
<P>
   Ease of access is a common theme among the projects. As
concourses expand to serve ever-larger aircraft, ``Kennedy is going
to be a place of moving walkways,'' said Ted D. Kleiner, the
program director for the redevelopment of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers will increasingly find ticket counters set like
islands in the middle of check-in areas, rather than arrayed along
the back like a hurdle. Broad open spaces, skylights and glass
walls will delineate the travel paths _ first to the shopping
centers and then to the aircraft gates beyond _ even for those who
cannot read the signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The structure will assist the passengers in wayfinding,'' said
Ashok Raiji, a principal in Ove Arup &AMP; Partners, the consulting
engineers on the International Air Terminal and the British Airways
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the tails of the aircraft sitting out there on the
apron,'' added Gregory Hodkinson, another principal at Arup.
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that every new terminal seems to have a
swooping roof. ``We want big open spaces,'' Hodkinson said. ``If
you have that, an efficient form is the curve, because you can get
the arch action of the trusses. People are drawn by the shape of
the roof to get to the other side, which is just where we want them
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Clear travel paths contribute to security, said Abramowitz of
the Port Authority. ``There's no place to hide without sticking out
like a sore thumb,'' he said. ``There's no reason for anyone to
dally.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless it is to shop. Stores and restaurants are proliferating
in the areas between check-in counters and departure gates.
``Retailing in the '60s was a modest convenience, not a product of
having to arrive two or three hours before a flight,'' Kleiner
said. ``Marketers have found an opportunity that's there to be
captured.''
</P>
<P>
   Terminals must grow vertically since real estate is such a
scarce resource at Kennedy. ``Ultimately, you run out of places to
park aircraft,'' Hodkinson said. The central terminal area is
bounded on the north, east and south by runways, including 13R-31L,
a 2.8-mile stretch that is the longest commercial runway in North
America and a formidable barrier to expansion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Only on the west could a 40-acre building site be created for
American Airlines by realigning taxiways. But even there, much of
the new terminal will rise on the site of the old buildings, which
must remain in service while construction is under way.
</P>
<P>
   That is also the case at Terminal 4, which is being built in,
around and alongside the International Arrivals Building of 1957, a
process not unlike performing open-heart surgery on a patient who
is simultaneously running a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   The parabolic arch over the old arrivals hall has already been
demolished, as has the old west concourse, and the rest of the
structure will soon follow.
</P>
<P>
   The current Terminal 8, built by American in 1960, is doomed,
although the airline plans to salvage in some form the
317-foot-long abstract stained-glass facade by Robert Sowers.
Terminal 9 next door, built for United Airlines in 1959, will also
be razed.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern terminal of 1959 was demolished to make way for
Terminal 1, which was developed by Air France, Japan Airlines,
Korean Air and Lufthansa German Airlines. Also high on the
endangered-species list are Terminal 6, by I.M. Pei &AMP; Partners, and
Terminal 3, the former Pan Am Worldport, an umbrellalike structure
designed by Tippetts-Abbett-McCarthy-Stratton, now TAMS
Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when the dust clears, only one building may remain from
the original Terminal City complex at what was once Idlewild: Eero
Saarinen's TWA Flight Center of 1962, now called Terminal 5. Were
it not an internationally renowned architectural icon and a
designated landmark, there is little doubt that Terminal 5 _
woefully small and outdated _ would have been swept away, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiner said the Port Authority had ``accepted the challenge of
developing plans which would provide for keeping the most
well-known exterior visual image and interior spaces of the main
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Port Authority planners are not unmindful of Terminal City's
positive legacy. ``We are trying to recreate that whole verve and
excitement that you're entering the world's greatest gateway,''
said William R. DeCota, the director of the aviation department.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration believes that little good _ and not
enough revenue _ comes from the authority's stewardship of Kennedy
and La Guardia airports. ``They are two of the worst airports in
America, for large airports,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said last
year. ``This is the worst form of a government bureaucracy that is
running something that should be run by private enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, four groups responded to the city's search for a
private operator to serve as a consultant until 2015 and then take
over management of the airports after the Port Authority's lease
expires.
</P>
<P>
   One respondent was the group that is now building Terminal 4, a
consortium composed of Schiphol U.S.A., the American subsidiary of
the Dutch company that runs Schiphol Airport in Amsterdam; LCOR, a
New York developer, and Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Other responses came from BAA, the private successor to the
British Airport Authority, which operates 14 airports including
Heathrow and Indianapolis; Hochtief AirPort, a German company that
runs the Duesseldorf airport and is developing a new airport in
Athens, Greece, and the Zurich Airport company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response reflects a very healthy appetite on the part of
the bidders to participate in the running of the airports and the
privatization of the airports,'' said Michael G. Carey, the
president of New York City Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited about that,'' Carey said. ``It confirms
that we're going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in the eyes of the Port Authority, which opposes wholesale
privatization, even though it has handed over many smaller
functions to private operators. ``The Port Authority has retained
control of all the common elements,'' DeCota said. ``We've operated
the airports, in the public interest, as a system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People think the Port Authority is ignoring Kennedy, but $9
billion is real,'' DeCota said. According to the Port Authority,
about $5.1 billion is being spent on passenger terminals, $600
million on cargo terminals, $1.5 billion on AirTrain and $1.8
billion on runways, taxiways, roads, parking garages and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   And even as it excoriates the Port Authority, the Giuliani
administration has played a role in the redevelopment, most
recently by providing access for American Airlines to the
tax-exempt bond market, through the sale of $1.3 billion in bonds
issued by the city's Industrial Development Agency. Because
proceeds from a municipal bond are exempt from federal, state and
city taxes, they carry a lower interest rate, which makes them
attractive to borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   Given the uncertain nature of Kennedy's future, American has had
to negotiate one lease with the Port Authority and a ``mirror''
lease with New York City, guaranteeing that its terms of occupancy
would continue should the airport revert to municipal control in
2015 or earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The second lease is under review, said Gary J. Pelletier, the
project manager in the airline's corporate real estate department.
</P>
<P>
   But the work is already under way. The first challenge is to
move utility lines. This is not simply a matter of an electrical
conduit here and a gas pipe there, but of storm sewers 12 feet
wide. ``We're actually relocating culverts,'' Pelletier said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its sheer volume _ at 2.2 million square feet it will be
almost 50 percent larger than Terminal 4 _ the American gateway
will also be distinctive in the layout of its concourses, which are
parallel to the roadway rather than perpendicular.
</P>
<P>
   The first two concourses will form the legs of an H whose
crossbar contains the arrivals area on the lower level and the
departures hall on the upper level. The third concourse will be an
island in the middle of the apron, reached by moving sidewalk
through a 420-foot-long tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Given the height of the water table, about 6 or 7 feet below
grade, the tunnel has to be designed to withstand immersion and
also to defeat its natural buoyancy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the midfield concourse will begin next year. Its
opening will permit demolition to proceed on the old buildings.
``At one point, you'll have one new and two existing terminals
running,'' said Edmund A. Narbutas, managing principal in the New
York office of Daniel, Mann, Johnson &AMP; Mendenhall, the architect
for Terminal 8.
</P>
<P>
   The midfield concourse is intended primarily for domestic
traffic, while the concourse closest to the roadway will serve the
commuter jets of American Eagle. The intermediate concourse will
have room for 10 Boeing 747-400s at one time. This will allow
American to accommodate its partners in the OneWorld Alliance, like
Finnair and Qantas, Pelletier said.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as three years ago, American intended to keep its
older terminals and to build a new center concourse at the midpoint
between them, where it had earlier built a connecting structure,
designed by Murphy/Jahn and engineered by Arup.
</P>
<P>
   That was the first project at Kennedy for Arup, one of a number
of architectural and engineering firms that are not widely known by
the general public but are very active and influential in airport
design.
</P>
<P>
   Arup has worked on some of the largest-scale airport-development
projects of the late 20th century, including Chek Lap Kok Airport
in Hong Kong and Kansai International Airport in Osaka, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Ove Arup, a Danish engineer, founded the firm in London in
1946, focusing first on the reconstruction of Europe after World
War II. Arup attracted international attention in the early 1970s
for engineering the audacious Sydney Opera House, designed by Jorn
Utson. The firm now has nearly 6,000 employees in offices around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   It is associated on the Terminal 4 project with Skidmore, Owings
&AMP; Merrill and TAMS Consultants, which was also responsible for the
concept of the new American Airlines terminal, now being refined by
Daniel, Mann, Johnson &AMP; Mendenhall.
</P>
<P>
   Terminal 4 breaks the mold by extending far into the central
parking area, a suggestion made early on by Paul Fernandez, a Port
Authority architect, in part to preserve precious apron space for
airliners.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the terminal forward allowed it to incorporate an
AirTrain station that is structurally independent from the building
that surrounds it. ``When you stand here, you won't feel the train
there,'' said Nancy Hamilton, a senior associate at Arup, as she
walked through what will be the customs checkpoint, directly under
the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The arrivals hall extends under and beyond the elevated roadway
leading to the departures hall, meaning that travelers will be
greeted by a wall of glass rather than the underside of a viaduct.
But they will no longer be greeted by Alexander Calder's 40-foot
``Flight'' mobile, which used to hang in the International Arrivals
Building. That is to be moved upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   Vast as the terminal already is, it has been designed to permit
future enlargement. ``Who knows what's around the corner?'' said
Raiji of Arup. ``You have to build with flexibility in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Terminal 4 is a crazy-quilt hybrid of the new
and old. Although the project is not scheduled for completion until
May 2001, the spacious west concourse opened for service Feb. 11
with the arrival of an Air India flight.
</P>
<P>
   As a commercial real estate venture, Terminal 4 is competing for
tenants just as an office tower would. David A. Sigman, a senior
vice president of LCOR, said the developers expected to sign
seven-year leases next week with their first tenants: Sabena,
Swissair and TAP-Air Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Terminal 1, which has been open since May 1998, has seven
tenants besides the airlines that built it. They are Air Afrique,
Austrian Airlines, Olympic Airways, Royal Air Maroc, Singapore
Airlines, Turkish Airlines and Virgin Atlantic Airways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to say we're the cream right now,'' said August F.
Vettorino of Terminal 1 Management Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Although it will end up as the smallest of the new passenger
buildings, Terminal 1 affords a preview of the future at Kennedy,
with four ticketing islands set into a spacious departures hall.
The passport-control area and the ``sterile'' corridor leading to
it are suffused with daylight.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a pleasant throwback to the days when observation
decks were the rage. The upstairs food court offers views out to
the taxiways and Runway 13R-31L. ``You can sit and look out
airside,'' Kleiner said, as a Royal Air Maroc 747 pushed away from
the gate, ``which you haven't had a chance to do for many years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
