<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RECRUIT-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPERATE TIMES: CITY WOOS TEACHERS TO A MERENGUE BEAT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Need can be a powerful force.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, it transformed a high school auditorium into
Fantasy Island, and the interim schools chancellor, Harold O. Levy,
into Ricardo Montalban, the casual proprietor in linen pants,
greeting wide-eyed guests.
</P>
<P>
   The heaps of fresh strawberries, a 14-piece merengue band and
offers of low-cost mortgages for the hundreds of prospective
teachers who came to a job fair held by the Board of Education
Saturday pointed to a looming problem: the city needs to fill about
54,000 teaching slots within five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you all for coming,'' Levy told applicants as they
streamed from the auditorium of Stuyvesant High School in Manhattan
after listening to a 90-minute sales pitch. ``Hope you find
something you like,'' he added, with a manner more suited to a
dinner party host than a desperate city official.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only two hours of lectures. It gets better now. Now,'' he said
with a winning smile, ``it's recess.''
</P>
<P>
   The band then broke into song and the applicants were treated to
a buffet of cantaloupe and muffins where principals lurked,
offering jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The job fair was the latest effort to address a potentially
crippling teacher shortage. A recent survey by the city's teachers'
union, the United Federation of Teachers, found that about 14,000
of the city's 78,000 public school teachers plan to retire over the
next 18 months. The union estimates that the system will need to
hire 54,000 teachers in the next five years. In addition, more than
300,000 children may have to attend summer school in a few months,
and the city may have to recruit more than 16,000 teachers for the
summer program.
</P>
<P>
   Given the size of the need, food and music were a modest start.
Recently, Levy proposed giving $1,500 in cash bonuses to every
certified teacher who agreed to work over the summer, and
round-trip airline tickets to anywhere in the United States to
summer school teachers whose students met certain improvement
goals.
</P>
<P>
   While Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani attacked the ticket offer as a
costly gimmick that all city workers might demand, the suggestion
underscored the city's desperation. This month, the city approved
an emergency amendment to allow teachers who are credentialed in
other states to teach in New York City, even before they have
passed certification exams.
</P>
<P>
   At the job fair, Levy focused less on the teacher shortage,
which he called ``terrible,'' and more on ``the auditorium full of
eager young people here to devote themselves to a special
calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Young applicants milled about, clutching their resumes and Kate
Spade handbags, jobs unfolding before them. Principals waited for
them, with plates of mints and Tootsie Rolls, to pitch their
schools as homey and safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful place to be,'' Linda Falcon, principal of the
Luis Llorens Torres Children's Academy, just north of Yankee
Stadium in the Bronx, told David Kampel, a social worker
considering a midcareer job change.
</P>
<P>
   Falcon nodded kindly as Kampel laid out his strategies for
keeping unruly students in line and reducing classroom rules to the
most important ones, like: keep silent.
</P>
<P>
   At the next table, Danielle Haug, 21, who has a degree in
special education from New York University, got a job offer for
$32,000 a year on the spot from the Don Pedro Albizu Campos School
in West Harlem. ``If you're committed to us, we're committed to
you,'' the principal, Barbara Brown, told her. ``We are looking for
teachers who are really energized.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown characterized one of the central difficulties of keeping
good teachers in the system by adding, ``We could waste our time
training you for two years, then you want to go to Scarsdale and
take our training with you.''
</P>
<P>
   At another table, Charles Majors, principal of Middle College
High School in Crown Heights, Brooklyn, flattered a soft-spoken,
almost inaudible applicant. ``You sound like a risk taker to me,''
he offered, inviting him to visit the school.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of power was hardly lost on young applicants. ``It's
nice to come and get these types of responses,'' said Dianne
Alonso, who was seeking a job that would be within walking distance
of her home in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want you,'' she said, adding: ``It feels like a shift.
They're selling it as a quality environment.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Roseanne Wahl, 21, the draw was neither a low-cost
mortgage nor the ideal of shaping future generations. It was simply
the vast number of openings the city has, she said while filling
out an application.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend Jeanette Orlic, also 21, agreed. ``I need a job,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by reporters, Levy seemed to revel in the turnout. ``A
corporate recruiting effort would not have been better,'' he said.
``We would not have had the merengue band.''
</P>
</TEXT>
