<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-UCONN-NYT &LR;      03-18 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN FACES CLEMSON, WHICH SEEKS AN UPSET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Connecticut Coach Geno Auriemma has not quite
forgotten the experience. Ten years ago Clemson upset UConn, 61-59,
in the second round of the East Regional of the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament at Gampel Pavilion. It was the
second loss the Huskies had endured on their new court _ they began
to play at Gampel that season _ and it is one of only 15 defeats
the UConn women have incurred there against 158 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma and UConn evened the score a year later in the NCAA
tournament with a three-point triumph over Clemson at the Palestra
in Philadelphia in the championship game of the East Regional en
route to the Final Four. That leaves the two teams tied at 1-1
going into Sunday night's second-round matchup in the East regional
tournament at Gampel Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, top-ranked Connecticut, 31-1 and seeded first
in the East Regional, will be an even stronger favorite over
ninth-seeded Clemson, 19-11, which finished with a 9-7 record in
the strong Atlantic Coast Conference and was one of five ACC teams
selected for the national tournament. Clemson, which lost four of
its last six games, gained the matchup by beating eighth-seeded
Drake, 64-50, while Connecticut crushed 16th-seeded Hampton,
116-45, on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But Auriemma and the first-team all-Americans Shea Ralph and
Svetlana Abrosimova, in particular, vividly recall how UConn barely
averted an upset in last year's second round at Gampel before
edging lightly regarded Xavier, 86-84. The Huskies then lost to
Iowa State in the Round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've showed them tapes of that game over and over, and both
Shea and Svet know how bad they played,'' Auriemma said, with Ralph
and Abrosimova nodding as they sat alongside in the post-game news
conference Friday. ``But I don't think we'll see any repeat of that
Sunday, since we're a little more mature.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with three starters over 6 feet tall _ Hampton had none _
Clemson presents a far more athletic and skilled opponent than
vastly overmatched Hampton, which was 13-14 during the regular
season. With a swarming defense that is similar to UConn's, Clemson
has limited opponents to an average of 59 points per game, only
five points more than Connecticut's defensive average.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tigers' shooting average is only 39 percent, as against
UConn's 53.5. And where Connecticut has a 13-1 record against
top-25 teams this season, Clemson is 2-6.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams have had only one common opponent, 14th-ranked Old
Dominion. In the Coaches Cancer Classic in Hartford last November,
the Tigers lost to Old Dominion by 11 points, after which the
Huskies routed Old Dominion by 43 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
