<SLUG> BC-BKC-INDIANA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR KNIGHT AND THE HOOSIERS, ANOTHER SHORT STAY IN TOWN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Bob Knight is taking his Indiana Hoosiers home
early again. In recent years, this has become traditional at the
NCAA basketball tournament, as predictable as mascots, cheerleaders
and pep bands.
</P>
<P>
   Although Knight's teams have won three championships in his 29
seasons at Bloomington, the last one came in 1987. Against
Pepperdine on Friday night in the Hoosiers' opener in the East, his
team was embarrassed, 77-57, as an 11th-seeded team beat his a
sixth-seeded squad.
</P>
<P>
   Blunt as always, Knight said: ``We just got beat badly. We just
got pounded.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons was the absence of Kirk Haston, Indiana's
starting center, who played only two minutes in the first half and
left with a knee sprain after scoring two points.
</P>
<P>
   Haston averaged 15.8 points this season, second on the team, and
was the rebound leader with an average of 8.6. But A.J. Guyton, who
entered the team with an average of 20.3 points a game, was
healthy. He played 34 minutes, but only scored three points, all on
free throws. He was 0 for 2 from the field, both 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a great job defensing me,'' Guyton said. ``It seemed
like they were a step quicker than us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hoosiers fell to 20-9. The Waves, 25-8, advanced to the
second round on Sunday and will play Oklahoma State, which trounced
Hofstra, 86-66.
</P>
<P>
   The game was the last for Hofstra guard Speedy Claxton, who
finished with 20 points and sustained a dislocated finger. Desmond
Mason, a 6-foot-5-inch senior forward, finished with 30 points for
the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   In the other bracket in the East Regional, Seton Hall will play
Temple. The Pirates, seeded 10th, upset seventh-seeded Oregon by
72-71 on an overtime layup by Shaheen Holloway, who dribbled the
length of the court through Ducks defenders and banked the ball off
the backboard with 1.9 seconds remaining. Holloway led all scorers
with 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   Temple, seeded second in the East and favored at this site,
ousted 15th-seeded Lafayette,73-47, behind 17 points from Quincy
Wadley. The winners of Sunday's two games will advance to next
weekend's four-team regional finals in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana-Pepperdine game began at 10 p.m., one of several
things that irked Knight this week. The leading scorers for
Pepperdine were Brandon Armstrong with 22 points and Nick Sheppard
with 17.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before the game, Knight was the subject of a
television report that alleged he had choked a former player three
years ago. Knight kept his temper under control Friday night, on
the bench and in the post-game news conference The Hoosiers also
lost their last two games of the regular season in the Big Ten.
Knight seemed to agree with a suggestion that Guyton was fatigued
from too much of a work load.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 15th consecutive appearance in the tournament for the
Hoosiers and the fourth time in the last six years that they have
been eliminated in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   During that span, the Hoosiers are 2-6. Knight last took the
Hoosiers to the Final Four in 1992, losing to Duke in the
semifinals. His NCAA tournament record over 29 years is 42-21.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Indiana's early exits in recent years, Knight
said, ``We haven't been real good.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine, coached by Jan van Breda Kolff, offers a retro look
in terms of appearance. In an era in which many players shave the
hair from their heads, several Waves players sport Afros with
headbands, similar to the look of some athletes in the 1970s _
Artis Gilmore, for instance, or the early edition of Julius Erving.
</P>
<P>
   For Friday night, at least, the Waves played a quick,
entertaining style that seemed to leave the Hoosiers flat-footed
and gaping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it would be an athletic mismatch,'' van Breda
Kolff said. ``I don't think we thought our athleticism was going to
intimidate them by any means. But I think the way we play is a
little bit different than the Big Ten teams. Our presses and our
half-court traps are a little bit different than maybe what
Michigan State does. Our style of play was maybe different than
what they see on a game-in and game-out basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Michael Lewis of Indiana a leading question,
noting that the Waves seemed to have fun playing basketball. Is it
important to have fun? Do the Hoosiers have fun?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fun playing the game,'' Lewis said. ``If you're trying
to say `Does coach take the fun away out of the game for us?' You
know, he doesn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
