<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-ROWHOUSES-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: BALTIMORE RETURNING TO ITS ROW HOUSE ROOTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Mich.)   (jw) 
 By CHARLES BELFOURE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE, Md. _ For the second time, Baltimore has turned to
its architectural roots to rebuild its public housing. A high-rise
superblock that wiped out a row-house neighborhood in the 1950s has
been razed and replaced with a newly appreciated Baltimore fixture,
row houses.
</P>
<P>
   The Terraces, with 303 row houses built at a cost of $60
million, has taken the place of Lexington Terrace, five 11-story
towers with a total of 677 apartments. The 18-acre complex opened
in 1959 and was demolished in 1996. Along with the new row houses,
a four-story building with 88 apartments for the elderly has also
been constructed, plus an office building with retail space on the
ground floor. The site is on the western edge of downtown, across
Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard from the University of Maryland's
Baltimore campus.
</P>
<P>
   Lexington Terrace was one of the most crime-ridden and
deteriorated housing projects in the city, and when it was
demolished, only about half of its apartments were occupied. Along
with five other city projects, it became a symbol for a failed
housing policy that was championed by planners and architects in
the years immediately after World War II. They favored mostly
high-rise buildings on one gigantic block physically isolated from
the rest of the community, not traditional attached houses.
</P>
<P>
   John Torti of Torti, Gallas &AMP; Partners CHK of Silver Spring,
Md., whose firm designed the Terraces row houses with TLBC Inc., a
Baltimore architectural firm, said: ``It's a big repudiation of
modernist planning. We again understand the value of streets and
row houses, with their front doors and stoops.''
</P>
<P>
   The Terraces is part of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development's Hope VI program. Its goal is to demolish or
rehabilitate troubled buildings, replacing them with housing that
includes people of all incomes.
</P>
<P>
   The first Hope VI project in Baltimore was Pleasant View
Gardens, with 228 row houses completed in 1998. It replaced
Lafayette Courts, a high-rise project. ``A definite goal is to
blend the new housing into the surrounding community,'' said Elinor
Bacon, the deputy assistant secretary for public housing
investments at HUD. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Terraces achieves this effect by using many of the design
elements of Baltimore's traditional row houses, like brick facades
and porches. ``I recently brought a group of people through the
site, and their first reaction was that it doesn't look like public
housing,'' said Daniel P. Henson III, a former commissioner of
Baltimore's Department of Housing and Community Development.
Henson, who left his position in December when a new mayor took
office, is widely given credit as the driving force behind the
success of the city's Hope VI projects.
</P>
<P>
   Another important design decision for the Terraces was restoring
the streets once cut off by the superblock. Now, Saratoga, Vine and
Lexington streets run through the neighborhood again.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 303 row houses, 100 were earmarked for sale at market
rates, and the rest as rental units for low-income families. But in
design, the two are virtually indistinguishable. ``I dare anyone to
tell which are which,'' said Torti, who is working on 22 other Hope
VI projects across the country. The goal, he explained, was not to
stigmatize public housing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only difference between the units is that the ones
for sale have basements. All but 14 are two stories, with a total
of 1,240 square feet containing three bedrooms and two baths. The
14 three-story houses have a fourth bedroom. All of the houses have
central air-conditioning, washers and dryers and built-in computer
desks, and all are wired for high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 houses offered for sale were completed last year, and
all sold in less than 12 months for $60,000 to $70,000. The
remaining 203 houses _ appliances are being installed in the last
of them now _ have been leased at rents averaging $300 a month. A
majority of the rents are subsidized by the Baltimore Housing
Authority. All the houses have fenced rear yards that lead to
alleys, another traditional part of the Baltimore streetscape. The
alleys, by request of the tenant groups who participated in the
design process, have locked gates at both ends to prevent strangers
from coming through.
</P>
<P>
   Financing for the Terraces came from a variety of sources: $20
million of the project's $60 million cost came from the federal
Hope VI program. A joint venture team of Struever Bros. Eccles &AMP;
Rouse, a Baltimore developer, and Mid-City Financial Inc./Edgewood
Management, a Baltimore company that specializes in affordable
multifamily housing, won the competition to develop the site in
September 1995. They completed the project using private mortgage
money, state financing and tax credits for putting up low-income
rental and elderly housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``An objective of Hope VI is to develop these sites through a
public-private partnership,'' said Carl William Struever, the
president of Struever Bros. Eccles &AMP; Rouse.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America provided financing for the 42,000-square-foot
office building, the Parren J. Mitchell Business Center, the first
of its kind in any Hope VI development. Sharing the same parking
lot is a stand-alone 11,000-square-foot store, which is being
leased by Rite Aid.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Terraces is technically a city public-housing
project, it will be managed by two private companies, Edgewood
Management and Cooperative Services Inc., an Oak Park, Mich.,
company that specializes in housing for the elderly.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directly north of the Terraces is what will become the third
site to be reconstructed, a vacant 15-acre parcel where the George
B. Murphy Homes and Emerson Julian Gardens were demolished in
August.
</P>
<P>
   At Heritage Crossing, as the new development will be known, 75
low-income rental houses will be built, along with 185 houses that
will be sold at market-rate prices of $70,000 to $90,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
