<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRIBUNE-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRIBUNE CO. RETURNS, BUT TO A VASTLY CHANGED MEDIA TOWN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., N.Y., N.J., Conn., Md., Pa., Fla.)   (jw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1991, when the Tribune Co. of Chicago had its last
brush with newspapering in New York, before paying Robert Maxwell
$60 million to take over The Daily News and its intimidating
unions, the region's media life was simpler.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Alley and America Online were in their infancy.
Satellite television broadcasting was for the rural West, not the
Upper East Side. News 12, the local news channel of Cablevision
Systems Corp., was available to perhaps 675,000 households in the
New York suburbs, not 3.3 million. There were more daily
newspapers, more locally owned newspapers and more newspaper
readers.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is one thing the Tribune Co. has shown in the last
decade, it is that it revels in media complexity, and, arguably,
handles it better than it handled New York's newspaper unions. So
Monday, when it announced its $6.45 billion merger with the Times
Mirror Co. _ owner of Newsday, the Long Island newspaper _ the
question immediately arose: now that it is back, what will it do?
</P>
<P>
   Asked last week about possible expansion in the New York area _
perhaps by buying still more newspapers here _ Jack Fuller, the
president of Tribune's publishing unit, said such speculation was
premature. Overall, he said, the deal to buy Times Mirror was a way
to further the company's goal of reaching larger audiences more
ways. And of reaching them with local news.
</P>
<P>
   Besides The Los Angeles Times, The Baltimore Sun, The Hartford
Courant and Newsday, Times Mirror owns The Morning Call in
Allentown, Pa., The Advocate in Stamford, Conn., and Greenwich
Time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know,'' Fuller said, ``is that this positions us in that
world strongly to take advantage of the developments as they
emerge. That's what we're trying to do. What that means in the way
of ventures or alliances, it's not possible to predict.''
</P>
<P>
   But from newspapers to broadcasting _ Tribune has owned WPIX, a
Warner Brothers network affiliate, since its creation in 1947 _ to
cable television to sports broadcasting to the Internet, Tribune
will find new links and new possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention some old grudges. Most of Newsday's employees are
union members, represented by local 406 of the Graphic
Communications International Union. The local's president, George
Tedeschi, well remembers the bitter 1990 battle between Tribune and
the unions that represented workers at The Daily News, the
newspaper that Joseph Patterson, a member of Tribune's founding
family, created as a New York media powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wait-and-see situation,'' Tedeschi said last week.
``Let's hope the Tribune Co. is not coming in here trying to be the
villain. Let's hope they hope to come in and cooperate with the
union and employees to prosper, just the way Times Mirror was able
to prosper.'' He said that a multiyear contract for Newsday's
employees had about five years to run.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question for Tribune is whether to try to crack the
New York City market with a print product. WPIX, which ranks fifth
among New York's six network-affiliated broadcast stations in prime
time evening hours, is a stealth power in the 7-to-9 morning slot _
the domain of NBC's ``Today Show'' and ABC's ``Good Morning
America'' _ where it ranked third in the most recent Nielsen
ratings. The prospects for improving that ranking are strong:
Tribune's KTLA station in Los Angeles is a close second in that
time slot with an all-news program, and its WGN station in Chicago
has become the No. 2 morning news program.
</P>
<P>
   The potential to lure audiences and advertisers with improved
broadcast-news performance is there. But can Tribune get back
newspaper readers in the city? Does it even want to?
</P>
<P>
   Newsday, the successor to the newspaper bought in 1939 as a
wedding present for Alicia Patterson _ Joseph Patterson's daughter
_ by her husband, Harry F. Guggenheim, has grown from a circulation
of 15,000 in 1940 to 575,000 today. Its household penetration rate
is the highest in the country: 53.8 percent daily and 63.7 percent
on Sunday, among 877,300 households in Nassau and Suffolk Counties.
</P>
<P>
   And ever since the demise of New York Newsday in 1995, the paper
has been sending tendrils back into Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing in Queens is exactly what we've been doing
for several years: adding three, four and five reporters a year,''
said Anthony Marro, Newsday's editor. Among the Newsday journalists
responsible for New York news coverage, he said, are 25 reporters,
five assigning editors and some page designers. In addition, there
are financial and arts and entertainment reporters based in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to running a daily newspaper devoted to the
city, both Newsday and Tribune have been there and done that, and
it did not end well for either of them. Buying one of the existing
tabloids, The Daily News _ owned by Mortimer B. Zuckerman and Fred
Drasner _ or Rupert Murdoch's New York Post, does not seem to be an
option.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Zuckerman, who recently told his staff that his young daughter
would be the next publisher of The Daily News, said he expected
Newsday to continue its pursuit of Queens readers.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent figures available show that The News reached 16
percent of Queens households with its daily paper and 19.7 percent
on Sundays. Newsday reached about 13.1 percent daily and 14.9
percent Sunday, outselling The New York Times, which reached 7.1
percent daily and 8.9 percent Sunday. The New York Post, which like
The Times is strongest in Manhattan, trailed the pack in Queens,
with 5.71 percent daily and 5.8 percent penetration on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But in the city as a whole, Newsday is a relative pipsqueak,
with 3.4 percent daily penetration of 2.9 million households and
3.6 percent Sunday. So it is unlikely that Tribune will buy its way
into the five boroughs immediately, if ever, and it would be
expensive to accelerate the gradual assault on New York from the
Queens front.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an equally attractive audience is one that Cablevision
commands on Long Island, in Southern Connecticut and in New Jersey
with its 24-hour local news channel, News 12.
</P>
<P>
   News is just one way to lure audiences. Sports can be even more
effective. Tribune owns the Chicago Cubs baseball team and its
broadcast rights. In New York, Cablevision, which itself is
one-third owned by AT&AMP;T, has an equivalent sports portfolio, owning
the New York Knicks, New York Rangers and Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Charles F. Dolan, Cablevision's chairman, hails synergy in the
same terms that Tribune executives use. And Dolan's company's forte
is fine-grained local news and sports, which is the foundation of
Tribune's multimedia efforts in Chicago and in Orlando, Fla. So
Cablevision is in some ways one of the most potent competitors or
partners for Tribune in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In northern New Jersey, where the print players are newspapers
like The Record in Hackensack, owned by the Borg family, and The
Star Ledger in Newark, News 12 is a major presence _ and it is also
a partnership. Cablevision jointly owns and manages the New Jersey
service with Newhouse, the parent company of The Newark Star
Ledger, whose journalists contribute to its programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are moving away from a specific platform,'' Dolan said.
``You are a newspaper and someone else is a broadcaster. Those
identities may be archaic. You are first and foremost a journalist,
and an expert in a particular area of coverage _ that's what's
ultimately important to a reader or viewer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1735EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-SOUTH-NYT     03-18 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-SOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORWARDS, FOR A CHANGE, MAY DECIDE BOTH GAMES IN BIRMINGHAM
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Though play in the NCA A tournament has been
guard-driven in recent years, size drives the four teams playing
Sunday in the South Regional.
</P>
<P>
   They are an unusual mix of towering, tenacious teams that play
the post. When Connecticut (25-9) plays Tennessee (25-6) and
Stanford (27-3) meets North Carolina (19-13) here at the
Birmingham-Jefferson Civic Center, what happens under the basket,
in the paint, could prove more crucial than what occurs on the
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, guard play will be important, especially for Connecticut,
the defending champion. The Huskies will probably start Khalid
El-Amin at point guard. He suffered a sprained right ankle Friday
afternoon in their 75-67 victory over Utah State. But the question
of how effective and how long El-Amin can play on the sore ankle
makes Connecticut squirm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only have 48 hours to take care of it,'' El-Amin said. ``I
did some ultrasound and ice and I have a lot more treatment to go
through before the game. It's going to be a game-time decision.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an issue Connecticut must address since El-Amin is the
soul of the team's playmaking on both ends of the floor. If El-Amin
is unable to perform, Connecticut will turn to a couple of
freshman, first Tony Robertson and then to Marcus Cox, to
orchestrate its game plan.
</P>
<P>
   But equally important for Connecticut is defending the post,
where Tennessee features two 6-foot-8-inch players, C.J. Black and
the versatile, slashing Ron Slay, plus forward Isiah Victor (6-9)
and forward Vincent Yarbrough (6-7).
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, in turn, gives Tennessee plenty to ponder in the
paint in center Jake Voskuhl (6-11) and forward Kevin Freeman
(6-7). Add the Huskies' center Soleymane Wane (6-11), forward Ajou
Deng (6-10) and forward Edward Saunders (6-8), and Tennessee will
find that rebounding, shot blocking and post points will heavily
decide the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The same applies to Stanford and North Carolina, where the twin
Collins brothers, Jason and Jarron, both 6-11, tangle with North
Carolina center Brendan Haywood, who is 7 feet. Haywood was
dominating in a 28-point, 15-rebound output in the Tar Heels' 74-60
victory over Missouri, which was easily the best game of the season
for him and his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is standard in tournament play that the further you advance
that guard play rises to the top,'' said Tony Fuller, assistant
coach of Stanford. ``In those first-round games, higher seeded
teams are usually much bigger teams against little teams and the
size factor is so evident. But these games here on Sunday are going
to be odd because all four teams may start with the emphasis inside
more than outside. And it could finish that way, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Haywood, in particular, is on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   He is a junior who has been labeled as soft and easily winded, a
guy who has barely tapped his ability. He has heard enough of the
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard people doubt me all of my life,'' Haywood said.
``When I was 13, nobody thought I'd get to this position in college
basketball. People think because you're big you're supposed to do
more than the average guy in basketball. I know I'm always the key
to other teams' defenses, but people don't think about that. I want
to get us to the Sweet 16 and see what people have to say about
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't expect me to play well against
Stanford's big guys because they have the big starters and then
more big guys coming off the bench. We'll see on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Missouri, North Carolina made Haywood the focal point of
its attack. It plans to do the same against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had an up-and-down season and I can see why people have
counted us out,'' said Tar Heels point guard Ed Cota. ``We haven't
played to our potential. But against Missouri everybody on our team
played their roles, got the ball to Brendan and didn't worry about
getting credit or how their stats looked. We've put the selfish
play behind us, and that is Carolina basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford features balance inside and out, but its inside players
_ especially the Collins brothers and forward Mark Madsen, who is
6-9 _ are flexible and powerful players full of presence.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Collins kept the focus on Haywood. ``I've been playing
against Brendan for a long time in high school and AAU games,'' he
said. ``He is physical and likes to work low. He likes the short
jumper and hook and to rebound and put the ball back. I have to
push him up the lane more. I have to make him work harder for his
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut wants to push Black out of the middle, too, and keep
Slay from creating opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennessee has athletic guys in the post,'' Saunders said.
``But we play good team defense and I think we are more athletic
than them. We're going to have to battle them hard for 40 minutes
and establish the post as ours. It's hard work down there with
little glamour. But it's where these games will be won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1736EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-THEHOOD0319-COX     03-18 2412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THEHOOD0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National Felony League
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two of the NFL's top stars say Baltimore Ravens
linebacker Ray Lewis violated one of the basic ``entourage'' rules
on Jan. 31, when he shuffled passengers into his limo and left a
crime scene in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to surround yourself with people who want to
accomplish what you're looking to do,'' said Falcons running back
Jamal Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you have to talk with them before you go out,'' said
Terrell Davis, running back for the Denver Broncos, ``and tell
them, `If something goes down, we walk away.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the National Football League, that's been an
easier-said-than-done.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewis left Buckhead hours after Super Bowl XXXIV, two men
lay dead in the street from multiple stab wounds. Lewis and two
friends, both with serious criminal backgrounds, were arrested on
charges of murder.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second murder charge against an active NFL player _
there have been three in league history _ in three months. In
November, Carolina Panthers receiver Rae Carruth was charged with
murder in the slaying of Cherica Adams, 24, his pregnant
girlfriend. Police say Carruth plotted Adams' shooting with two
acquaintances who had histories of criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   The Carruth and Lewis incidents sandwiched a string of serious
charges against NFL players and their associates. While the
transgressions shocked the nation, they have not been surprising to
those close to the league.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials say they realize that the new generation of
athlete, made instantly rich on draft day, is creating serious
problems. Many come from impoverished backgrounds and won't, or
cannot, break ties with the streets. Some players have entourages
that include convicted felons and gang members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each NFL franchise has a responsibility to try to understand
who they're bringing into their locker room,'' said Dr. Harry
Edwards, a sociologist at the University of California who works
with the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these teams are really doing is blindly mixing chemicals.
It may end up that they're producing diamonds and gold by winning
Super Bowls. But they also could have the whole thing blow up in
their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we get on top of it, we're going to see bombs going off
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Some think it might be the biggest challenge the league has ever
faced. Although the NFL maintains its crime numbers are dropping,
commissioner Paul Tagliabue and players union head Gene Upshaw met
with several players in New York two weeks ago to discuss
off-the-field conduct. Tagliabue is expected to address the
violence issue during a meeting with the league's 32 owners later
this month in Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the NFL resembles a crime-laden mine field.
Carolina running back Fred Lane was arrested in Jackson, Tenn., on
drugs and weapons charges. Earlier, Indianapolis Colts defensive
back Steve Muhammad was charged with battery in the beating of his
pregnant wife, who died in November from labor complications
brought on by injuries suffered in a car accident. Miami Dolphins
running back Cecil Collins was charged with fondling women in two
separate incidents, and his probation was revoked in his native
Louisiana. And Arizona Cardinals running back Mario Bates was
arrested last week on charges of slapping his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't have this kind of thing,'' Kansas City Chiefs owner
Lamar Hunt said. ``We want to be able to focus on football. We want
to concentrate on the draft and minicamps and some of those kinds
of things.... I can't recall anything quite like what has been
happening off the field lately. We must find a way to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue, NFL commissioner since 1989, has expelled one player
from the league for off-the-field violence. Former Eagles offensive
lineman Kevin Allen served 33 months in jail for a 1990 rape, and
his request for reinstatement later was denied by Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the NFL instituted an anti-crime policy for off-field
charges, but the punishment often was light. The first year the
players were disciplined with counseling, then fines.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the recent transgressions creating a public-relations
nightmare, Tagliabue seems to be taking a tougher stance. Last
week, the NFL disciplined four players _ three offensive linemen
who were involved in a fight outside a bar last summer and a
Tennessee Titans defensive back who pleaded guilty to assaulting
the mother of his son.
</P>
<P>
   Three players _ Matt O'Dwyer of the Bengals, Jumbo Elliott of
the Jets and Denard Walker of the Titans _ were suspended two games
this season; Jason Fabini of the Jets was fined $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an organization whose continued success depends on
integrity and public confidence, the NFL simply cannot tolerate
conduct that victimizes other individuals and results in a loss of
respect for NFL players,'' Tagliabue said. ``We are raising the
disciplinary standard in order to underscore that this type of
behavior won't be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   But the league seems to be looking the other way in some cases.
Last month, Kansas City Chiefs receiver Tamarick Vanover pleaded
guilty to the felony charge of aiding and abetting the sale of a
stolen vehicle that crossed state lines. Vanover, who remains on
the team's active roster, is cooperating as a witness in a federal
drug and car-theft investigation that has left 23 people charged
and 10 convicted. Former Chiefs running back Bam Morris also has
been mentioned in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory E. Burns, whom authorities identified as Vanover's
personal assistant, is facing federal drug-trafficking, weapons and
car-theft charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries me league-wide is the hanger-on crowd,'' Chiefs
coach Gunther Cunningham said. ``It is an issue the league, and we
as an organization, will address and look at carefully. If our
players go down to the local gym to play basketball and `Joe Smith'
shows up, well, who is Joe Smith? The team as a whole has to stand
guard for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   LEAGUE'S CHECKS NOT ENOUGH
</P>
<P>
   The league and its teams hire psychologists and security
personnel to conduct extensive background checks of its players.
The NFL also stages several programs for its players, ranging from
financial planning and postcareer counseling to dealing with anger
control, domestic violence, sexual responsibility and substance
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL can't control who is riding in the passenger seats
of players' cars, sleeping in their spare bedrooms or sharing in
their newfound wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, one of the nation's leading sociologists, and other
experts attribute some of the off-field problems to causes ranging
from an increasingly violent society to many athletes coming from
crime-infested neighborhoods and impoverished backgrounds. Big
money also is an issue _ the average NFL salary in 1998 was $1
million _ and some players aren't prepared for the wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who in 1998 signed a four-year contract worth $26
million, will be tried with longtime friends Joseph Sweeting, 34,
and Reginald Oakley, 31. Sweeting has served prison time for
burglary and numerous weapons charges. Oakley has beencharged with
assaulting a police officer, trafficking cocaine and shooting into
an occupied dwelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ray Lewis) was trained to be a great athlete,'' Cleveland
Browns owner Al Lerner said. ``He was never trained to be a
multimillionaire. He was never trained to handle that kind of
exposure and the things that got shoved in front of him. How many
times do we remember walking away from an incident and it was good
that we did? These kids may not know enough about just walking
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the biggest factor in off-field violence may be a
player's background and the team's ability to deal with it. NFL
scouts say that in years past, there were serious character
questions about three or four athletes in each draft. Some years,
that number has increased to more than two dozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do a better job of screening and profiling and
understanding the baggage involved with some of the personnel we're
bringing into the league,'' Edwards said. ``We're not a social work
organization whose mandate is to save souls. But we're dealing with
human beings, and that carries with it a responsibility to
professionally understand who these players are. ... Negative
associates can be family members. We've got players in the NFL who
have family members in jail. We've got players who have family
members on death row. You can't pull a person out of a network of
associates that is so deeply embedded.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL running back Darick Holmes, who last season played for the
Colts, has said that gang members helped pay for his education at
Portland State. His brother, Karl, was convicted of a gang-related
murder and is on death row in San Quentin State Prison in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Darick Holmes, who at age 15 spent 10 months in youth camp for
selling marijuana, has remained out of trouble during his five-year
NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   OLD TIES THAT BIND
</P>
<P>
   ``People say the (gangs) pick you, you don't pick them,'' Holmes
told the Buffalo News in 1996. ``But you can make your own
decisions, even though you grow up right there. You're tempted to
join. I had my chances where I could have joined. I might have
hustled, trying to make some money gambling, but other than that I
wasn't going to join.''
</P>
<P>
   Other NFL players have struggled to break the ties. Wide
receiver Charles Jordan, who spent last season with the Green Bay
Packers, grew up on the streets of Los Angeles. He was a gang
member of the Bloods, whose rivals were the Crips.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, Jordan was accused of _ but never convicted of _
armed robbery, drug dealing, driving a stolen vehicle and carrying
a concealed weapon. When he was 19, Jordan and two other members of
his gang were arrested in connection with the murder of a Crip.
Jordan refused to give police the name of the shooter, and after
spending five months in jail, he was released.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, signed as a free agent by Los Angeles Raiders in 1993,
has had a lackluster six-year career in the NFL. But he has grabbed
plenty of headlines for off-field trouble. During an interview with
ESPN in 1997, Jordan admitted sending part of his salary to gang
members in California.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who says he severed his gang ties after the birth of his
first child in 1992, was cut by the Miami Dolphins in February
1999. He was released after being charged with two felonies related
to accusations of fighting with police outside a bar in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. Before the Packers cut him earlier this year,
Jordan was charged with obstruction and paid a $5,000 fine for
lying to police about a traffic accident involving teammate Antonio
Freeman in Green Bay, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials say gangs are such a widespread
epidemic that it would be naive to think that the problem hasn't
infected the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gangs are a trend that is sweeping the country,'' said Wes
Daily Jr., president of the National Alliance of Gang Investigators
Association. ``Why wouldn't you expect to see them in sports? Not
all of these kids are wild, war-torn and poor. Some of them
graduate from high school and go to college. They do go into sports
and corporate America, but they still keep their alliances in the
gang.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards: ``Anytime that you have a society that has the growing
gang problem that America has, and you're tapping into that youth,
you're going to have a gang problem. I don't think gangs are an
overwhelming problem for the NFL. Is it there? Sure, it's there. Is
the league concerned? Yes. But is it something that could topple
the league over? No.''
</P>
<P>
   According to NFL statistics, the number of players who were
investigated by law enforcement for violent crimes decreased from a
total of 50 _ from more than 2,000 players _ in 1997 to 37
investigations in 1999. The league also said convictions for
violent crimes also dropped, from 23 in 1997 to nine in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some gang experts contend that problems start at the college
level, where schools recruit student-athletes with questionable
pasts and expect them to change overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're recruiting ball players. They don't care if they're
gang members or not,'' said Wes McBride of the Los Angeles County
Sheriff's Department, a past president of the Gang Investigators
Association. ``That's the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Lucas was the head coach at Pomona (Calif.) High School
in 1984 when then-coach Bill McCartney approached him about joining
his staff at the University of Colorado. The Buffaloes were coming
off a 4-7 record in 1983, and McCartney knew he had to turn the
program around quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Let's see how we can get some of these inner-city
kids,''' said Lucas, now a coach at Adams City High School in
Colorado. ``Florida and Florida State made a living recruiting
those kids. He wanted to go for the quick fix and that was the
inner-city kids.''
</P>
<P>
   With Lucas recruiting talent-rich California, the Buffaloes
signed future NFL players Eric Bieniemy, Deon Figures and Charles
Johnson, among others. Bienemy, now a free-agent running back, and
Figures, a cornerback with the Jaguars, have both acknowledged past
gang ties. Both have been model NFL players.
</P>
<P>
   With those players leading the way, Colorado shared the national
championship with Georgia Tech in 1990. Lucas was fired after the
following season.
</P>
<P>
   Daily, a detective with the Suffolk County Police Department in
New York, says some coaches ignore obvious warning signs because of
the pressures to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wrong expectation to think you can take a kid out of a
community ravaged by gangs, put a psychologist in front of him and
change him,'' Daily said. ``It's too deep. Gangs don't consider
themselves as gangs. They consider themselves as an organization or
family. Some people grow up and get out of that environment, but
others don't. It's gotten a lot of athletes in trouble because they
haven't separated themselves from their friends, who still
associate with the gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying on the street, `Once a member, always a
member. Once a gangster, always a gangster.' Now that these
athletes have hit it big, their friends are coming up to them,
saying, `Hey, help us out. You're big now.' And some of those guys
don't walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
