<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOODCAP0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salary cap restricts leadership
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stringent salary-cap rules and free agency are among
the root causes of off-the-field violence committed by NFL players,
says one of the nation's leading sociologists.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harry Edwards, a professor of sociology at the University of
California, contends the league's salary-cap rules, which were
introduced in 1993 to bring more parity to pro football, are
depriving locker rooms of much-needed leadership. Edwards, who has
served as a consultant for the San Francisco 49ers since 1985, says
free agency strips teams of veterans, who often serve as role
models and mentors for younger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a situation where Thurman Thomas, Bruce Smith
and Andre Reed all are leaving the Buffalo Bills in one day, or a
Jerry Rice, Tim McDonald and Steve Young might leave the San
Francisco 49ers because of the salary cap and free agency, you
undermine the leadership, chemistry and structure of the locker
room,'' Edwards said. ``There's no continuity. There's no
significant core of tradition that the younger players can connect
with. Now, the younger players are going to connect with younger
guys, who most likely were college teammates that didn't make it to
the NFL, or their friends from the 'hood.''
</P>
<P>
   According to figures from the NFL Players Association, more than
120 free agents signed with new teams before last season. This
year, more than 100 players already have signed with new teams,
including former Bills defensive end Smith, running back Thomas and
receiver Reed, who were released by Buffalo for financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   As teams scurried to get under the $62.172 million salary cap by
the Feb. 10 deadline, veterans were some of the first players
released. Carolina cut linebacker Michael Barrow in a cost-cutting
move. Vikings offensive linemen Randall McDaniel and Jeff Christy
signed with the Buccaneers when Minnesota couldn't afford them, and
the Falcons did not re-sign defensive end Chuck Smith for financial
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said Baltimore Ravens linebacker Ray Lewis, who goes on
trial in May on charges of murder in the Jan. 31 stabbings of two
men in Atlanta, might have lacked a veteran presence in the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ravens stated that they were going to talk to Ray Lewis
about the people he was associating with,'' Edwards said. ``Well,
it's not a one-time talk. It should be an ongoing discussion
between Ray Lewis and a veteran leader throughout the course of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   After a recent meeting in New York to discuss off-field
violence, players union head Gene Upshaw said players favor more
player-to-player mentoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things players seemed to be saying over and over is
that one-on-one, player-to-player type of relationships should be
developed, probably better than we have,'' Upshaw said. ``There are
clear role models out there, and it's among our peers. There are
really good guys out there waiting for a call to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said he prefers a system that would slot free agents on
each team. Under that plan, clubs would only count a certain
percentage of a veteran's salary against the cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free agency and the cap have definitely contributed to the
problems in sports,'' Edwards said. ``There has to be some system
where you can stabilize veteran players.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
