<HEADER>
A1131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HOODSIDE0319-COX     03-18 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOODSIDE0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL stars find it difficult to turn away pals
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Running backs Jamal Anderson of the Falcons and
Terrell Davis of the Denver Broncos are two of the biggest stars of
the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Both players have a large network of friends and associates, but
Anderson and Davis have managed to stay out of the police blotter
during their pro careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have an entourage as big as the best,'' Anderson said.
``But I'm not going to put myself in a situation that I might
regret.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the former University of Georgia player who was named the
NFL's Most Valuable Player in 1998, grew up in a tough neighborhood
in San Diego. One of his brothers served 5 1/2 years in prison for
shooting a pregnant woman during a robbery. Davis said his best
friend was murdered. But Davis escaped the streets through
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're growing up as a kid, there are a lot of
opportunities to get into trouble. I got into trouble as a kid,''
Davis said. ``I think when you've grown up and you have friends
that you've known since you were 5 or 6, and you're in the position
you're in with all the money and stature, it's hard to distance
yourself from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to change. But you've got to explain it to your
friends before you go out. You tell them, `Look, if something goes
down, we walk away.'''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said one of his biggest concerns is that some of his
friends think they're his bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are overprotective,'' he said. ``I've got
friends who think they're watching my back. If they think I'm not
in the mood to talk, they'll push someone away. That can start an
altercation right there.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been easier for Anderson, who grew up around celebrity.
While Anderson was growing up near Los Angeles, his father was a
bodyguard for Muhammad Ali, Sugar Ray Leonard, Diana Ross, Arsenio
Hall and Richard Pryor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have friends who have done things that we're not proud
of,'' Anderson said. ``You've just got to prioritize what you're
trying to get done in your life. I was raised to know that I should
surround myself with people who wanted to accomplish what you're
looking to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got some friends who are screw-ups. It's a tough
situation. Everyone is telling you not to change, so you don't want
to quit associating with the people you've known your entire life.
But you also don't want to have friends who can get you into
trouble. It's a different ball to handle. It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Chiefs tight end Tony Gonzalez said it's easier said
than done for players to disassociate themselves with friends they
grew up with.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize these players have grown up with those
guys since they were little kids,'' Gonzalez said. ``You can tell
them to change, but it's hard to do. These are the people who were
there before you became who you are today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell someone like that, `Hey, I can't hang out
with you anymore. Even though you've been with me my whole life,
now I can't talk to you anymore.' I mean, that's a hard position to
be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
