u a BC-NJ-DENTIST-INJURY-535     03-18 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DENTIST-INJURY-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENTIST IS INVESTIGATED AFTER BOY'S LEG IS BROKEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yeni Rivero said she always had a slightly uneasy feeling when
she was told she could not accompany her 5-year-old son, Mario,
into the treatment room when they visited the Children's Dental
Center in Union City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when an assistant called her into the treatment
room, that unease was borne out: She found her son with a broken
leg that she believed was caused by the dentist, Dr. Kevin P. Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son was pale white and crying, and he told me, `Mommy, I
can't walk,''' Rivero said Friday in a telephone interview from her
North Bergen home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dentist explained to me that my son was struggling, and
that he had begun to kick his legs in the air and had kicked him in
the head,'' she said. ``He told me, `I pressed down on his leg, and
I heard his bone snap.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mario Rivero has a broken right femur, and has a cast on his
entire right leg, part of his left leg and halfway up his chest,
his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, 42, did not respond to telephone messages left at his
office Thursday and Friday; neither did his lawyer, Vincent
Loughlin.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson County prosecutor's office has started a criminal
investigation. As a result of reports of Mario Rivero's injury,
Ward is no longer practicing at two other offices, in Vernon and in
Maywood, where he worked one day a week. But even as the state's
Department of Consumer Affairs, which oversees the board that
licenses dentists, reviews the matter, Ward continues to practice
at Children's Dental Center in Union City, where he now works most
of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mario's injury, Hudson County prosecutors said they had
learned that Ward was sued in January by the family of an
8-year-old girl who said he broke her wrist while she was having a
tooth pulled in his Vernon office several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And state officials said Ward had his license suspended for a
year in 1987 after a child under anesthesia died in his office.
During a state hearing in that case, Ward admitted to ``a
significant error in professional judgment,'' according to a
transcript.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Board of Dentistry prohibited him from using
general anesthesia unless he completed 60 hours of course work, but
he failed to do this, according to Jennifer Salvato, a spokeswoman
for the Division of Consumer Affairs. Ward is still allowed to
administer local anesthetics.
</P>
<P>
   Salvato said the 1987 suspension was the only action the
consumer affairs office had taken against Ward during his 16-year
career in New Jersey. No criminal charges have been brought against
him.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the Rivero matter, the consumer affairs office is
reviewing Ward's license, Salvato said.
</P>
<P>
   Edward DeFazio, the deputy first assistant Hudson County
prosecutor, said it might be difficult to bring criminal charges
against Ward for Mario Rivero's injuries because the only witness
against him is a 5-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is denying there was a fracture of the child's leg, and
that it apparently occurred when he was being treated by the
dentist,'' DeFazio said. ``The question is: Is there sufficient
indication of intent to make it a criminal case? Under the law,
negligence is not sufficient state of mind for an aggravated
assault.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The lawsuit against Ward in January was filed by Cathy
Caliendieri of Rockaway Township for a 1996 incident in which her
daughter, Amanda Schwab, then 4, went to his Vernon office to have
a tooth pulled and emerged with a broken wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first and last visit to him,'' she said. ``I was
told that I was not allowed in the room. That was their policy. Who
was I to argue with the doctor?''
</P>
<P>
   When Ward emerged from the treatment room with Amanda, the girl
said he had hurt her arm, her mother said. Caliendieri said Ward
told her, ``We had a little problem,'' and explained that Amanda
would not hold still, so he had to hold her down.
</P>
<P>
   She said police officials who questioned Ward told her that they
would not file criminal charges, because they concluded that the
child's injuries were the result of an accident.
</P>
<P>
   In Mario Rivero's case, his mother said that when Ward told her
he had had to restrain her son, the dentist did not seem very
concerned, even when he explained that he had heard Mario's bone
snap. ``He said that at that time my son stopped stirring, so he
finished the procedure on him,'' Rivera said. ``I almost passed out
when he explained that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to him: `How could you continue working on him? Why
didn't you call me or come and get me?''' she said. ``He didn't
answer me.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she wanted to call an ambulance, and Ward told her she
should have her own pediatrician examine the boy. Instead, Rivero
said, she used her cell phone to call her husband to the office,
and they called 911. ``Dr. Ward never said, `I'm sorry.' He never
offered us the use of his telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   After she contacted 911, the police were sent to the dentist's
office along with an ambulance, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was during the police officers' questioning of Ward, Rivera
said, that she learned he had worked on the wrong tooth. She said
that her son was struggling because he was trying to tell the
dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rivero, like Caliendieri, thinks she should have gone into
the treatment room with her son. There are no regulations governing
whether doctors and dentists must allow the parents of minors into
the treatment room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't come out,'' Rivero said of Ward. ``His policy is
that kids go in and they're taken care of. He doesn't come out and
explain anything to parents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
