<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SYRACUSE-KENTUCKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORANGEMEN MUDDLE ALONG, THEN SAVE BEST FOR LAST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LIZ ROBBINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Preston Shumpert, his long black socks covering his
spindly legs, was alone in the corner at the baseline Sunday,
waiting patiently. His Syracuse teammate, Jason Hart, driving
through the lane, had a shot, but delivered it instead to the
steady sixth man on a designed play.
</P>
<P>
   When the ball came to Shumpert, he launched it with confidence
and rhythm, breaking a 50-50 tie with only 36.8 seconds remaining
in a seesaw affair against Kentucky. That last shot proved enough
to send Syracuse (26-5) to the Round of 16 for the first time in
three years and sent Kentucky (23-10) home to Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   ``From shooting lots of shots, it's just repetition,'' Shumpert
said of his long-range accuracy, especially under pressure. ``It
all feels the same. I just shot it and it went up.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Kentucky's Tayshaun Prince fell to the floor as his
fadeaway last-second jumper missed the mark, it was, fittingly,
Shumpert who got the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Shumpert then sent the ball straight up into the cool
Convocation Center air, more than 60 feet up. He led the Orangemen
with 12 points in their satisfying 52-50 victory over Kentucky. He
was the only Syracuse player in double figures on a dismal shooting
afternoon in which Syracuse shot only 31.7 percent and Kentucky
40.5. In the end, Shumpert decided the sloppy contest with the
cleanest of shots.
</P>
<P>
   The game was still in doubt with 10.7 seconds remaining. At that
point, Kentucky coach Tubby Smith called back-to-back timeouts,
with nine seconds left on the shot clock and the Wildcats still
trailing, 52-50. Then Syracuse called another timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the court, the Kentucky freshman Keith Bogans
missed a runner on the baseline and Prince's 3-point follow shot
fell flat.
</P>
<P>
   Until then it seemed that Souleymane Camara, a 6-11 Kentucky
sophomore who averaged only seven points a game this season, might
turn out to be the player of the game. He had a blocked shot and
two consecutive thundering dunks in the final three minutes, tying
the score at 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams carried their banners proudly into the game. Kentucky
had seven national championships to boast, as well as the best
all-time record in college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse had two runners-up trophies but believed the past
experience was not as important as the present. As it turned out,
the three senior Orangemen _ Hart, Ryan Blackwell and Etan Thomas _
did not contribute as much as the sophomore sixth man.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell gave his team a 48-45 advantage with 3:57 to play.
Eleven seconds later, Syracuse took a severe blow when Thomas left
the game with five fouls. With him went an intimidating presence in
the middle. But the Wildcats could not capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's lone senior starter was Jamaal Magloire, a 6-10
center who made an aborted attempt at playing in the NBA this past
summer until he decided he would improve his marketability by
staying at Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's better for it and we're better for it,'' Smith said. ``We
both got as much as possible from his return.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Magloire ignited the Wildcats by scoring
eight points and keeping the teams close. Then Prince, his
sophomore teammate, who was the hero of the first-round
double-overtime victory over St. Bonaventure, scored eight straight
to give Kentucky a 42-40 lead with nine minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams played frantic defense throughout the first half,
forcing bad shots and a combined total of 19 turnovers, setting the
tone for a sloppy affair between two evenly matched teams.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the chilly Convocation Center, Syracuse shot an anemic 29
percent from the floor in the first half, Kentucky 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated matchup between the senior centers, Thomas and
Magloire, did not produce many offensive highlights in the first
half, but Thomas proved why he had 102 blocked shots during the
season to Magloire's 54. With six minutes remaining in the first
half, Thomas stuffed Saul Smith on a pull-up jumper, blocking it so
resoundingly that the ball bounced higher than twice Smith's 6-1
height.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all timing, that's all,'' Thomas said with a shrug before
the game.
</P>
<P>
   His timing could not have been better. Though Syracuse failed to
capitalize on its next possession, Thomas had another block the
next time down the court. That seemed to jump-start the Orangemen's
surge toward the end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, Syracuse had gone nearly 11 minutes without a
field goal, yet never trailed by more than six points.
</P>
<P>
   DeShaun Williams connected on Syracuse's first 3-pointer of the
game with 3:27 remaining in the half to bring the Orange within a
basket, 18-16. Then Shumpert, in a preview of things to come,
knocked down another jumper 3-pointer to give Syracuse its first
lead in over seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
