<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOSEPH'S DEFENSE A CONCERN FOR RUTGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ Before Rutgers eliminated Holy Cross, 91-70,
Friday night in the National Collegiate Athletic Association
women's tournament here, the Scarlet Knights' Shawnetta Stewart
watched the first half of the opener between St. Joseph's and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's mind was on her own upcoming game, but she noticed
enough to draw a conclusion. Tenth-seeded St. Joseph's was on its
way to a 69-48 victory, holding the seventh-seeded Longhorns to
their second-lowest point total of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're going to be a test,'' Stewart said of the
Hawks, the Scarlet Knights' second-round opponent here on Sunday in
the West Regional. The winner will advance to the round of 16 in
Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights (23-7) were to watch film of the Hawks
(25-5) Saturday. They will find a disciplined team that adjusts its
zone defense to its opponent and is patient on offense. St.
Joseph's allows 53 points a game, the second-lowest average in the
nation. The Hawks rely on center Jana Lichnerova (14 points and
seven rebounds a game) and forward Susan Moran (16.4 points, seven
rebounds) for most of their points, and Angela Zampella (eight
assists a game) to get them the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Moran squirmed into the key for several short jumpers and layups
to score 24 points against Texas. ``I think we run our offense so
well that it looks like I get the ball a lot by chance,'' Moran
said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph's has been scrimmaging against men to acclimate
itself to the physical play of the tournament, and the Hawks will
likely get a healthy dose of it from the Scarlet Knights.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers outrebounded Holy Cross, 42-25, and slashed through
screens to shut down the Crusaders' star, Anna Kinne, during a 24-4
second-half run after Kinne had scored 19 points in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 10 turnovers, and we outrebounded them,'' Stewart said,
``and those were the two key things that coach Stringer wanted us
to do well on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
