<HEADER>
A1135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HOCKEY-PARENTS-980&AMP;AD     03-18 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEY-PARENTS-980&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAULT CHARGES PUT FOCUS ON PARENTS' BEHAVIOR AT YOUTH HOCKEY
GAMES
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By COREY KILGANNON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After 38 straight losses, the 10- and 11-year-old
members of the Staten Island Sharks ice hockey team finally had
something to cheer about: a hard-fought 3-2 victory on Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The game was also a moment of jubilation for the players'
parents, who spend thousands of dollars for equipment and league
fees and anxiously study their children every second they are on
the ice.
</P>
<P>
   But one parent was angry. Matteo Picca, whose son Steven plays
forward, grabbed his son's two sticks from the bench at the War
Memorial Rink and confronted the coach, Louis Aiani. The argument
grew heated. According to the Staten Island district attorney's
office, Picca rammed the coach in the face with the sticks in what
the hockey world calls a cross check, breaking his nose and causing
facial injuries requiring stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that Picca was upset that his 10-year-old son
remained on the bench during the final minutes of the game, while
Aiani kept his better players on the ice. Picca has maintained that
his complaint had been about the coach's win-at-all-costs attitude.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing testimony from parents, coaches and league
officials, a grand jury indicted Picca on Tuesday on charges of
second-degree assault and fourth-degree criminal possession of a
weapon. He is scheduled to be arraigned in state Supreme Court on
Staten Island this Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors called the attack ``one of the worst examples of
parents acting overly aggressive and irresponsible with regard to
their child's athletic activities.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews last week, parents, coaches and league officials
on Staten Island, where ice hockey's popularity has surged in
recent years, could not recall any other time that a parent had
physically attacked a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Most agreed, however, that the incident illustrated that parents
were quicker to lose control at their children's games. Maybe, one
joked, there should be a separate penalty box for parents.
</P>
<P>
   While the phenomenon of parents behaving badly is present in
most junior league sports, it is particularly noticeable in ice
hockey. Parents often pay thousands of dollars per season to
register and outfit their children, and drive them to practices and
games early in the morning and late at night. So the amount of time
the coach allows the child to take center stage on the ice is at a
premium, and closely monitored by parents.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey teams usually have at least three five-player units that
alternate on the ice at the coach's discretion. First-string
players tend to play longer shifts than second- and third-string
players.
</P>
<P>
   Also, fierce rooting, sometimes bloodthirsty, can get parents
into altercations with referees, coaches and one another. Unlike
many other sports, where parents of opposing teams sit separately,
many hockey rinks, including the two on Staten Island, have no
spectator seating, so parents of children from both teams usually
stand at the edge of the ice, near the benches for the players and
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk to any coach on Staten Island, and he'll tell you
that the perfect rink would be one without parents,'' said Loretta
Giamboi, secretary for the six hockey teams at Monsignor Farrell
High School on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glass is around the rink but it should be around the
parents,'' Giamboi said. ``They yell things like `Get that guy,
take him down.' They're all playing through their kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks' league has banned Picca from attending games and
practices. After the incident, his two sons did not return to
league play for the rest of the season, which ended last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is to give all kids equal playing time,'' said
Louis Wein, a senior vice president of the league, ``but you
frequently hear things like, `My kid missed two minutes this
period,' or, `He was only on the ice 32 seconds, and the other kid
got 47 seconds.' So if a coach keeps his best line in during the
last two minutes, does that warrant a physical assault?''
</P>
<P>
   Picca appeared with his son the ``Early Show'' on CBS on
Thursday morning to insist that he did not start the fight.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Nicholas Gravante Jr. of Manhattan, insisted
Friday that his client had approached Aiani only to complain that
his son had been verbally abused throughout the season. The fight
broke out, he said, ``only after the coach raised his hand first.''
Aiani's wounds were very likely caused by Picca's fists, Gravante
added, ``but if the coach was indeed hit by the sticks, it was
accidental, in the scuffle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravante claimed that Steven Picca was frequently harassed
verbally by Aiani and would come home crying after hockey practice
``because this coach told him he stinks and was calling him a
moron.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with playing time,'' he said, adding
that Aiani had a win-at-all-costs attitude at the Jan. 23 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vince Lombardi philosophy is not appropriate in junior
league hockey,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aiani, 43, works for the New York City Board of Education as a
district supervisor, said his attorney, Michael E. McMahon, who
called the incident ``an indictment of parental misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a national issue, parents getting overly involved
emotionally in their kids' games, like every game's the Super
Bowl,'' he said. ``A guy bashes his son's coach in the face with a
hockey stick in front of children, and instead of apologizing, he
goes on national TV concocting some phony excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   At a hockey clinic at the War Memorial Rink last Thursday night,
fathers leaned over the boards cheering on their sons, many of whom
wore their family names on the back of their jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kids that play, but some of these parents think
they're on the ice,'' said Andrzej Bajor, whose son Michael, 11,
plays defense in the Sharks' squirts division.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jenine Fuca, whose twin boys, James and Nicholas, 16, play
hockey at Monsignor Farrell, added, ``They should let in the kids
and keep out the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Roses pays about $5,000 per year for her sons Brett, 9,
and Kirk, 10, to play hockey for the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no guarantee that these kids are going to get a lot of
ice time,'' she said. ``Parents should know that going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Mark Schofield, from Middletown, N.J., watched his son,
Mark Jr., 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving your kid three hours to a game, only to watch him sit
on the bench, while some other kid gets 15 minutes a period,'' he
said. ``That can build up psychologically over the course of a
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominick Volpe, the rink manager, said he regularly broke up
disputes between parents there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid playing baseball, my father didn't even know
where I was,'' he said. ``Some of these parents these days are
ridiculous. It's bad enough the kids get pressure from their
coaches and friends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
