<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: COLUMBIA AND HIGH-TECH PARTNER DIVIDE AND CONQUER
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: (at) designates the `at' symbol.) 
(jw) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Columbia University's school of continuing education
and Eureka Broadband, a high-technology start-up, have agreed to
share space at 100 William St. in Lower Manhattan, in an unusual
arrangement that participating executives say will benefit both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Paul M. McNeil, Columbia's associate dean for continuing
education, said the proliferation of dot-com companies and other
computer-driven industries has been good for the university, with
more workers seeking advanced training in programming and related
skills. Enrollment in the computer technology and applications
program has grown 25 percent in the last two years, and now it has
650 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't accommodate more growth in our existing labs
uptown,'' McNeil said. Since many of the prospective students work
downtown, he began looking for space in the area. But space
downtown, once cheap because of then-high vacancy rates, has become
more expensive as the vacancies have been filled. Rents for Class A
space in the area are now approaching $40 a square foot, according
to brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I found,'' McNeil said, ``was out of my price
range.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he could have afforded it, he simply did not like some
of the spaces he was shown. One was the basement of the building at
55 Broad St., the first in the downtown area to make major of use
technology as a marketing tool. ``One of the things we have to do
is create a mini-campus in the evenings,'' McNeil said. ``Two
underground rooms filled with computers do not say campus.''
</P>
<P>
   But the university had one advantage: it only needed the space
at night and on weekends. During business hours it would be
available if another user could be found that could take advantage
of a fully equipped computer laboratory during the day.
</P>
<P>
   That led to the deal with Eureka. The company, whose main
business is wiring buildings for high-speed access to the Internet,
also planned to get into the business of running conferences and
training sessions on using new technology. During the day the space
will be operated by Eureka at the Think Tank (at) 100 William and
rented for $2,000 to $15,000 a day, depending how much of the space
is used.
</P>
<P>
   Eureka, now a company with 160 employees, raised $22 million in
venture capital last October. But when the talks with Columbia
started in the summer of 1998, it was ``three men with a business
plan,'' said Robert W. Vanech, the president.
</P>
<P>
   Brought together by officials of the Alliance for Downtown New
York, Vanech and McNeil found they shared a common view of the use
of technology and a willingness to structure an unusual deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a way to leverage Columbia's cash and wanted the
association with Columbia as a way to legitimize our business,''
Vanech said.
</P>
<P>
   The university provided $600,000 toward the $1.3 million cost of
building out the 13,000-square-foot second floor of the building.
In return, Eureka makes the space available to Columbia for an
average $22 a square foot over 10 years _ well below the market
rate.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement brings the university back to its roots
geographically. The William Street location, at the intersection
with John Street, is just a few blocks away from Trinity Church,
where the university was established in 1754 as King's College in
Trinity's schoolhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Columbia University downtown,'' McNeil said.
</P>
<P>
   But that is as far as nostalgia goes. Because of the connection
with Eureka, the space is thoroughly wired, with Internet
connections over very high capacity T-3 telephone lines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The space at 100 William St. presented a design challenge, since
it is shaped like a triangle around an atrium. Timothy Johnson, an
architect at NBBJ in New York who did the interior design, said it
apparently was originally considered to be retail space.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, there is glass on both the exterior walls and
those facing the atrium, bringing in a lot of natural light and
permitting visual contact between people in different parts of the
space. ``It's an easy place to manage _ I can see everybody,'' said
Jenny Hess, the director of what Eureka calls ``new media
conferencing.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he tried to design a visual expression of the
technology incorporated in the space. As is the fashion with many
dot-com companies, all the cables run along exposed overhead racks.
The heating and cooling duct work is also exposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything Eureka does is in a box or a wire,'' he said. ``We
wanted to give it a physical image, a place that looks as fast as
the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   A flat-panel display greets visitors at the entrance. During the
day it flashes a Eureka logo, but at night McNeil said it would be
used for academic messages, like class schedules.
</P>
<P>
   A closed ``R &AMP; D bubble'' stands to the left of the entrance.
This is used to house the latest data distribution equipment and to
direct visitors to the right, toward the combined Think Tank and
Columbia labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is enough equipment in that bubble to light up a small
town,'' said Sang Lee, Eureka's vice president for technology,
referring to fiber-optic technology. He said the bubble contained
secure power supplies, telephone and data switches, equipment to
handle video conferences and devices to handle multiple messages on
fiber-optic lines. He said the Columbia labs use about a twentieth
of the equipment's capability.
</P>
<P>
   (Those who turn left anyway would end up in space occupied by
Eureka engineers, although that could change, given the pace of the
company's growth. ``We expect to keep doubling every 60 days,''
said Vanech, the company's president.)
</P>
<P>
   The space includes two computer labs where subjects like the
C(plus sign)(plus sign) programming language and software
development for electronic commerce are taught. Each is equipped
with 25 flat-screen Dell workstations and such aids as
ceiling-mounted liquid crystal display projectors and white drawing
boards connected to a network so hand-drawn images can be stored
electronically.
</P>
<P>
   The space also includes a lecture hall that can seat 75 people
and two conference rooms, one that accommodates 18 people and
another that accommodates 10; all incorporate visual displays.
There is an informal space where students can gather before or
after classes and a long hallway known as the ``e-bar.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``e-bar'' space faces the glass wall of the atrium and is
equipped with a long, narrow table and bar-style chairs. Like most
of the rest of the space, the ``e-bar'' is fully wired, so students
can plug in their laptop computers there and connect with the rest
of the wired world.
</P>
<P>
   Less visible, but just as essential, is the additional
air-conditioning that Eureka added to supplement what was supplied
by the building and to substitute for it when the building shuts
its services down after office hours. Communications networks
operate around the clock, so services provided on a ``6 a.m. to 6
p.m.'' basis are not adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Vanech said he was planning to add other Think Tank conference
centers and has equipped the William Street space with a kitchen so
that events there can be catered. He uses words like ``hip'' and
``cool'' to describe what he is trying establish.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was also planning to get into the technology
incubator business as well. Incubator operators offer fully
equipped space to small technology companies, often in return for a
share of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to call them `Thinkubators,' '' Vanech said. He
said he expected to announce an incubator venture with a New York
real estate company in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil, the Columbia dean, said he thought the William Street
project was a good illustration of how ``the nonprofit sector can
work with the profit sector to satisfy mutual needs.'' And he said
the project built a bond between an educational institution and a
company that expected to hire students when they completed their
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at the project's development, he said the
relationship allowed him to do business in a way that might have
surprised his colleagues at Columbia's law school. ``We did it all
on a handshake,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
