<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-BUCKS-NYT &LR;      03-18 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-BUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS MOVE UP IN PLAYOFF RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When the buzzer sounded as the New
Jersey Nets and Milwaukee Bucks scrambled around for the loose ball
that was slipping off hands and through legs, Stephon Marbury
excitedly pumped his fist, making perhaps the first move of the
long and arduous game that did not seem tinged with rust.
</P>
<P>
   Following an unusual stretch of five days off that seemed to
cause the Nets to forget everything that they had learned this
season, they took the floor at the Continental Airlines Arena and
spent most of the game throwing balls into the stands and launching
shots that never came near their target.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the aesthetics of the game may not have earned the Nets
any believers, the result just might as they overcame an ugly
performance to survive with a 92-90 overtime win over the Bucks,
taking another awkward step in their improbable march to a playoff
berth. Who could argue that something strange is happening when the
Nets persevered for their first overtime win since Jan. 21, 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The win, the Nets fourth straight, moved them within two games
of the Bucks and the Orlando Magic for the eighth and final playoff
slot in the Eastern Conference and secured the tiebreaker for the
Nets against both those teams. Saturday, the Nets shrugged off the
rust just as routinely as they have moved on from the loss of
Jayson Williams and the 2-15 start that seemed destined to line up
everyone from players to management on the unemployment line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great game for us to win today,'' said Marbury, who
had 19 points and 11 assists and nearly had a dubious triple-double
as he matched a season-high with eight turnovers. ``We were really
rusty at the beginning, but those are the games you have to win. It
was very frustrating, but we got the job done. The win was the most
important thing. We all were kind of rusty and we got off to a slow
start, but eventually we picked it up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eventually would not come until the extra session as the Nets
had to struggle to force overtime. And even after they took a 91-90
lead with 2:28 to play in overtime on a 3-point field goal by
Lucious Harris, they did their best to keep the Bucks alive. Tim
Thomas, who had tied the game late in regulation by driving past
Keith Van Horn, tried again, but misfired this time with 15 seconds
left.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn grabbed the rebound and was fouled with 10.2 seconds
left. He made the first free throw, but missed the second that
would have given the Nets a 3-point lead. But they got a reprieve
when Jamie Feick tapped the errant shot out near midcourt where
Kendall Gill ran the loose ball down. Gill was fouled with 7.2
seconds to play, and the 72.4 percent shooter missed both free
throws for what he claimed was the first time in his career, giving
the Bucks the ball and one more chance with 5.2 seconds remaining. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But, playing as little like a contender as the Nets, Glenn
Robinson slipped as he caught the inbounds pass. He pushed the ball
out to Sam Cassell, but the former Nets' desperation three-point
attempt caught the front side of the rim and went to the floor
where the clock expired as neither team, fittingly, could pick the
ball up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were extremely rusty,'' Gill said. ``We weren't doing half
the things we normally do. But it was defense in the end and the
belief in ourselves that we could win towards the end. They played
a great game. We just gutted it out. I wouldn't even say we had
more will than them. The ball just bounced our way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, who led the Nets with 27 points on 10-of-16 shooting,
added: ``That was unbelievably big, in terms of standings, in terms
of confidence coming off the five days off, and also in terms of
the tiebreakers because this was another tiebreaker game for us, a
crucial tiebreaker and it a great win. ``We didn't play great
tonight. It was definitely an ugly win. But we played solid defense
and that's what carried us because our offense definitely wasn't
there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In regulation, the play may have been worse. The Nets trailed by
four points with less than a minute to play, but Marbury closed the
gap to one when he drove the lane and flipped in a reverse layup,
turning it into a three-point play with 55.7 seconds to play. One
free throw by Feick tied the score and then the Nets moved in front
when Ray Allen missed badly on a drive and fouled Harris on the
battle for the rebound. Harris hit a pair of free throws with 16.5
seconds left to give the Nets a two-point lead.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Nets then gave up a far too easy layup to Thomas as the
New Jersey native drove from the top of the circle, blowing past
Keith Van Horn and over Feick with 12.7 seconds to play in
regulation. Marbury then isolated Sam Cassell up top for one final
shot, but as he got in the lane, his shot bounced off the back of
the rim as time expired. ``What do you want us to do, give it
back?'' Nets coach Don Casey said. ``It wasn't very effective at
times. The layoff did affect us to some extent. You could sense it,
but they hung in there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
