<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1151 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-LAWS-JAKE-2TAKES-KAN &LR;      03-18 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWS-JAKE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED `JAKE'S LAW' JUST ONE EXAMPLE OF EFFORT TO CHANGE LAWS
AFTER A TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYANIKA SAMUELS and RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ``Megan.'' ``Amber.''
``Stephanie.'' ``Jessica.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   These common names have prompted uncommon political activism
because of the tragic stories that accompany them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake'' may be next.
</P>
<P>
   Gina Gerdes said she cried for a week after reading about Jake
Robel, the 6-year-old Independence boy dragged to his death last
month in a car theft.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rayville woman's grief turned to anger when she learned
that Kim L. Davis, the man accused of killing Jake, had been
released from jail by mistake hours before the crime. Authorities
failed to check and discover that Davis had an outstanding warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Days later Gerdes met Kim Thomason of Lee's Summit on the
Internet. And like many people before them, they decided to take
action.
</P>
<P>
   The two wrote ``Jake's Law'' and have been pushing to make it
federal law. The proposal would require police to check for
warrants before releasing inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sit around as a concerned citizen and as a mother
and watch this happen to anyone again,'' Thomason said. ``It was
time to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   High-profile tragedies often compel people to seek change in a
system they believe failed them. This compulsion can propel the
crusaders for years until that change happens.
</P>
<P>
   Only then is the appetite for change satiated. Only then do
those involved feel that something good has come from otherwise
horrifying news.
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Megan's Law.''
</P>
<P>
   Megan Kanka, 7, was raped and murdered in 1994 by a neighbor,
Jesse Timmendequas. Her parents, who lived in a small New Jersey
town, had no idea that Timmendequas was a twice-convicted
pedophile.
</P>
<P>
   They channeled their grief into a campaign for laws to notify
residents when a sex offender moved into their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1996, President Clinton made that proposal law. At the
signing ceremony in the Oval Office, Megan's mother said her
daughter's death now had some meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Gerdes and Thomason are hoping to do the same for Jake. Though
police routinely check inmates' backgrounds for outstanding
warrants, there is no actual law. ``Jake's Law'' would make the
practice a federal requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Christy Robel, Jake's mother, said her family fully supported
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just incredible what they're doing,'' she said. ``Policy
and procedure is not good enough. Nobody is held liable when it's
just policy and procedure, but somebody will if it is a law.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushing for new legislation helps restore the feeling of control
that seems lost in the wake of a public tragedy, said Thomas
Underwood, director of the Center on Violence and Victim Studies,
at Washburn University in Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't control the fact that this tragedy happened,''
Underwood said. ``But what we can control and influence is
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the journey from pain to policy is neither swift nor smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy and Gene Schmidt of Leawood, Kan., know this all too well.
Their 19-year-old daughter, Stephanie Schmidt, was murdered by an
ex-convict and repeat sex offender.
</P>
<P>
   The Schmidts have spent the last seven years lobbying state
officials to create laws to deal with sexual predators. They have
sacrificed their careers to the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do something right, you've got to give all your time,''
Peggy Schmidt said. ``It's more time-consuming, but it's more
rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   Their work began slowly, with an appearance on a radio show a
day after their daughter's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators and other supporters helped set up a task force to
discuss ways to protect society from convicted sexual predators.
</P>
<P>
   The Schmidts trekked from their Leawood home for about four
months of meetings at the Kansas Capitol. They spent so much time
in Topeka, they decided to rent an apartment there. They gave up
their advertising business, liquidated their assets and lived off
their savings.
</P>
<P>
   They did not plan to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't do anything more to help Stephanie,'' Gene Schmidt
said. ``But we could help her sister and her friends, and that
became our motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas sexual-predator law, which permits some inmates to be
locked up for treatment after completing their sentences, was
signed nine months after Stephanie Schmidt's death. The Schmidts
also worked to pass a similar law in Missouri and now talk to
people about passing sexual-predator laws in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The Schmidts said they had found that passing laws at the state
level was easier than working on federal legislation.
</P>
<P>
   One factor is the competition among hundreds of bills.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Rep. Vicky Hartzler, a Harrisonville Republican, said
Gerdes and Thomason would have to work to make ``Jake's Law'' a
priority. It helps to assign a public tragedy to a proposed law,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is a large public outcry against a wrong, it gives
impetus to legislators to change the law in an expeditious
fashion,'' Hartzler said. ``Since this is such a visual case, it
will work in their favor.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps also to have a namesake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts a name and a face to the legislation and clearly
demonstrates the direct need for it and the impact it could have on
people,'' Hartzler said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartzler recalled voting for ``Jessica's Law'' in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Leicht, a St. Louis-area third grader, was struck and
killed when she darted in front of a school bus. The driver did not
see her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jessica's Law'' requires school buses to have ``safety arms''
that swing out in front of buses when they stop to pick up or
unload children. That forces students to arc around the bus and
stay within the driver's sight.
</P>
<P>
   Amber Hagerman, 9, was abducted from her Texas home and killed
in 1996. After her death, Arlington police created the ``Amber
Plan'' to notify the public of a child kidnapping immediately
through the media.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has been adopted in several other states including
Kansas and Missouri, where it is called the ``Amber Alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartzler is hoping that a bill named after a Cass County teen
soon will become law. She plans to re-introduce ``Stacy's Bill,''
named for 15-year-old Stacy Cox, who died in a 1995 car crash.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would increase penalty points against careless drivers
who cause an accident or death. The bill also would require
mandatory chemical testing of a driver who causes a fatal accident.
</P>
<P>
   Though having a name helps, many efforts have been successful
without it.
</P>
<P>
   For John Walsh, host of ``America's Most Wanted,'' persistence
paid.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh lobbied the federal government to address the plight of
child victims after his 6-year-old son, Adam, was kidnapped and
killed in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed two laws in the early '80s, one of which created
the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children.
</P>
<P>
   Linda and Galen Bird of Grandview did not assign their
daughter's name to their cause, either.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Bird, 20, was killed in 1992 when a car she was riding in
crashed into the end of a guardrail, which speared the car.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after her death, the family learned that the type of
guardrail that killed their daughter was known for decades to be
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of an official from the Federal Highway
Administration, the Birds started working to make guardrails safer.
States, which would have to pay to upgrade to safer guardrails,
fought the change.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sept. 30, 1994, the Highway Administration told states to
change their guardrails. In 1996, Kansas began a five-year program
to modernize highway guardrails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just knowing that we're saving lives helps,'' Linda Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where human error is the problem, however, passing more
laws will not help, said R. Chris Martin, professor of psychology
at the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Punishment is not the way to correct a social problem,''
Martin said. ``We should use incentives as opposed to the threat of
a stick. Use the carrot instead of the stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Gerdes and Thomason said they would not rest until
``Jake's Law'' became federal law.
</P>
<P>
   They have been working with U.S. Rep. Karen McCarthy, a Missouri
Democrat. A spokesman for McCarthy said last week that government
officials were still studying what steps, if any, should be taken
on the federal level.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Gerdes and Thomason's efforts got a boost when five
Missouri state representatives filed a bill to require all
correctional facilities in Missouri to do warrant checks before
releasing prisoners. Anyone failing to do so would be charged with
a Class A misdemeanor and be suspended, under the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize it could pass on the Missouri level really soon,
but we're not going to stop there,'' Thomason said. ``And if anyone
thinks we're going to shut up and go away, we're not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
