r a BC-GAMER-COMPUTER-2TAKES     03-18 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMER-COMPUTER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AREA TEEN HAS CHANCE AT $40,000 PRIZE -- PLAYING COMPUTER GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Johnathan Wendel is
on the verge of realizing many teen-agers' wildest dream _ making a
living playing computer games.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kid stuff?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. He's one of the favorites to win a $40,000 first prize
in an upcoming computer tournament in Dallas. What's more,
game.MDBO/.MDNM/ experts say they would not be surprised to see the
Lee's Summit teen make more than $100,000 this year as tournaments
grow bigger and richer.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel, 19, is one of the best computer game players in the
world. And when he plays his game of choice _ a first-person action
game called Quake 3 Arena _ he is unbeatable. Well, virtually.
</P>
<P>
   In the last half-year, Wendel has won Quake tournaments in
Missouri, Texas, Kentucky and California. In January he won the
world championship in Sweden by going 18-0. In the five months he
has been playing in tournaments, he has lost a grand total of three
games. He is so good, a computer-mouse maker wants to sponsor him _
and put his picture on its products.
</P>
<P>
   Any wonder he practices sometimes 12 to 15 hours a day?
</P>
<P>
   Competitive computer gaming has grown rapidly, thanks to the
Internet and the proliferation of home computers. Millions of
people worldwide play, and advertisers are taking notice. More and
more companies are sponsoring tournaments that offer prize money.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that hundreds of thousands of gamers follow the
competitions over the Internet, ensuring advertisers access to a
young, technology-savvy audience with loads of disposable income.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel thinks he can be one of the stars of a professional
circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have seen him play believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Johnathan in person play on four different
occasions,'' said Robert Krakhoff, the general manager of Razer, a
San Francisco company that makes precision products for serious
gamers. ``And my personal opinion is he is the top player today.''
</P>
<P>
   He will get a chance to test his abilities again April 13-16 in
Dallas when the Cyberathlete Professional League holds a $100,000
Quake 3 tournament. The tournament, which offers a record first
prize of $40,000, will feature top players from New Zealand,
Russia, South Africa, Sweden, Germany, the United Kingdom and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel is one of the early favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to be very talented at everything I do,'' he said.
``I'm just trying to be the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the best at Quake 3 is not easy. It is one of the most
popular computer games in the world. Players control futuristic
gladiators and use strategy and cunning (not to mention an arsenal
of machine guns, rocket launchers, plasma guns and other weapons)
in a game of survival.
</P>
<P>
   The game features plenty of grunts, explosions, footsteps and
countless other sounds of battle. In the game _ often played
against one or more human opponents on the Internet _ a player
moves inside any of several enclosed arenas that feature dark
corners, hallways, stairs, different levels, weapons, ammunition
and protective armor.
</P>
<P>
   Quake 3 portrays virtual violence, but Wendel said that was not
what interested him. He plays Quake for the strategy and takes
advantage of the computer option that allows him to turn off blood
and gore.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel plays in the finished basement of his father's home. He
hunches over the glowing machine, which sits on a long table under
a photo gallery of sports heroes. He plays as ``Sarge,'' a large
and menacing animated bruiser who quickly finds a weapon and begins
looking for a reason to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Using the mouse he moves forward, side to side, searching for
his opponent, gun at the ready. He runs up stairs, moves between
levels.
</P>
<P>
   He listens for an opportunity to kill an opponent who may be
right around the corner. He sets up his attack. His opponent comes
into view. Wendel is in perfect position.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may stereotype Wendel as some sort of slack-jawed
cybergoof.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be further from the truth. As a senior at Blue
Springs South High School last year, he was an honor student with a
3.71 grade-point average and captain of the tennis team. He has a
girlfriend and is an excellent swimmer, pool player, baseball and
football player. Sitting in the living room of his father's home,
Wendel seemed fit, unassuming and happy.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel is in college now at DeVry Institute of Technology.
Officially he's studying to get a job in the computer field. But
emotionally there's no secret where his real desire lies. He wants
to be a ``professional'' gamer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for sure this is going to turn into something like the
PGA (Professional Golfers' Association), where they have
tournaments all the time,'' he said. ``Eventually you will have a
set amount of people who will be on the pro tour, and everybody
will make money.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wendel, his newfound Quake experience is as exciting as
Christmas morning. He remembers the thrill less than two months ago
when Swedish tournament organizers offered to pay for his trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, that would be awesome!'' he said, his voice
steeped in youthful enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   So Wendel, who had never been overseas before, flew to
Stockholm, Sweden, by himself. In only his second tournament he
calmly conquered an international field of top players without
losing a game.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one way to get that good.
</P>
<P>
   He tweaked his computer for maximum performance, discovered
places to hide, places to avoid, when to be aggressive and when to
run away. And more important, he discovered what nearly every sound
in the game meant. Recognizing sounds can give players an advantage
by helping them keep better track of their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can be this good. Educational experts worry that
the increasing money for top game players may cause more young
people to forgo their studies to concentrate on playing games.
</P>
<P>
   But just as few people can become Kobe Bryant and star in the
National Basketball Association out of high school, they said, few
people are good enough to make a living playing computer games.
Even though Wendel plays a lot, experts note that he did not
sacrifice his schoolwork or outside activities.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, clash with his mother over playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel's parents are divorced and remarried to other people.
Wendel used to live with his mother. According to him, she disliked
the nature of the game and limited his playing time. Recently,
Wendel's mother said she had no comment about her son and his
gaming.
</P>
<P>
   Last May tensions in his mother's house reached an impasse,
Wendel said. His mother and his stepfather grounded him from his
computer for three months for staying on the computer too long, and
using a telephone line he had been told not to use to connect to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   So one day after high school, he took computer equipment he had
paid for _ his sound and video cards, his Pentium II 350 processor,
his modem and speakers _ loaded them in his Ford Explorer and drove
to his father's house.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel's father, James Wendel, knows the stereotypes of
heavy-duty gamers. But he notes his son is healthy, smart and in
college.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/``We don't know how he does it,'' he said. ``He's just a
very good boy, and we're behind him all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. Wendel has received free trips, free hotel
stays and offers of lucrative corporate sponsorship. He's also won
about $7,000 in cash prizes. The April tournament will be his first
test to see whether he can win the big money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty confident,'' he said. ``I feel ready to go. This
will be a big thing for me if I win. This will affect my whole
future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
