<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1155 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FISHER-REOPEN-KAN &LR;      03-18 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-REOPEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBIRTH OF RESTAURANT REKINDLES MEMORIES OF LADY WHO MADE IT A
LANDMARK  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   GALLATIN, Mo. _ A north Missouri
landmark that brought a modicum of gentility to this land of corn,
hogs, callused hands and sunburned necks reopened Tuesday after
being closed for three years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The McDonald Tea Room restaurant, a white structure southwest of
the Daviess County courthouse square, was crowded almost from its
opening at 11 a.m. And the crowds continued the rest of last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting calls from Utah, Illinois, all sorts of places,''
said Jean Kirkendoll, who with her husband, Bud, owns the Tea Room.
</P>
<P>
   Jean expects to attract not only the local lunch and contract
bridge crowds but also bus tours, weddings and family reunions,
plus the tourists who flock to nearby Jamesport with its Amish
customs, and the Mormons who come to the Adam-ondi-Ahman historic
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are coming,'' she said. ``The response from the minute
we started working last summer has just been unbelievable. They
were making reservations even back them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kirkendolls, who have owned the meat locker here for years,
bought the old structure from the local bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for a whole lot,'' Jean said. ``But then you should have
seen the shape it was in.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple have poured thousands of dollars into renovations,
turning the building into a reproduction of a Victorian inn with
delicate wainscoting and 18 tinkling chandeliers, tablecloths and
quilted napkins, and polished staircases and gleaming mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Virginia would be pleased,'' Jean said.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia, of course, was Virginia Prather McDonald, dead since
1969, yet still an ethereal presence in Gallatin. Those middle-age
and older still talk of her.
</P>
<P>
   In 1907 Virginia married Charles McDonald, a drummer (what
traveling salesman were called then), in Austin, Texas. They came
north to his native Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Virginia fell ill with tuberculosis, spending several
years in semiseclusion in a small house just north of the structure
that is now the restaurant, but which in those years was the home
of Charles' parents.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1920s, Virginia regained her health, her husband's
parents were dead, and the childless couple moved into the big
house. They converted part of it into an emporium, where they sold
groceries and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   They were also in debt to the tune of $8,000 _ then an absolute
fortune _ because of Virginia's illness.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Depression clamped down, Virginia had an idea.
</P>
<P>
   She would bring fine food to this place, where the standard fare
often consisted of a heap of meat and potatoes, creamed corn, white
bread for sopping up the brown gravy, big glasses of ice water and
a huge slice of pie. Farm fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia liked what she served to look nice,'' Jean said.
``Little pads of butter shaped like roses. Garnishments on the
salads like carrot curls. Her corn bread was round, not square.
She's put cheese and peas in baked potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of variety. And the portions were smaller. Not
like you'd get at a cafe. And the food, they said, was delicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia opened the Tea Room in 1931. Suddenly, in little
Gallatin, there was a place to eat with real napkins, beautiful
dishes and glassware. Women diners wore hats and white gloves, and
men dressed in coats and occasionally even wore ties.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Tea Room, the crushing economic malaise could be
pushed away. At least for the time it took to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she did,'' said Joe Snyder, 82, the former newspaper
editor here and a friend of Virginia, ``was send Charlie down to
the train depot. Back then we had the Wabash and the Rock Island.
Charlie could spot the drummer 'cause he had been one, and he'd
tell them about this place where they could get a real meal, not
the greasy-spoon kind they were used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that started it. Drummers spread the word. And before you
know it she had people piling in.''
</P>
<P>
   Other people, that new breed called motorists, talked up the
meals they had here. That brought people from St. Joseph; Des
Moines, Iowa; Omaha, Neb.; Kansas City; and points in between. For
a couple of generations in this part of the country, a trip to the
McDonald Tea Room was a high point.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did it hurt that in 1937, culinary guru Duncan Hines, author
of Adventures in Good Eating, selected the Tea Room as one of the
best restaurants in America. It was on the list for 27 straight
years.
</P>
<P>
   There were write-ups in Better Homes and Gardens magazine and in
innumerable Sunday supplements. Another bonus was that Virginia's
cookbook, How I Cook It, was chosen by the Book-of-the-Month Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia loved the publicity,'' Snyder said. ``She'd go off
and speak in New York or Chicago or down south. She was something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   R.L. Woody, who as a boy worked at a big grocery store here,
remembers a woman in flowing dresses, high-heeled shoes and
large-brimmed hats _ said to come from milliners in New York and
Paris _ floating across the square.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd tap on the store's window, and we'd go out and get the
list of what she needed for the Tea Room,'' Woody said. ``She
wouldn't come in. That wasn't for her. We'd fill the order and take
it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said Virginia's style rankled some.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some thought she was too fancy for us,'' Snyder said. ``You
know how people think _ do well, but don't do so well that you make
us look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one story that J.C. Penney, the department store
mogul, had come to Gallatin from down the road at Hamilton, Mo.,
his birthplace, and that Virginia refused service because he didn't
meet her dress code.
</P>
<P>
   ``Completely false,'' Snyder said. ``Farmers ate there all the
time. But that was the kind of story people told on her. Maybe she
was a little eccentric in her later years. To me, she was a sweet,
old lady who occasionally lived in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie died in 1951. Virginia held on 18 more years. After her
death, the Tea Room went through a succession of owners. But, said
Doris Lynn, a former cook, ``You could just see the business drop
off a little every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean, 55, said she and Bud, 57, thought long about getting into
the restaurant business. Once they made up their minds, she said,
they aimed to do it right. Jean has hired five cooks and 20 servers
and, being a good cook herself, will oversee what comes out of the
new kitchen, the only part of the structure they totally demolished
and rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have glazed ham, baked spaghetti, pork chops, steaks,
chicken, and all the nice salads and wonderful desserts Virginia
had,'' she said. ``The one thing we won't do is use raw eggs like
Virginia did. Look at her recipes and she loved to put raw eggs in
food. The state won't let you do that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The recipes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes,' Jean said. ``I've got them. I've got them all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
