<HEADER>
A1156 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-AMAZON-ECOMMERCE-2TAK     03-18 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-ECOMMERCE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIN STREETS OF AMERICA PROVIDE REAL LINKS TO INTERNET COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Arthur Valdez looks
slightly embarrassed as he picks a compact disc and a children's
book off the concrete floor of the Amazon.com warehouse he oversees
in Coffeyville, Kan.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They fell off 12 miles of conveyer superhighway whizzing at
different heights throughout the 750,000-square-foot metal cavern.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez strides purposefully up a flight of yellow metal stairs
to an intersection of conveyers. He runs the items' Universal
Product Codes under a scanner and then drops them on a conveyer.
They stop abruptly beneath a red laser beam while the computer
seems to do an ``Ah, there you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they are whisked away to different destinations, where they
will be packaged, labeled, sorted by delivery service and shipped _
all within 24 hours of the Internet click that started the process.
</P>
<P>
   To Valdez, tens of thousands of products shipped from the
11-month-old Coffeyville warehouse are on their way to a fictitious
Betty in North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to become intimate with that brown box because
unfortunately we do not have the ability to go meet our customer at
the time of delivery,'' Valdez said. ``So our customer is Betty,
who is in that brown box right now, and we need to treat her as if
this is the most important event since sliced bread.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdez has captured the essential issue facing the e-commerce
world.
</P>
<P>
   The flamboyance of e-commerce may be in Silicon Valley, but
industry experts believe the war will be won on the main streets of
towns like Coffeyville. And even dominant e-tailer Amazon, which
last year lost 44 cents for every $1 of net sales it brought in,
has yet to strike upon a profitable strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon spent $200 million developing five distribution centers
in the United States last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Infrastructure is all this mass lurking underneath the
iceberg, and it is very important. It's where your brand is either
made or broken,'' said Jim Daniell, chief executive of OrderTrust
Inc. The Boston area company operates a computer network to connect
Web merchants with suppliers and distributors. ``If people don't
get their merchandise and they are unhappy, they will tell 10
others, and those people will never come to your site.'' Keeping
customers
</P>
<P>
   When Amazon began selling books on the Internet in 1996, it
opened a modest, 93,000-square-foot warehouse at its Seattle
headquarters. Orders came in, and books were mailed out. A year
later it tripled its warehouse space by opening a second facility
on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when Amazon morphed its vision into becoming an
Internet supermarket, carrying everything from toys to band saws,
how to house and distribute millions of products became critical.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon decided it had to own its distribution to control its
destiny. Inherent in Internet shopping is the element of instant
gratification. To satisfy customers, Amazon promised it would ship
orders within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate calling them distribution centers. These are plants
where we manufacture customer delight,'' said Jeff Wilke, vice
president in charge of distribution worldwide. ``If demand for
products surges beyond the plan, we don't have to negotiate for the
attention of our provider. Many of our competitors ran into
problems doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Research showed Internet companies that were unprepared for
demand spikes in the 1998 holiday season ended up with back orders
and upset customers.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence that its investment paid off, Wilke said more than
99 percent of Amazon customers got the products they ordered in
time for the 1999 holidays. Even an order made at 8:05 p.m. Dec. 23
was delivered to Honolulu by 3:55 p.m. Dec. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's warehouse expansion ``was to ensure one thing,'' Wilke
said, ``that we would ship more orders to our customers in time for
the holiday than anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The speed of the expansion created some problems, he
acknowledged. Some products were not where they needed to be. Some
orders had to be ``split,'' meaning multiple items ordered at the
same time were shipped separately, for the same cost as a single
order.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Amazon reported $39 million in inventory costs in its
fourth quarter, or 16 percent of sales, up from 10 percent of sales
the year before.
</P>
<P>
   That was for a quarter in which it reported a net loss of $323
million, up from $46 million the year before. Amazon reported a
loss for the year of $720 million, up from $124.5 million the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Amazon is famous for being the Internet stock darling
that has yet to make a cent. Despite mounting losses, its stock
soared from $41 in August to $113 in December, adjusted for splits,
before declining in recent weeks to the $65 range. It closed Friday
at 64 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Daniell said Internet merchants had learned that there were two
factors for success: selling vast numbers and flawless execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon has been preaching that all along,'' Daniell said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Amazon have elaborate computer systems that take
orders, verify credit cards, alert warehouses, and locate, move and
track product. But Daniell said some companies were still
``sneakernetting.'' That involves taking orders through an Internet
computer system and then walking them to another computer system to
be entered for processing.
</P>
<P>
   Daniell, however, said that even low-level systems, taking
orders by e-mail or fax, could work if the right system was in
place.
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing is knowing there is a problem before
the customer does.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 2.5 percent of Internet orders just disappear,'' Daniell
said. ``If you know first that something is wrong or unavailable,
then you can contact the customer, maybe offer them an upgrade at
no charge, do something to keep them happy so you don't lose
them.'' Wants and needs
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts predict that companies like Amazon will eventually
have store locations. For now it has one of the most sophisticated
distribution systems in e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   When last year it decided to bulk up its delivery system for the
1999 holidays, there wasn't time to find perfect locations and
build new facilities, Wilke said. A computer model identified zones
close to populations and distribution centers. Amazon uses the U.S.
Postal Service for 60 percent of its deliveries and United Parcel
Service for most of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Teams then looked for existing buildings that were near the
sizes needed, in communities that had the work ethic they wanted
and that wanted them.
</P>
<P>
   That meant economic incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Coffeyville made $1 million in infrastructure improvements and
offered up to $3.5 million in cash grants based upon Amazon
employing 1,000 people a year for 10 years. The money will come
from its municipal electric company, but between this project and
the $350 million expansion of a Farmland refinery, the city has
been able to reduce rates to all of its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the technology and the 500 jobs so far, Coffeyville
leaders say Amazon has added a cache to the community of 13,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been amazing,'' said Leroy Alsup, Coffeyville city
manager. ``I don't know how you could pay for the positive exposure
to our community for something as exciting as Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffeyville had a former Golden Books warehouse for sale that
was about 450,000 square feet. Amazon added 300,000 square feet and
fitted it out with its material-handling system.
</P>
<P>
   Over the hum of machinery and beeping of forklifts, Valdez
explained the process.
</P>
<P>
   The company's central computer system directs orders to the
distribution center best equipped to handle them. Associates known
as ``pickers,'' who like all Amazon employees get stock options,
will select the items they are directed to by the computer. It
tells them which and how many items to select. Those are put in
green plastic totes and then placed on conveyers.
</P>
<P>
   Individual orders are combined in totes and go directly to an
automated shipping area. Multiple orders are combined, put on the
conveyor and dumped onto another conveyer that will sort them and
deliver them to one of thousands of chutes, where they are combined
by customer order before going to shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Items are scanned at least 17 times from the time they enter the
warehouse until they leave to make sure the consumers get what they
order, Valdez said.
</P>
<P>
   While this is still warehouse work, Amazon leaders stress to
workers that it is vital to the anticipated financial success of
the company. Managers such as Valdez have been recruited from
retailers like Wal-Mart and J.C. Penney. Warehouse pickers commute
from as far away as Tulsa, Okla., to be where virtual rubber hits
the real road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every associate on this floor is such an important part of the
process because they are the last point of contact with the
customer,'' said Emily Glassman, a spokeswoman for Amazon. ``You
just can't minimize the role that Coffeyville and the associates
here play in Amazon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
