<HEADER>
A1159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BACKTALK-AMATEURISM-N     03-18 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKTALK-AMATEURISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TALK: UP CLOSE AND PERSONAL WITH UNDER-THE-TABLE PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 Allen L. Sack, who played on Notre Dame's 1966 national
championship football team, is a professor of management at the
University of New Haven and co-author of ``College Athletes for
Hire: The Evolution and Legacy of the NCAA's Amateur Myth''
(1998).  
 By ALLEN L. SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although I grew up just outside Philadelphia, I have spent
little time in the downtown area since leaving for college in 1963.
Recently, though, my wife and I stopped to visit our son, who is a
graduate student at the University of Pennsylvania, and had an
opportunity to stroll around Center City.
</P>
<P>
   While walking down Locust Street, we came upon an elegant old
hotel, called the Warwick, that I was almost certain was the one I
had visited some 37 years earlier when I was a high school football
recruit. Given the many years that had passed, I decided to enter
the lobby just to make sure. I found a restaurant exactly where I
remembered one being and asked the headwaiter how long it had been
there. He guessed about 40 years. I then asked if he had ever heard
of Leonard Tose. When he responded that Tose has been a regular
customer for decades, I knew I had stumbled upon a significant
landmark from my past.
</P>
<P>
   When I first met Tose, I was one of the most sought after high
school quarterbacks in Pennsylvania. Tose, a trucking magnate who
would one day own the Eagles, had asked me to come to Philadelphia
to have dinner with him, and to discuss the possibility of my
accepting a football scholarship to the University of Notre Dame.
Tose was an enthusiastic Notre Dame ``subway alumnus.''
</P>
<P>
   I remember taking a train into the city. When I met Tose in the
lobby of the Warwick, he was impeccably dressed and wore what today
would be called a power tie. I had borrowed my brother's green
blazer for the occasion, and Mr. Tose, as I called him then,
remarked that it made me look as if I belonged at Notre Dame.
During dinner, we talked about my family, my educational goals and
the other colleges and universities that were recruiting me.
</P>
<P>
   When our discussion turned to finances, Mr. Tose said that if I
attended Notre Dame he would pay my travel expenses during the
school year, try to get me a summer job and help out with expenses
that my scholarship would not cover. I saw nothing particularly
unusual about these offers. After all, several universities had
already paid my travel expenses to visit their campuses, and
dinners, banquets, free game tickets and other special treatment
seemed like a normal part of the recruiting process. When I was
only in 10th grade, a recruiter offered to pay my tuition to a prep
school in Pottstown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   I ultimately attended Notre Dame on a football scholarship.
After leaving for college, I never spoke with Mr. Tose again, but
he kept his promise. Whenever I needed money, I dropped him a note.
To the amazement of my friends, a check would arrive in a week or
so. My requests were fairly modest by today's standards, averaging
several hundred dollars a year, mostly for airline tickets to get
home for holidays. He also came through on summer jobs, some of
them involving heavy labor that helped me to bulk up for my new
position as a defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the arrangement I had with Mr. Tose was a
violation of the traditional concept of amateur principles. At its
first annual convention in 1906, the National Collegiate Athletic
Association included among violations of amateurism, ``the offering
of inducements to players to enter colleges or universities because
of their athletic abilities, or supporting and maintaining players
while students because of their athletic abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   (When contacted last week, Leonard Tose, who lives in
Philadelphia, said that any assistance he provided to Sack was
``absolutely legal'' under NCAA rules.)
</P>
<P>
   If violating amateur rules is a mortal sin, Mr. Tose and I are
going to burn in hell. I should add, however, that unless God
suffers from the same historical amnesia as most modern
sportswriters, the NCAA and the college presidents it represents
are going to be right there with us. Not only did the 1906
legislation prohibit gifts from alumni and boosters, it also
prohibited financial inducements to athletes from any athletic
organization, including university athletic departments. The
principle of amateurism clearly forbids the awarding of athletic
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until 1956 that the NCAA, responding to the demands
of the burgeoning college sports industry, changed its constitution
and bylaws to allow colleges to pay the educational and living
expenses of talented athletes, many of whom had no financial need
or remarkable academic ability. This landmark decision ushered in
the era of NCAA-sponsored professionalism. In the years that
followed, the NCAA passed rules that gave coaches the kind of
control over athletes one usually associates with employment.
</P>
<P>
   When viewed in light of the historical record, the athletic
scholarship I received from Notre Dame was just as much a violation
of amateurism as the financial arrangement I had with Leonard Tose.
In other words, when the NCAA investigates what it calls ``improper
benefits,'' the issue is not amateurism but the violation of a
system of rules whose primary purpose is to enforce an
industry-wide salary cap. College athletes are already being paid;
the industry simply wants to keep tight controls on how much and by
whom.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the NCAA has used its substantial legal and public
relations resources to support the fiction that scholarship
athletes are merely amateurs engaged in sport during their free
time is obvious. If scholarship athletes were recognized as the
paid entertainers they have in fact become, the college sports
industry would be subject to unrelated business income taxes,
antitrust scrutiny and demands by players for a bigger share of the
revenue. Amateurism is the ultimate tax shelter.
</P>
<P>
   When I walked out of the Warwick Hotel the other night, I felt
more strongly than ever that it is the NCAA that should be under
investigation, not the players, agents and boosters who refuse to
accept its phony amateur code. The NCAA has evolved from being a
defender of amateur principles into an economic cartel that
cynically manipulates the concept of amateurism to serve its
financial interests. Nothing short of a class-action lawsuit by
players is likely to bring about meaningful reform.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, I will take Mr. Tose out to dinner to
celebrate; only this time, the bill is on me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1904EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1165 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-ELECTION-2NDLD     03-18 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECTION-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN NATIONALISTS LOSE PRESIDENCY AFTER HALF-CENTURY REIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to correct spelling of Lee Teng-hui in 4th graf; Lee Teng-hui
is correct)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Chen Shui-bian, an opposition politician who
long advocated Taiwan's independence, was elected its new president
Saturday, ending half a century of Nationalist rule and risking
dangerous new tensions with mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, a 49-year-old lawyer who served as mayor of Taipei and
struggled and against martial law in the 1980s, won with 39 percent
of the vote in a bitter three-way race. The Nationalist candidate
slumped to third place.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's victory, the first transition of power in Taiwan's young
democracy, was made possible by a schism in the Nationalist Party
that led one of its leaders, James Soong, to mount an independent
candidacy. Soong, a populist former governor of Taipei province,
came in second with a strong 37 percent showing; Vice President
Lien Chan, the Nationalist candidate, got just 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Chen and his Democratic Progressive Party called for
independence from the mainland, which considers Taiwan a wayward
region that must return to the motherland. The president-elect, who
will take office May 20, succeeding Taiwan's first elected
president, Lee Teng-hui, has recently moderated that position,
saying no declaration of independence is needed because Taiwan is
already sovereign.
</P>
<P>
   But Beijing has called Chen deceitful and issued dire warnings
against his election, with Prime Minister Zhu Rongji all but saying
last week that it could provoke a war.
</P>
<P>
   To reassure nervous citizens and governments abroad _ including
Washington, which has pledged to help Taiwan defend itself if
attacked _ Chen tried to reach out to the Chinese in his victory
speech Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   He avoided inflammatory references to Taiwanese ``statehood,''
and said he would seek deeper economic ties and ``a permanent
peace.'' He has promised he will not declare independence or hold a
referendum on the issue unless Taiwan comes under attack.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a statement certain to anger Beijing, he also
pledged, ``We won't let Taiwan become another Hong Kong or Macau.''
Those former colonies have been handed back to China, which has
granted them broad autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement read on Chinese television, Beijing said it
would adopt a wait-and-see attitude toward Taiwan's new leader, and
reiterated its view that Taiwan is part of Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton said he saw the election as a
demonstration of the vitality of democracy and an opportunity for
Taiwan and China to open a new dialogue.``The United States
strongly supports such dialogue and is committed to promoting
peace, stability and prosperity in the region,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some 83 percent of Taiwan's voters turned out after a campaign
dominated by worries over relations with China and public
impatience with the corrupt political practices of the
Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Chen faces a legislature still dominated by the Nationalists,
who have ruled firmly since Chiang Kai-shek retreated here from the
Communist-dominated mainland in 1949. Taiwan is in for a period of
unprecedented political reshuffling and uncertainty, even as it
faces a possible confrontation with China.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Speaking to thousands of cheering supporters, Chen declared
Saturday night that his success ``is not a victory for the
Democratic Progressive Party _ it is a victory for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a subtle friendly gesture to China and to some of his
fiercest enemies at home _ those who fled the mainland after the
Communist victory in 1949 _ Chen gave his acceptance speech in
Mandarin Chinese rather than in the Taiwanese dialect he often used
in campaign rallies.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen refuses to accept China's hallowed notion of ``One
China,'' and in answer to a question Saturday night he said China's
``one country, two systems'' formula for enlisting Taiwan as an
autonomous region ``would never be accepted by the Taiwanese
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to defend this island but we are also
determined to seek peace and stability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reassure foreign governments that he will not
take reckless actions, Chen has promised to retain the current
defense minister, top national security officials and the military
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, like 85 percent of the island's population and many
supporters of his political party, is considered an ethnic
Taiwanese, descended from people who immigrated from the mainland
centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Taiwanese resentment of the brutal takeover of their island
by Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists in the late 1940s eventually
spawned a dissident movement for democracy and independence. In the
1970s and '80s, early leaders of what would later become the
Democratic Progressive Party were imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Chen became involved as a defense lawyer for the dissidents and
then entered politics after martial law was lifted in 1987 and the
Democratic Progressives became the main opposition party. For many
of the party's supporters, Saturday night's victory is an emotional
culmination of decades of struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists, for their part, have been thrown into turmoil
and their powerful chairman, President Lee Teng-hui, is now on the
spot. Lee's feud with Soong helped cause the devastating defeat,
and the party could suffer a permanent split if the popular Soong
tries to form his own party now.
</P>
<P>
   Soong apologized to his supporters for losing, but did not say
whether he would seek to form a new party or try to take over the
Nationalist Party.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Already Saturday night, Huang Quen-huei, the secretary general
of the Nationalists, offered his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, a large crowd of Soong's supporters, most
of then longtime Nationalists who felt Lee had betrayed the party
by snubbing Soong, marched to Lee's official residence and his
party's headquarters in central Taipei to shout for Lee to step
down as party boss. Both buildings were surrounded by riot police
and there were some scuffles.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has called for public disclosure of the Nationalists'
multibillion-dollar investments and confiscation of any properties
that should belong to the state rather than the party.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen also said Saturday night that he bore no animosity
toward his campaign opponents and that he hoped to work with the
Nationalists to build a ``cross-party alliance,'' though he did not
offer specifics.
</P>
<P>
   His ability to forge a coalition will be crucial to his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chen Shui-bian's immediate challenge is that he has to act as
a president, not just a leader of an opposition movement,'' said
Chu Yun-han, a political scientist at National Taiwan University.
``Nearly two-thirds of the electorate didn't vote for him, and many
are deeply suspicious of his approach to the mainland.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeated Nationalist candidate, Lien, had used scare tactics
in the final weeks of the campaign, suggesting that Chen could
bring disaster to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night he was more gracious in conceding, calling the
transition a milestone for Taiwan's democracy. ``I hope the new
president will handle state matters properly, leading our country
into a new era,'' he said before a crestfallen line of party
leaders. ``We can still regroup. From today we need to engage in
self-examination and reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee remained silent and secluded in his residence, where he
summoned the military chief of staff and the defense minister.
There have been reports here of Chinese troop movements on the
mainland, although no one expects imminent military action.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's victory reflected, in part, a demographic trend that
bodes ill for the Nationalists and also for China's hope of
peaceful reunification: many younger people have no allegiance to
the Nationalist Party their parents long served, and think of China
as a distant concept.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first presidential election in 1996, more than 1
million young people became eligible to vote, Chu noted. And fully
half of them said in recent surveys that they were voting for Chen,
who is seen as representing youthful energy and cleaned-up
politics.
</P>
<P>
   China's military threats do not intimidate such people. A
typical example is Yang Jie-lung, a 27-year-old graphic designer.
Approached Saturday morning as he left the polling booth, he would
not discuss his preferences until his mother, a lifelong
Nationalist, was out of earshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Chen Shui-bian can win,'' he said. ``He's the best one
to clean up the problems left by the Nationalists, and as mayor he
did a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the mainland's dark warnings, he said: ``We are not
obliged to take any advice from China. We are electing our own
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in Lee's hometown of Sanchi, northwest of Taipei, voters
rebuffed the president's plea to keep the Nationalists in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I listen to Lee Teng-hui?'' asked Pan Yue-ching,
38, a homemaker. ``I have my own opinions.'' The voters also
appeared unimpressed with the threats from China. ``It's always the
same between these two countries,'' said Lee Fung-lin, also 38 and
an unemployed restaurant worker. ``They just shout at each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
