<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING READY TO TAKE ON SHAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ It was 1994 when Shaquille O'Neal was spitting
his first rap lyrics into a microphone and gripping the endorsement
world as tightly as a Pepsi in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the unglamorous Patrick Ewing took it all in.
Mostly, he was silent as his place as the East's most dominating
center was being threatened by the 7-foot neophyte who once asked
within Ewing's earshot: Who's the man?
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels he's the man,'' Ewing responded in February of 1994.
``I feel he's not the man, not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is indisputable. Although the pop-culture hype has since
faded, O'Neal is the leading man in the NBA. With an earth-moving
body built by Caterpillar, O'Neal dominates everyone on every night
as the looming star of Hollywood's team, the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has no illusions about this fact. Although he is prodded
by the challenge of facing O'Neal and the league's best team at
Madison Square Garden Sunday, he knows what a nearly impossible
task it will be to get the best of O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq is going to get his points,'' Ewing said Saturday after
the Knicks practiced at SUNY-Purchase. ``I just want to slow him
down. I'm just going to play my game.''
</P>
<P>
   He can still hit the fade-away jumper. He can still whirl
through the lane on a vintage runner. Six years, and two
career-threatening injuries since O'Neal caught Ewing's attention,
the Knicks' aging center is still standing as an example of just
how pride can be turned into a miracle drug.
</P>
<P>
   No one knew what Ewing had to give when he returned from his
Achilles' tear 20 games into this season. It was hard to know what
was going on inside of him. He had been aloof, felt unappreciated
and pouted during his rehab. Members of the organization wondered
if his dark mood was really a manifestation of his fear that
everyone was right, that maybe he did not have a reserve of star
power left in his 37-year-old body.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, Ewing has displayed proof that he still has
tread on the tires and a cashmere touch in his fingertips. It is
not the mid-'90s, but Ewing is averaging an impressive 14.6 points
and 10 rebounds a game. To him, there is nothing remarkable about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Robert Parish at 37 or 38
still kicking my butt,'' Ewing said. ``So, I'll just let other
people worry about what's left. As long as I feel I still have the
skill, I'll play. I mean, I'm not as athletic as I was a few years
ago, but if I knew the things that I know now when I was younger,
forget Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. But one thing that has not changed: Ewing's
confidence is still as stubborn as a grass stain. Inside, Ewing
probably has hopes of luring O'Neal into foul trouble and has
visions of popping jumpers outside his reach. It would not be like
Ewing if he didn't think he had a response for O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is pride in every game, not just this one,'' Ewing said.
``When you play against people who are supposed to be the best, you
want to play at your best. I've been that way my whole life.
There's nothing that's going to change. I mean Shaq's a great
player, and he's having a great year. Naturally, I want to play at
my best Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   In 19 games against O'Neal as a member of the Magic and with the
Lakers, Ewing has won just seven of them. Over that span, Ewing has
shot 45 percent while O'Neal has hit 54 percent of his attempts.
Ewing has averaged 26.3 points and 11.6 rebounds to O'Neal's 27.6
points and 12.3 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two ends of the court,'' an undaunted Ewing said.
``I have to make him work on defense just as much as he's going to
make me work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's work ethic is unquestioned. Without it, he would not
have made it back from two devastating injuries. Without it, he
would not stand a chance of countering O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think in these type of games, one, Patrick does have
great pride,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``Two, he does get
himself ready. And three, great players play well against the best.
And O'Neal, without a doubt, is the most dominant player in the
league. Patrick's going to give it his best.
</P>
<P>
   If he is not a factor, the Knicks' chances of taking down the
best team in basketball _ and gaining confidence should they ever
meet the Lakers in the finals _ will grow dimmer by the minute.
Maybe Ewing's not ``The Man'' anymore, but he is still a factor
after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could still play,'' Ewing said. ``The naysayers said
I couldn't play. I don't care what nobody else says or writes just
as long as I feel I can go out there and produce. I have one more
year on my contract, and then I'll see if I want to play at that
time. Right now, I'm enjoying this one and I'm trying to do the
best job I can. I'm trying to get to the championship and hopefully
win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still playing, I'm still productive. And regardless of the
injuries, I'm still a great player. Even though I don't have the
athletic ability I had younger, I'm still a great player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
