r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN     03-18 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON DIDN'T NEED NEW YORK `HASSLES'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - One way or another, Phil Jackson would have a chance
to return to the NBA Finals this season. If not in his role as
Lakers coach, then possibly in some undefined role with today's
opponent, the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and the Knicks discussed employment a year ago, during
the season, igniting controversy amid speculation he was angling
for coach Jeff Van Gundy's job. All that became moot once the
Knicks made the Finals, and Jackson was hired by the Lakers in
June.
</P>
<P>
   But he said his discussions of a job here ``never got defined to
any level. It was just initial kind of talks.'' And Jackson said
there wasn't much temptation to return to the organization he
played for and won a championship with.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you don't fantasize about things like that,'' he said.
``The idea of living in New York is the reality. If you go work for
an organization, you live in a community. And that's a reality, New
York has its own set of positives and negative things that you have
to deal with as a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``And having been there, understood it, understood the press,
the type of life that you have to live, all those things, there's a
lot of intrigue about living in New York.... And the aspect of
having a life that's full of hassles, just one thing after another
about living there, that makes (it necessary) to have a certain
temperate course to kind of go through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said any bond he had with the Knicks has faded since he
left the team in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nobody in the organization even that was there
when I was there,'' he said. ``But it's still the same faces in the
city and the Garden. And the fans and the community is still the
same. It's one of those things where if you walk down the streets
and you played on a championship team, people still recognize
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Of greater intrigue for Jackson is the game itself, a matchup
that pits the defending Eastern Conference champions against the
favorites to win the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playoff-potential opponents if we can ever make it
that far,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rice rises: After a six-point game against Sacramento last
Sunday, Glen Rice has rediscovered his touch again. After an
8-for-12, 19-point game at Detroit, he's averaging 20.3 points on
23-of-42 shooting (54.8 percent) over the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going out there and I'm focused, trying to do the
things I know I can do,'' he said. ``Just trying to keep my mind
free. I'm planning on staying in that zone. A lot of times when I
miss a couple, I go thinking about it too much. I'm just trying to
get back to the basics, go out there, play hard, the shot goes in,
it goes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq attack: When Shaquille O'Neal scored 40 points against
Denver and Washington, he became the first Laker to do so in
consecutive games since Jerry West in February of 1970. O'Neal
could have hit the 40 mark a third straight game, but he settled
for 35 points in 36 minutes Friday at Detroit, before Jackson
pulled him.
</P>
<P>
   West was also the last Laker to score 40 or more in three
straight games, in January of 1965.
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff: 9 a.m., Madison Square Garden
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Channel 4; KLAC-AM (570)
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (54-12) update: Their last extended road trip of the
season concludes with an imposing back-to-back set of games - the
Knicks today and Miami Heat on Monday. The Lakers are 23-3 against
the Eastern Conference, 11-2 on the road vs. the East.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks (40-24) update: After being upset by Washington in
overtime March 8, they've won four straight, including victories
over San Antonio and Charlotte. The Knicks finally returned to full
strength when Marcus Camby was activated last week.
</P>
<P>
   - Howard Beck
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
