<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTERS COULD BE TAKEN EARLY IN NBA DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We interrupt the NCAA Tournament to assess the
level of evil it will visit upon the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's a lie. We're here to discuss how great big centers
are disappearing from the league's landscape like fans from the
fourth quarter of a Clippers game. But let's take a moment to whine
about the NCAA's refusal to prevent its participants from playing
defense with their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The lane has become the scene or more silently sanctioned
grabbing than the back seat on prom night.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why the centers aren't developing.
</P>
<P>
   That was dandy attempt at segue, but also a failure.
</P>
<P>
   No, we can trace the absence of pivot phenoms to a sociological,
hip-hop paradigm that suggests it is very, uh, whack to play with
your back to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Let's play with our backs to some numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA's Eastern Conference, the short list has become too
long for the paper. Of the conference's 15 teams, 11 boast starting
centers who stand 6-foot-10 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Of the league's 29 starting centers, a dozen were born outside
the United States. Of the 17 starting centers who had their
umbilical cords snipped on American soil, only six (if you count
Elden Campbell, a longtime power forward) stand at least 6-11.
</P>
<P>
   So, perhaps we're experiencing a trend that features the big
center as something to be placed behind the Soloflex in your
storage room.
</P>
<P>
   Good premise, bad execution.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Eastern Conference's top three teams start 7-foot
pivots, and the third - Miami - starts Alonzo Mourning, a
card-carrying monster center who just happens to check in at a mere
6-10.
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference, the four top teams - including the
Lakers and large, MVP citizen Shaquille O'Neal - all start 7-foot
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Where can general managers score a few more big lads?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the NBA Draft 2000 could feature four centers among the
top eight selections. The No. 1 pivot suspect is Chris Mihm, a 7-0
junior from Texas who is threatening to remain a Longhorn for his
senior season. Close behind is junior Loren Woods, a 7-1,
slot-blocking fiend from Arizona whose back has eliminated him from
tournament play.
</P>
<P>
   He's expected to make a full recovery, but insiders can't get a
feel for his interest in the draft; he'd probably be selected in
the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Our next candidates are Joel Przybilla, a 7-1 sophomore who
ditched the University of Minnesota midway through the Big Ten
campaign, and 7-0 North Carolina junior Brendan Haywood.
</P>
<P>
   Przybilla already has an agent, Bill Duffy (Michael Olowokandi),
but has yet to hire an offensive game. Haywood, who had 28 points
and 14 rebounds in Friday's bullying of little Missouri, goes about
270, which makes his skill for completely disappearing at
inopportune moments even more amazing.
</P>
<P>
   If the enigmatic Haywood leaves UNC, some team in need of a
center will choose him fairly soon, inspiring a collective sigh
from those GMs who didn't want to select him but might have,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Wild cards who could creep up from the last third of the first
round are two players whose names appeared in this column weeks
ago: Iakovos Tsakalidis, a 7-1, 21-year-old who plays for AEK of
the Greek League, and 7-2 Soumaila Samake, the 22-year-old center
for the Cincinnati Stuff of the IBL.
</P>
<P>
   Samake, the IBL's reigning player of the week, has been
described as a bouncier version of Dikembe Mutombo. He had 15
points, 17 rebounds and 4 blocks in one game last week; most scouts
compare IBL competition to that of a mid-major NCAA Division I
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Schea it ain't so
</P>
<P>
   Local hero Schea Cotton, who's been through more schools than
McGruff the Crime Dog, has left the University of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   If you had ``less than one year'' in the office pool, you're the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Schea's latest maneuver may be miles less than shocking,
but he did list a serious reason for leaving the Crimson Tide. His
father, James Cotton, Sr., has prostate cancer; the former Bosco
Tech and Long Beach City College ace, who according to scouts was
considering a hop to the NBA, anyway, has returned to the L.B.
area.
</P>
<P>
   One independent scouting service rates the 6-5 Cotton as the No.
6 shooting-guard prospect regardless of class as a suggestion to
NBA people who may think differently. Of course, this service also
ranks DePaul sophomore Quentin Richardson No. 1, ahead of Fresno
State's Courtney Alexander, Cincinnati's 6-9 freshman DerMarr
Johnson and Morris Peterson of Michigan State; Richardson won't be
chosen ahead of those guys unless they are abducted by creatures
from outer space. Abducted and not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton, according to three real NBA scouts we contacted, may
slip into the second round of this year's draft if other aspiring
college evacuees declare as expected. But the same scouting
characters think Alabama freshman Rod Grizzard, a 6-8 swingman with
a tight handle, 3-point range and no public inclination toward
leaving school after one season, could be a late lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   It's not news that the NBA has been Schea's goal, so we wish him
luck. And our best to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   With Donald T. Sterling making the final call, attempting to
roll logic into the Clippers' process of hiring a permanent head
coach is a waste of time. So let's waste it. According to Larry
Brown observers, the current Sixers and former Clips coach recently
sold his home in Malibu. Another tasty rumor involves ex-Cavalier
coach Mike Fratello, who does not have a fan in Elgin Baylor, the
Clippers' VP of basketball operations. This doesn't eliminate him
from Sterling's interest, but Sterling's predictable reluctance to
match Fratello's TV-analyst salary probably does. Four Clippers who
are signed through next season say they'd like to see current
assistant coach Dennis Johnson slide over to the big chair when
that time comes. ... Picked up on the radar of NBA scouts was news
that Eddie Griffin, maybe the nation's top high school senior, was
suspended from Roman Catholic High in Philly for his role during an
on-campus fight. But the school will allow Griffin to complete his
course work at home and graduate; East Coast sources also say the
6-8 Griffin intends to honor his commitment to Seton Hall. For at
least one season. ... The list of college seniors expected to show
off at the Portsmouth (Va.) pre-draft camp (April 5-8) includes
Long Beach State's Mate Milisa, the Big West Player of the Year.
... If the NBA wanted to score ratings points, it should have
slipped a microphone on J.R. Rider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 1936EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
