r s BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     03-18 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS TRIES TO STEAL CREDIT FOR RAPTORS' RISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ It's not enough that Isiah Thomas has been a
woeful announcer and studio analyst for NBC since joining the
network. Now, he seems intent on using his national podium to
rewrite history, and secure a new job for himself in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas infuriated the Toronto Raptors this week by trying to
take partial credit for the incredible success the team is enjoying
this season, saying his long-term planning as general
manager/part-owner was a reason Toronto has become a surprise
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate that NBC lets (Thomas) have the platform to put out
incorrect information,'' Raptors coach Butch Carter said. ``I don't
know why he's doing it. For some reason, he needs to take credit
for what has gone on here and I think that's a little broad for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, if Thomas had any inkling of how successful the
Raptors would become, he would not have left Toronto 2 1/2 years
ago during an unmemorable 16-66 season.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't trade for Vince Carter. He didn't trade for Antonio
Davis. He didn't stick around to nurture Tracy McGrady.
</P>
<P>
   There was little evidence the Raptors would ever surge toward
the top of the league when Thomas quit. If anyone is responsible,
it's Butch Carter and Raptors general manager Glen Grunwald.
</P>
<P>
   Besides having the sense to acquire Vince Carter, they convinced
Charles Oakley to re-sign and were sensible enough to hold on to
McGrady before the trade deadline despite a deluge of offers from
among other teams, the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But if Thomas said this, he wouldn't be able to push himself as
a viable candidate to run and coach another basketball team. His
name surfaced briefly in Dallas, and now he is being touted as the
leading candidate to replace Lenny Wilkens in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't want to hire him, if they believed any of his TV
comments?
</P>
<P>
   Tempting offer: Celtics coach Rick Pitino offered to step down
as coach in a secret meeting with owner Paul Gaston last week,
according to the Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   But Gaston, who owes Pitino four more years on his contract,
said he supported his coach and refused to accept the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Wish lists: Clippers guard Derek Anderson has put the Denver
Nuggets near the top of his list of teams that he will considering
signing with after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about it a whole lot,'' Anderson said. ``They are
one of the top teams. I have to be in a situation where I fit.
Right now, it's my choice and I can go where I want.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Maurice Taylor, he has narrowed his list to four teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have family in Orlando, so Orlando would be a spot I'd like
to go to,'' Taylor said. ``Detroit, which is my hometown and
Indiana and New York. Those are the places I'm thinking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Love'em and Hate'em: Miami Heat fans are nothing if not intense.
An Internet poll conducted by the Palm Beach Post asked readers how
far the Heat can go in the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven percent said the Heat would win the NBA title. But
38 percent said the Heat would be ousted in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Triangle troubles: It's easy to get caught up in the hype
surrounding the triangle offense, when Michael Jordan, Kobe Bryant
or Shaquille O'Neal are running it, but Bulls coach Tim Floyd has
had just about enough of the holdover formation from Phil Jackson's
reign in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may drop the triangle,'' Floyd said. ``It depends on who we
draft and which free agents we sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: It's outta here.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bulls veteran Will Perdue endorsed a new offensive
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty with the (triangle) is that all five guys on
the floor have to make the same read or see the same thing,''
Perdue said. ``That very rarely happens. I don't think this is an
offense for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   What's he thinking? The return of San Antonio's Sean Elliott,
the first pro athlete to return from an organ transplant, was a
heartwarming story this week, but not everyone welcomed the Spurs
forward back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the dumbest things I've ever heard,'' Dallas coach
Don Nelson said. ``He had a perfect scenario for going out as a
champion. Why the need to come back, I question it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson relented, and said he would support Elliott's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I love the guy to death. All that said, if that's the way
he wants to live his life. I'm happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson should know something about disregarding common sense and
refusing to retire well before you wear out your welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The future is . . . dim: Utah forward Karl Malone isn't exactly
cheerful when he thinks about how the NBA will look after he and
some of the other older stars retire in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here are some young superstars on the rise now, but after
awhile, people ain't even gonna want to go watch games,'' Malone
told Penthouse magazine. ``I believe that. You know what the
quality of the game is going to be? Gimme the ball, don't worry
about a pick, we'll go one-on-one and break (the other guy) down
and dunk so we can be on SportsCenter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
