<SLUG> BC-BKC-SETON-DALEMBERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTER'S LESSONS FROM GIRLS VOLLEYBALL
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ When he was a boy growing up in Haiti, Samuel
Dalembert took school trips and played games with a ball. It was
not a basketball, as it is now when Dalembert plays center for
Seton Hall. It was a volleyball and he learned important skills
from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to play volleyball with the girls on the beach,''
Dalembert said Saturday after his team practiced in preparation for
Sunday's game against Temple. ``They used to tell me what to do.
They'd turn the ball to me and I'd just smack it to the other side.
That was exciting. Even though shot-blocking is hard to do, it is
really exciting. It's kind of like playing volleyball.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalembert, a 6-foot-11 freshman, used this technique well in the
first game of the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament against Oregon on Friday. He blocked six shots as the
Pirates beat the Ducks, 72-71, in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The clinching shot, Shaheen Holloway's layup after a
floor-length run, was the highlight that made the newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   Dalembert could be seen in the corner of the TV screen, blocking
out his man and clearing the path for Holloway. And Dalembert was
important in other ways, pulling down 12 rebounds, scoring six
points and staying out of foul trouble until near the conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's first game, Oklahoma State will play Pepperdine.
Sunday's two winners will go to Syracuse next weekend as members of
the Sweet 16 for the regional finals. Sunday's second game is
partly a match of guards _ Holloway for Seton Hall, Pepe Sanchez
for Temple. It is also a match of coaches: John Chaney, the wise,
old Owl of Temple against Tommy Amaker, the young Buccaneer leading
the Pirates. But another important matchup will be among the big
men on the forward lines.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney said his players didn't have the quickness or mobility of
Dalembert, who weighs only 232 pounds and loves to leap, and looks
as long and lean as a numeral ``1'' on his back. But Chaney does
have big guys like centers Ron Rollerson, at 6-10 and 290, and
Kevin Lyde, at 6-9 and 240. ``I'm going to try to put two of them
in there and see if we can't make a sandwich out him,'' Chaney
said, referring to Dalembert. Lyde predicted ``a lot of banging,
physical play, elbows thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he is 18 years old and a year out of high school,
Dalembert is still a work in progress and his game has flaws. He
tends to get fouls in bunches and that puts him on the bench. On
attack, his hands are not the softest. Occasionally, he will
accidentally spike passes from teammates. But they admire his
skills, like his personality and predict great things. Holloway and
Rimas Kaukenas, the senior co-captains, know as guards what
Dalembert can do to opposing shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody gets intimidated when you shoot a mid-range jumper
and it gets blocked,'' Kaukenas said. ``That's a big plus for us.
He's done a terrific job, especially for him being so young and
adjusting to college basketball so quick.'' Holloway said Dalembert
contributes away from the court to the team mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great sense of humor,'' Holloway said. ``He's a
silly, young clown at times, which I love. The team needs the sense
of humor that he brings.'' As for Dalembert's skills, Holloway
said: ``If we don't have him this year, we're not where we are now.
When Sam comes ready to play, I don't think there's any big guy in
the country who can match him. He's still raw. He's still young.
Once he gets his offensive skills with his defensive skills, he's
going to be a No. 1 draft pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Amaker hopes that won't be for three more years, long after next
year's recruiting class arrives and ripens. ``If he picks up early
fouls, we're scrambling right away,'' Amaker said of Dalembert.
``He changes the game for us. He blocks shots. He can rebound. He
can run. A times, he can be an offensive weapon down low. We need
his presence. Our players are much more confident with him on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dalembert, a self-confident person, said he planned to stay
free of fouls, play many minutes, and use his quickness to
counteract the Temple bulk while establishing the transition game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make them go up and down the floor and everything will be
good,'' Dalembert said. ``They've got big guys and we've got skinny
guys. I'll use my quickness to not let them get the ball inside too
deep. I'm not nervous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
