<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BAYHILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE WILL BE TRYING TO CATCH WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The lead still belonged to Tiger Woods, but the
day belonged to Davis Love III.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the third round six strokes behind Woods, and in danger
of falling out of contention, Love played his best round of the
year Saturday, putting together an impressive display of power and
finesse that caught everyone's attention at the Bay Hill
Invitational. Love made two eagles, six birdies, and chipped in
twice. And he put himself in position to challenge the world's No.
1 player in a Sunday showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Tying the course record in relation to par, Love shot a 9-under
63 and closed to within two strokes of Woods heading into Sunday's
final round. Woods, who shot 67, was 16-under for the tournament
(200), two strokes ahead of Love (14-under), and six strokes ahead
of Mike Weir (10-under), who made a costly double-bogey at No. 18
when his tee shot sailed out of bounds. Love's score was the first
63 at Bay Hill since 1997, when Stuart Appleby shot 63 in the
second round. Andy Bean and Greg Norman have both shot 62 at Bay
Hill, but that was when the course was a par 71.
</P>
<P>
   Like talent rising to the top, Woods and Love distanced
themselves from the field, setting the stage for a Sunday that will
test Love both mentally and physically. Woods has beaten Love
soundly in recent head-to-head encounters, including last month at
the Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship, when Woods spanked
Love, 5 and 4, in the semifinals. Love is still ranked No. 4 in the
world, but he has not won in almost two years, since the 1998 MCI
Classic. Will Love turn the tables and end Woods' dominance? Love
admitted he was eager to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody starts beating you, you start thinking, `Can I beat
him?,''' said Love. ``He thrives on that. Coming down the stretch,
he's not only going to play good, but the other guy is not going to
play as well because he's trying too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player. He's driving the tour now the way Jack
Nicklaus did, and Arnold Palmer, Tom Watson, whoever. We've got to
learn how to compete with him. Somebody has got to knock him down
in the dirt and make him think that he can lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Love will have a difficult task, not only trying to beat
Woods, but trying to win a tournament that has haunted him with
unhappy endings. Love has never won at Bay Hill, but he has
suffered many close calls, finishing second twice, and third last
year. For Love to win the tournament hosted by Palmer, and to beat
Woods in the process, would be memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great,'' said Love. ``But honestly, it would be
nice to win anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Woods wants to win everywhere, and his ability to close
tournaments has been a hallmark of his remarkable career. He has
won the last 12 times that he has either held or shared the lead
after third round of a tour event. Woods was beaten by Darren
Clarke in the Andersen Consulting championship match, but as Love
said, ``It doesn't look like it has shaken his confidence any.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods still had the lead. And he didn't plan to lose it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a big believer that they have to come and get
me,'' said Woods. ``That's the philosophy I've always had. The more
difficult the golf course, the better that philosophy works.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods was red-hot with his putter Saturday, using it to either
make birdies, or to make key par saves. In a round that included
six birdies and just one bogey, Woods made a 30-footer for par at
No. 11, a 20-footer for par at No. 16, and he made a 12-footer to
save par on No. 13 and a 10-footer to save par on No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Love was hot with every club in his bag. His highlights
included a 30-foot putt for birdie at No. 1 and a 50-footer for
birdie at No. 11. Then on No. 12, Love chipped in from 25 feet
behind the hole for eagle, then he pitched in from 40 feet for
birdie at No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Love was at 12-under, two strokes behind Woods,
who was playing nine groups behind. Love momentarily tied Woods at
14-under with an eagle at the par 5, 517-yard No. 16, when Love
reached the green with a driver and a 5-iron, then made a 12-foot
putt. However, Woods recaptured his two-stroke lead with birdies at
No. 12 and No. 16, setting the stage for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While Woods seems to win almost every month, Love believes he
should win more often. Love will be 36 years old next month, and he
does not want to let more opportunities slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've let a lot slip away the past couple of years,'' said
Love. ``And when Tiger is winning every other week, it's hard to
find your week. He's the No. 1 player in the world. There's no
getting around that. How do you perform when you play against him
is the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Love would learn a little more about himself Sunday, in another
chance to measure himself against the best. But with two wins
already this year, and the only player in the tournament with three
rounds in the 60s, Woods liked his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd rather be in the lead than behind,'' said Woods. ``If I
go out and make 18 consecutive pars, they are going to have to
shoot under par to beat me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
