u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-GOODWILL03     03-18 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-GOODWILL0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves supply Venezuela relief
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Onlookers have described the bare brown
marks left from the December mudslides on the mountains near this
city as tiger scratches.
</P>
<P>
   And that is truly how it looks, like giant claws have marred the
vegetation, leaving bare, raw reminders of the tens of thousands of
people who died in this country in December and the 150,000 left
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   But for a few hours on Saturday, there was another sort of
``Cat'' scratching going on and it was the soothing kind.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' Andres Galarraga, returned home for two exhibition
games against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, along with teammates Eddie
Perez, Fernando Lunar and Devil Rays Miguel Cairo and Wilson
Alvarez, rode through those mountains to deliver relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
   They traveled to LaGuaira, a town along the Venezuelan coast 25
miles north of Caracas, where the floods were most devastating.
</P>
<P>
   In the early afternoon before Saturday's game, they delivered
10,000 pounds of medicine, food and supplies to a refugee camp,
along with plenty of good cheer.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he left the hotel to when he returned more than
three hours later, people flocked to Galarraga's side, smiling,
waving, asking for autographs, taking pictures, reaching for a
touch.
</P>
<P>
   As the van rode along the highway, peoples' faces lit up as they
realized who was in the caravan with its own police escort. The
trip took an hour, through the congestion of downtown Caracas to
the more peaceful countryside, where mountains were dotted with
makeshift brick homes stacked on top of each other.
</P>
<P>
   The vans passed through a tunnel which had been flooded and
blocked by mud only months before and emerged to a backdrop of the
sea and Venezuela's international airport.
</P>
<P>
   A few turns later, the vans climbed slowly up a bumpy dirt road
past waving children, to what once was an office building in the
making, now temporary home to 435 families.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter, which is run by the Venezuelan Red Cross, has
cinder block floors, with only sheets of plastic protecting each of
the ``homes'' from each other and the outside. There is no running
water.
</P>
<P>
   As Galarraga got out of the van in his dress pants and shirt,
sunglasses, Braves baseball cap and smile, he was flanked by
teammates and reporters, and soon after children and adults alike.
</P>
<P>
   As he began his walking tour of the shelter, he was joined by
12-year-old Juan Jose Mendez, who said ``Hola!'' to Galarraga and
then smiled and said ``Hola!'' into one of the TV cameras. He told
Galarraga what a good ballplayer he was and how he loves to watch
him play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fantastic person and very helpful to his community,''
Mendez said through translator Jose Martinez, special assistant to
Braves general manager John Schuerholz. ``I feel like he's a part
of my family. When he comes here, he brings peace to all the
families. It's a big emotion to have Galarraga come and bring help.
We appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes after a presentation was made and the players had
addressed the crowd and signed countless autographs, they loaded
back into the vans. Galarraga opened his window briefly to give a
few autographs. He took off his Braves cap, put it on a toddler and
then waved goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for them man,'' Galarraga said. ``We need to find
them homes, something. At least I feel better that we got some food
to them. So many young people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see it in their faces they were happy to see us,''
Perez said. ``I wish I could do more than that. If a lot of people
do what we did, it'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
