r s BC-BBN-KARROS-LADN     03-18 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KARROS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS SURVIVES WITH STRONG WORK ETHIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. - You can trace the origins of Eric Karros'
success back as far as you want. The sweat-filled days in
greenhouse-like batting cages of the minor leagues, or the
sacrificing of fraternity parties to work on his stroke when he
attended UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   But for Karros, the work ethic that's brought him a nine-year
major-league career began when he cut down a raggedy net while
attending Patrick Henry High in San Diego. He took that net, strung
it in his garage, had his folks move the cars and then spent
countless hours hitting off a tee into the net.
</P>
<P>
   It's that work ethic that's enabled Karros to prove baseball
people _ scouts, managers, player personnel directors, general
managers and more _ wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He calls himself a two-tool player, admitting his lacking of a
strong arm or sensational defense. Scouts chart his speed on the
base paths with a sundial. But here he is, his niche forged into
Dodgers history as an endearing example of what hard work can mean.
</P>
<P>
   He's hit 211 home runs, trails only Ron Cey for the L.A. record
of 228, has driven in at least 100 runs four times and is the most
recognizable Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   So why was nobody willing to take Karros seriously? Even UCLA
failed to offer a scholarship, instead making Karros walk on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come watch me for a couple days or a week, I might look
like one of the worst players in the history of the game,'' Karros
said. ``I also might look great, but I'm not the type of player
you're going to watch and come away saying, `Wow.' But over the
course of the season, I'll be right there with the guys you see and
say, `Wow.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been like that. Right from high school. I don't do
anything really well, but collectively, I figure out ways to be
successful. I don't think anybody, upon first impression, is
enamored with me.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Ted Kubiak, who was managing the Single-A Modesto A's a
decade ago, saw Karros play, he said Karros worked hard but lacked
the skills. Karros remembers cutting out those comments, pasting
them on his bed and looking at them every day.
</P>
<P>
   It's why, a few years later, decision-makers within the Dodgers
organization said Karros would be fortunate to reach the major
leagues. Having a productive career was never an option.
</P>
<P>
   Even Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone, who scouted Karros at
UCLA, had a hard time projecting Karros as a big-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit the ball hard and hit it far,'' Malone said. ``But
until you get to see a guys make-up, the intangibles... that's
probably his biggest asset. His mental toughness and work ethic and
will to succeed reminds me of (Cal) Ripken.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where everyone got Karros wrong. While everyone was ready
to bury Karros because his physical skills aren't as impressive as
many others, they never figured just how hard he would work to make
up for it.
</P>
<P>
   It began in his garage, and continues now. He hits in the
batting cages nearly every day of the season. Manager Davey Johnson
recalls seeing Karros working out in hotel swimming pools while on
the road, and during the offseason Karros keeps in condition with
intense workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Work is in his blood. Even last season, with a horrific 162-game
odyssey nine innings from ending, Karros was in the bowels of the
Astrodome taking batting practice three hours before first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will never be embarrassed because he's not prepared,''
Dodgers hitting coach Rick Down said. ``We have quite a few guys
who have great work ethics here, and I'm sure some of it comes from
his success, and how he prepares, and the younger players see that.
He's consistent. And because of his consistency, he's overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros, almost begrudgingly, acknowledges his talent. But he's
quick top point out that the major leagues, as well as the minors,
are filled with talent. The work is what Karros believes carries
his success.
</P>
<P>
   In four of the past five seasons Karros hit at least 30 homers
and drove in 100 runs. The exception is 1998, when he missed 21
games. But he responded last season with a career year in which he
hit .304 with 34 homers and 112 RBI. The reward was a three-year
contract extension with an option for 2004 year. He's guaranteed
$24 million.
</P>
<P>
   With the new contract comes piece of mind. Karros has a no-
trade clause for the first two years, which means he no longer has
to keep up with the rumor mill that had him going to nearly every
other city in the league over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past I made sure I was aware of what was going on
around me,''Karros said. ``Probably moreso than I should've, but I
wanted to make sure I was aware of my situation. Now, I can control
my situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it's the first time Karros can say that. He dealt
with the trade talk from his first season through being unprotected
in the latest expansion draft through trade rumors last season that
nearly sent Karros to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   But, sensing public sentiment would shoot through the roof if a
trade was made, management continually pulled back. It happened
when Fred Claire was the general manager and the O'Malley family
ran the club, and it happened again last season with Malone as the
general manager and Fox in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it gets right down to it, the Dodgers probably recognized
how valuable this guy is,'' Malone said. ``Once you get close (to a
deal) and analyze it, Eric Karros is too valuable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
