<HEADLINE>
NASHVILLE NO PUSHOVER FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A casual look at the schedule would suggest
tonight's game with the Nashville Predator should provide the Kings
with two of the 90 points they probably will need to reach the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing casual about the second-year Predators
these days. They might have the worst record in the Western
Conference (25-40-7), but their four-game road trip clearly is
their postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, they rallied to tie Phoenix then defeated them 4-3
in overtime. A victory by the Coyotes, who have dropped three
straight, would have moved them ahead of the Kings for fifth in the
West.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville opened their trip with a 3-2 overtime loss to the
mighty Red Wings in Detroit on Tuesday then followed with a 2-2 tie
in Colorado on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That makes three playoff teams the Predators have taken to
overtime in a four-day span.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an awesome feeling,'' Predators forward Scott Walker
told reporters after beating Phoenix. ``We've had three tough
overtime games against three of the top teams in the league. But it
makes things feel a whole lot better when you can win like
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Predators have dropped all three games to the Kings
this season, their gritty work ethic always scares coach Andy
Murray. Last year, its first in the league, Nashville beat the
Kings three times.
</P>
<P>
   Murray watched the tapes of those games last summer after
joining the team and it shaped his approach to this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be teams with more talent, but we will not be
outworked,'' Murray said. ``We saw the Predators were our first
game on the schedule and we made that game a priority throughout
training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings won that game 2-0 and opened the season 4-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville has struggled on offense most of the season. The
Predators are last in the West with 183 goals. In goaltender Tomas
Vokoun's last 10 starts, Nashville had 17 goals.
</P>
<P>
   So it didn't look good when Phoenix went up 2-0 just seven
minutes into Friday's game then allowed a third goal late in the
first period after Vokoun misplayed the puck in his end.
</P>
<P>
   But Vokoun, who is 9-19-1 this year despite a respectable 2.70
goals against average, shut down Phoenix from there. Greg Johnson
scored in OT to give Nashville the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost started crying when we scored the fourth goal,''
Vokoun said. ``I've waited so long and worked so hard. I think I
deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   KINGS vs. NASHVILLE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 p.m. at Staples Center
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Fox Sports Net, KRLA-AM (1110)
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Coming off their first shutout of the season, the Kings
face a team they have beaten in all three meetings this season. The
teams last met March 4 at the Staples Center with the Kings winning
3-2 on an overtime goal by Jozef Stumpel. The Kings continue to
struggle on the power play. They went 0 for 7 in Friday's 4-0 loss
to St. Louis and are 1 for 32 in the last six games. Luc Robitaille
is tied with injured Ziggy Palffy for the team lead with 66 points.
But Robitaille, who was on pace to surpass last year's total of 39
has stumbled recently. He does not have a goal in his last seven
games and just one in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Matt McHale
</P>
</TEXT>
