<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, PEPPERDINE HAS EVERYONE'S ATTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. - The locker room fell quiet for a moment, it was
as if the significance of the situation had finally hit the
Pepperdine basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   In a few minutes the Waves would take the floor against Indiana
in the first round of the NCAA Tournament. A national television
audience was waiting, not to mention 20,000 fans inside the HSBC
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   These are moments that sometimes determine the mentality a team
takes onto the floor, whether it plays with fear or confidence.
</P>
<P>
   And it was a moment Waves coach Jan van Breda Kolff, who leads
Pepperdine into the second round today against Oklahoma State, was
well prepared for.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff and his assistants had had edited a 12-minute
video tape of Pepperdine highlights from this year, then put them
to music. When he concluded his pregame speech, van Breda Kolff
surprised Pepperdine with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys didn't know we'd done that, so when we were finished
talking, I said let's go to this other room,'' van Breda Kolff
said. ``We put the tape in and all of a sudden our guys were
like..., I mean they were like...And I said, that's a pretty good
basketball team. Let's go out and show all these people that that's
the basketball team we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-seeded Waves then proceeded to dominate 6th-seeded
Indiana, 77-57, to push into the second round today and perch
themselves atop the national stage.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was as shocking as it was thorough, not because of
the outcome, but the ease with which the Waves handled Indiana and
the swagger they displayed in doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took it to us,'' said Indiana's Michael Lewis. ``There
wasn't a time we were really in the game except right before
tip-off.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-hour window between Friday's game and today's might not
be enough for van Breda Kolff to come up with another motivational
ploy, but maybe he doesn't need one. The Waves were a confident
bunch Saturday as it prepared for Oklahoma State, enjoying their
moment in the spotlight but not yet ready to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   The win over Indiana may have awakened the rest of the country
to Pepperdine, but the Waves weren't surprised at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected to be here, we knew we had a good team,'' said
Pepperdine point guard Tezale Archie, who had a career-high 11
assists Friday. ``We're just glad to get the opportunity to show
the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State coach definitely noticed. The Cowboys (25-6) were
happy to avoid a top seed in the second round, having lost there to
No. 1's Duke and Auburn the last two years. But after watching
Pepperdine embarrass Indiana, they weren't so sure they had an
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the easiness in which they were able to beat the
Hoosiers surprised our coaching staff and players,'' Oklahoma State
coach Eddie Sutton said. ``They present a little bit of a problem
for us in that we really haven't seen anyone that plays the style
that they play. Their changing defenses, their trapping. But
hopefully we're mature enough to handle all the different
defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State finished tied for fourth in the Big 12, then lost
to Iowa State in the semifinals of the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys share similarities with Indiana - both play rugged,
man-to-man halfcourt defense and are disciplined on offense. The
difference is,they're more physical then the Hoosiers, have better
athletes and their success offensively isn't determined by one one
or two players.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine shut down Indiana All-American A.J. Guyton Friday,
limiting him to three points and no field goals on just two shot
attempts. The Hoosiers floundered without Guyton and the Waves
rolled to an easy win.
</P>
<P>
   But Oklahoma State isn't as dependent on one player. Desmond
Mason, a 6-5 forward, averages 18 points to lead the Cowboys,
including 30 against Hofstra Friday in an 86-66 first-round rout.
But Glendon Alexander (12 ppg), Brian Montonati (12 ppg) and Joe
Adkins (11 ppg) all contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Doug Gottlieb, who played at Tustin High and was a
teammate of Waves forward David Lalazarian at Notre Dame, does a
good job spreading the offense around. But he's a liability from
the field, shooting just 36 percent for his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when (Mason) has played well and scored big it's
certainly a lot easier for us to win,'' Sutton said. ``But I do
think if (Pepperdine) puts that much emphasis on controlling him,
then our other people can step up and score.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommie Prince will guard Mason in Pepperdine's half-court-zone,
and it's a good matchup for the Waves. At 6-5, 215, Prince is just
as big and strong as Mason, who physically dominated Hofstra.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one guy we do have to concentrate on, he had a good
game,'' said Waves guard Brandon Armstrong, who had 22 points
against Indiana. ``We don't know how the game is going to turn out,
but we're going to play our game and try to limit him and his
points.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
