<HEADER>
A1205 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-NOTES-     03-18 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-NOTES-(MATCHUP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIRKY WAVES ENCHANT PRESS
</HEADLINE>
 BOX AT BOTTOM)-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ In less than 48 hours, Pepperdine went from
unknown to darlings, and the Waves are enjoying their new status.
</P>
<P>
   That's what a shocking win over a higher seed will do for a
team, and their 77-57 rout over Indiana was just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were behind us (Friday), probably because we were the
underdog but also because a lot of people don't like Bobby
Knight,'' Pepperdine guard Tezale Archie said Saturday, drawing
laughter from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than that. The national media here have taken to
the Waves' eclectic personalities, asking just as many questions
about their headbands and hairdos as half-court traps and
rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Pepperdine is one of the more colorful teams in the
tournament. Tommie Prince sets the tone with his 1970's Afro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The headbands come from a sense of family, to show our
togetherness,'' Prince said. ``As far as our hairstyles, there are
a lot of changes as far as the NBA and the NCAA. You see a lot of
people with Afros, braids and dreadlocks and that nature. Dr. J is
my favorite athlete, so I just wanted to imitate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not like the old days: Oklahoma State coach Eddie Sutton has
seen many changes in 30 years of coaching, and not all of them
good. He is especially discouraged over the lack of friendship
between coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have the brotherhood among coaches that you once
had,'' Sutton said. ``I can remember going to those early Final
Four sessions where the (coaches) room was open and all the coaches
were in there discussing basketball. You don't see that anymore. I
can remember Mr. (Hank) Iba and Mr. (Adolph) Rupp on their knees
and one of them had Coke bottles and one of them had 7-up bottles
and they were trying to outcoach each other there on the floor 'til
about 2 o'clock in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Change of plan? Should Pepperdine win today, the Waves are
considering staying in New York this week instead of flying home
Monday. The East Regional final is in Syracuse next Friday-Sunday.
The Waves may opt to avoid two more cross-country plane rides and
another time change.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MATCHUPS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pepperdine vs. Oklahoma State, 9 a.m. &QL; 
Second round, East Regional. HSBC Arena, Buffalo N.Y. &QL; 
Backcourt: Doug Gottlieb and Joe Adkins (11 ppg) give Oklahoma
State solid point-guard play and a dependable scorer at off guard.
The Waves counter with Tezale Archie (9.8 ppg, 5.7 apg) and Brandon
Armstrong (14.1 ppg). Archie is similar to Gottlieb with his
passing and court management, but he's a better shooter and steps
up to take important shots. When he stays within himself (a
career-high 11 assists Friday), he's effective. As Armstrong showed
Friday with 22 points against Indiana, he can stroke the outside
shot and get to the basket on drives. He's a tough matchup for
anyone. &QL; 
Edge: Armstrong can do too many things _ his quick hands forced six
steals Friday _ and he likes big situations. Archie and Gottlieb
are a push in terms of passing, but Pepperdine has the edge because
Archie has shown he can score. &QL; 
Frontcourt: Oklahoma State has size and offense in Brian Montonati
(6-10, 12.2 ppg, 72. rpg), a physical offensive and defense
presence in Desmond Mason (18 ppg, 6.8 rpg) and a big body in
Fredrik Jonzen (8.8 ppg, 6.8 rpg). Pepperdine isn't nearly as
skilled offensively up front, but Tommie Prince (9.8 ppg), Kelvin
Gibbs (9.1 ppg, 4.8 rpg) and Nick Sheppard (8.8 ppg, 6.8 rpg) can
all defend and score when needed, plus their size gives the Waves a
physical edge over most teams. Sheppard, 6-11, showed Friday how
important he is when he hits his shots (17 points) inside, which
opens the perimeter. &QL; 
Edge: Mason is the best player on the floor, and Jonzen and
Montonati give the Cowboys a versatility advantage. &QL; 
Bench: Craig Lewis (7.7 ppg) and David Lalazarian (8.2 ppg) have
played like starters all year for the Waves, although Lalazarian
has struggled in the postseason. Al Minihan and Cedric Suitt (6-10)
get spot duty at guard and center. Suitt came up big Friday when
Sheppard got into foul trouble. Oklahoma State goes two-deep on the
bench, with Glendon Alexander (12 ppg) coming in at guard and
forward. But he's the only Cowboys reserve of note. &QL; 
Edge: Lalazarian and Lewis are creative, energy-boosters off the
bench, and each can get on shooting rolls to either extend leads or
pick up a sluggish offense. Suitt is a shot blocker and gives
Pepperdine another long, active athlete defensively. &QL; 
Intangibles: Oklahoma State played in the deeper Big 12 Conference,
finishing in a third-place tie with Oklahoma but just two games
behind first-place Iowa State. Six teams from the conference went
to the tournament. Pepperdine has the momentum factor working _ its
big win over Indiana on Friday elevated the Waves' confidence to a
whole different level. They've enjoyed their moment in the national
spotlight thus far, enough that they may not want to give it up
just yet. &QL; 
Edge: Pepperdine is now a media darling but don't be fooled. To
some people the Waves are surprise winners, sleepers sneaking by
against higher seeds on last-second shots. But Pepperdine was
simply the better team against Indiana. They don't consider
themselves a sleeper and they aren't playing like one. &QL; 
Coaching: Jan van Breda Kolff has the Waves prepared and
consistently comes up with defensive schemes to confuse opponents
and take their best scorer out of his game. Pepperdine bought into
his system immediately, and credit his style for its success. Eddie
Sutton, like Bobby Knight, is one of the best ever, winning 656
games over a 30-year career. He's the only coach to take four teams
to the NCAA Tournament (Kentucky, Creighton, Arkansas and Oklahoma
State) and one of just 11 to take two teams (Arkansas and Oklahoma
State) to the final four.) &QL; 
Edge: Sutton is the proven veteran, but van Breda Kolff's star is
on the rise. The Waves may get beaten by more talent, but they
never get outcoached. &QL; 
Outcome: Oklahoma State can match up to Pepperdine's size and
athletic ability, and Mason gives the Cowboys the one player who
can carry his team for either club. Oklahoma State 75-69. &QL; 
_ Vincent Bonsignore &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
