<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOCK TICKING ON EDMONDS DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- Of all places, Jim Edmonds might have spent one
of his final days in an Angels uniform in Hermosillo, Mexico, where
the Angels played the Arizona Diamondbacks Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Various published reports indicate the Angels have set today as
a deadline for teams interested in Edmonds to make a final offer.
The only two teams believed to be in serious consideration are the
Yankees and A's, as the Mariners are expected to drop out of the
Edmonds sweepstakes once they make a trade for the Tigers' Bobby
Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will not confirm setting a deadline for any offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a deadline I'm not aware of it,'' Angels assistant
general manager Ken Forsch said. ``I don't know why somebody would
back themselves into a corner like that. We still have the rest of
spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels general manager Bill Stoneman along with manager Mike
Scioscia and most of the team's front-line players went to
Hermosillo Saturday to play the Diamondbacks while the rest of the
team played the Diamondbacks in a split-squad game in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are concerned about going into the season with
Edmonds' status up in the air and it causing a distraction. But
they have remained firm in their demands for pitching that could
step into the starting rotation this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' Ramiro Mendoza would fit the bill, but Yankees
manager Joe Torre has been insistent on keeping him because of his
ability to both start and pitch out of the bullpen. Torre, though,
could be overruled by Yankees owner George Steinbrenner, who has
been annoyed at the Yankees' poor play this spring and who could
order a deal done.
</P>
<P>
   Other Yankees that could be included in a deal are highly-touted
infield prospect Alfonso Soriano, right-handed pitcher Ryan Bradley
(a Covina native and Ayala High graduate) and outfielder Ricky
Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Spiezio is beginning to wonder where he fits in to this
year's team. And with good reason. Signed as a candidate to win the
starting job at second base, Spiezio has played the last three
games at third, including two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia explained that Spiezio is his best option to back up
Troy Glaus at third. But Spiezio, who had been a third baseman
until the A's moved him to second in 1997, says it takes an
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much the ground balls, but the throw,'' said
Spiezio, who his hitting .323 with two homers and seven RBIs this
spring. ``At third you come over the top and at second it's more
from the side. It's something I have to concentrate on.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that Spiezio is being worked into a utility role
in anticipation of the Angels acquiring Soriano from the Yankees,
who could step in and start at second.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they use me as a utility guy, that's their decision,''
Spiezio said. ``I prefer to play every day here, I won't think
about anything else. (Scioscia) told me he wanted to get me a
couple games at third just in case anything happened to Troy.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty of his status does not bother him, Spiezio said,
not after what happened last season with the A's, which included a
demotion to the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can deal with last year, I can deal with a lot of
stuff,'' he said. ``My head's not messed up, it's my arm angle.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Candiotti's spring ERA rose from 2.16 to 6.08 after giving
up seven runs and 12 hits in five innings in the Angels' 9-3 loss
to the Arizona Diamondbacks Saturday afternoon at Tempe Diablo
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, he got hit by two line drives -- in the
same place and by the same better (David Delluci) in two different
at-bats. Candiotti was hit on the base of his thumb on his left
(glove) hand, and it was swollen after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti gave up three home runs, including two by Kelly
Stinnett. But he wasn't discouraged by his performance because he
was throwing the knuckleball for strikes. The problem was the dry
Arizona climate, which limits the amount of movement on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back over everything, I probably should have given up
two runs,'' Candiotti said. ``The (lack of) rotation on the
knuckleball was great. Without looking at how they hit the ball,
(catcher) Matt (Walbeck) said I was locating it well. I try not to
gauge how what happens, but how the ball is coming out of my
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti wasn't the only 40-something (42) pitcher on the mound
Saturday. Forty-year-old Mike Morgan started for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
