<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERMANNED RANGERS ENHANCE PLAYOFF CHANCES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Rangers found themselves in an
all-too-familiar position Saturday afternoon: clinging to a
one-goal lead in the third period like a prizefighter trying to
survive the final round of a championship bout.
</P>
<P>
   Too many times this season, according to the team's captain,
Brian Leetch, the Rangers have left points on the table in such
situations. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   With two-thirds of their top line out of the lineup because of
injury, the Rangers received two goals from Valery Kamensky and a
tie-breaking score from Mathieu Schneider, and held on for a 3-2
victory over the Eric Lindros-less Philadelphia Flyers at First
Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   The come-from-behind effort kept the Rangers, who received an
outstanding performance from the backup goaltender Kirk McLean,
right in the thick of the Eastern Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with Pittsburgh's 3-2 loss in Boston, the Rangers
(29-33-11-3) moved back into a tie with the Penguins for the eighth
playoff spot with 72 points. Eight teams in each conference qualify
for the postseason. Montreal, in the seventh playoff spot with 73
points, beat Carolina, which is in the 10th spot with 70 points, by
3-2 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers _ who were without Petr Nedved (bruised ribs) and
Jan Hlavac (hip pointer) Saturday _ have played 73 games this
season, to 71 for Pittsburgh. The Canadiens and Hurricanes will
have played 72 games after Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes Sunday night's contest in Pittsburgh as big a
game as the Rangers have played all season long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given up the lead so many times, it was nice to hold on
to one,'' Adam Graves said before the Rangers flew to Pittsburgh.
``Especially against the Flyers. But with that said, we have to
take this into tomorrow night or it doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers cannot afford to wallow too long in the aftermath of
their first victory over Philadelphia this season. And that is
because Saturday's victory was just the Rangers' second in their
last seven games (2-4-1). Still, it could not have come at a better
time. Or against a tougher team from the Rangers' standpoint, with
or without Lindros, who is flying to Chicago for a Monday
appointment with a doctor who specializes in concussions.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers had manhandled the Rangers by a combined score of 7-0
during the teams' first two meetings early this season, before
rallying back from a one-goal, third-period deficit for a 3-2
victory at Madison Square Garden on Feb. 20. Since the Rangers ran
off nine victories in 10 games from Jan.5 to 25, they have
squandered at least a dozen points in the standing because of their
inability to hang on to third-period leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little bit of a problem late in the third period when
we were playing half-ice hockey,'' said Coach John Muckler, who was
nevertheless pleased with the Rangers' all-around effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were a little like Weebles all afternoon: no matter
how much the bigger Flyers knocked them around, the Rangers
wobbled, but got right back up and kept on plugging away.
</P>
<P>
   Kamensky, who now has 12 goals this season, has scored four in
the last four games. Both of Kamensky's tallies (at 5 minutes 4
seconds and at 8:51 of the first) came in response to goals by the
Philadelphia rookie Simon Gagne (at 1:01, on the game's first shot
and at 8:14).
</P>
<P>
   And after Schneider blasted a one-timer from the right point
past John Vanbiesbrouck at 13:24 of the second, the Rangers took
what has become for them the dreaded one-goal lead into the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   They did not add to it. In fact, they played most of the final
period in a shell. But the Rangers did not relinquish the lead
either. Progress sometimes comes in small increments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people don't think we can make it,'' said Tim
Taylor, who, with his linemates Rob DiMaio and Eric Lacroix, earned
Muckler's praise for their work with defensemen Stephane Quintal
and Rich Pilon on the Flyers' line of John LeClair, Keith Primeau
and Keith Jones. ``But we believe we can make it. And it's going to
be a great thing when we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people talk about all the money we're making. But the
money means nothing. I think earlier in the season we were thinking
we should kill teams offensively because we make so much money as a
team. But we don't have to blow teams out.''
</P>
<P>
   They just have to find a way, like Saturday, to hang on to those
third-period leads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
