<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICHARDSON-OPEC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARDSON TO MEET WITH OPEC OFFICIALS  
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
 
WASHINGTON _ U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson continues his
whirlwind diplomatic efforts today to prod the OPEC nations to
boost their oil production and help ease prices at the gas pump.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richardson leaves today to confer with oil ministers from
Nigeria, Indonesia, Algeria and the United Arab Emirates, after
meeting Saturday with Saudi Arabian Oil Minister Ali al-Naimi in
California and speaking by telephone to Kuwaiti Oil Minister Saud
Al-Sabah, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   He then will meet with his counterparts from the other
industrialized nations at the International Energy Agency in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's latest trip comes just eight days before the 11
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries gather
in Vienna, for what, arguably, will be the cartel's most critical
meeting since the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is trying to persuade the OPEC
producers to increase their oil exports substantially to overcome a
supply-demand shortfall approaching 2 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Richardson has traveled to Saudi Arabia, Kuwait
and Venezuela, as well as non-OPEC producing nations Mexico and
Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, President Clinton revealed that he had spoken with Saudi
Arabia's King Fahd, leader of the world's largest crude exporter,
to discuss the oil issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to work with foreign countries to help close
the gap between production and consumption,'' the president said
Saturday in his weekly radio address. ``Several important
oil-producing countries already have expressed their support for a
production increase.''
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC nations already are pumping 1 million to 1.5 million
barrels of oil a day more than their existing production quotas
would allow. Some OPEC watchers fear the producing nations will
merely legitimize the existing production levels rather than agree
to bring new barrels to the market.
</P>
<P>
   Iran, OPEC's second-largest producer, will play a critical role
at the March 27 meeting. And it has many incentives not to go along
with Washington's oil strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has very little spare production capacity. That means
Tehran, which now is enjoying oil prices above $30 a barrel, would
not be able to share in the benefits of increased OPEC production,
but it would feel the effects if world crude prices were to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced
plans to ease U.S. sanctions on a number of Iranian products, from
Persian rugs to pistachio nuts, as a gesture to Tehran's new, more
moderate government.
</P>
<P>
   The oil sector was not part of the announcement, but a number of
oil analysts interpreted the move, in part, as a carrot to
encourage Iran's cooperation in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, White House Chief of Staff John Podesta denied there
was any link between Albright's announcement and the upcoming OPEC
meeting. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Saturday were quick to criticize the
administration's ``quiet diplomacy'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton-Gore foreign policy towards OPEC countries has
crashed and burned, and the American people are suffering for it
today,'' Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people deserve trustworthy leadership, not empty
promises, reckless rhetoric and radical, last-ditch proposals,''
Nicholson argued.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the OPEC nations also are beginning to bristle at the
mounting U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
   An official newspaper in the United Arab Emirates Saturday
noted: ``The most dangerous thing is that the (United States')
wishes have this time been transformed into threats, and the calls
(for increased output) have turned into orders,'' Agence France
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   To address more long-term issues of oil supply and dependence on
foreign sources, the White House Saturday threw its support behind
some modest tax measures to help domestic producers.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal would alter the tax treatment for the cost of
exploring for and developing oil and gas reserves. The
administration estimates allowing producers to expense these costs
would boost U.S. oil production by 126,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   A second incentive would allow producers to expense ``delay
rental payments,'' compensation paid to a royalty owner when
drilling on a lease does not begin on a scheduled date. Producers
would be able to deduct these payments in the year they occur and
thus free up cash flow for more production.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M, who had asked the administration to
include these tax incentives called them ``small but important
tools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased the administration has taken action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also unveiled a plan that would take 2 million
barrels of oil from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve _ the nation's
emergency crude stockpile _ to create a regional reserve in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Home owners in New England and the Mid-Atlantic states were hit
with whopping home heating oil bills this winter, caused in large
part by some supply and distribution problems experienced during a
three-week cold snap.
</P>
<P>
   The new reserve would be designed to supply additional heating
oil in the market in the event of a future shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration also is backing measures to promote
renewable energy sources, produce more fuel-efficient cars and
trucks and make homes more energy efficient.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, Clinton tried to reminded voters
that while gasoline prices ``are higher now than they have been for
some time, our overall economy is still the strongest it's ever
been.''
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORYXXXXX $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
