<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDICTION: THIS RANGERS TEAM IS BETTER THAN MORE POWERFUL
PREDECESSORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ On a shelf next to Doug Melvin's office
desk, there's a stack of new baseball magazines, all of them
previewing the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read them, and we don't fare so well,'' said the Rangers'
general manager. ``I saw us picked last in our division in one.
Most of them have us third. It's like we dropped off the earth or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, has been an ongoing national theme this spring.
The trashing of the Rangers is pretty near unanimous in
publications and on the TV cable shows.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rangers Juan Gonzalez and Mark McLemore joined the piling
on last week, although Juan, in particular, appeared to be
motivated by terminal bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's way too shocking for a lot of people to believe
we could actually win with good pitching,'' Melvin said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Everything involved with Grapefruit League play thus far
indicates otherwise. Pitching is very much a strength. Other areas
are also improved. Run production is a scary unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here's another prediction for 2000, this one delivered
with confidence:
</P>
<P>
   Although it's very different, the Rangers team that leaves
Florida in 10 days will be improved over last season's edition, and
also from the season before. The pitching will be a large surprise.
The defense will be much better on the left side of the infield and
in right field. Run production will obviously be down, but by how
much?
</P>
<P>
   In a total reversal from the past, the bats will have to surpass
current expectations for this team to duplicate a 95-victory
season. Less emphasis on the home run continued this week, when Lee
Stevens departed in a trade for David Segui, which is supposed to
bring the lineup a higher average, fewer strikeouts and a better
on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   But these Rangers can win 90 games and still be more balanced
overall, plus more of a playoff threat.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, does anyone remember recent history? The two
consecutive American League West titles? And that the 95 victories
last season were a franchise record and only three less than the
Yankees while playing a balanced league schedule, save for
interleague play?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel we got the deserved respect for the 95 wins,''
Melvin said. ``And somehow lost in the mix are such things as us
having four All-Stars last season, plus the MVP of the American
League _ our third MVP in four years _ and also that we've won not
only back-to-back divisional titles, but three in four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hold it right there. How could all that be suddenly forgotten?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are being remembered and judged for one thing: playoff
results against the Yankees the last two years,'' Melvin answered.
``That's where we've received our most national exposure, and the
results weren't so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand people having watched us in the playoffs and
said, `My gawd, I thought they could hit.' Right away, we were
disregarded as overrated, and that's what is sticking with us this
spring.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a bingo for Melvin. But there's also more, like the
departure in the off-season of Gonzalez, Todd Zeile and Aaron Sele.
With that trio, big numbers are subtracted in RBI, home runs and
pitching W's.
</P>
<P>
   For so many years the Rangers lived by the bat _ and died with
the wood in the playoffs _ so it's still a foreign concept to think
of this team depending on pitching and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``But why not?'' pitching coach Dick Bosman asked. ``The other
way didn't work for us when it needed to work'' in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, few in baseball share Bosman's glowing optimism for
what left-hander Kenny Rogers is going to accomplish this season.
And Darren Oliver, too. Both were down the list of quality
free-agent pitchers available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been one to try and oversell our pitching
staff,'' Bosman said. ``I think this staff will be very good, and,
again, that's not overselling anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the other spring questions.
</P>
<P>
   Third base: Out of nowhere, 25-year-old Tom Evans, released by
the Blue Jays last year, has won the job with ``Boooo-shell'' glove
work. It's unfair to say he's as good as Mr. Buechele, but the
improvement over Zeile is immense.
</P>
<P>
   With two lefties now in the rotation, and a third when Justin
Thompson is ready, left-side defense is more vital than ever. More
ground balls will be headed that way. The question is whether Evans
will hit enough to justify his glove being in there.
</P>
<P>
   Second base: Still iffy, but Frank Catalanotto is better than
expected and Luis Alicea has struggled. Advantage Catalanotto, who
has an interesting bat, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   Right field: If Gabe Kapler can hit a lick, he might surpass
Rusty and Pudge as the fans' darling in Arlington. A hardball
player all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Center field: Put a hold on that instant superstardom for Ruben
Mateo, but that's not knocking anything about Ruben this spring.
Going to be great; it's only a matter of when, and if he can stay
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Leadoff man: Shortstop Royce Clayton has done a reversal from
last spring. The confidence level has soared, both in the field and
at the plate. He relishes the responsibility of leading off, and it
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, even with the offensive holes, it's a team that's
actually easy to like, although nationally, many don't.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
