<HEADLINE>
BORDER ATTRACTING DESPERATE EUROPEANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sixteen and pregnant, Renata Hajnos must have pictured the ideal
ending: fleeing her dirt-poor mountain village in Poland for an
idyllic new life with her lover in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   What she got instead was a room in a central Arizona immi
gration detention center, where her dreams are in tatters and the
only Polish voice she hears is her own.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, Hajnos was intercepted with several other
Poles who entered the United States illegally near Nogales, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, Hajnos is another sad statistic, one more hopeful
immigrant risking life and limb to reach the land of opportunity.
But the Immigration and Natu ralization Service said she per
sonifies a new trend: Eastern Europeans taking advantage of
Mexico's relaxed immigration policies to get into that country.
From there, it's a short hop over the fence to the promised land.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mexican immigrants still account for the huge major ity
of illegal border crossings in the Southwest, the number of
Europeans and other non-Mexi can border crossers is inching
steadily higher, reflecting the ever-changing economic and po
litical climate around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, the start of the fiscal year, agents in southern
Arizona have snared 46 Poles entering the country illegally,
already more than last year's total. Eighteen have come in the past
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, two Yugoslavs were captured. From October to
February, Border Patrol agents caught Ukrainians, Bulgarians and
Romanians, not to mention a host of people from China and India.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's experience mirrors the rest of the Southwestern
border. In one odd case last month, authorities detained 37 Poles
in Houston after they flew in from Mexico City under falsi fied
Austrian passports.
</P>
<P>
   The changing dynamics of bor der traffic are explained, in part,
by Mexico's revised immigration policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand they've really loosened up their requirements
for Poland, specifically,'' Border Patrol spokesman Rob Daniels
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, Mexico and Poland have allowed free travel between
their countries. Where issuance of visas was once tightly regu
lated, the two nations now allow an unlimited number of each
other's tourists to enter without visas.
</P>
<P>
   Marek Purowski, head of the immigration section of the Polish
Consulate in Los Angeles, said the problem could be alleviated if
the United States' restrictive and overly bureaucratic entry poli
cies were loosened. When Polish citizens hit roadblocks, he said,
they seem to take the Mexican route.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Rychtarczyk, 56, the mother of Hajnos' boyfriend, has been
a legal resident of Chicago for 10 years. Her son, Krzysztof, 19,
the father of Hajnos' baby, legally joined his mother and family
three weeks ago. Already, he has a job. But he was forced to leave
Hajnos behind.
</P>
<P>
   Although the mother offered to host Hajnos in a visa
application, Hajnos feared her own mother's two previous U.S. visa
rejections would kill her chances.
</P>
<P>
   With cash scraped together by her family, Hajnos left her vil
lage of Ludzmierz in southern Poland and headed for Krakow, where
she boarded a plane to Mexico City, her mother, Halgor zata, 40,
said by telephone from a neighbor's home.
</P>
<P>
   Left behind were Hajnos' seven siblings, who are surviving on
the equivalent of $80 a month in child support. It is a hard life,
with Poland's 11 percent unem ployment rate magnified in its rural,
underdeveloped northern and southern extremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those regions have suffered greatly, economically,'' Purowski
said.
</P>
<P>
   From Mexico City, Hajnos made her way to Nogales, So nora,
crossing into Arizona about March 1 with her sights on Chicago.
Instead, the Border Pa trol had its sights on her. Authori ties
won't discuss their investigation, but they believe Hajnos and
other Poles got help from a smuggling ring.
</P>
<P>
   Hajnos now awaits an uncer tain fate. She speaks no English and
has no money. And as if things weren't bad enough, the detention
center was quarantined last week for chicken pox.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Rychtarczyk, who weeps over Hajnos' plight, said she has
hired a lawyer. She is trying to compile such documents as Hajnos'
birth records and paren tal consent forms so they can persuade the
INS to let her son marry Hajnos.
</P>
<P>
   Hajnos told the Rychtarczyks by phone Wednesday that she wants
to stay in the United States, but there are too many variables to
predict her success.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Ahr, an INS spokes man, said the agency rarely lets
minors in its custody wed with out clear parental consent. Even if
a wedding takes place, there are years-long waiting lists for
foreigners hoping to join loved ones in the United States. Even if
Hajnos' child were born in Amer ica, there's no guarantee she'd be
permitted to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road, no matter which way, is a long one,'' Ahr said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the distance, Hajnos' mother last week sent a message:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell her I really love her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
