<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-LSU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS' ROAD BLOCKED BY LSU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ With about three minutes to play, a berth in
the Sweet 16 became a mirage in the desert for the University of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, LSU made the kinds of plays that teams that
advance make in the NCAA Tournament. The Longhorns didn't. So it
will be the fourth-seeded Tigers who move on to the West Regional
semifinals next week in Albuquerque, N.M. after a 72-67 victory
over the fifth-seeded Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just beat ourselves,'' UT center Chris Mihm said.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm finished what could be his last game in a Texas uniform _
should he declare early for the NBA draft _ with 13 points and 10
rebounds. But he converted only 5 of 14 shots from the floor and
missed 5 of 8 free-throw attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't myself today,'' Mihm said. ``I couldn't find a way to
put \Rthe ball\S in. I played hard, got position, but I couldn't
get the ball to go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm's free-throw shooting was a typical performance on this day
for a team that converted only 8 of 17 shots from the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frustrating,'' coach Rick Barnes said. ``We got the ball
inside where we needed to get it, got fouled and got to the line
and didn't convert 'em. The truth be told, we didn't play very well
in the last few minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams were locked in a 60-all tie with 3:04 to play. But LSU
scored seven unanswered points and snatched the game away over the
next two minutes. After Tigers point guard Torris Bright broke the
tie with a driving layup at 2:10, the game then turned permanently
on the ensuing sequence.
</P>
<P>
   First, LSU forward Stromile Swift blocked Mihm's short jumper in
the lane, then Swift hit in close from the left baseline over Gabe
Muoneke at the other end. Back downcourt, Brian Beshara picked off
a low pass inside and Ivan Wagner was forced to foul him to prevent
an easy breakaway layup. Beshara made both free throws with 1:19
left. A Muoneke turnover and foul sent Swift back to the line,
where he made 1 of 2 for a 67-60 LSU lead at 1:08 that Texas never
overcame.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Swift's block might have been the game's key
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that was the turning point,'' said Swift, who
scored a game-high 23 points. ``I tried to play good defense every
trip down the court. It just so happened I was able to get the big
block and it motivated us a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a little, Bright said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That got us motivated,'' he said. ``Texas was looking down.
That was the turning point of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a good job of sealing \Rthe lane\S at the end and
that's how they won,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Wagner nailed a 3-point shot with 18.4 seconds to play to
pull Texas to 70-67, but Jermaine Williams sealed the deal for the
Tigers with two free throws four seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   Texas twice lost chances to take command. The Longhorns lost
most of a nine-point lead late in the first half (32-23) , built on
a Wagner 3-pointer at 4:39. But they scored only one more basket
before the half as LSU cut the deficit to 34-31.
</P>
<P>
   The other missed opportunity came when Mihm clanged two free
throws at 10:25 of the second half with Texas ahead 55-51. Chris
Owens drew his fourth foul going for the rebound of the second
miss, came out and played only 1:06 more, before fouling out with
5:45 to play. Swift hit two free throws on Owens' fourth foul and
LSU re-took the lead (56-55) on Bright's 3-pointer at 9:03.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of the year there is a fine line between winning and
losing,'' Barnes said. ``When a four seed plays a five, it usually
gets down to one or two possessions. Things went against us at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who scored a team-high 19 points in his last game,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the stretch they came up with the bigger plays,'' he
said. ``And our free throws came back to bite us in end. This
doesn't leave a very good taste in our mouths, but I think we left
it all on court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we gave the game away. We had every opportunity to walk
away with a victory, but it didn't happen for us today.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
