A1432 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC- &UR; STADIUM-AZR &LR;      03-18 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS, LEGISLATURE AT IMPASSE 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- STADIUM-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NENA BAKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona Cardinals learned a hard lesson last week in the
political reality of financing a new football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are in no mood to play ball unless the team, or
another private source, can carry a bigger chunk of the
construction cost for a proposed $341 million stadium that will
seat 78,000 under a retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who say they generate fewer revenues from stadium
operations than any team in the NFL, maintain what lawmakers are
asking for can't be done:
</P>
<P>
   The team can't stretch beyond the $75 million capital
contribution it has pledged without cutting into its ability to
build a winning team in the high-priced world of free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Personal seat licenses, or charging fans for the right to buy
season tickets, isn't a viable way to raise more private money in a
four-sport market like the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   And the NFL is already giving the Cards a subsidy for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   At $75 million, the team would be paying 22 percent of the
stadium cost, with the Fiesta Bowl and other users kicking in an
additional $20 million of private funds. The Cards said that if the
team is required to ante up more, it will kill a deal that would
also generate new money for state tourism, the Cactus League, the
Fiesta Bowl and amateur sports facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers have made it clear they're willing to risk
watching the Cards flee the Phoenix area for greener pastures and
put the top-tier status of the Fiesta Bowl at risk if it means
ponying up a public subsidy for the stadium plan.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to the state Senate to find any common ground between
politicians and pro football. The stadium bill, trimmed up like a
Christmas tree with 17 House amendments that raise the Cards'
stadium capital contribution to $170.5 million and force the team
to relinquish naming rights, moves to the Senate this week. If a
final bill ever emerges, the question will go to a statewide vote
in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere in the middle, there is a compromise that should be
forwarded to voters,'' said Sen. Scott Bundgaard, R-Glendale,
finance committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But finding it won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING A SHELL GAME?
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers perceive that the Cardinals are playing a shell game,
offering an amount of money the franchise can easily recoup through
stadium naming rights, valued in the tens of millions, and an NFL
subsidy. The league allows teams with new facilities to retain a
percentage of revenues that normally go to visiting teams. That
would give the Cards $25 million over 30 years of financing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cards and the league maintain their plan is the
most innovative of 23 NFL stadium deals negotiated in the past 10
years. Beyond a new stadium, it benefits a wide range of
activities, they said, while allocating 85 percent of the overall
cost to hotel and car-rental taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can unequivocally say the package that's been developed is
unprecedented,'' said Rick Horrow, the NFL's facility develop ment
consultant and a professor of sports law at Harvard Univer sity.
``It will be a model for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers opposed to pub lic financing of stadium projects
greet such talk with exaspera tion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be happy to find a solution with private financing,''
said Senate President Brenda Burns, R-Glendale, who has the power
to send the stadium bill to a conference committee for revi sions
or let it die. ``I think having an NFL team helps the economy and
adds to the way of life, but you can't give blanket approval to
something. The components of the plan have to make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the Cards' proposal to other stadium deals around the
country is difficult because ev ery project is different in terms
of size, amenities and revenue allocations.
</P>
<P>
   But team contributions to new facilities have ranged from noth
ing (Tampa Bay Buccaneers) to $180 million (Washington Red skins).
In deals that don't include personal seat licenses, the aver age
team contribution for a new stadium has been $54 million, well
below the $75 million pledged by the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Vice President Roger Goddell said the league has a policy of
contributing to stadium projects ``because it adds stabil ity to
the league in making sure our teams succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   But sports business consult ants say there's another reason the
league is concerned about new facilities: They add astro nomically
to the value of a franchise, at a minimum dou bling the worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the public out cry when billionaire owners get
public financing,'' said Andy Ap pleby, president of General Sports
and Entertainment, a sports consulting and marketing firm in
Rochester, Mich. ``But at the same time, it makes commu nities
better in many cases.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cards, for now, have dug in their cleats on the amount of
capital they can contribute to a stadium project, as well as the
need to retain naming rights.
</P>
<P>
   AREAS OF COMPROMISE
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Betts, the Cards' chief lobbyist, said other amend
ments, including one that calls for bringing Arizona schools up to
minimum standards before stadium financing can proceed, may be
areas where compromise is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this funding package needs to recognize the higher priority
of education, I think that can be talked about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It may be cold comfort to the Cards, but they aren't the only
NFL team that has faced legisla tive opposition to a stadium fi
nancing plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Steelers were forced to come up with an alter
native deal after Pennsylvania lawmakers blocked a stadium
referendum from going to voters in 1997. Art Rooney, vice presi
dent, said the key to success was support from the governor, the
mayor and other civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wound up piecing to gether a seat license program, got a
(subsidy) from the National Football League and then came to a
basic decision on our part to make a larger investment on our
own,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Steelers upped their contribution from $40 mil
lion to $75 million to help pay for the $255 million stadium that's
set to open in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Persistence pays,'' Rooney said. ``The basic message was:
We're not going to go away until we get this done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 2340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
