<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO BE RICHER THAN BILL GATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Undated) - Step One: Get a job on a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Step Two: Tell a story. Some thing personal, if possible. Per
haps about the time 10 years ago when you accidentally re corded a
telephone conversation with your parents. And about how, since they
passed on, you play back the tape on their wedding anniversary,
just to hear their voices.
</P>
<P>
   Step Three: Collect dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom and Dad died a year apart almost to the day,'' wrote a man
from Phoenix. ``I have on audiotape a conversation I re corded from
a late-night talk show years ago on KOY. It was a show live from
Las Vegas, and the guest was Charo. Mom woke up and caught me
listening to the radio instead of sleeping. I was 14. I told her
Charo was on the radio and that I was waiting my turn to talk with
her, with my recorder at the ready. Well, Mom wanted to talk to
Charo, so I gave her the phone. What followed were laughs and my
mother's beautiful voice in Spanish (telling) Charo, `I'm listening
to the radio here con mi hijo.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There were dozens like it.
</P>
<P>
   A woman with a tape of her own wrote, ``A couple of years ago,
my sister found some movie film labeled `the kids.' The kids turned
out to be my dad and his brother in about 1945. My dad died in
1958, when I was about 11. This wonderful film from before I was
born shows my father and his par ents and his brother playing with
my older sister, who was a toddler. I have watched this 10-minute
movie about a hun dred times.''
</P>
<P>
   The economics of shared ex perience allows even a hack like me
to participate in the greatest get-rich-quick scheme of all time.
All a writer has to do is invest a little time and personal capital
and the dividends come pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, I keep the proceeds for myself. But after
years of raking in the revenue, the vaults of my mem ory are
stuffed with the stories of others. It's time, this once, for a
little profit-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have many videotapes of my dad, who passed away (this past
October),'' an adult daugh ter wrote. ``He was in town from
Michigan visiting my fam ily and to see my five children on
Halloween. I treasure every video with his sparkling Irish eyes and
infectious smile. I would do anything to hear my last birthday
message on my answering machine. Every year, he and my mother would
call and sing in their off-key way Happy Birthday to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And another, who wrote, ``My pop passed away a year ago tomorrow
and my mom six years ago. I have the sound of her voice carefully
stowed away in my memory, invariably responding to my phone calls
with `I was just thinking about you.' And even though I am just
past 50, Dad always opened with `Baaby!' I tried to break him of
that for a while when I was younger, but it was a little thing
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   And a man from Sun City West, who wrote, ``I lost my mother last
March, and she would be 90 years old on the 15th of this month. I
have a video of her singing a gospel song, and I listen to it once
in awhile when I need her touch.''
</P>
<P>
   That's it.
</P>
<P>
   Call me selfish, but the rest I'm keeping for myself _ stories
about hearing a lost parent's voice on an answering machine tape,
or hearing them laugh in the background of a wedding video, or
preserved on a recorded ``letter'' to a soldier son in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no money in po etry,'' the writer Robert Graves once
said, ``but then there is no poetry in money.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impolite to gloat, particu larly if you're rich. But, hey,
Bill Gates, eat your heart out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
