<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-GONZAGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK SHOT ENDS RED STORM'S SEASON  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ There were two minutes left and Matt Santangelo was
stuck on the right side of the lane. The Gonzaga guard leaned into
Erick Barkley and rocketed a line drive from 15 feet. The shot
banked in and the sold-out crowd at the McKale Center roared the
roar that accompanies destiny and an upset.
</P>
<P>
   It was 71-64, and the heave that looked more like a pool shot
might have been the one that was going to end St. John's tumultuous
season with a second-round upset loss in the West Regional.
</P>
<P>
   If the Red Storm faithful wanted to believe that their team had
one more comeback left in them on Saturday, Santangelo _ Barkley's
backup on a summer team _ dashed that hope less than a minute later
with a 3-point shot from the key that turned St. John's desperate.
</P>
<P>
   With 17.4 seconds left, Barkley drained a fall-away jumper from
near the St. John's bench to cut the lead to 79-76. And Santangelo
missed one of two free throws with 15.9 seconds left to ever so
slightly open the door. But Barkley could not hit another 3-pointer
and Lavor Postell batted the rebound out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, St. John's ran out of court. Tenth-seeded Gonzaga
upended No. 2 St. John's, 82-76. The Red Storm's loss came on the
same night No. 1-seeded Arizona was upset by Wisconsin, 66-59, in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps a fitting end to a difficult season, the Red Storm
was booed as it left the floor because all but Bootsy Thornton and
Lavor Postell decided to exit before congratulating the victorious
underdogs. The Bulldogs? They were cheered once more as they hugged
at midcourt and bounded off the hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, the Bulldogs took their first lead by
bombing from the 3-point line. Ryan Floyd lofted one from the key
to give Gonzaga a 40-39 lead with 17:49 left in the game. Two
minutes later, the 6-foot-11-inch Axel Dench stepped behind the
line to give the Bulldogs a 45-44 lead. But St. John's fought back
and with 12:58 left. Thornton _ after absorbing a hard foul from
Mark Spink that caused a brief scuffle _ tied the game at 49-49 by
making one of two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   For the next four minutes, the two teams dueled brilliantly.
Casey Calvary dropped inside for a layup; Postell answered with a
15-footer from the wing. Richie Frahm hit his first shot of the
game, a 24-foot 3- pointer from the right wing; Barkley answered
with a 3 to tie the score at 54-54. When Spink took a pass from
Santangelo for a left-handed runner, the Bulldogs went up by 56-54
and the crowd was behind Gonzaga the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   With 7:30 left in the game, Santangelo brought the crowd to its
feet by hitting a 3-pointer from the top of the key for a 59-54
lead. But Reggie Jesse put them back in their seats with a six-foot
runner. Less than a minute later, however, Barkley leaned in on
Frahm and picked up his fourth foul. Frahm sank both for a 61-56
lead.
</P>
<P>
   When Postell reached in on Calvary and picked up his third foul,
the Bulldog dropped them both and Gonzaga had a 7-point lead,
63-56.
</P>
<P>
   But Glover again asserted himself. With 5:25 left, he stole a
pass intended for Calvary, threw the outlet to Thornton and
followed the play. Thornton shoveled it back and Glover cut the
score to 63-58 with a flying lay up. The Red Storm would have to
scramble.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, St. John's Coach Mike Jarvis said his players
could look across the court at Gonzaga (25-8) and might see
themselves. The similarities were striking as the Red Storm took a
36-33 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Like St. John's and its threesome of Barkley, Postell and
Thornton, Gonzaga's Santangelo, Frahm and Dench formed the core of
a team that nearly made it to last year's Final Four. The Red Storm
went down to Ohio State in the South Regional final. In the West
Regional final that year, the Bulldogs lost, 67-62, to the eventual
champion Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Each team, too, has had to persevere through rocky seasons, but
for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga lost back-to-back games against Cincinnati and Temple
early in the season and later dropped three of their last four
regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's, on the other hand, has been embroiled in an National
Collegiate Athletic Association investigation the last six weeks
during which Barkley missed three games over two separate
suspensions. The investigation still hovered over the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs turned the ball over 24 times in their 77-66 upset
of No. 7 Louisville and needed 19 points in the second half from
Frahm. The Red Storm's pressure defense harassed the Bulldogs into
seven first-half turnovers. Barkley, Gray and Thornton combined for
five steals and hounded Santangelo and Frahm on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs' vaunted guard tandem of Santangelo and Frahm was
half its usual self _ Santangelo had 10 first-half points, but
Frahm came up empty. He was 0 for 3 from the field _ including a
blown breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm, meanwhile, survived Barkley and Postell's
combined 7-of-23 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different and explosive Postell who scored the first
two field goals of the game by backing Frahm on the baseline and
lofting two turnaround jumpers over him. His first half was
interrupted when he picked up his second foul with 13:37 left in
the half. He didn't return until 8:05 left in the game and was a
perfect 3-3. Barkley, however, struggled on the offensive end of
the floor. He was just 2 of 6 from the field
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Anthony Glover bulled his way in the paint and forced
Calvary to pick up two fouls in the first two minutes of the game.
The 6-7 sophomore employed every up and under move in his arsenal
to lead St. John's with 10 first half points against Dench. He also
helped the Red Storm win the rebounding war 19-16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
