<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OIL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS FOR NEW RESERVE OF HEATING OIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for new lead)  
 (HLW)  
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton endorsed legislation Saturday to
create a new reserve of heating oil to cushion against future
shortages in the Northeastern states, but beyond exhorting foreign
nations to boost their oil production, he proposed no short-term
steps to relieve rising fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he urged Congress to focus on long-term efforts to
reduce fuel consumption, including conservation tax credits and
research spending, which Congress has rejected when he proposed
them before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no overnight solution to this problem,'' Clinton said
in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
   He did not propose any emergency steps, like releasing oil from
existing federal reserves, which are for emergency use, or lowering
gasoline taxes. And he ruled out increasing domestic production in
Alaska by drilling in protected wildlife habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that while the spike in fuel prices this spring was
hard on people with modest incomes who must drive long distances to
work, and on independent truckers (who have protested by driving
their rigs through Washington), the overall economy remained
strong.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bernard Sanders of Vermont, an independent, said that he
was ``delighted'' that Clinton had endorsed the legislation, which
was sponsored by Sanders, to create a heating oil reserve for the
Northeast. The bill already has 92 cosponsors in the House. ``I
think his support will give the impetus to get the legislation
passed,'' he said. Sanders said he also favored immediate sales of
oil from the federal stockpile to help bring prices down.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the president's proposal envisioned a
pool of some 2 million barrels of oil drawn from existing federal
oil stockpiles, to be stored at existing facilities in the
Northeast so that they could be released during shortages or to
deal with transportation bottlenecks.
</P>
<P>
   They said the administration would ask Congress to pass a new
law establishing the program, so that conditions for releasing
heating oil onto the market could be specified.
</P>
<P>
   However, the president conceded that his other energy
conservation ideas have received short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   ``For over two years, Congress has refused to pass common-sense
tax credits I've proposed to promote fuel-saving cars of the future
and energy-efficient homes, buildings and equipment,'' he said,
urging Congress to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's long past time for Congress to fully fund the more than
$1 billion I've requested to accelerate the research and
development of more efficient energy technologies,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The average price of gasoline, which was about $1.25 at
Christmas, has risen in recent weeks to above $1.50, and the Energy
Department now projects that it could reach as much as $1.80 this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil and gasoline stocks in the United States are at
``alarmingly low'' levels not seen in decades, the agency said, and
``as the gasoline season gets under way, stocks will plumb
uncharted depths if they follow their usual seasonal pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York, a candidate for the Senate,
said Clinton's proposals showed that ``he has had a slight
awakening from his nap,'' and urged the administration to sell oil
from existing reserves ``right now.'' He said the administration
should also try to persuade Kuwait and Saudi Arabia to ``break up
the illegal cartel,'' a reference to the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., said in a statement Saturday
that ``it is critical that the United States make clear to OPEC,
publicly or privately, that we stand ready to immediately release
oil from the reserve if the OPEC ministers do not agree to a
substantial production increase.'' Schumer is a close ally of
Clinton and a supporter of Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who
recently visited Middle Eastern oil states, would continue to lobby
cartel members to increase production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
