s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     03-18 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 26)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SINGLE &AMP; SINGLE &LR;  By John le Carre. Pocket Star, $7.99. A master
of Cold War spy fiction finds fresh material in the no less
treacherous world of global finance in this novel about the son of
a British merchant banker who betrays his father to save him from
Russian mobsters. ``It is a rich idea, which le Carre writes
richly,'' Michael Lewis wrote in The New York Times Book Review
last year. He handles his craft ``with his usual spark and
originality.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORGAN: American Financier &LR;  By Jean Strouse. HarperPerennial,
$18. In this voluminous biography, which was selected by the
editors of The New York Times Book Review as one of the best books
of 1999, the enigmatic J. Pierpont Morgan is portrayed as an
inarticulate man who had little interest in introspection but whose
imperious, ruthless, indefatigable personality enabled him to forge
the financial superstructure of the leading American industries in
the Gilded Age. The author ``debunks many of the errors propagated
by both hagiographers and muckrakers and elucidates in ample detail
Morgan's financial maneuverings'' and personal life, Richard
Lingeman wrote in The New York Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOING FAST: Poems &LR;  By Frederick Seidel. Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $13. These poems _ whether about AIDS, nuclear testing or
the gleaming possibility that is New York _ are filled with echoes
of the last millennium and a nostalgia for a less technocratic
world. ``The poet ranges over the century and picks his targets,
often wisely and with an ironic and acerbic tongue,'' Melanie Rehak
wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; HANDWRITING: Poems &LR; , by Michael Ondaatje (Vintage
International, $11), the author of ``The English Patient'' explores
exotic themes drawn largely from the history and mythology of India
and China. Last year, Adam Kirsch admired the collection's ``richly
sensual images'' and ``lush descriptions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARILYN MONROE &LR;  By Barbara Leaming. Three Rivers, $15.
According to this biography, the screen icon may have been used and
abused, but she was an intuitive strategist who was fueled by a
furious desire to succeed despite daunting odds. ``The author
restores Marilyn's humanity, gives flesh and blood, intelligence
and initiative, to the archetypal dumb blonde,'' Molly Haskell
wrote in 1998. It is a ``gripping and corrective book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON SUNSET BOULEVARD: The Life and Times of Billy Wilder &LR; , by Ed
Sikov (Hyperion, $17.95), chronicles Wilder's turbulent career from
his roots as a gigolo in Germany to one of Hollywood's most
iconoclastic directors (he cast Monroe in ``The Seven Year Itch''
and ``Some Like It Hot''). In 1998 the reviewer Andrew Sarris
called this ``a perceptive and profound appreciation'' of ``the
man, the artist, the showman, the self-promoter ... and the
successful businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TYRANNY ON TRIAL: The Trial of the Major German War Criminals
at the End of World War II at Nuremberg, Germany, 1945-1946 &LR;  By
Whitney R. Harris. Southern Methodist University, $14.95. The
author, who served as a trial counsel during the Nuremberg trials,
has revised and updated his 1954 legal and historical analysis of
the tribunal. ``This is one of those books that are heart-rending
to read and perilous to ignore,'' Saul K. Padover wrote. It is ``a
masterly and meticulous'' work.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THE PARNAS: A Scene From the Holocaust &LR; , by Silvano Arieti
(Paul Dry, $14.95), an Italian psychoanalyst tells of his work with
a tormented leader of the Jewish community in Pisa who was later
murdered by the Nazis. The result is ``a work of art that is in
ennobling contrast to the pain and suffering from which it
sprang,'' Caroline Seebohm wrote in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KAFKA'S CURSE &LR;  By Achmat Dangor. Vintage International, $12.
This novel employs magical fables to explore the psychic damage
wrought by apartheid that continues to haunt South Africans of all
races. ``Dangor writes lyrical ... prose that switches suddenly
into blazing anger,'' Christopher Hope wrote last year. ``He shows
brilliantly the violent mixture of race, rage and gunfire that
gives South Africa its crazy speed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EVENSONG &LR;  By Gail Godwin. Ballantine, $14. This novel follows
the marital and spiritual travails of a pastor in a Smoky Mountain
town and her husband, an older priest, as they struggle to balance
the practical and philosophical demands of their faith.
``Meticulousness and precision are ... Godwin's greatest
strengths,'' Claire Messud wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMATEUR: An Independent Life of Letters &LR;  By Wendy Lesser.
Vintage, $13. The founder of The Threepenny Review, who describes
herself as an ``18th-century man of letters,'' reveals herself in a
series of essays about a life hopelessly entwined with literature,
dance and theater. The result is a ``deeply humane, modest and
beautifully constructed narration,'' James Shapiro wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AGE OF TERROR &LR;  By David Plante. St. Martin's Griffin,
$13.95. This novel's hero is a young American expatriate who
struggles to maintain his moral and religious compass when he gets
involved in a messy Oedipal triangle in the chaotic final years of
the Soviet Union. ``Plante leads his readers into some deep, dark
woods,'' Caleb Crain wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
