<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1449 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-HIGH-SCHOOL-     03-18 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-HIGH-SCHOOL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL MORE FUN WHEN IT'S ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there a teenager anywhere who can't wait to get out of high
school? &QL; 
The awkward growth spurts, the uncomfortable social situations, the
raging hormones _ it all adds up to one ugly time.
</P>
<P>
   So why is it so much fun to go back _ on TV?
</P>
<P>
   By which I don't mean a televised visit to a modern high school,
like in Popular or, until the gang went to college this season,
Buffy the Vampire Slayer. High school shows have always been a
television staple, since (and even before) the days of The Many
Loves of Dobie Gillis.
</P>
<P>
   I mean actually going back, back in time, on shows such as
Freaks and Geeks, which returned Monday from a monthlong hiatus,
and That '70s Show. Although the two are markedly different _ That
'70s Show is a straightforward half-hour sitcom set during the Ford
and Carter presidencies, while Freaks and Geeks is a more complex,
hourlong time-machine trip to 1980 _ both rely on their creators'
high-school memories to fuel them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can write a much more honest high school show if I write
about when I was in school,'' says Paul Feig, Freaks creator,
``because I really have no take on what is going on in there today.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we wanted to be is the guys in their 30s
running around going, `OK, what are the kids saying these days?'
and pulling out some term that's already two years out of date and
a band that's over, and we're like, `Oh, we thought they were
cool.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when kids dance to a Styx song in Freaks, it's funny, not
embarrassing, as it would be if the show took place now and
everyone did the Macarena.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to this than following the age-old adage of
writing what you know. While we're tossing about adages, how about
throwing ``time heals all wounds'' into the mix?
</P>
<P>
   ``The freshness of the wound has gone away,'' says Mark Brazill,
creator of That '70s Show, laughing. ``The humiliating time has,
God willing, receded from your mind, so you can look at it with a
sense of humor, as opposed to, `It was awful; they looked at me in
the shower.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a certain amount of time to pass before you have the
perspective you need to retell certain parts of your life. I'm 37.
But my perspective is so much better than it was at 18. I feel like
I see (high school days) pretty clearly. It actually makes me happy
to think about. It was a pretty good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after your last wedgie, at least, it seems like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tragedy plus time equals comedy,'' Feig says. ``It's a bit of
an archaeology, going back and finding the roots of your personal
civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   And the beauty of this science is that, although it's based on
the writers' lives (so much so that Brazill uses his yearbooks for
research), it doesn't demand total accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who ever stood in the shower after football practice in
ninth grade, paralyzed with angry fear because a couple of
sophomores hit you with soap and dared you to do something about
it, would like the chance to rewrite history. (Purely theoretical
example, mind you.)
</P>
<P>
   These guys get to.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed as well. Some of the funniest moments in That
'70s Show revolve on the characters _ gasp _ smoking dope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marijuana was kind of funny at that time,'' Brazill says.
``Cheech and Chong were like the Jim Carrey of that decade. Now?
God, the whole country has a completely different attitude about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, theirs was not just an artistic decision. There are
business concerns to setting the shows in the past, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``A show about high school 20 years ago is going to get kids who
are in high school now (who) will want to watch, just because it's
about people their own age,'' Feig says. ``And yet people who have
been out for 20 years could enjoy it, too, because it has that
throwback for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, Freaks and Geeks doesn't get much of either
audience, despite being one of the best shows on TV. And although
That '70s Show is a hit, it took a while to pick up a sizable
viewership.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, Freaks and Geeks will, as well. If you've got to
relive the cold chill of visiting the assistant principals office,
there's no better place to do it.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of both shows _ although the details of teen
life change from one generation to the next, turning on the TV on
is still a lot easier than getting turned down for a prom date.
Always has been, always will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a different home life,'' Brazill says.
``Everybody has a different family. Everybody has a different job.
But for the most part, high school is universal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad news if you're still in high school, maybe. Good news for
the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Good TV, anyway. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
