<HEADLINE>
DALLAS BURN DOUSES CHICAGO FIRE IN MLS OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Plenty of goals, the debut of an international
standout, and a goal and two assists from a player who had no
points until yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for the first game of the 2000 MLS season.
</P>
<P>
   And not bad for the Burn either, who came out the 4-2 winner
yesterday at the Cotton Bowl with another come-from-behind victory
against the Chicago Fire before 12,891.
</P>
<P>
   After twice trailing by one goal, the Burn managed to shake off
a lackluster first half with three goals in the second half to
defeat the Fire, who was knocked out of the playoffs by the Burn
last season in almost exactly the same fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge win by the fact that we were behind two times,
and we were able to come back and put them away when we needed
to,'' said Burn midfielder Chad Deering, who had two assists.
``There are some things we still need to iron out, but all in all
I'm pleased with the performance. It was a good way to send Billy
out.''
</P>
<P>
   While the game marked the last for outgoing president and
general manager Billy Hicks, who is leaving the Burn to take a
position with the XFL, it also marked promise for some
up-and-coming players.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn had goals from their usual candidates, forwards Jason
Kreis and Ariel Graziani, but defender Eric Dade notched his first
MLS points in regulation with a goal and an assist. His goal, which
came in the 79th minute, came off a perfectly executed passing
scheme with assists from Kreis and midfielder Oscar Pareja that
threaded right through the Fire defense for a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd save them for this year,'' Dade said, referring
to his points. ``\RCoach\S Dave \RDir\S has been letting me get
forward a little bit more. I got a good ball from Oscar and put
together a couple of good passes with Jay, and it happened to work
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fire had noteworthy performances from its top newcomers,
17-year-old striker DaMarcus Beasley and Bulgarian standout Hristo
Stoitchov, who marked his MLS debut by scoring both of the Fire's
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game is always hard,'' Stoitchov said. ``It's sad we
lost. We need better movement within our team, and that will come
with practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoitchov's goals gave the Fire (0-1) a 2-1 halftime lead. In
the 28th minute, Deering found Kreis for a header off a free kick
to give the Burn lts first goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani, who played with an Ecuadorian team, Emelec, during the
off-season, didn't miss a beat from his scoring tear last season,
notching the Burn's second goal to tie the game at 2-2 in the 55th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani found his touch again six minutes after Dade's go-ahead
goal, sending a screaming shot off an assist from Dade into the top
of the net past Chicago rookie goalkeeper Greg Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a fun conversation at halftime and got back to where
the concentration needed to be discipline-wise,'' Dir said.
``That's going to be a challenge this season. We can't live on last
year's season. We've got to keep the focus and step up from where
they were last season.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
