<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICH.-ST.-UTAH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARTANS FOLLOW THE LEADER, CLEAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Double high step. Double fist pump.
</P>
<P>
   Mateen Cleaves was celebrating. A notoriously average jump
shooter, he had reason to act out. His 3-pointer had just given
Michigan State a 64-50 lead. Utah coach Rick Majerus responded by
calling a 20-second timeout. On the way to join the Spartans'
huddle, Cleaves gave an umpire's safe sign indicating that the game
was over.
</P>
<P>
   It was. Thanks to Cleaves' hostile takeover, the top-seeded
Spartans avoided an upset, winning, 73-61, in the second round of
the Midwest Region. Michigan State (28-7) made 61.9 percent of its
second-half shots to foil the efforts of the Utes (23-9).
</P>
<P>
   Utah, playing with a depleted roster, shot 56.5 percent in the
first half to take a 35-32 lead. The Utes made their first four
shots of the second half and led 43-37 with 17:50 remaining. From
there, Cleaves took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, they played good D on me, but I sort of
took myself out of the game,'' said Cleaves, who finished with 21
points, and made 4 of 7 3-point attempts. ``I just pushed it in the
second half. I wanted to force the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 10 minutes, the Spartans went on a 27-7 run.
Cleaves scored 11 _ hitting two 3-pointers _ and assisted on three
other baskets, including 3-pointers by Morris Peterson and A.J.
Granger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got in my face after I got a rebound and said, `That's what
I'm talking about,''' Peterson said. ``It was like a demon came out
of him.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Cleaves-inspired spurt, Utah never got closer than
nine points. With 18 seconds remaining and Michigan State dribbling
out the clock, Majerus capitulated and started walking toward the
Spartans' bench to shake hands with coach Tom Izzo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt Cleaves' strength wasn't the outside shot,'' said
Majerus, whose team shot 52.2 percent. ``We tried to make Cleaves
score, and he proved it to us. We picked our poison.''
</P>
<P>
   Majerus said before the game that the game wouldn't be about
wrinkles (tricky strategy) but about personnel. Michigan State's
edge in the personnel file was Cleaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was winning time, he took over,'' Izzo said. ``He's
done it year in, year out, game in, game out.'' \Ntagtop:Wendell
Barnhouse, (817) 390-7238 \Ntagbottom:wbhoops\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 2348EST &QL; 
