<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-WISCONSIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISCONSIN PLANTS TOP-SEED ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Wisconsin is frequently regarded as a plodding,
defensive-minded, middle-of-the-road program in the Big Ten;
Arizona is one of college basketball's elite.
</P>
<P>
   But perceptions don't win games in the NCAA Tournament. And
yesterday the eighth-seeded Badgers pulled the NCAA Tournament's
biggest stunner to date by knocking out the West Region's No. 1
seed, 66-59.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I could adequately describe how good we feel, or
how proud I am of this team,'' Wisconsin coach Dick Bennett said.
``They carried out our game plan as close as is humanly possible.
To defend a great team like Arizona is something I'll remember for
a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   In being held to a season-low point total, Arizona made only 20
of 51 shots, a percentage of .392 as opposed to Wisconsin's 57
percent second half and a game percentage of .489. The Wildcats'
inside trio of Luke Walton, Justin Wessel and Michael Wright
combined for only nine points as Arizona obviously missed the
presence of injured center Loren Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Wildcats coach Lute Olson alluded to the youth of his team _ he
started three freshmen and two sophomores _ as a factor in the loss
to the more experienced Badgers, making their second consecutive
NCAA appearance after finishing sixth in the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an indescribable feeling,'' said Badgers forward Andy
Kowske, who scored 12 points and pulled in 10 rebounds. ``It's the
best feeling in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Mark Vershaw led four Badgers scoring in double figures
with 15 points. Forwards Maurice Litton and Kowske combined for 27.
All are juniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very obvious they were the better team,'' Olson said.
``One, from the standpoint of maturity and toughness. I told our
team afterward that it's a difficult lesson to learn, but it was
very obvious that Wisconsin's maturity and toughness is something
that every one of our freshmen and sophomores have to be aware of
if we're to get where we want to get as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They did an unbelievable job inside with their big guys. Their
defense made it very difficult for us. They did a great job using
their strength and size inside. We had a number of opportunities
that we were not able to take advantage of and when that happens,
you look at the other team's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to scramble when we got down, but there's no question
the better team won the basketball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona led only once, after a game-opening jumper by guard
Gilbert Arenas, who led the Wildcats with 21 points. Wisconsin led
28-23 at the half and stretched that to 50-33 with eight minutes to
play. Arenas hit a 3-point shot to cut the margin to 64-59 with 17
seconds left, but Wisconsin held.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers won the NCAA title in 1941, but are making their
first appearance in the Sweet 16 in the modern era.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
