<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BLACKHAWKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS LET LEAD GO TO WASTE IN LOSS TO BLACKHAWKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Stars winger Brett Hull, his father, Bobby, and Guy
Carbonneau went to grab some lunch Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And dad dispensed some fatherly advice to his struggling son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to get himself in shape physically and mentally.
The playoffs are coming up and people are counting on you,'' Bobby
Hull said. ``He just needs to get his confidence back. He'll be OK.
You'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, father does actually know best, because Brett Hull looked
OK and then some against Chicago yesterday, scoring what would've
and probably should've been the game-winner had the Stars not
coughed up a two-goal lead in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   But they did, and the 2-2 tie with the Blackhawks they left town
with is the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not going to win too many games getting two goals,''
Brett Hull said. ``That's usually the problem. It's par for the
course.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's any consolation for Hull, the Blackhawks spoiled goalie
Ed Belfour's comeback as well.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour hadn't played since being charged with misdemeanor
assault and resisting arrest on March 8. He missed five games.
Except for a couple of early-game jitters, though, Belfour said he
felt fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solid,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock called him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He only missed, what, two games, less than a week?'' Brett
Hull said. ``It's not like he's coming back from a broken leg or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The ironic thing is, Belfour said he felt his rhythm returning
in the third period, which is when the Blackhawks scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   Both goals came during a 90-second span of four-on-four in the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   With Blackhawks winger Michal Grosek and Stars defenseman Darryl
Sydor both in the penalty box, Chicago came alive. First, Hawks
center Michael Nylander scored at 11:32. Then, defenseman Boris
Mironov scored 72 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kind of chances happen in four-on-four,'' Belfour said.
``Of course, it would've been nice to make those saves, but I
didn't. The nice part is I felt more comfortable as the game went
on. I started seeing the puck and feeling it better.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing he did, too. The Blackhawks outshot the Stars
11-6 in the third period and 3-2 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   So, were the Stars maybe sitting on the lead?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we so much sat on it,'' Stars winger Kirk
Muller said. ``We just didn't have that killer instinct. We have to
get a little bit more of that killer instinct to get that third
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   With how easily the first two came, the Stars had to figure the
third one wouldn't be too far away.
</P>
<P>
   When Stars winger Mike Keane scored on a rebound of an Aaron
Gavey shot, almost 55 minutes remained in the game. And his goal
was only 28 seconds after Hull's.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Hull scored 4 minutes, 43 seconds into the first period, a
pretty wrist shot from the point that Blackhawks goalie Jocelyn
Thibault didn't see until it was past him. The goal was Hull's 21st
of the season and 607th of his career. He's only three away from
tying his father for eighth on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, right away quick, when he scored first, I said,
`God, he's got the whole game to get three more. He could do it
right here,''' Bobby Hull said. ``I wanted him to do it. I can't
wait until he passes me. In my opinion, he's the greatest goal
scorer ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, for his part, wanted no part of the tying-dad talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' he said when asked about it. ``I'm not going to
talk about it. It's stupid. Right now, it is because I haven't done
it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Brett, you're only a hat trick away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could happen before next Christmas at the pace I'm
going,'' Hull said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 2348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
