r s BC-BKC-SYRACUSE-KENTUCKY     03-18 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SYRACUSE-KENTUCKY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRACUSE GETS THE SHOT, SENIORS WHEN NEEDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Good shooters operate in a blissful, empty-headed
state. No matter how many shots chip paint, it's ``the next one''
that's going in.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse moves on to the Sweet 16 because sophomore Preston
Shumpert is a good shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Shumpert's 18-foot jumper from in front of his team's bench with
36 seconds left gave the fourth-seeded Orangemen a 52-50 victory
against fifth-seeded Kentucky (23-10) in yesterday's second round
of the Midwest Region. Syracuse (26-5) will meet top-seeded
Michigan State, a 73-61 winner against Utah, in the Midwest
semifinals Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get shots like that, first thing you do is tense
up,'' said Shumpert, a 6-foot-6 guard who wears knee-high black
socks for a distinctive look. ``You don't worry about the past, you
just shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Shumpert's recent past said this: Don't shoot. He had missed 10
of 13 shots before making his game-winning jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had made a couple earlier, you wouldn't have needed to
make that one,'' Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim said.
</P>
<P>
   No need to single out Shumpert, Coach. Both teams settled into
zone defenses that strangled the opposition's shooters. The
Wildcats shot 40.4 percent, the Orangemen shot 31.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse's saving grace was its senior leadership.
</P>
<P>
   When senior center Etan Thomas fouled out with 3:46 remaining,
the Orangemen had a 48-45 lead. During a brief huddle, senior point
guard Jason Hart took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason yelled at me and said, `Don't worry about it, we're
going to win,'' Thomas said. ``He said he wasn't going to let us
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kentucky tied it at 48-all on a Jules Camara dunk, senior
forward Ryan Blackwell scored over Kentucky center Jamaal Magloire.
And after another Camara dunk tied it at 50-50, Hart made
game-turning plays at each end.
</P>
<P>
   First, he forced a jump ball (alternate possession: Syracuse)
against Kentucky junior point guard Saul Smith with 51.2 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it coming, I knew he was going to drive,'' said Hart,
who missed eight of 10 shots. ``The refs were calling it tight, but
I tried to get as much of the ball as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   On the following possession, Hart drove the left side of the
lane. Instead of trying to shoot over the 6-10 Magloire or the 6-11
Camara, Hart bounced a pass to Shumpert. His shot eluded the
lunging block attempt of Kentucky's Tayshaun Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky had two shots to tie. Freshman Keith Bogans drove
through the lane and launched a 10-footer that was short. Prince
flashed in for the rebound, but his follow to beat the buzzer
bounced long.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got it, I didn't know how much time there was, so I was
trying to get it to the rim,'' said Prince, who scored 10
consecutive points to give the Wildcats a second-half boost. ``But
I was off balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse had a 40-23 rebound edge; 21 of those boards were on
the offensive glass and resulted in 22 significant second-chance
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won this game because we got on the backboards,'' Boeheim
said. ``It was a game where neither team could get anything going
on offense. It was just a matter of will and determination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
