<DOCNO> NYT20000318.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-18 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1468 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     03-18 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TRADE COULD HAUNT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ Considering the reputations Ismael Valdes and Eric
Young left behind in Los Angeles, it's a wonder the stars of the
latest controversial Dodgers trade are up to the manual task of
putting on their new Chicago Cubs uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Young is the second baseman with the stone hands, murder on a
fielding percentage, symbolic of a rigid personality. Valdes is the
pitcher with the tender hands, prone to blisters, emblematic of a
delicate psyche.
</P>
<P>
   You picture one of them fumbling his socks, bobbling his cap,
leaving a trail of laundry across the Cubs clubhouse floor. You
imagine the other bloodying a knuckle on his belt buckle.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there they were in the HoHoKam Park clubhouse as a Cactus
League night game wound down, neatly decked out in Cubs blue, red
and white, looking quite comfortable, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be where I'm wanted,'' Young said in his corner
of the dressing room, across the way from Sammy Sosa. ``The
situation pretty much got ... cloudy ... over there in L.A. It was
good to come to a little more sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers are the past,'' Valdes said at his cubicle, closer
to the center of the room, directly across from Kerry Wood. ``My
present and future are the Cubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was on his honeymoon (big on ``privacy,'' he won't say
where) when he heard on television Dec. 12 that he and Young had
been sent to the Cubs in exchange for workhorse pitcher Terry
Adams, Double-A pitcher Chad Ricketts and a player to be announced,
Single-A pitcher Brian Stephenson.
</P>
<P>
   Young was at home in Tennessee when he got a phone call from Don
Baylor, his manager when both were Colorado Rockies and his new
Cubs manager.
</P>
<P>
   Young's reaction was shared by most of us in Los Angeles: ``It
was a steal for the Cubs.''
</P>
<P>
   This might have been the (begin ital)most(end ital)
controversial trade in recent Dodgers history. The Mike Piazza deal
is beyond debatable by now. It's agreed that was a bad move.
</P>
<P>
   This move, it could be argued, was necessary, as one-sided as it
looks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were intent on trimming last year's $83 million
player payroll, Young and Valdes were due to receive more than $10
million combined in 2000, and Valdes will be eligible for free
agency next winter.
</P>
<P>
   Young was out of favor with Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, a
permanent wall having gone up between them when Young was benched
in July after failing to turn what Johnson considered a
``room-service'' double play.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes had been out of favor with most of the clubhouse for most
of his six seasons with the Dodgers, a right-hander with Orel
Hershiser's talent but none of the Bulldog's intangibles. Pitching
coach Claude Osteen questioned Valdes' toughness in September,
saying he submitted too easily to the ``negatives'' in his head,
giving public voice to the private complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what people say. They can talk all they want,''
Valdes said unemotionally the other night. ``How much proof do they
need? I'm a 200-inning (a season) pitcher. What do they want?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had success in the past,'' he adds. ``I have to continue
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the case against the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was a double-digit winner four times as a Dodger, and his
career ERA of 3.38 ranks 10th among active major-leaguers. He left
a hole in the Dodgers' rotation. Young's 51 stolen bases are 13
more than the rest of the Cubs' spring roster combined had in 1999.
He left the Dodgers without an experienced second baseman or
leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes chooses his words carefully and expresses no bitterness
toward the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great memories with the Dodgers. I appreciate all they
did for me,'' he said. ``I have nothing against them. I wish the
best of luck for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Valdes look forward to pitching against them?
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's my turn, yes. If not, well, nothing I can do,'' he
said. ``They're just another team now.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest of us, Dodgers-Cubs will be a matchup to
anticipate.
</P>
<P>
   In the two full seasons Young and Valdes were both in Los
Angeles, the Dodgers won 160 games, three more than the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Young and Valdes were a couple of the Dodgers' most notable
recent failures. How they fare in 2000, and how their old and new
teams compare, will help to determine whether the failure was
theirs or the Dodgers'.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-18-00 2358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
